bruce g. clarke, a retired four-star general who was the army commander-in-chief in europe when berlin was the focal point of the cold war between the united states and the soviet union, has died. he was 86
clarke, who died thursday at walter reed army hospital, had suffered a stroke
the mclean, va. resident was born in adams, n.y. he was graduated from the u.s. military academy at west point, n.y. in 1925, and he later received a master's degree in civil engineering from cornell university and a law degree from la salle extension university
during world war ii, he commanded the combat command a in the 4th armored division and later commanded the division. during the korean war, he commanded the u.s. i corps and later the x corps of the far east command
later, he commanded the u.s. army in the pacific, the u.s. 7th army in europe and the continental army command at fort monroe, va
he was commander-in-chief of the army in europe from 1960 to 1962 and was credited with keeping his troops in a high state of training and morale while supervising patrols of air and ground routes to berlin
clarke devoted himself to army affairs after retiring in 1962, writing frequently on matters such as training and command and making an inspection of vietnam in 1968
his wife, the former bessie mitchell, died in 1956
he is survived by three sons _ bruce c. clarke jr. of st. anton a.d. jessnitz, austria; dr. david a. clarke of colorado springs, colo.; and army col. gordon m. clarke of san antonio, texas _ a daughter, mrs. elisabeth clark of leesburg, va.; two sisters, mary griffin of adams and frances saternow of oswego, n.y.; 18 grandchildren and five great-grandchildren
a six-year study of the largest population ever contaminated by the toxic chemical dioxin found no apparent increase in birth defects
the study, published in friday's journal of the american medical association, focused on babies born in and around seveso, italy, from 1977 through 1982
a 1976 chemical accident ata factory in the area released a cloud of dioxin that contaminated more than 37,200 residents in seveso and the neighboring towns of meda, cesano maderno and desio
the study said that if there is any increased risk related to dioxin, ``the overall risk is unlikely to be large or might be limited to very rare and specific birth defects.''
still more important,'' the study concluded, ``is the fact that no infant with a major malformation was identified in the most highly contaminated zone.''
dioxin, a byproduct of pesticide manufacture, causes cancer in laboratory animals. it has not been directly linked to cancers in humans
in the italian study, doctors considered as defects only those congenital malformations obvious at birth. congenital problems that manifest themselves later in life, such as mental retardation, were not considered
the seveso congenital malformations registry, established shortly after the accident, found that in 15,291 births, 742 infants were born with deformities, a rate of 48.5 per 1,000
the prevalence of deformities over the same period in a nearby uncontaminated area used as a control was 48.8 per 1,000 births, the study found
the quantity of dioxin released into the environment ``seemed to be enormous'' but was never precisely determined, according to the study
levels of dioxin concentration found on the ground in the area surrounding the factory were nearly 1,000 times higher than the levels termed safe by state and federal officials after a cleanup at times beach, mo
times beach is now deserted and hundreds of families have filed lawsuits against companies and individuals over their exposure to dioxin contained in waste oil sprayed on their streets to control dust in the 1970s
questions about the effects of exposure to dioxin have lingered since the vietnam war. dioxin is in agent orange, a defoliant used during the war
some veterans have sought government compensation, contending their exposure resulted in cancers, rashes, headaches and other side effects, as well as birth defects in their children
the veterans administration has contended numerous studies have found no link between exposure and reported symptoms. honduras, u.s. activity at air base. picks up 4th graf pvs, two battalions ...; subs grafs 23-24, ``the u.s. official ... with 2 grafs to conform.</note>
planeloads of u.s. soldiers streamed into this air base thursday in a show of strength ordered by president reagan to counter what he called an invasion by nicaraguan forces
in northern nicaragua, warplanes dropped bombs near a sandinista military headquarters thursday, but no casualties or damage resulted. reporters at the scene said the explosives fell on the honduran side of the border
nicaragua and a u.s. official said earlier that the raid was aimed at the military post
the american troops were to engage in joint exercises with the hondurans. but the u.s. airlift was so hastily arranged that american commanders were left scrambling to develop training exercises to keep the men busy
hundreds of soldiers bedded down in dusty fields near the airstrip awaiting orders for training missions which normally are arranged months in advance
the american troops were told to expect to spend about 10 days in honduras, but spokesmen said there was no official timetable yet for them to leave
two battalions from the renowned 82nd airborne division of fort bragg, n.c., and two battalions from the 7th light infantry division of fort ord, calif., were combined into a task force of 3,000 troops
a honduran official said his government had given the sandinistas 24 hours to get out of the country, which they entered in pursuit of contra rebels
president daniel ortega of nicaragua responded that his army was ``ready to combat and liquidate the famous forces of the 82nd airborne division.''
maj. gen. carl w. stiner, commander of the 82nd airborne, said he knew of no plan to have u.s. troops enter into the battle between the sandinistas and the u.s.-backed -contras
we have not been told to do so,'' he said before leaving fort bragg. he said the force was capable of that, if needed
stiner also said there was no plan to use the troops if more trouble broke out in nearby panama
the american forces began arriving at palmerola at 10:15 a.m. as part of what the pentagon called operation ``golden pheasant.''
the 26 c-141 transport planes landed in the intense heat at 30-minute intervals at this air base, headquarters of u.s. military operations in honduras, 40 miles northwest of tegucigalpa
the deployment was about 125 miles west of the area where reagan administration officials say the nicaraguan sandinista army has chased rebel contra forces over the border into honduras
col. manuel suarez benavides, a honduran armed forces spokesman, said the deadline for the sandinistas to leave was final
he said 2,000 nicaraguan soldiers had crossed the border and penetrated about six miles in pursuit of contra rebels. a military intelligence source said earlier the nicaraguans were surrounded by about 4,000 honduran troopers
suarez benavides would not comment on pentagon reports of new nicaraguan attacks inside honduras
the sandinista movements did not appear to be a full-fledged invasion, stiner said, adding that he saw the u.s. operation as a deterrent
ortega would not say whether his soldiers had crossed the border in pursuit of the u.s.-supported rebels
here the question is not if army troops penetrated honduran territory or not, but that we have dozens of camps of mercenary forces in honduran territory, in view of and tolerated by the honduran government,'' he said at a news conference in managua
he said nicaraguan soldiers would not withdraw from the border area. ortega called the u.s. troop deployment ``a dangerous act'' and demanded a meeting of the u.n. security council
a spokesman for the nicaraguan foreign ministry said before the news conference that nicaragua had begun pulling its troops back from the frontier region after driving about 2,000 contra rebels back into honduras. the defense and foreign ministries denied that nicaraguan troops entered honduras
nicaraguan presidential spokesman manuel espinoza enriquez later said that air attackers fired at least five rockets thursday at the nicaraguan military headquarters at bocay, near the honduras border. sandinista gunfire forced the planes to turn back, he said
reporters saw two planes entering nicaraguan air space from honduras. they saw nothing to support a report from a u.s. official in washington that a soviet-built helicopter had been destroyed
manuel suarez, a honduran spokesman in tegucigalpa, denied the honduran air force crossed the border, and said it dropped at least five bombs inside honduras along the border near bocay
heavy fighting was reported wednesday in the olancho border province about 125 miles east of palmerola
included in the american forces are two battalions from the 82nd airborne and two from a new division organized for quick movement around the world. the 82nd airborne and 7th light infantry are based at opposite ends of the country
the final 800 u.s. troops are to arrive friday by parachute, weather permitting
in addition to the c-141 aircraft, a giant c-5a transport was loaded with helicopter gunships for the exercise
the honduran intelligence source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said: ``we will not allow the sandinistas to move farther into the interior of our territory. we want to avoid a large conflict, but if it isn't possible, we will have to face the invading troops.''
secretary of state george p. shultz said in washington the soldiers were being sent to ``get people's attention to what is happening in central america'' and say to the honduran government: ``we are your friends.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the complete deployment would take about 27 hours. the defense department said nine helicopters and two light tanks were also sent
it was the the most dramatic show of u.s. force since the contras began fighting in nicaragua six years ago, and it came in response to a request for help from president jose azcona hoyo of honduras
since 1981, honduras has been a key u.s. ally in central america and a major element in reagan administration policy of fighting nicaragua's leftist government
about 1,100 american soldiers normally are stationed at several military installations in honduras. in addition, other national guard and army troops rotate through for joint exercises, road-building and other projects. protest. picks up 9th graf pvs, `at fort ...'</note>
protesters flattened police barricades thursday in san francisco and spray-painted slogans against the sending of troops to honduras, while demonstrators stopped traffic in minneapolis and marched in boston and philadelphia
about 25 people were arrested in san francisco in one of several protests in california. at fort ord, wives of some of the soldiers sent to honduras were among protesters at the gates. about 100 people demonstrated in santa rosa
in minneapolis, 400 people dragged newspaper racks and benches into a busy street, bringing traffic to a halt during the afternoon rush hour
in boston, 200 people marched in a circle and chanted ``u.s. troops out of honduras'' outside the john f. kennedy federal building. police said six people remained inside after closing but were evicted without incident
protesters in philadelphia erected a 30-foot ``central america war memorial'' that mimicked the vietnam memorial in the nation's capital. it bore the names of central americans killed in the region's civil wars. about 200 people marched in front of the federal courthouse
in san francisco, 500 demonstrators outside the federal building knocked down police barriers and chanted slogans
a few protesters linked arms and sat down, blocking the entrance to the building. general services administration spokeswoman mary filippini said 25 people were cited for obstructing the entrance and creating a disturbance
later thursday, up to 2,000 demonstrators gathered at the building. about 100 pounded on the windows as the crowd chanted, ``no more contra aid.'' a few spray-painted slogans on the locked building. no further arrests were made
at fort ord, where 1,200 soldiers of the 7th light infantry were ordered to honduras, the demonstrators included the wives of some soldiers who were shipped out from the base 90 miles south of san francisco
a pregnant renee worthing, 21, wife of soldier james worthing, carried a sign that said, ``stop the lies.''
i think the whole thing has just been a lie,'' she said. ``i also think it has something to do with the presidential elections because every time a presidential election comes up, a crisis comes up and the president runs to the rescue. the community is not going to stand for this.''
churches were given increased protection from libel suits in matters of religious doctrine thursday when california's supreme court refused to reinstate a $1.26 million verdict
the high court, in a 5-2 vote, refused to hear an appeal by a woman who sued the worldwide church of god after a minister proclaimed her ``one of the enemies of god's church.''
the court's action returns the case to los angeles superior court for a retrial based on a new legal standard: whether the minister knew his statements were false, or spoke in reckless disregard of whether they were false
that standard already applied to libel suits filed by public figures and government officials against newspapers and other news media
in a precedent-setting decision that now has statewide effect, a lower appeals court said the freedom of religion requires the same constitutional protections to churches and their officials when discussing religious doctrine
the suit was filed by leona mcnair of pasadena, former wife of raymond mcnair, deputy chancellor of the church-run ambassador college
she was a prominent church member who later became associated with a dissident faction and was divorced by mcnair in 1976 after 20 years of marriage
the court said their divorce and mcnair's remarriage the next year prompted criticism within the church, which recognizes divorce in only a few instances
in a 1979 speech to about 1,000 people at the church's annual meeting in tucson, ariz., roderick meredith, the church's director of pastoral administration, sought to explain why the mcnair divorce was justified by ``desertion by an unconverted mate,'' one of(the grounds recognized by the church
mrs. mcnair, he said, ``had left the church and was virtually cursing (mcnair) ... spitting literally in people's faces and as hateful as a human being can be.''
she departed so far that she is one of the major enemies of god's church in southern california,''he said
meredith returned to the subject several months later in a written report, repeating some of his previous accusations and saying mrs. mcnair had ``refused to be a wife to (mcnair) for over two years'' before the divorce
in the suit against the church, meredith, mcnair and others, a jury found that the statements were false, and that the pastor's report had caused mrs. mcnair extreme emotional distress
the appeals court overturned the verdict because jury was not asked to find that the statements were intentionally or recklessly false
the right to free exercise of religion is a constitutional guarantee of equal significance'' to freedom of the press, the appeals court said, adding that meredith's remarks, however personal, ``were made while he was explaining church doctrine'' on divorce
a missile attack on a tanker in the persian gulf early friday set the ship on fire, killed one sailor and critically injured three, shipping executives and hospital officials said
iran was suspected in the attack on the 4,127-ton maria ii, which flies the panamanian flag
as many as 19 korean crewmembers who had jumped off the vessel, which was laden with highly explosive liquefied gas, were plucked from the water and from lifeboats by salvage tugboats, the executives said
hospital officials identified the dead man as a japanese citizen
the tanker was sighted on fire just after midnight in the southern gulf, about 10 miles from the port of dubai, said the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity
they said the fire was put out after about 90 minutes and that it was apparently the result of an iranian attack, although they were unsure whether it was from air or sea
three salvage tugboats that rushed to fight the blaze reported a hole on the starboard side, indicating the vessel had been hit by a missile
the executives said the dead man's body was found floating in the water
the survivors were taken to dubai's al-rashid hospital, where officials said three were in critical condition and six were being treated for less serious injuries. they said the rest had suffered minor bruises and were treated and released
one hospital official quoted the survivors as saying they had ``thrown themselves overboard once the ship was bombed.'' he said they were not sure what had struck the ship
iran usually attacks commercial ships in the southern gulf in retaliation for iraqi strikes on its own tanker lanes. the two belligerents, at war since september 1980, have concentrated in recent weeks on attacking each others cities
there had been a lull in the so-called tanker war, except for two confirmed iraqi strikes this month. iranian retaliation is usually on a ship-for-ship basis. more than 400 ships of different nationalities have been hit or damaged by both sides
the destination of the ship was not immediately known, nor where it had picked up the shipment
the city agreed thursday to restrict police in their search for a sexual-assault suspect after the police department was accused in an aclu suit of detaining hundreds of black men without cause
the agreement, signed by city attorneys and the american civil liberties union, prohibits officers from detaining anyone merely because he matches the race or age of the man suspected of attacking eight women in the past five weeks
however, the agreement allows police to stop anyone to seek their voluntary cooperation in the investigation
a similar dispute involving a police department dragnet in an hispanic neighborhood ended with the city paying a $45,000 settlement to about 80 people in 1985
barry steinhardt, executive director of the aclu in pennsylvania, applauded the agreement, saying police commissioner kevin tucker recognized that the investigation ``should not become the occasion for the random mass questioning of black philadelphians.''
in the suit filed earlier thursday, the aclu sought a federal court injunction to prevent police ``from stopping, frisking, questioning and detaining'' black men in the search for the so-called center city stalker
the suit, filed on behalf of two men, charges that several hundred men were questioned without probable cause
attorneys for the aclu and deputy city soliciter ralph teti met thursday with u.s. district judge james mcgirr kelly, who approved the agreement
aclu legal director stefan presser said: ``we do believe that a large number of people were illegally detained and we will now pursue the question of damages.''
teti could not be reached for comment thursday night
earlier in the day, the police commissioner defended the conduct of the police
obviously, our feeling is we have a composite (sketch) and we feel we're following proper guidelines,'' tucker said. ``if the courts think we're doing things differently, then we will abide by their ruling.''
the center city stalker has generally approached victims leaving an elevator an empty hall. with a gun, he has directed victims into an empty room, robbed them, tied their hands hands and ankles and sexually assaulted them
the attacks have created fear among women in downtown office buildings, leading to an increase in the sale of chemical mace
in 1985, police questioned 125 hispanics after a police officer was shot to death in his patrol car in an hispanic neighborhood
a federal judge ordered the department to stop the ``disgraceful activities'' and ``unlawful conduct'' in rounding up hispanics indiscriminately, and the city later agreed to a monetary settlement
women who smoke half a pack of cigarettes a day are twice as likely to have a stroke as women who have never smoked and those who smoke two packs a day have six times the risk of a stroke, researchers say
their study, presented thursday at a meeting of the american heart association, is the first to show a conclusive link between smoking and strokes in women, said the study's principal author, dr. graham colditz of the harvard university school of medicine in boston
taken in conjunction with the results for men, this clearly implicates cigarette smoking as a risk factor for strokes in women,'' colditz said
before 1984 smoking was not considered a risk factor for strokes in men or women. in 1984, however, the american heart association listed cigarette smoking as a possible risk factor for strokes
little has been known about the effect of smoking on strokes in women, however. earlier less definitive studies had suggested it increased the risk, some had found no effect and one had found that smoking decreased the risk, colditz said
heart disease and stroke have been studied less extensively in women than in men, possibly because those diseases are less common in women than men. but heart disease and stroke, taken together, are the leading cause of death in women _ as they are in men
the heart association estimates that 500,000 americans have strokes each year. in 1985, the latest year for which figures are available, 152,700 americans died from strokes
colditz said his results are more convincing than those of previous studies largely because of the number of subjects in his study _ almost 120,000. they are nurses who were recruited in 1976 for a huge study attempting to correlate various aspects of diet, health, family history and such things as height and weight with the occurrence of disease
in a separate finding reported thursday, analysis of the nurses' drinking habits showed that even modest amounts of alcohol can lower the risk of coronary heart disease, marked by clogging of the coronary arteries that supply blood to the heart
this effect has been observed in men, but it has not been as thoroughly studied in women
a couple of drinks a week is enough to lower the risk,'' colditz said
meir stampfer of harvard, the principal author of the alcohol study, said analysis of the alcohol intake of 87,566 of the nurses showed that as little as two drinks a week could lower the risk of coronary heart disease by 40 percent
there is a catch, however. alcohol has been shown to raise the incidence of cancer _ and that effect begins to occur with the consumption of three drinks a week, colditz said
most authorities believe that the question of alcohol's effect on health has not been answered well enough yet for them to recommend that people drink moderately
alcohol's hazards are well known, and public health officials worry that some people might conclude, for example, that if two drinks are good, four drinks are better
the army's 15,000-soldier 82nd airborne division is a troubleshooting unit for handling hot spots around the world
the division is used as kind of a fire department _ a unit that can move quickly into an emergency, bring with it the tools and techniques to put out fires and restore order,'' military writer hans halberstabt said in his 1988 book, ``airborne: assault from the sky.''
here's a brief history of the 82nd airborne division:
_ 1917: the 82nd is activated at camp gordon, ga., but discontinued in 1919
_ 1942: the 82nd is reactivated under gen. omar bradley at camp claiborne, la. the first airborne unit is trained here in preparation for combat. all five combat airborne divisions, the 82nd, 101st, 11th, 13th and 17th, are trained in the fort bragg-camp mccall area
_ 1943: the division is deployed to north africa
_ july 9, 1943: paratroopers from the 82nd airborne division make their first jump in sicily
_ june 6, 1944: paratroopers from the division, along with the 101st division, lead the charge in the invasion at normandy
_ 1944: the 82nd paratroopers participate in the battle of the bulge
_ 1945: division ordered to berlin for occupation duty
_ 1946: 82nd returns to the united states and is assigned to fort bragg, n.c
_ 1965: division deployed to santa domingo in the dominican republic to evacuate americans
_ 1968-1970: division's 3rd brigade sent to vietnam
_ 1983: two brigades of 82nd airborne division sent to grenada to rescue american medical students
the deadly earthquake that shook the los angeles area in october led scientists to accept a theory that says the region is more prone to damaging jolts than once believed
a study of the quake, published today in the journal science, concludes buried faults hidden by folds in earth's crust present ``additional potential earthquake hazards to the los angeles metropolitan area.''
the theory by consulting geologist thom davis was publicized in november when scientists met to discuss the oct. 1 whittier narrows quake, which measured 5.9 on the richter scale. with its aftershocks, it caused eight deaths, more than 200 injuries and $358 million in damage
the new study, in which 17 scientists joined davis as co-authors, says the hidden fault system running directly under dodger stadium and downtown los angeles is ``capable of generating moderate-sized destructive earthquakes.''
we all sort of knew in the back of our minds that there had to be (hidden) faults there, but the whittier narrows earthquake kind of brought it home,'' said the study's chief author, university of southern california seismologist egill hauksson
now we can no longer ignore the geologists like thom davis who said these (faults) extend along the whole northern edge of the (los angeles) basin,'' he said
the study's co-authors include researchers from the u.s. geological survey, usc, the california institute of technology and the california division of mines and geology
while davis quietly studied the hidden fault hazard, ``nobody else was even thinking about the problem'' because they focused on the seismic threat from known, visible faults, said usgs seismologist lucile jones, a co-author of the study and hauksson's wife
when the (whittier narrows) earthquake occurred on exactly the kind of fault he said should be there, we listened more closely,'' she said. ``the idea that a system of faults capable of earthquakes underlies the northern los angeles basin is becoming generally accepted.''
hauksson said the whittier narrows quake was small compared with quakes that might be generated if the hidden faults are interconnected and rupture at once. if that happens, ``we're going to have a much bigger disaster on our hands,'' he said
such a quake could measure up to 7.5 on the richter scale of ground motion, jones said. previous studies have shown a magnitude-6.5 in los angeles would be more damaging than an 8-magnitude ``great'' quake on the more distant san andreas fault. officials have said a great quake on the southern san andreas could kill up to 14,000 people and cause $17 billion in damage
jones said the hidden system of faults runs west to east from the santa monica mountains above malibu through the beverly and hollywood hills to dodger stadium and downtown los angeles and then toward the whittier area
richard andrews, the california office of emergency services' assistant director for southern california, said the california earthquake prediction evaluation council met march 11 in los angeles to discuss the study in science
the council was unable to make any recommendations on how the added hazard should be incorporated into emergency plans, because not enough is known about how often such quakes will occur or how strong they will be, andrews said
prince charles and eight other members of britain's royal family attended a funeral service for charles' friend, maj. hugh lindsay, who died in an avalanche that narrowly missed the prince
the 39-year-old heir to the throne read a eulogy in a steady voice during the service thursday at the royal memorial chapel on the grounds of the royal military academy in sandhurst, west of london
among the mourners were lindsay's widow, sarah, who is six months pregnant with their first child
the 34-year-old career army officer and former aide to queen elizabeth ii was skiing with charles off the main trail at klosters in the swiss alps on march 10 when an avalanche struck
charles and other members of the party skied clear and escaped injury, but lindsay and another friend, patti palmer-tomkinson, were swept away. mrs. palmer-tomkinson survived with broken legs and lung injuries
jazz trumpeter miles davis had to cancel concert tour stops in chicago, detroit and overseas after being hospitalized for treatment of a leg infection, his publicist said
davis, 62, entered a new york city hospital, whose name was not disclosed, on march 3 and was expected to remain under treatment three more weeks, terrie williams said thursday
davis injured the leg in france, second stop on a tour that began in italy. dates in chicago and detroit and in hawaii, new zealand and australia have been canceled, williams said
davis' condition was unrelated to a hip implant he received after a car accident in 1975, she said
gov. john mckernan jr. has become a hunted man
dozens of amateur photographers have flocked to the governor's mansion here hoping to get a shot of mckernan walking to his office at the capitol as part of a scavenger hunt being sponsored by radio station wmme-fm
the photograph of maine's chief executive on the hoof is one of several items needed to win the $1,000 prize in ``the wild moose hunt.'' others include a losing state lottery ticket, 92 signatures from 92 different people and an air-sickness bag from an airline
some shutterbugs have waited up to two hours for the governor to appear since the contest was announced tuesday. about 150 people showed up thursday
it wasn't our idea to have a picture in the scavenger hunt to include me, i can tell you that,'' said mckernan, who slipped out of the house 20 minutes early one day, prompting 15 late-comers to march to his office and ask for an impromptu walk
by that time, however, he had already left town for the day, his press secretary said
the scavenger hunt ends saturday, but the governor's office announced he would give contestants one more chance to snap his picture between 7:40 a.m. and 8 a.m. today
