drummer archie francis won his 11th trophy, and fiddler johnny gimble and steel guitarist j.d. maness each won their 10th trophies to lead other winners in ballots cast by the 2,500-member academy
the winners were announced thursday by academy executive director bill boyd; trophies will be presented during the 23rd annual academy of country music awards on monday in buena park
david hungate tied gordy in the bass category, ronnie milsap tied hobbs in the keyboard category, and ricky skaggs, who plays mandolin, tied with jerry douglas, who plays the dobro, in the specialty instrument category. with nixon reax; picks up 5th graf pvs bgng, `nixon was'</note>
the chairman of the house judiciary committee and two other lawmakers thursday introduced a resolution to impeach convicted federal judge walter l. nixon jr. of mississippi
judiciary chairman peter w. rodino jr., d-n.j., acted just two days after receiving a recommendation from the judicial conference, the governing body for federal judges
the conference certified to the house that nixon had engaged in conduct which might constitute grounds for impeachment. judges are appointed for life, and can only be removed by congress in an impeachment proceeding
the house votes for impeachment articles, similar to an indictment, and the senate then conducts a trial
my family and i are very upset at this time,'' nixon said in a telephone interview from his home in ocean springs, miss. ``beyond that, i have no further comment. any other comments i may have must come through my attorney.''
nixon was convicted in february 1986 of two counts of perjury before a federal grand jury. he had been acquitted of bribery charges by a federal jury regarding his business relationship with wiley fairchild, a wealthy investor who sold three oil well properties to nixon in 1980 at bargain prices
but the grand jury convicted him of lying when he denied discussing drug charges against fairchild's son with the elder fairchild and with a mississippi prosecutor
the supreme court last jan. 19 refused to review the conviction. nixon is scheduled to go to prison next wednesday
nixon, the chief judge for the southern district of mississippi, said on jan. 20 he would not resign. he stopped hearing cases after he was indicted, but continues to draw his annual judicial salary of $89,500
sponsoring the resolution in addition to rodino were reps. don edwards, d-calif., chairman of the judiciary subcommittee on civil rights; hamilton fish of new york, ranking republican on the full committee; and rep. f. james sensenbrenner jr., r-wis
rodino said, ``in view of the fact that judge nixon has been convicted of a serioius federal crime, and his direct judicial appeals have been exhausted, it becomes incumbent upon the house of representatives to initiate impeachment proceedings.''
the last impeachment was about 18 months ago, when the senate convicted and removed u.s. district judge harry e. claiborne of nevada
illegal aliens are depressing wages and worsening working conditions for legal immigrants and native americans in low-skilled and low-wage jobs, the general accounting office says in a new report
citing empirical data and several case studies, the congressional watchdog agency said both u.s.-born and legally documented immigrants are being hurt, especially those working as janitors and farm and food processing workers
the report identified restaurants and companies producing auto parts, shoes and clothing as others that often employ illegal aliens
the willingness of illegal aliens to work in low-skill jobs for less than the minimum wage in those industries has depressed wages and benefits for comparable native and legal immigrant workers, the gao said
but it also concluded that the low wages paid to illegal aliens allow some of the businesses to grow or survive foreign competition, indirectly expanding job opportunities and wages for higher-skilled workers in the same trades
without a pool of flexible illegal immigrants willing to work at sewing machines in high-fashion garment plants or as shoemakers, the gao said, many companies would shut down or move out of the country
it also said a growing practice by restaurants of using illegal immigrants as dishwashers and busboys allowed the businesses to keep their prices low and thus expand, providing more jobs for more highly skilled waiters and chefs
the labor department disagrees with those conclusions, saying none of the studies surveyed by gao offered any concrete evidence of a positive effect from using illegal workers. it said the only evidence came in comments from employers
in a formal reply to the report, the department also disputed gao's premise that legal workers won't take many of the low-wage jobs, particularly in the shoe and garment industries
the fact is that large numbers of native and legal u.s. workers are in the same labor market as illegal workers,'' the labor department said. ``furthermore, if wages were not depressed by illegal workers, even greater numbers of native and legal workers would be in that labor market.''
the gao said the 1986 immigration reform law and its fines for hiring illegal aliens, if successful, will force wages up for legal immigrants and natives and cause ``considerable stress'' financially for growers and shoe and garment manufacturers
congress asked the gao to survey all available studies and data on illegal immigrants' impact on native and legal immigrant workers in 1985, when it was weighing the employer sanctions that were adopted a year later
the gao has now finally submitted the study to congress, saying that after examining 230 academic and other treatises on the issue, it found scarce useful information. the biggest problem, the gao said, is that illegal aliens are a hidden population, making it hard to identify them for use in any empirical study
about two dozen case studies, however, suggested that employers' use of illegal aliens has displaced native workers and legal immigrants from their jobs and driven down wages of those who remain
the most dramatic examples were among janitors and farm and food processing workers in california
for example, janitors in downtown los angeles office buildings _ most of them black or legal hispanic immigrants _ had won wage and benefits reaching a peak of $12 an hour by 1983 under labor contracts negotiated by the service employees international union
however, in the 1980s a group of aggressive non-union janitorial services hiring predominantly illegal immigrants began wresting the best building contracts away from the unionized firms, driving the union scale back down to $4 an hour and below
of 2,500 black janitors working under high-wage contracts in 1977, only 100 still enjoyed comparative wages by 1985. the union still had 600 working members but 500 of them had suffered large pay cuts
similar events occurred in the southern california citrus and tomato fields, where farm labor contractors using illegal immigrants drove down wage and benefits of legal migrant crop pickers from mexico by 18 percent between 1975 and 1985
the agriculture department thinks its 40-year-old national school lunch program should have had at least a walk-on role in a forthcoming nbc television movie about hunger among children
as it is, the network's hour-long movie, ``a place at the table,'' will be broadcast the night of march 20 without mention of the school lunch program. department officials are giving the movie less than rave reviews
curt block, nbc vice president for media relations, said the purpose of the film's producers ``was to take a broader focus of the problem of hunger'' among children and to ``get across to the public how pervasive the problem is.''
block said the intent was also to show that ``there are a number of ways we can get food to children.''
assistant secretary john w. bode, who oversees school lunch and food stamp programs, said in a statement that ``despite the laudable public service aspects of the movie, it contains serious inaccuracies'' about hunger
in the movie, children are encouraged to donate their brown bag lunches to classmates who are so hungry they attend a soup kitchen after school,'' bode said. ``the film does not acknowledge the existence of the national school lunch program, which provides free school lunches to children of low-income families.''
further, he said, preschool breakfasts are also provided in schools which participate in the usda program
school lunch is only one of a number of federal food assistance programs, including food stamps, which provide more than $20 billion worth of help a year to needy americans,'' bode said. ``that figure translates into $56 million a day in food help.''
further, he said, the school lunch program is one of the largest food service providers in the country, serving more than 24 million children daily, nearly half of whom receive lunches free of charge
since 1980, the federal budget for school lunches has increased 21 percent to the current annual level of $3.4 billion, bode said
according to usda budget officers, about $3 billion in cash subsidies will go to schools to help with lunch programs in the fiscal year that began last oct. 1. an additional $400 million in surplus food commodities also is being distributed
students from families with income of less than 130 percent of the federal poverty line ($14,560 for a family of four) qualify for free meals. the usda pays a subsidy of about $1.54 per meal for those. about 10.3 million students are in that category
reduced-price meals costing no more than 40 cents are available to about 1.6 million students from families with incomes between 130 percent and 185 percent of the poverty level (between $14,560 and $20,720 for a family of four). the usda subsidy is about $1.14 per meal. about 1.64 million students participate
full prices are paid by student from families above 185 percent of poverty (those with incomes of more than $20,720 for a family of four). nearly 12.8 million children pay full prices, but those meals are also subsidized by usda at the rate of about 26 cents per meal
farmers are continuing to make a strong financial comeback from the pounding they endured in the early 1980s, according to a new agriculture department report
cash income still is expected to recede from last year's $57 billion to between $50 billion and $55 billion in 1988, the department's economic research service said thursday
the projected decline will result from lower livestock receipts, rising expenses and lower government payments, the report said. those will more than offset a rise in 1988 crop receipts
net cash income is the difference between gross cash income and cash expenses in the calendar year
the income and debt-service problems that plagued agriculture during the 1980s have largely been weathered, although financial problems persist for some producers who acquired long-term debt at high interest rates,'' the report said. ``a major contributor to increased cash flow is a marked reduction in interest expenses since the difficult 1980-83 years.''
economists said receipts from crop sales are improving as a result of increased domestic and export demand for major commodities, including wheat and corn
receipts from livestock sales should be off slightly, as red meat and poultry production expands almost 2 percent and prices falter,'' the report said. ``fruit prices this spring will be below a year ago as larger supplies come to market.''
consumers can bite into some bargains at fresh fruit counters these days, says a senior agriculture department official
j. patrick boyle, head of the department's agricultural marketing service, said large harvests of apples and winter pears have helped dampen prices. the leading variety of u.s. apple is the red delicious, and the most abundant winter pear is the anjou, he said
the agency estimated that the 1987 apple harvest was up 25 percent, while winter pear output climbed 21 percent
barring unexpected developments, consumers will continue to find apples and winter pears of excellent quality at attractive prices in their grocery stores for several more months,'' boyle said thursday
the first step in bailing out texas' largest bank holding company is raising concerns about the long-term health of the fund that insures deposits in most of the nation's commerical banks
the federal deposit insurance corp. said thursday it was loaning $1 billion to banks owned by first republicbank corp. of dallas for six months in a move to reassure depositors worried about the banks' shaky real estate loans
the infusion represents only about 5 percent of the fdic's insurance fund, which backs deposits of $100,000 and less at 13,600 banks. but bank analysts believe it could turn out to be the first big hit of a bad year for the fund
fdic chairman l. william seidman isn't saying how much he believes his agency ultimately may have to spend to rescue the $33.2 billion holding company, the largest in texas and the 13th biggest in the country
the analysts, however, are suggesting that the first republicbank loan is, in effect, a down payment on a $2 billion to $4 billion problem
first republicbank is about the same size that continental illinois corp. was in 1984 when it required the largest-ever government bank bailout of $4.5 billion
and more bad news is likely from other banks, particularly in texas, where mcorp, a $21 billion, money-losing bank holding company, has been exploring restructuring options
but seidman says the situations of continental and first republicbank are not the same and he points with hope to fdic conversations with private investors and to signs that texas' economy is rebounding
he notes his fund's survival during 1987, the worst year for commercial banking since the great depression, both in terms of low profits and the number of bank failures
despite the rescue of first city bancorporation of houston and the failure of 184 banks in 1987, the fdic fund still managed a modest increase to $18.3 billion
therefore, we don't see anything that we are going to do this year that is going to cause a substantial decline in the fund. i mean by substantial, 25 percent,'' he said
however, bert ely, an alexandria, va., financial consultant, said, ``my sense is they are going to lose money.''
the fund's income from interest and from premiums paid by member banks _ $3.3 billion last year _ is increasing at a slower rate than deposits, he said. the ratio of fdic assets to insured deposits has fallen from more than $1.20 per $100 in 1981 to close to $1.10
still, the fdic fund is in far better shape than its sister fund for the thrift industry, the federal savings and loan insurance corp. unlike fslic, the fdic probably would still be in the black after accounting for all of the problems suffered by its member institutions, ely said
industry experts are skeptical of the chances for fdic's efforts to attract private investors to take on some of the risks of operating a restructured first republicbank
i'm sure there probably are people who are kicking the tires and have expressed an interest to the fdic,'' said stephen skaggs, a senior analyst for sheshunoff &amp; co., an austin, texas, consulting firm
but i just don't see that there's any great appetite for investments (like first republicbank) unless the fdic is willing to assume substantially all of the risk.''
according to sandy flannigan, an analyst with paine webber inc. in houston, the search for private capital for first republicbank does not improve the chances for other texas banks such as mcorp to attract new investors
first city, which is getting $500 million from a private investment group in addition to the fdic money, ``was first to the well,'' she said. ``they are in far better shape than those who follow. there isn't an infinite number of investors interested in texas banks.''
ironically, the deepening bank crisis comes amid signs that texas' economy is improving
the whole thing is just a very sad situation,'' said paul getman, senior financial economist of the wefa group, a philadelphia-area consulting firm. ``just when people thought the situation in texas might turn around, it has in fact worsened. ... the overall economic situation ... has picked up a bit, it has just not improved fast enough to help these banks. ... it's just too little too late.''
the scary thing ... is that if right now these banks are doing so poorly with an economy that is doing fairly well nationally, what will happen to them if the national growth turns sluggish for the next few years?'' he asked
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,966.26 points, up 93.97 points, on the tokyo stock exchange friday. bombs fell in nicaraguan territory, a third in honduras. picks up 5th graf pvs, `a honduran ...</note>
two unidentified jets from honduras roared into nicaraguan territory on thursday and dropped bombs near a sandinista military encampment along the border
two bombs fell in nicaragua and a third landed across the coco river in honduran territory, sandinista officers said. there was no damage or injuries
the raid came a day after honduras accused nicaragua of sending thousands of soldiers across the border in pursuit of u.s.-supported contra rebels
a honduran armed forces spokesman in tegucigalpa, the honduran capital, said the bombs were aimed at sandinista forces that crossed into the neighboring country. he denied the planes entered nicaraguan airspace
more than 3,000 american soldiers began arriving in honduras in a show of support thursday. ortega declared his army ready to ``combat and liquidate'' the americans and said his soldiers will not withdraw from the border region
nicaragua has committed an estimated 6,000 soldiers to an anti-rebel operation in an area running from the central region to the border, with most at the frontier
about 25 reporters, most of them americans, watched as the jets roared into nicaragua at about noon thursday. the journalists dived for cover but were not hurt as the bombs exploded as close as 70 yards away
the leftist sandinista government flew the journalists to the region for a briefing on its offensive against the u.s.-supported contra rebels
none of the five soviet-made helicopters used in the area for movement of troops or evacuation were hit by the bombs. in washington, sources who spoke on condition of anonymity claimed that one soviet-made helicopter on the ground had been damaged. the soviet union supplies the sandinistas with military hardware and training
the sandinistas opened fire at the planes with anti-aircraft guns but apparently did not hit either of them
some military officials in nicaragua described the planes as french-made mysteres, while others said they were u.s.-made f-5s. the honduran air force has both
a u.s. official in washington said two u.s.-built f-5s and four super-mystere attack jets of the honduran air force carried out the raid
this was totally a honduran operation,'' the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity
upon hearing of the raid, ortega abruptly left a meeting with opposition politicians called to discuss their differences with the government. a presidential source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said ortega held an urgent meeting with his military chiefs
later, foreign minister miguel d'escoto said he had sent a diplomatic note to secretary of state george p. shultz ``formally and energetically protesting'' the attack, which he blamed on the united states
the government voice of nicaragua radio also said thursday that unidentified planes from honduras buzzed corinto, nicaragua's main port, and anti-aircraft batteries fired on them
the broadcast gave no details. corinto is on the pacific, about 70 miles northwest of managua
honduras has one of central america's smallest armies and relies on air superiority for defense. it and mexico are the only nations in the region with jet fighters
ortega called the dispatch of u.s. troops to honduras ``one more escalation of the war against nicaragua.'' at nicaragua's request, the u.n. security council will meet in urgent session friday on the nicaraguan-honduran border crisis and on the dispatch of u.s. troops to honduras
in managua, ortega said: ``we logically are going to maintain our offensive. ... we are not going to withdraw our troops now that we have recovered our territory
we are ready to combat and liquidate the famous forces of the 82nd airborne division.''
earlier, a foreign ministry spokesman said nicaragua already had begun withdrawing troops from the border region after driving about 2,000 contra rebels back into honduras
the operations have succesfully been concluded, and we don't plan to stay along the border region,'' the spokesman, alejandro bendana, said on nbc's ``today'' show
the 3,200 u.s. soldiers who began arriving in honduras on thursday include two battalions from the 82nd airborne at fort bragg, n.c
ortega accused the united states of pressuring honduras into asking for the american presence
the c-141 planes carrying the u.s. troops were arriving every 30 minutes at palmerola air force base, the main center of u.s. military operations in honduras. the base is about 125 miles west of the border, where heavy fighting was reported wednesday
bendana denied u.s. and honduran allegations that sandinista troops entered honduras. ortega himself wouldn't say if sandinista troops crossed the border
but honduran military officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said about 4,000 honduran soldiers were surrounding about 2,000 nicaraguan soldiers thursday. the sources said the entire honduran military was on alert
ortega told reporters the nicaraguan ``invasion only exists in the warped imagination of the north american leaders.''
we demand that the united states withdraw its troops from honduras immediately and, with this, contribute to the meeting that is going to be held in sapoa march 21 having positive results,'' he said
government and contra representatives are scheduled to begin three days of peace talks monday in sapoa, a town in southern nicaragua near the border with costa rica
ortega said the united states would use the current situation to give the contras logistical and military aid not approved by congress
u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar called for restraint in the conflict but had not decided whether to send in an observer team. to clarify where bombs fell. picks up 6th graf pvs, `the journalists ....' deletes first reference to carrion in 12th graf pvs `lt. col javier...'</note>
nicaraguan officials apparently wanted to show reporters how quiet this jungle-covered border region was when they flew them here thursday, following a major offensive against contra rebels
but as officials were briefing about 25 journalists at a military base, two unidentified jet planes from honduras roared into nicaraguan territory and dropped bombs along the border
the reporters dived into the dirt for cover. no one was hurt
some military officials in nicaragua described the planes as french-made mysteres, while others said they were u.s.-made f-5s. the honduran air force has both
the bombs landed along the coco river, which marks the border between the two countries. puffs of black smoke curled over the banana trees
lt. col. javier carrion, the deputy chief of the sandinista army's general staff, said two bombs landed in nicaraguan territory and one in honduras
the journalists' briefing came after reagan administration officials had claimed that nicaraguan troops had penetrated honduran territory in pursuit of the u.s.-backed rebels. nicaragua and honduras share a long, ill defined border
as the jets roared in thursday, drowning out the lapping of the slow-moving river and the chirping of crickets, journalists and soldiers threw themselves against the earth
some of the bombs exploded about 70 yards away from where they lay
maj. rosa pasos, the defense ministry spokeswoman, lost her eyeglasses in the weeds but quickly found them. she wore an american-made uniform that had apparently been taken from a contra rebel
the sandinistas opened fire at the planes with anti-aircraft guns. they apparently didn't hit either of them
none of the five soviet-made helicopters used in this area 175 miles from managua was hit. in washington, sources who spoke on condition of anonymity claimed that one soviet-made helicopter on the ground had been damaged. the soviet union supplies the sandinistas with military hardware and training
carrion, who had been conducting the offensive against the contras, said that jets had buzzed the coco river earlier in the day
asked whether sandinista troops had crossed the border in their offensive, carrion replied, ``well, no.''
there are sectors in the mountains here where you can get lost. it's easy to confuse the topography.''
however, carrion displayed a map showing where sandinista troops had destroyed contra camps along a six-mile route on both sides of the coco river
thursday's attack came hours after 3,200 american troops arrived in honduras in a show of force
nicaraguan officers said the air attack appeared to be aimed at harassing the sandinistas
senators are pressing the reagan administration with a host of worries about how plywood, potatoes and other home-state products would fare under the u.s. and canadian agreement to phase out tariffs
the outpouring of concern came thursday at a senate finance committee session with treasury secretary james a. baker iii and u.s. trade representative clayton k. yeutter
dropping potato tariffs under the plan will magnify the importance of canadian potato subsidies and a canadian ban on maine potatoes, declared sen. george j. mitchell, d-maine
will you gentlemen explain to me and maine potato farmers why this agreement is good for them?'' mitchell said
before i fully support a free-trade agreement, i must make sure that it will not hurt coal,'' said sen. jay rockefeller, d-w.va
we're being moved out of their markets'' even without the agreement, said sen. david durenberger, r-minn. ``and it is wheat, and it is potatoes and it is corn.''
sen. donald w. riegle jr., d-mich., said that of the nation's $13 billion trade deficit with canada last year ``nearly half of that is in auto and truck activity.''
i must say to you that i have very serious reservations about that section of the treaty,'' riegle said
finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen, d-texas, told the administration officials that they must not merely dismiss the questions as narrow concerns that skirt the big picture
baker declared that the agreement ``is in the national economic interest or we wouldn't have sent it up here for approval.''
it is unlikely that we'll ever negotiate a utopian agreement,'' yeutter said
sen. bob packwood, r-ore., called for approval of the u.s.-canada treaty, but he expressed concern that canada already has violated the agreement by failing to retest u.s. plywood that canada says cracks in extreme cold
they're used in nome, they're used on the north slope (in alaska),'' he said. ``they don't crack where they're used.''
and bentsen expressed impatience when yeutter said energy provisions of the agreement will be valuable to the united states ``in the long run.''
the oil-state senator, who has been concerned about sagging petroleum prices, replied that ``in the long run we'll all be dead.''
i'm concerned about what's happening while we're all still around here,'' bentsen said. ``i have a state that's in a depression.''
with some of the most expensive campaign states coming up, the presidential candidates are pressing fund-raising appeals anew and only george bush is out of the financial woods
after costly excursions into the 20 super tuesday states on march 8, the candidates now face money-draining states like new york, pennsylvania, california and ohio
bush has almost finished raising as much money as he can legally spend, and still has more than $4 million available to spend at this time, a spokeswoman said. gop rival pat robertson has spent nearly to the $27 million limit and has to dramatically scale back his campaign
among democrats, sen. paul simon of illinois and rep. richard gephardt of missouri both are looking for enough cash to keep their campaigns afloat beyond caucuses on march 26 in michigan and primaries march 29 in connecticut and april 5 in wisconsin
the democratic money leader, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, has an active april fund-raising schedule, and remains in good financial shape, his campaign said
democrat jesse jackson, whose fund-raising has trailed that of opponents, has been picking up money through an aggressive mail program, and will appeal for money in california this weekend
sen. albert gore jr.'s campaign is ``in the black'' and has ``a sufficient amount of money to do what we need to do,'' said spokesman arlie schardt
we're in good solid shape,'' schardt said, but declined to give any specifics. gore borrowed heavily for pre-super tuesday tv ads
bush plans to shut down his fund-raising operation by the end of april, after a handful of high-ticket dinners and one final mailing to his faithful contributors, said campaign treasurer fred bush, who is no relation to the candidate
at that point bush will have raised the $27 million, plus another $2 million or so for legal and accounting costs, which are exempt from the limit. however, he has not spent the limit, so he can continue campaigning
as bush continues the road to all-but-certain nomination this summer, people are flocking to give him money and two dozen had to be refused tickets to a $1,000-a-person dinner at a private home this week, the treasurer said
robertson is in a different situation, having spent nearly the limit. he says he will rely heavily on volunteer efforts to see him through the rest of the campaign
sen. bob dole's spokeswoman, dale tate, said the kansas republican's poor showing on super tuesday and in illinois did not result in a dramatic decrease of contributions, although, ``we're not bathing in dollars.''
conversely, contributors have been calling to urge dole to stay in the race, she said
on friday, callers pledged $140,000, on monday $95,000 and on tuesday $60,000, she said, adding, ``these are republicans saying we think there should be a race.''
dukakis spokesman mark gearan said the campaign raised $100,000 wednesday night in new york, and is getting financial mileage out of the candidate's strong super tuesday showing
dukakis has about $1.5 million in the bank, not counting the more than $600,000 he got this week in federal matching funds, said spokesman leslie dach
simon and gephardt, who face uphill struggles in fund-raising after their poor super tuesday showings, both said they are out of debt at this point
both also said they had record fund-raising months in february _ gephardt collecting $1.2 million and simon more than $900,000
and gephardt spokesman mark johnson said, ``it's a day-to-day thing.'' he said the campaign was aggressively seeking money, and gephardt was putting in personal calls to contributors
gephardt is targeting michigan for a heavy advertising campaign, but johnson said he has no idea whether any loans will be taken out
simon spokesman david carle said the campaign, which has scaled back its payroll and operations, had around $300,000 in cash on hand
simon collected about $60,000 at a chicago event monday night, and expected to bring in another $25,000 thursday night in new york, he said
a mailing to simon's 50,000 contributors will go out next week, and unsolicited donations came in following simon's victory in his home state of illinois, carle said. he declined to give specific figures
simon will strongly contest wisconsin with a large television campaign, but will not buy ads in michigan, he said
traffic fatalities in the united states last year were the ``lowest in history'' based on miles driven, according to the department of transportation
the department reported on thursday that fatalities dropped significantly in 1987 and attributed the decline to increasing use of seat belts and a reduction in drunken driving
the department said its characterization of the 1987 fatality rate as the lowest in history used as a yardstick the number of deaths per 100 million miles of travel. for 1987 that figure was 2.4 deaths. the highest number was the 24.08 deaths per 100 million miles in 1921, the first year the calculation was made
the department's national highway traffic safety administration also released figures estimating that 8,035 lives were saved and 95,500 injuries prevented by seat belts since 1983
the rate of deaths per 100 million miles of travel dropped from 2.5 in 1986 and 3.3 in 1980. about 40 percent of the fatalities last year involved drunken driving, a drop from the 46 percent three years earlier
the department said 32 states and the district of columbia have mandatory seat belt laws and estimated 1,350 lives were saved in 1987 alone because of the laws in effect
an avianca jetliner smashed into a mountain minutes after takeoff, triggered a landslide and burst into flames, killing all 137 people aboard, officials and witnesses said
among the 131 passengers were a roman catholic auxiliary bishop and more than 30 soccer players, officials said. there were no americans aboard, they said
the boeing 727 clipped trees before hitting the snow-covered mountain 50 miles away near zulia, witnesses said
the craft took off in heavy fog at 1:16 p.m. thursday from cucuta, 250 miles northeast of bogota, on a domestic flight to the caribbean port of barranquilla
rescue workers who reached the wreckage thursday night said there were no survivors, col. miguel benedetti, civil defense director for the state of north santander, said in a interview by radio-telephone from zulia
the impact of the plane against the mountain was so violent that it caused a landslide which buried part of the aircraft,'' said benedetti
work crews, some using helicopters, were to return to the crash site today, said col. edgar lozano, spokesman for the civil aeronautics agency. rain, snow and rough terrain hampered rescue efforts thursday
airport officials lost radio contact with the plane four minutes after it took off, although no problems had been reported up to that point, said lozano
lozano said the plane apparently was unable to get enough altitude to fly over the 8,000-foot mountain
zulia police said three witnesses reported that the plane clipped some trees, then slammed into the mountain and burst into flames
we heard a tremendous noise ... and ran toward the mountain where we saw the ruins of the plane,'' said victor pineda villamizar, a schoolteacher, in an interview with the radio network rcn
he said local rescuers could not reach the crash site because of the rough terrain
avianca and the government air agency reported the plane was carrying 131 passengers and six crew members. they both had had given different numbers earlier
the agency said the passenger list included monsignor horacio olave velandia, 44, who was named auxiliary bishop of tibu in february, and at least 31 soccer players from two teams who were flying to a tournament in cartagena
the soccer teams were affiliated with the state petroleum company ecopetrol
colombia's last major air crash occurred july 27, 1985, when an air force transport plane went down in the amazon jungle, killing 74 people. the military plane was carrying civilian passengers because of an airline strike
peace talks scheduled to begin monday between the contra rebels and the nicaraguan government are off unless sandinista troops withdraw from honduras, a contra leader says
if this situation does not take a radical turn, we will not attend,'' aristides sanchez, a member of the five-person directorate of the nicaraguan resistance, said thursday. the group has its headquarters in miami
sanchez said the contras would attend the meeting only if the sandinistas withdraw at once from honduras. ``there could be changes in the next four days, but i doubt they will be positive,'' he said
nicaraguan government officials maintain their troops didn't advance into honduras, but the reagan administration claims they did and dispatched 3,200 american soldiers to honduras because of their presence
the sandinista government of daniel ortega and contra representatives are scheduled to begin three days of talks monday in sapoa, a town in southern nicaragua near the border with costa rica
if monday's meeting is held, it will be the first on nicaraguan soil between the two sides
a contra spokeswoman in miami said intense fighting continued thursday with 2,000 sandinista troops still in honduras
the intention of the sandinistas was to weaken our position at the negotiating table,'' marta sacasa said. ``it's also timed to coincide with the end of united states aid.''
preliminary reports indicated 10 contra rebels were killed and 56 wounded in the sandinista offensive, she said
they have been able to overrun certain of our positions and we have had to disperse,'' ms. sacasa said. ``we're trying to avoid a frontal engagement and rely on guerrilla tactics.''
contra leaders had no comment on the american troops airlifted to honduras in a show of support for the central american nation, ms. sacasa said
the united states troops did not go to honduras to involve themselves with the fighting in any way, so we have no comment,'' she said. 2nd graf pvs bgng, ``the opening jump...</note>
the u.s. dollar rose sharply and stock prices continued to rally friday as traders in tokyo reacted to favorable economic reports
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues finished the day's trading at 25,966.26 points, up 93.97 points, or 0.36 percent, from thusday's closing figure
the dollar closed at 128.35 yen, up 0.92 yen from thursday's close, but down from its 128.65-yen opening
the opening jump was in reaction to sharp rises in the dollar recorded on the new york and london markets due to the u.s. trade figures,'' said a foreign exchange dealer, who requested anonymity, with a major bank
another dealer, who also asked not to be named, said the dollar later receded because of selling pressure from exporters and insurance companies
figures released thursday in washington by the u.s. commerce department indicated the u.s. trade deficit for january rose to $12.44 billion from $12.2 billion the previous month. but although the gap widened by 1.9 percent, imports to the united states declined by 6 percent during the month
improvements in the u.s. trade deficit reduce the pressure for a weaker dollar, which has been a key weapon in the reagan administration's attempts to narrow the imbalance
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average index of 225 selected issues closed the morning session at 25,911.10 points, up 38.81 from thursday's close. volume in the first section was estimated at 750 million shares
the early gains on the nikkei average followed three consecutive closing rallies that brought the index to a level higher than that just prior to the october crash
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir urged american jews to close ranks behind israel as it tries to quell riots by palestinians in the occupied territories of the west bank and the gaza strip
when unity breaks down, then our enemies exploit every critical statement to their own end,'' shamir said to enthusiastic applause from 1,600 american jews at a fund-raising banquet on thursday
he apparently referred to criticism by some jews of the israeli army's use of beatings and live ammunition to quell riots in the occupied territories. at least 100 palestinians have been killed in more than three months of violence
shamir also warned israel's supporters not to compare the palestinian protests to a civil rights struggle
these are not passive civil rights marches. these are another expression of the arab refusal to accept israel, to coexist with us, and to recognize that israel is a permanent feature in the region,'' shamir said
if there were some excesses, they were isolated cases that were blown way out of proportion by the media,'' he added
those attending the $60-a-plate benefit at the century plaza hotel agreed to pledge at least $1,000 to either the united jewish fund or israel bonds during the coming year
earlier thursday, at a ceremony dedicating a cornerstone for a museum commemorating the holocaust, shamir told about 1,500 people that americans and europeans may wrongly interpret the arab rebellion
they cry, `palestine is arab,' and openly declare that all of palestine is theirs,'' he said
shamir also was scheduled to address a luncheon meeting today of the los angeles world affairs council. he is scheduled to leave los angeles on saturday evening
the prime minister, fresh from his meeting with president reagan, secretary of state george p. shultz, and congressional leaders in washington, reiterated his opposition to an american plan for peace in the middle east that calls for an international conference
president reagan toasted ``seamus wright'' among other adversaries during a capitol hill luncheon after paying a surprise visit to a tavern in a celebration of st. patrick's day
standing thursday at a table covered with a green cloth and decorated with green carnations, the president wished house speaker jim wright ``warm words on a cold evening and a full moon on a dark night.''
wright, who wore a green jacket and green tie, declared that ``we've buried all differences that might exist between political parties and branches of government on this day of st. patrick.'' he toasted reagan, 77, for his youthfulness
wright's great-grandmother, grace hannington, emigrated from county dungannon, ireland, in 1837. the irish for james is seamus
reagan traces his irish roots to his great-great-grandfather, michael o'regan, who left county tipperary during the potato famine of the 1840s
before he arrived at the capitol, reagan paid a surprise visit to ireland's own, a noisy pub in suburban alexandria, va., where he sipped beer and sampled corned beef and cabbage with columnist james j. kilpatrick
the president, a moderate drinker, left most of the beer in his glass, but joined the tavern crowd in singing ``when irish eyes are smiling,'' and clapping to guitar and fiddle music
reagan, who like most presidents is seldom seen handling money, reached in his pocket for some currency and paid his own check when he left
on a more serious note, reagan issued a statement urging concerned americans to refuse financial or moral support to irish terrorists
northern ireland continues to suffer from senseless violence, which tragically we have seen repeated in recent days, and high unemployment,'' he said
we can best address these problems by supporting those who seek peaceful settlements to disputes, and rejecting those who seek solutions through terror.''
meantime, members of congress commemorating st. patrick's day said britain's refusal to prosecute certain cases of criminal conduct by its forces in northern ireland is ``intolerable'' and tarnishes britain's international reputation
we call on the british government to prosecute any member of the security forces who has engaged in criminal conduct in northern ireland,'' said a statement issued by friends of ireland in congress, a 160-member bipartisan group
it is intolerable not to pursue and bring to justice individuals known to have perverted justice.''
the statement did not mention a recent string of violent incidents that started march 6 when british troops in gibraltar killed three unarmed irish republican army guerrillas who allegedly were on a bombing mission
another congressional group, the ad hoc congressional committee for irish affairs, which includes 41 house and senate members from both parties, called for a new investigation of the royal ulster constabulary, the british police force in northern ireland
both groups urged britain to enact laws to help stop discrimination against the roman catholic minority in northern ireland that has resulted in jobless rates of more than 50 percent among catholic men in some areas
three democratic presidential hopefuls _ who also are the leaders in the national delegate race _ were campaigning in kansas, which holds county caucuses on saturday
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and jesse jackson were campaigning today in the state, a day after a foray by tennessee sen. albert gore jr
at saturday's caucuses, local delegates will be elected to district conventions april 23 and the state convention may 2. at the district and state conventions, 39 of kansas' 43 national delegates to the democratic convention in atlanta in july will be elected
the candidates who win the most local delegates saturday will claim the national delegates at the later conventions. four state party leaders automatically are national delegates
gore, the first of the democratic contenders to come to kansas ahead of the caucuses, scored something of a coup thursday when he was invited to address the state house of representatives and gained a qualified endorsement from state democratic party chairman jim parrish
dukakis was speaking at a rally in the capitol rotunda today, then holding a statehouse news conference. jackson scheduled a speech at washburn university and another at wichita state university
missouri rep. richard gephardt has the support of kansas' two democratic u.s. house members, dan glickman and jim slattery, but has not campaigned here in advance of the caucuses. illinois sen. paul simon, who is strapped for cash and concentrating on races in michigan and wisconsin, made little effort here
there are two ways, perhaps more, of looking at the results of president reagan's six-year effort in support of the contra rebels
in the administration's view, the contras have kept the focus of nicaragua's leftist government on surviving, preventing it from promoting the spread of revolution elsewhere
as a result, the administration says, each of nicaragua's neighbors has been able consolidate or at least make a beginning on building democratic institutions
reagan's worst-case scenario for the region _ a belt of pro-soviet states extending from the panama canal to guatemala with the possibility that mexico itself ultimately will be threatened _ has not been borne out. he believes the contras deserve much of the credit
but the other view is that the costs of the policy have been exorbitant, far outweighing the benefits
administration critics maintain that american backing for the contras has led to tens of thousands of dead and wounded and set back the nicaraguan economy by a generation
and nicaragua has been, in some ways, a wrecker of reputations, playing the same role that vietnam did two decades ago
on wednesday, the same day that reagan decided to send u.s. troops to honduras, a federal grand jury indicted former national security adviser john m. poindexter, lt. col. oliver l. north and two of their associates, richard v. secord and albert hakim
as independent counsel lawrence e. walsh described it, ``the heart of the case'' against the four was their role in diverting funds from iran arms sales to the contras
poindexter and north, two of the most influential figures in government less than a year and a half ago, face the prospect of extended jail terms because they are alleged to have disregarded the law in their zeal to support the contras
the contra cause has divided american public opinion more than any other issue during reagan's presidency. no other dispute has generated more distrust and acrimony between the administration and the congress
while reagan has compared the contras with america's founding fathers, sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., calls them ``our terrorists.'' both sides believe the other's policies will lead inevitably to an american troop commitment in the region
the u.s. policy has fluctuated over the years. the contras took up arms with american encouragement but now live month to month without knowing whether they can count on continued u.s. backing
their latest setback had its origins in the feb. 29 cutoff of u.s. aid. within days, the sandinistas began preparations for an offensive against a rebel concentration in the bocay valley near the honduran border
as described by bosco matamoros, a contra spokesman, the rebels were left virtually without food and other supplies and the means to evacuate their wounded. the sandinistas, whose offensive got under way in earnest on tuesday, claim the contra death toll is in the hundreds
reagan administration officials say that if the sandinistas succeed in destroying a key supply depot in the area, the impact on the remaining 10,000 or so contras deployed elsewhere in nicaragua could be decisive, both materially and psychologically
administration critics say none of this would have happened if reagan had not been so foolish as to believe the contras could have prevailed against the sandinistas in the first place or to think that such a small, poor country could represent any threat at all to u.s. security
the administration counters that congress is to blame, and that reliable u.s. support for the contras would have eventually produced a sandinista surrender, ushering in peace and democracy in central america
the administration's problem all along has been that it can't prove its worst-case scenario, unless it happens
if indeed the collapse of the contras leads to the communization of central america and a new security situation for the united states, reagan will have been proven correct
but if that day ever comes, reagan will be long gone and a successor administration will have to deal with the consequences

editor's note _ george gedda has covered foreign affairs for the associated press since 1968
colorado's roy romer is ready for a brokered democratic convention: ``i'm going! i'd like to have a voice.'' but arkansas' bill clinton is not so sure about a deadlocked meeting in atlanta, as the democratic governors worry about their party's still unresolved presidential battle
it depends entirely on how all the major players conduct themselves,'' said clinton, who considered entering the 1988 race himself. ``if it turns out to be a really divisive fight waged in front of the entire american people on national television, it could be devastating.''
the democratic governors are major players in the 1988 democratic nomination battle, for they make up part of the 645 unpledged super delegates to the atlanta convention in july
with the democratic race still confused and lacking a clear front-runner after a month of primaries and caucuses, the governors also now take on the role of leaders who can nudge the party to unify behind one candidate or to take the race to atlanta
there will be brokering,'' new york gov. mario cuomo said thursday. ``the question is when and how. either you broker at the convention ... and the whole united states will see you in the grubby business of cutting deals. i say that's no way to do it. let's do it when they're not watching.''
one of the governors' own _ michael dukakis of massachusetts _ leads jesse jackson narrowly in the race for national convention delegates, but both are far short of a majority of those chosen
dukakis sought to widen his delegate lead thursday by working capitol hill, where he picked up several endorsements. he visited with sen. bill bradley of new jersey, who is said to be leaning toward endorsing the massachusetts governor
colorado's romer _ who recently endorsed dukakis with favorite son gary hart out of the race _ was one of the few governors who has made his choice who still likes the brokered convention idea
it is possible it wil be undecided by the time we get there and i don't think that's bad,'' he said. ``it helps in the sense it keeps the excitement going.''
romer brushed aside democratic party chairman paul kirk's suggestion that party leaders get together after the primary ends in june to unite the party behind the leading candidate at that point
wait a minute! if you have three people pretty close and one's a little bit higher than the other, i don't think you can make that decision before the convention. why do you have a convention? ... i'm going! i'd like to have a voice,'' he said
but maryland gov. donald schaefer said trying to guide one's delegation at a multiballot convention would be dangerous: ``i'm going to step in with a light toe.''
minnesota's gov. rudy perpich doesn't think a brokered convention _ where no candidate has a majority of the delegates and compromises must be sought to decide on a nominee _ would be so bad. and he does not agree with kirk's call for the party leaders to step in a month before the convention
clinton said kirk's idea might work if one of the candidate has more than 1,400 delegates at the end of the primary process _ of the 2,082 needed to win the nomination
cuomo, who is the oft-mentioned white-knight candidate to be tapped by a deadlocked convention, said the nominee must be decided in advance of atlanta
there are other people who say, `no, let's do it in the convention, in the open the way we always have historically.' we haven't always done it that way. carter didn't do it that way, mondale didn't do it that way,'' he said
both jimmy carter in 1976 and walter mondale in 1984 picked up enough delegates outside of the caucus and primary process to win the nominations
i think that's the way we ought to do it again, but i don't think my position is a particularly popular one and i'm afraid that it may come out that you'll wind up brokering at the convention,'' said cuomo
cuomo said he expected to play a part in any brokering ``just by virtue of the place i occupy as governor of the state. we're the largest state ... with a democratic governor.''
reaction to kirk's idea was varied. connecticut gov. william o'neill said that it is too early to be talking about such moves. and maryland's schaefer said circumstances in june will shape such possibilities: ``it all depends. that's a nice theory but you've got to be practical.''
hawaii gov. john waihee and vermont gov. madeleine kunin join in fearing a brokered convention, in part because both are dukakis backers
tennessee gov. ned mcwherter, a strong supporter of sen. albert gore of tennessee, said he believes gore ``is in a strong position to get the nomination by the time the convention begins,'' so brokering won't be a factor
wyoming gov. mike sullivan thinks that a brokered convention is a good possibility _ and that it is too early to judge its impact
i don't think you can answer that good or bad,'' he said. ``i think it would depend on how it was handled during the convention. it certainly is going to generate some enthusiasm that will be absent in the republican convention.''
dukakis has 464.5 delegate votes, just ahead of jackson with 460.55. gore has 354 and sen. paul simon of illinois 171.5. rep. richard gephardt of missouri has 145 delegates. a total of 272.65 are uncommitted
among the super delegates, dukakis has 42.5 votes, gephardt 21, gore, 19.8, jackson 19.55, simon 15.5 and uncommitted 237.65. says</head>
surgeon general c. everett koop says he fears the tendency of the young to believe health warnings are not intended for them could lead to the aids virus spreading among high school and college-age americans
my greatest concern is with the group aged 15 to 24,'' koop told a convention of hospital administrators thursday
officials may have a better idea of the extent of the aids virus among college students by the end of the year as more colleges go along with a centers for disease control request to conduct blind blood testing, koop said
under such procedures, already used by hospitals in about 40 cities, blood drawn for other purposes is tested for aids without the sample being identified by patient
he noted that sexually transmitted diseases in general are rising at the steepest rate in 16 years ``in spite of the tremendous educational campaign in 1987, where for the first time in history we were discussing in the print media and on television very blunt statements about aids and sexually transmitted disease.''
if there is hiv (the aids virus) out there, and we know there is, then there can't help but be some infection going on that we're not going to see until we get down the road about five years,'' he told the federation of american health systems
it can take five years or more for aids to develop after a person contracts the virus
so with teen-agers, who think that they're immortal, who always think the health message is meant for the person next to them, who have sort of a sense that risk-taking is sort of fun, we have our most difficult target group, especially with regard to heterosexual transmission.''
earlier, the federal official who oversees the medicare and medicaid government health programs for the elderly and poor told the hospital executives they have been given ``an almost impossible task: controlling physician decision-making.''
in the coming years, the challenge of cost constraint will continue unabated, but the focus will have to shift from hospital to physician payment reform,'' said dr. william l. roper, head of the health care financing administration
there is deep-seated ambivalence in america about intruding on physician decision-making,'' said roper, ``but we cannot have both physician autonomy and cost constraint.''
the republican party chairman of this u.s. commonwealth and five other people connected to the government were charged by a federal grand jury with extorting money from businessmen
among those named in two indictments returned thursday were the party chairman, jesus mafnas, a government personnel officer; commonwealth rep. mariano bermudes; former commonwealth senate president ponciano rasa and his brother, oscar rasa, publisher of the now-defunct commonwealth examiner newspaper
also indicted were former senate legal counsel james doerty and former senate employee leo pangelinan
one indictment accused mafnas of soliciting and receiving a $22,760 bribe in 1986 from adrian johnston, owner of the surf hotel
in exchange for the money, mafnas guaranteed that the marianas public land corp. would grant the hotel a lease for a piece of public beachfront land located next to the hotel, the indictment said
in the second indictment, the rasa brothers, pangelinan, bermudes and doerty were accused of demanding payments of $222,000 in 1983 from sumitomo corp. and subsequently receiving $113,000 in bribes from the japanese construction company
according to the indictment, the five conspired to force sumitomo to pay a 1 percent commission on all northern marianas business awarded the company
mafnas and bermudes were each charged with one count of extortion. the rasa brothers were each charged with two counts of extortion, while doerty and pangelinan each faced three counts of extortion. mafnas also was charged with one count of conspiracy to commit extortion
at the request of assistant u.s. attorney george proctor, u.s. district judge alfred laureta set bail for mafnas, ponciano rasa, pangelinan and bermudes at $25,000 each. laureta also issued arrest warrants for oscar rasa and doerty, who now live in california
arraignment was set for march 25
bermudes had no comment on the indictment, pangelinan and mafanas have unlisted numbers and could not be reached for comment and ponciano rasa did return a telephone call to his home, the pacific daily news reported
severe cutbacks are devastating the coast guard's drug interdiction and search and rescue operations, the agency's chief said in asking congress for an immediate transfer of $60 million from other accounts
we have coast guard cutters sitting at docks and planes on the runways,'' said adm. paul a. yost, commandant of the coast guard. ``congressional approval of the reprogramming request would let us put those ships and planes back to work patrolling the high seas.''
president reagan on thursday asked congress to transfer money from highway, mass transit and amtrak funds to restore the patrols, which were ordered cut back by the administration last month to help make up for a $103 million budget shortfall
the coast guard eliminated routine search and rescue patrols, cut drug patrols by 55 percent, eliminated 1,100 jobs, closed down nearly 30 coast guard installations and severely reduced other stations
none of the jobs or installations would be restored with the $60 million. that money would be devoted exclusively to restoring patrol levels to their pre-cutback levels, yost said
before the cutbacks, yost said, 90 percent of the agency's drug seizures came from routine patrols. last year, $3 billion in cocaine alone was seized by the coast guard, he said
the commandant said it was too early to quantify the cutback's impact on drug seizures or rescue missions, but he predicted it was heavy
yost said he and transportation secretary james burnley conferred with lawmakers before making the recommendations
i will do everything i can to work with congress to get it passed,'' yost said
the request would not increase overall spending since the money is already appropriated
under the administration's plan, $25.3 million would come from federal highway administration funds that are not earmarked for specific projects; $17.3 million from mass transit grants; $12.4 million from a 2 percent reduction in amtrak's budget; and $5 million from last year's coast guard research and development funds
yost said even if congress approves the administration's budget proposal for fiscal year 1989 in full _ a $200 million increase from this year _ there are no plans to reopen the closed installations or rehire employees
nine members of the house energy and commerce committee have staged a quiet revolution against their chairmen in an effort to break a six-year logjam that has stalled committee action on air quality legislation
the low-key uprising led by rep. al swift, d-wash., came to a seemingly harmonious head thursday when the self-proclaimed ``group of nine'' unveiled a compromise plan to escalate the battle against urban pollution
their effort drew applause from the targets of their end-run around the committee system: chairman john dingell, d-mich., and rep. henry waxman, d-calif., chairman of the health and the environment subcommittee. the details of their plan didn't
swift and his allies effectively took over the committee's air quality deliberations last december after months of fruitless wrangling between dingell and waxman, the sponsor of an air quality bill endorsed by environmentalists but deadlocked in his subcommittee with a 10-10 split
it's a legislative product,'' swift told a news conference. ``none of us is happy with every last detail. ... this is a good piece of environmental policy, and it's cost effective.''
their plan in many ways is similar to waxman's bill and one produced last year by the senate environment committee but still awaiting a call to the floor by a major foe, majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va
each proposal calls for stricter emissions controls on industry and automobiles in an effort to reduce the carbon monoxide and smog-producing ozone that the environmental protection agency says have reached unhealthy levels for some 100 million people living in 60 or so metropolitan areas
the group's plan, however, would give states and localities more time to come up with plans to cut pollution, from three to 16 years, depending on the severity of their problems
the plan would leave most remedies up to epa and the states, but at minimum a city falling short of clean air standards would have to institute a vehicle inspection and maintenance program
swift and rep. dennis eckart, d-ohio, said group members would begin working next week on an acid rain plan, which has also been divisive
dingell, from an automaking district, has been firm against calls for cleaner vehicle exhausts, saying the retirement of older vehicles lacking emissions controls will cause vehicular pollution to continue to decrease
in a prepared statement, dingell said the group of nine plan is ``a vast improvement'' over waxman's bill and has a ``real opportunity to gain my full support.''
waxman called the proposal a ``very constructive step.''
earl mallich, chairman of industry's clean air working group, said the proposed tailpipe standards may not be technologically achievable. r.g. ensz, spokesman for the american petroleum institute, said that a proposal to make fuel less evaporative was not cost effective
the motor vehicle manufacturers association of the united states said the plan for cleaner exhausts would have imperceptible benefits to the nation's air
spokesmen for the sierra club and environmental action said they were pleased the plan called for tighter controls on industries and vehicles, but said the pace of controls was too slow
other members of the swift group are mike synar, d-okla.; phil sharp, d-ind.; jim cooper, d-tenn.; jim slattery, d-kan.; bill tauzin, d-la.; and rick boucher, d-va
the deadline set by secretary of state george p. shultz for arab and israeli replies to his mideast peace plan is passing with the outlook for eventual acceptance bleak
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir wound up four days of talks thursday critical of shultz's call for an international conference
he didn't say yes and he didn't say no to the plan, which also anticipates israel yielding at least part of the west bank and gaza in exchange for arab recongition
but most of what shamir had to say during his visit was critical of the proposal _ especially its call for an international conference hosted by the united states, the soviet union and the three other permament members of the u.n. security council: china, britain and france
the other major player in the shultz scenario, king hussein of jordan, has not replied to the u.s. plan. a jordanian official, speaking this week in amman on condition of anonymity, said he doubted there would be a definitive reponse for 10 days
an indication of arab reservations came thursday from clovis maksoud, the arab league's representative here. he criticized the exclusion of the palestine liberation organization and urged the united states to demand a total israeli withdrawal from the west bank and gaza
at least 100 palestinian arabs have died in a little more than three months in clashes with israeli forces. shultz's proposal would lead to self-rule for three years, with negotiations on an overall settlement to begin by december
israel took control of the territories from jordan and egypt in the 1967 six-day war. shamir and other likud bloc leaders have vowed not to surrender any of the land
shultz submitted his plan for negotiations two weeks ago to israel, jordan and also syria, which would be participate in the talks on an overall settlement. he asked for a reply by mid-march
as you know, i, in general, think that deadlines are good things in trying to get people to make up their minds,'' shultz told reporters on his mideast shuttle. ``so we have pointed out the fact that the situation carries inherent in it a certain sense of deadlines.''
and yet, shultz noted philosophically, ``you can't push people if they don't want to be pushed.''
shamir headed for los angeles from washington. he and the other senior members of the israeli cabinet will take up the u.s. proposal next wednesday. a vote by the full cabinet would be likely on sunday, march 27
if israel and jordan both say ``yes'' by then, the shultz plan could take off. but there would be little room, if any, to make changes
president reagan and shultz both have ruled out revisions. reagan said he would neither ``slice'' the plan apart nor abandon it. shultz told the senate budget committee on thursday, ``the united states will not permit any aspect of its proposal to be eroded or compromised.''
but shamir clearly is hoping for at least one major change. he wants to replace the international conference with a ``ceremony'' held by the united states and the soviet union. afterward, israel and the arabs would negotiate directly
shultz is trying to win shamir over with reassurances
he told the senate committee after a final meeting with the prime minister that the united states would not attend _ or remain _ at a conference designed to replace direct arab-israeli negotiations
the conference will be specifically enjoined from imposing solutions or vetoing what had been agreed bilaterally,'' shultz said
maksoud of the arab league called, meanwhile, for a u.s. commitment at the outset of negotiations backing arab demands that israel yield all the territory captured in the 1967 war
in a speech, maksoud also reasserted the arab position that the plo is the sole legitimate representative of palestinian arabs. some 1.5 million live on the west bank and gaza, which were controlled until 1967 by jordan and egypt
shultz's plan does not insist that israel relinquish all of the territory. also, it excludes the plo from the negotiations. palestinians approved by the plo would be in a delegation with jordan
maksoud said an international conference must have the power to settle disputes between israel and the arabs. ``it cannot be a ceremonial opening, or an event, or some sort of an international framework,'' he said _ taking direct aim at shamir's proposal
maksoud also criticized reagan's appeal to both sides to accept the u.s. initiative without modification
in light of what he called ``bitter arab experience,'' he said, ``we find ourselves unwilling to be rushed into a timetable presented on a take-it-or-leave-it basis.''
barry schweid has reported on middle east diplomacy for 15 years. lake</head>
a group of people living on the georgia-south carolina line says there's nothing wrong with strom thurmond unless it's the name of a lake shared by the two states
the group met privately with the veteran south carolina republican for 35 minutes thursday to present petitions signed by 42,000 people who want the senator's help in restoring the lake's original name, lake clarks hill
of the signatures, 30,000 came from the georgia side, and a legislative proposal to repeal the new name is sponsored by eight democratic congressmen from that state
thurmond said he would stay out of the dispute, which began in december when congress renamed the 42-year-old army corps of engineers lake quickly and with no public hearings
he told them he feels the matter is settled and since he did not instigate it or push for it, he feels it would be inappropriate for him to get involved now,'' press secretary christopher simpson said
the meeting also was attended by a group of south carolina legislators who want to keep the thurmond name. ``we're disturbed that this is going to be an embarrassment to sen. thurmond,'' said state sen. john drummond of greenwood
drummond said the south carolina lawmakers told the citizens group that it would be an embarrassment for thurmond to ``ask the whole congress and the president to reverse what they've done.''
thurmond himself had nothing to say, referring all questions to simpson
roy giles, a lincolnton, ga., restaurant owner and one of the leaders of ``keep our lake clarks hill,'' said the petitions presented thursday propose a compromise that would restore the name of the lake to clarks hill but would retain the new strom thurmond name for the dam and road
sen. thurmond will have his monument and the people will have their lake back,'' giles said of the compromise, which has been incorporated into a bill that rep. doug barnard, an augusta, ga., democrat, has introduced in the house with the backing of the other seven democrats in the georgia house delegation
giles said he was surprised when the south carolina lawmakers showed up at the meeting because thurmond originally had agreed to meet privately with representatives of the citizens group opposed to the name change
giles said the name change will cause financial hardships for businesses around the lake that have built their reputations using the clarks hill name. and he vowed that the group will continue its fight, even without thurmond's help
we're going to continue to get signatures,'' he said. ``we're not going to let up. this was just an opportunity to present our case to sen. thurmond and ask for his help.''
israeli representatives are trying to strike a deal with iran-contra prosecutors over immunity for four israelis and u.s. access to israel's swiss bank account records
the meetings with independent counsel lawrence walsh's staff began thursday, a day after a federal grand jury indicted lt. col. oliver north, former national security adviser john poindexter and two arms dealers. all four were involved in the diversion of profits from iran arms sales to the nicaraguan contra rebels
israel is seeking immunity from prosecution for four israelis involved in the sale of u.s. anti-tank missiles to iran in 1985 and 1986, said an israeli official who spoke on condition of anonymity
walsh, in turn, wants records of israeli transactions with north and the two indicted arms dealers, richard secord and albert hakim, the official said
yossi gal, a spokesman for the israeli embassy, said a meeting today was aimed at ``finding an acceptable solution for cooperation between the two governments.''
israel is seeking immunity for amiram nir, a israeli anti-terrorism official; david kimche, the former foreign ministry director; and businessmen yaacov nimrodi and al schwimmer. all worked with north on the iran arms sales
gal also said that rafael vardi, a retired israeli general who compiled a chronology of israel's role in the arms sales to iran, met with walsh on thursday. several israeli lawyers accompanied him, according to the israeli official who spoke anonymously
elyakim rubinstein, a top aide to israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, is expected to join vardi today for talks with walsh's staff, gal said
rubinstein, who has been in the united states with shamir for discussions on a middle east peace plan, also will meet with reagan administration officials about the case, gal said. he refused to discuss the meetings further
james wieghart, walsh's spokesman, said he knew nothing of the meetings but confirmed that walsh has been negotiating with the israelis for a long time about access to the records on the swiss accounts
the israeli official who spoke on condition he remain anonymous said walsh is seeking bank account records to corroborate other evidence about israel's transactions with north, secord and hakim
walsh angered israel last year by issuing subpoenas against nir, kimche, nimrodi and schwimmer, meaning they could be arrested if they visited the united states and refused to testify
under pressure from the united states, rubinstein and vardi compiled classified historical and financial chronologies that were provided to the congressional iran-contra committees last year. the documents detailed the role israel played in shipping u.s. missiles to iran as part of a plan to secure freedom for american hostages in lebanon
during the congressional hearings, israel refused to allow the four israelis involved in the arms sales to testify, but agreed to let vardi answer questions. the congressional panels did not call vardi, saying they were satisfied with the written chronologies
fbi director william sessions is coming under increasing fire on capitol hill in connection with the racial harassment case of black fbi agent donald rochon
on thursday, rep. john conyers, d-mich., accused sessions of ``sidestepping'' and engaging in ``a classic stall'' by promising to give a full report to congress at a later date on rochon and equal employment matters
i am frankly deeply disappointed in your lack of candor and outrage about the terrorism that is going on,'' conyers said in referring to the rochon case and other allegations of discrimination within the bureau
rochon is suing the fbi and the justice department, alleging racial discrimination, harassment and death threats from fellow agents and supervisors when he worked at fbi offices in omaha, neb., and chicago. the federal equal employment opportunity commission has upheld rochon's racial discrimination allegations in connection with his stay in omaha in 1983 and 1984
there has been no sidestepping at all, none,'' responded sessions, who has been fbi director for four months
he said he was in ``almost total agreement'' with conyers' concerns and said he is committed to seeing that the bureau ``is precisely what it strives to be, an organization which has no racism.''
however, sessions said that with lawsuits pending he cannot conduct a detailed discussion during this ``awkward period of time.''
in addition to the rochon case, hispanic agents have filed a class-action suit in el paso, texas, accusing the fbi of racial discrimination
blacks and hispanics each make up slightly more than 4 percent of the bureau's more than 9,000 agents
in prepared testimony before the house subcommittee on civil and constitutional rights, of which conyers is a member, sessions said he has designated executive assistant fbi director john d. glover, who is black, to oversee a complete review of equal employment opportunity matters within the fbi
sessions said glover ``will report directly to me'' concerning the rochon matter and other aspects of the fbi's equal employment opportunity program including training, handling of complaints, hiring and promotion policy
in both cases, i can assure this subcommittee that once these processes have been completed, i will make a full reporting to congress,'' sessions said
legislation to double the maximum amount of disaster aid to households and provide money to combat erosion and flooding along the great lakes faces an uncertain future in the senate after passing the house
the disaster relief amendments, opposed by the reagan administration as too expensive, passed the house thursday by a vote of 368-13. a companion bill with 27 co-sponsors has languished in the senate since its introduction there last year
under the amendments, the federal emergency management agency would be barred from paying less than a 75 percent share of aid to local governments qualifying for public repair projects following a disaster. the amendments also would add guidelines to speed the distribution of post-disaster aid, and permit federal funds to be used for local projects to lessen the effect of disasters before they strike
the cap on grants for states' disaster preparation programs would climb from $25,000 to $50,000, and the maximum on awards to individuals to rebuild households and clear away debris would go from $5,000 to $10,000, with the amount to be adjusted according to the economy
in addition, the legislation would provide, for the first time, a mechanism to appeal decisions on eligibility for disaster and emergency assistance
the legislation has its roots in the federal response to tornadoes that raced through western pennsylvania, ohio and surrounding areas in 1985, killing 88 people
fema agrees that ``fine-tuning'' is needed to the 1974 act establishing a coordinated federal program to prepare for and respond to hurricanes, tornadoes, storms and floods. but the administration has pushed for legislation that wouldn't increase costs to the federal government
the congressional budget office has estimated the cost of the house easure at $50 to $100 million per year. in addition to updating the disaster response program, the legislation would provide grants and army corps of engineers assistance for flooding and erosion prevention in great lakes states
high-water levels have caused an estimated $200 million in damage to shoreline houses and communities, the northeast-midwest congressional coalition said. states would be required to put up 30 percent matching share of the federal grants
u.s. rep. tom ridge, r-pa., the principal sponsor of the bill, said the 1985 tornadoes that killed 65 people in pennsylvania alone made him ``painfully aware'' of shortcomings with fema
disaster victims were waiting in line for temporary housing up to six weeks,'' ridge said during thursday's floor debate
i was touring demolished home sites arguing with federal officials about debris removal,'' he said. ``they weren't concerned about debris removal. they were concerned about the specific, inflexible application of regulations, regardless of the impact on public health and safety.''
the world's business and financial communities should be encouraged by the ease with which the house budget committee has approved a $1.1 trillion federal budget for the 1989 fiscal year, the panel's chairman says
chairman william h. gray iii, d-pa., made the remarks thursday after his committee approved the budget resolution with support from lawmakers of both parties
i think it's good in terms of helping the volatility out there in the equity markets ... and sending a signal to our trading partners that we're willing to work cooperatively in terms of addressing the deficit,'' gray said
the budget plan meets the spending and tax strictures established by last year's budget summit pact between congress and president reagan. that accord was sparked by october's stock market crash and the resulting calls to slash the government's deficits, which have surpassed $200 billion in recent years
the spending document would leave a deficit of $134.1 billion, according to the budget panel, enough to avoid automatic spending cuts under the gramm-rudman budget-balancing law
but to get to that figure, lawmakers adopted the white house's economic forecasts and abandoned gloomier estimates produced by their own congressional budget office that would have added $35 billion in red ink to the deficit projection
under gramm-rudman, the deficit target for fiscal 1989, which begins oct. 1, is $136 billion. spending would be cut to that level automatically if the deficit exceeds the target by $10 billion
the document, expected to be considered by the full house next week, reduces reagan's request for science and space and allocates the money to urban and social programs
the budget resolution was pieced together over the last several days during closed-door meetings between committee republicans and democrats. the panel approved the document, on a voice vote with no objections, during a five-minute public session
rep. willis d. gradison jr. of ohio, senior committee republican at the meeting, said the resolution had been written in an ``excellent spirit of bipartisanship'' and had ``very strong support'' from gop lawmakers
the bipartisan camaraderie was in stark contrast to last year, when republicans walked away from the budget resolution process and the bickering lasted for months
the budget pact reached last november between reagan and lawmakers locked in new taxes and spending levels for fiscal 1988 and 1989 for defense, foreign affairs and overall domestic spending
lawmakers are proving eager to avoid reopening those questions and sparking potentially bitter fights in an election year. thus, the main fight has been over distributing the $169.2 billion the summit allows for the domestic programs that congress directly oversees and are not financed under automatic formulas
i think the summit agreement basically set the tone for the year,'' said rep. leon panetta, d-calif
in the 1989 budget he presented to congress on feb. 18, reagan proposed a 20 percent increase in spending on space and science programs to $13.1 billion. the budget panel, looking to restore proposed cuts to several other domestic programs, pared that increase to $12.2 billion
the committee felt that was a realistic figure for nasa to carry out its mission,'' gray said
where reagan proposed cutting deeply into programs such as mass transit assistance and eliminating other programs such as federal aid to amtrak, the passenger railroad, the budget committee would retain current levels of spending or reduce it by 1 percent or 2 percent
for programs for low-income people such as job training and child health care, the budget panel's proposal would allow enough of a spending increase to keep up with inflation, expected to reach 4 percent this year
the committee's budget also rejects $1.2 billion in savings in medicare that reagan had proposed, spends $1.5 billion for aids research _ slightly more than the president proposed _ and retains previously planned levels of spending for education, fighting drugs and providing aid to the homeless
the panel also proposed a 3 percent pay raise for federal workers and civilian employees of the military. gray said lawmakers will have to decide later this year whether members of congress would qualify for the salary increases
the committee's budget leaves intact the summit agreement spending levels of $294 billion for military programs for the 1989 fiscal year, and $14 billion in new taxes, mostly on corporations
the senate plans to write its budget resolution next month. the resolution does not need the president's signature, and it serves as a blueprint for actual spending legislation to be enacted later
in a separate action, the white house sent congress a supplemental spending request for this fiscal year that would increase spending by $1.1 billion, mostly for veterans
another $57 million would pay for raises for federal court employees, and $54 million more would be for disability payments to people with black lung disease
the measure would allow an additional $4.2 billion to be transferred among agencies
a frustrated congressman had to turn to the japanese embassy this week to find out exactly what the senate was proposing to do on trade legislation
that is just not the way to do business,'' rep. tom downey, d-n.y., said thursday following a closed-door caucus at which grievances over the incident got a full-scale airing
at the caucus, rep. william frenzel, r-minn., expressed outrage that he had to rely on the japanese embassy to get a copy of the senate proposal on how best to crack down on japanese barriers to american exports
pat eveland, frenzel's administrative assistant, confirmed that the congressman was disturbed about the delay in transmitting the senate report to the house and raised the issue at the closed-door session
we think it would be nice if the senate would decide to give us the trade offer first before the private sector and the press,'' she said. frenzel himself was not available to discuss the matter, she added
the document was a compromise offer from senate members of a house-senate conference committee that is trying to merge rival versions of a 1,000-page trade bill passed by the two houses last year
among other things, the senate's offer proposed to erase from the bill the controversial trade plan sponsored by democratic presidential hopeful richard gephardt, d-mo. his plan, calling for 10 percent yearly rollbacks in japanese trade surpluses, is contained only in the house version
the senate's alternative proposal would require the u.s. trade representative to draw up a list of japanese barriers to american products and then either negotiate an end to them or retaliate
eveland said she was on the telephone with a japanese embassy official early wednesday morning, discussing the senate's offer, when to her surprise ``it became evident that they had a copy of it.''
she said she asked the japanese for a copy and they immediately duplicated theirs and sent it by messenger to frenzel's office on capitol hill. she said a version was not available from the senate finance committee until 12:30 p.m. wednesday
it remained unclear just how the japanese managed to obtain their copy of the offer
when eveland was told that several copies were distributed to reporters who worked late in the senate press gallery on tuesday night, she said, ``well, now we'll know where to go.'' claim</head> dropped matter; picks up 5th graf: `larouche, six ...</note>
henry kissinger may be called to testify at lyndon larouche's trial to rebut charges by larouche's lawyers that the government launched a vendetta against the political extremist, a prosecutor says
larouche's attorneys, who contend the federal charges against larouche were fabricated, showed the jury letters thursday in which kissinger, as secretary of state, requested an fbi investigation of larouche groups
kissinger may be called to testify that he was a target of protests and harassment by larouche followers and was justified in seeking the probe, assistant u.s. attorney john markham said
larouche lawyers said they would welcome an opportunity to cross-examine kissinger, whom the fringe politician has labeled a soviet spy
larouche, six aides and five larouche organizations are charged with conspiring to obstruct a grand jury investigation of alleged credit card and loan fraud by larouche's 1984 presidential campaign. four of the organizations are charged with fraud
also thursday, richard welsh, an accountant and treasurer with several larouche groups, testified that larouche's two campaign organizations budgeted up to $125,000 a month to pay back credit card charges that card-holders claimed were unauthorized
prosecutors allege the campaign relied on fraudulent charges to stay afloat when legitimate fund-raising stalled, knowing it would take several weeks before unauthorized charges would be deducted from the campaign's bank account
the campaign allegedly misused the charge-card numbers given by contributors for donations or by people who bought books and other literature from the larouche groups
the defendants contend evidence of widespread fraud and obstruction was fabricated by fbi and cia infiltrators as part of a reagan administration effort to ruin larouche and cripple his highly successful fund-raising
admitted as evidence to the jury thursday was a series of letters between kissinger, then-fbi director william h. webster and oliver revell, the fbi's executive assistant director, discussing larouche organizations
in an august 1982 letter to webster, kissinger complained that larouche supporters had become ``increasingly obnoxious'' in their criticism of him and asked whether the fbi could investigate larouche groups
revell responded with two letters saying the agency would investigate kissinger's complaint and that there appeared to be some evidence of illegal telephone use by larouche supporters to harass kissinger
no larouche followers ever were charged with harassing or threatening kissinger
the defense contends revell later directed fbi infiltration of larouche groups at the request of lt. col. oliver north, the former white house national security aide indicted wednesday for his role in the iran-contra affair
larouche contends he has been the target of a 20-year government vendetta that climaxed in 1984 because of his outspoken criticism of reagan's contra-aid programs
last week, the defense was given two declassified documents, one a memo to north from another pivotal figure in the iran-contra affair discussing apparent efforts to collect information against larouche
the discovery of those documents 60 days into the trial prompted keeton to order an extensive search of government records, including those of the white house and vice president george bush, for any evidence of infiltration or harassment of larouche groups. the searches are expected to be completed by next week
the army battalions ordered to honduras by president reagan include two from the renowned 82nd airborne division and two from a newly activated ``light'' division organized for quick movement around the world
the 82nd airborne and the 7th light infantry division are based at opposite ends of the country _ fort bragg, n.c., and fort ord, calif., respectively _ and are assigned to different corps
but the two divisions and their battalions share a common emphasis and mission _ maintain a high state of readiness and be ready to operate on short notice in virtually all parts of the world
the 82nd airborne, as its name implies, is trained to drop in uninvited by parachute when combat requires. the 7th light infantry, on the other hand, doesn't use parachutes but can arrive even more quickly
the 82nd is renowned because of its combat record and its role as the one army unit that is on constant alert
during world war ii, the unit participated in six different campaigns, including sicily and the normandy invasion. its commanders included gens. omar bradley and matthew ridgway
it was during and immediately after normandy that the 82nd really made its mark, taking horrendous casualties but preventing the germans from moving forward to stop the invasion
the 82nd also has fought in vietnam and grenada and some of its units have served with the peacekeeping force in the sinai. within the united states, it helped keep the peace during the integration battles in the south, quelled riots in detroit in 1967, and kept order during the republican national convention in miami in 1968
the 7th was the first of what the army hopes will be four active-duty light divisions. with about 10,500 soldiers assigned to it instead of the 17,000 assigned to a normal mechanized division, the 7th is full of riflemen, carries no heavy vehicles and is armed with only modest amounts of artillery and anti-tank weapons
the idea behind the light divisions was to provide a president the option of using a fairly large force that could be moved rapidly around the world
for example, a normal heavy division, such as those assigned to europe, would require about 2,850 flights of a c-141 to deploy. the 82nd airborne, if the entire division moved out, would require about 1,500. a light division could show up with just 500 flights
there's just so much more mobility,'' noted lt. col. greg rixon, an army spokesman. ``the tradeoff is you can't leave it (in a battle zone) on its own for very long. it has to be resupplied and sustained.''
the pentagon said thursday it expected the four battalions from the 82nd and 7th to link up on the ground in honduras as a brigade task force for a readiness exercise code-named ``golden pheasant,'' to be conducted in cooperation with honduran troops
the task force is commanded by army brig gen. daniel r. schroeder of the xviii airborne corps and a deputy, brig. gen. james j. johnson of the 82nd
besides the four battalions of infantry, the task force is bringing with it a small helicopter cavalry unit with eight aircraft; three batteries from field artillery units and a brigade headquarters company
normally, army units sent to honduras for exercises report to joint task force bravo, a small headquarters unit based in honduras to coordinate u.s. troop activities. as of thursday, for example, the pentagon said about 2,050 national guard and reserve engineers were on temporary duty in honduras
sen. bob dole, who has taken a beating at the hands of george bush in nearly all the republican presidential primaries, won hands down among a select group of young voters
one hundred and two high school student leaders were asked in january to name their favorite candidates in both the republican and democratic parties. the students are winners of the century iii leaders scholarship program sponsored by the national association of secondary school principals and shell oil co
on the gop side, the student leaders chose dole over bush by 70 percent to 15 percent, with 10 percent naming pete du pont, who is now out of the race, according to survey results released thursday
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis was the favorite on the democratic side, getting 37 percent of the students' votes to 17 percent for sens. albert gore jr. and paul simon, 10 percent for bruce babbitt (now a dropout), 9 percent for rep. richard gephardt and just 4 percent for jesse jackson
