trenton, n.j. (am) _ new jersey senate democratic leader john lynch says he will abandon a proposal to send a slate of uncommitted delegates to the democratic national convention
lynch said thursday he will drop a movement he headed and bow to the request of sen. bill bradley, d-n.j
bradley met with democratic leaders wednesday and asked them to drop their efforts toward an uncommitted slate, saying the drive could be interpreted outside the state as a movement to back him as a presidential candidate
senator bradley feels the uncommitted movement would be perceived as a `stalking horse' for a candidacy at a brokered convention,'' lynch said
lynch has said an uncommitted slate could enable new jersey to play a decisive role at the convention if no democratic candidate wins a majority of delegates in the primaries
robert dole's staunchest new jersey supporter, assembly gop leader chuck haytaian, says the kansas senator should drop out of the race for the republican presidential nomination
haytaian, who is chairman of dole's new jersey campaign, said thursday that vice president george bush has the nomination all but locked up, and dole ought to face reality
he knows how to count numbers,'' said haytaian. ``if he looks at the delegate numbers for bush, the numbers should tell him what to do.''
haytaian added he would continue to support dole as long as he remains a candidate
the coordinator of jesse jackson's presidential campaign in south carolina says he may ask a judge to postpone monday's county conventions
kevin gray said thursday he is frustrated by the inefficiency of the democratic caucus and the absence of delegate lists
the caucus process is rearing its ugly head,'' said gray, one of a growing number of democrats who believe the party should be holding a primary
eighteen counties' conventions are meeting monday and the other 28 counties are meeting march 28. jackson was the overwhelming winner at saturday's 1,788 precinct caucus meetings
gray said it's important to all of the campaigns to have access to the delegate lists so they can make sure their delegates know where and when to go to the county conventions and so they can seek the support of uncommitted delegates
political extremist lyndon larouche has been ruled off indiana's democratic presidential primary ballot because of inadequate petition signatures
the state election board concluded on thursday that larouche's supporters had failed to meet the requirements for signatures to qualify him for the may 3 ballot
indiana law requires 500 signatures from each of the state's 10 congressional districts. the larouche petitions met that requirement in nine districts and had more than 5,000 signatures overall, but the petitions had only 325 signatures in the 10th district, according to election board chairman john r. whitaker
a close friend of attorney general edwin meese iii said meese interceded on wedtech corp.'s behalf to gain federal approval for financing, a witness testified at the racketeering trial of rep. mario biaggi
the witness, former wedtech vice chairman mario moreno, said meese's lawyer and friend, e. robert wallach, told him at a 1983 meeting across the street from the white house that meese had asked then-commerce secretary malcolm baldrige to sign the necessary documents
moreno said thursday he was told that baldrige balked at signing because the matter was ``too hot politically,'' but two or three days later ``the matter was resolved.''
moreno recounted the meeting with wallach in his third day of testimony at federal court in manhattan, where biaggi and six others are on trial on charges of turning wedtech into a racketeering enterprise through an alleged series of bribery and extortion schemes
wedtech, a now-bankrupt defense contractor, at the time was delinquent on two loans of more than $2 million each, one from the commerce department's economic development administration, the other guaranteed by eda
the company in 1983 wanted eda approval to refinance the loans with a new bank
but the eda chief, assistant commerce secretary carlos campbell, resisted pressure from former white house political director lyn nofziger and his lobbying partner, mark bragg, to approve the plan
moreno, one of four ex-wedtech officials who have pleaded guilty to bribing public officials and other crimes, testified wallach ``said he was going to a national security meeting at 6 a.m. and told me to wait in lafayette park'' across from the white house
moreno said he saw wallach enter the white house and when he emerged two hours later, wallach ``said he talked to his friend over there.''
moreno said he understood that wallach's friend was meese, who was then presidential counselor
wallach said they would try to get another assistant commerce secretary besides campbell to approve the financing and moreno said he was told to call bragg
moreno said he was told that no assistant secretary could sign the papers legally but there was a vacancy in the department and perhaps a new assistant secretary could sign. two or three days later the problem was resolved, he said
nofziger was convicted last month of illegal lobbying for wedtech and other companies. the conviction is under appeal
last december, a special prosecutor said there was insufficient evidence to charge meese in the wedtech case
a small airplane crashed into a schoolyard moments after pupils were shepherded to their classrooms at the end of noon recess. the children escaped injury, but the pilot was critically hurt
it was the classic case of fate intervening,'' said kern county fire capt. tom pulcher. ``where his impact point was, eight minutes prior to that there was a schoolyard full of children.''
one class barely made it off the playground at north beardsley school in time thursday, fire officials said. the teacher had just lined her class up and was herding them inside when she heard the plane coming in
a small group were still outside,'' said assistant city fire chief henry pacheco. ``she told the kids to run, and they all ran out of the way.''
observers said the fuselage of the single-engine dornier came to rest against a breezeway at the grade school one mile south of meadows field, the main airport in this city 100 miles north of los angeles
the pilot, kenneth dale howard, 42, of anchorage, alaska, was taken to kern medical center where he was listed in critical condition in the intensive care unit
howard was making his final approach and preparing to land at meadows when his engine lost power, said wilbur friend, air traffic manager for the federal aviation administration tower at the airport
a national transportation safety board investigator requested a blood-alcohol test on howard after some containers of alcohol were found at the crash site, pulcher said. he added there was no immediate evidence that howard had been drinking
the following dispatch was filed jointly by steven komarow of the ap, otto kreisher of copley news service, fredrick kempe of wall street journal and robert cohn of newsweek. they are with the pentagon news pool covering the arrival of u.s. troops in honduras
a steady stream of air transports brought u.s. soldiers and equipment in a show of force so hastily arranged that american commanders scrambled to develop training exercises to keep them busy
a dramatic air drop of 800 paratroopers of the 82nd airborne division was scheduled for early today
planes later in the day were to bring 1,100 more soldiers from the 7th infantry division in fort ord, calif., completing the 3,000 man deployment ordered by president reagan to counter what he called an invasion by nicaraguan sandinista troops
hundreds of soldiers on thursday bedded down in dusty fields near the airstrip, awaiting orders for training missions which normally are arranged several months in advance for such exercises
this exercise got popped on us two days ago,'' said maj. mike nason, public affairs officer for the 82nd airborne. ``we're having to compress all the training arrangements.''
an example of how the operation was being altered because of the lack of planning was today's scheduled parachute drop. normally that would be the first wave of an airborne assault, but nason said the army needed to use carefully the limited air transport that was available on such short notice
army commanders met through the day thursday with their honduran counterparts and made plans for the first of a string of joint exercises
troops were told to expect to spend about 10 days in honduras, but military spokesmen said there was no official timetable yet for them to leave
the first joint exercise, a helicopter movement scheduled today, would take the u.s. troops 25 miles closer to the area where the white house claims the nicaraguans have invaded. however, they would still be more than 100 miles west of the area of reported fighting
commanders insisted their orders barred them from getting near the scene of the fighting. however, they said they were prepared to take action if the orders were made. the troops appeared eager for action
we wait for this,'' said pfc. dallas hutchison of germantown, md., who was manning an m-60 machine gun guarding the bivouac site
officers were eager to take advantage of the training exercise in a year when budget constraints forced them to cancel maneuvers
maybe at the highest echelons of the government they have some political reasons for us to be here. but we see it as a blessing in disguise,'' nason said
nason said the division's training budget had been cut 25 percent, and plans for exercises in panama had been canceled
a high-ranking sandinista officer flew about 25 journalists, most of them american, to this rugged outpost on the honduran border his troops retook from contra rebels in a major offensive
the reporters were brought in thursday to see it was quiet in the jungle region about 175 miles from managua and told the offensive had ended
about noon, two unidentified jet planes roared in from honduras and dropped at least five bombs. the journalists and their hosts dived for cover, the bombs exploding as close as 70 yards away
no one was hurt and nothing at the sandinista military encampment damaged
the region is where the white house claims nicaraguan troops entered honduras in pursuit of the u.s.-supplied rebels, and the attack came just hours after the first of 3,000 american troops began arriving in honduras in response to the alleged incursion
honduran said it had mounted the attack, but claimed it had targeted only sandinista forces in honduran territory
the bombs landed along the narrow coco river, which marks the border between the two countries. puffs of black smoke curled over the banana trees
lt. col. javier carrion, the deputy chief of the sandinista army's general staff, said two bombs landed in nicaraguan territory and one in honduras
he said the attack appeared more harassment than an attempt to hit any specific target. none of the five soviet-made helicopters in the area were hit
in washington, reagan administration sources who insisted on anonymity claimed one soviet-made helicopter was damaged on the ground in nicaragua. the soviet union suplies the sandinistas with military hardware and training
carrion said jets had similarly buzzed the coco river earlier in the day
he denied that sandinista troops had crossed the ill-defined border, but said: ``there are sectors in the mountains here where you can get lost. it's easy to confuse the topography.''
president daniel ortega has refused to confirm or deny whether an incursion had occurred. military officials in honduras said their troops were surrounding about 2,000 sandinista soldiers in honduran territory on thursday
standing in a jungle clearing, carrion showed the reporters on a map where he said sandinista troops had used artillery to destroy contra camps along a six-mile route on both sides of the coco river
he said the offensive, begun march 8, was halted on wednesday on ortega's instructions after the sandinistas had pushed 1,800 rebels back into honduras. carrion said his troops received air support from soviet-made heliopter-gunships and an-46 propeller-driven planes with bombs attached
the sandinistas killed 92 contras and wounded 300, but no prisoners were taken during the eight-day offensive, carrion said
he said it would be difficult for the contras to return to the area, which they had used since last year for makeshift camps
carrion said sandinista troops destroyed 120 plastic and wood shacks that the rebels had been using to store supplies, for sleeping and as clinics
the government says $20 million worth of clothing seized by the customs bureau will be given to homeless people and orphans in mozambique, malawi and zimbabwe
the clothing had been exported by china and was seized by inspectors after chinese officials notified the customs bureau that counterfeit visas were being used to send textiles into the united states
the customs bureau said thursday the first increment of the clothing _ cotton jeans, shirts, dresses, infants' shirts, denim jackets and pants and suspenders sets _ would be distributed by the world vision relief organization and the adventists development and relief agency international
convicted federal judge walter l. nixon jr. of mississippi would say only that he was ``very upset'' after the chairman of the house judiciary committee introduced a resolution of impeachment against him
the action thursday by judiciary chairman peter w. rodino jr., d-n.j., came just two days after he received a recommendation from the judicial conference, the governing body for federal judges
the conference certified to the house that nixon had engaged in conduct which might constitute grounds for impeachment. judges are appointed for life, and can only be removed by congress in an impeachment proceeding
nixon was convicted in february 1986 of two counts of perjury before a federal grand jury
nixon, reached by phone at his home in ocean springs, miss., said: ``my family and i are very upset at this time. beyond that, i have no further comment. any other comments i may have must come through my attorney.''
an advocate for quality children's television programs is urging congress to reinstate limits on advertising during children's shows, but the national association of broadcasters says such rules aren't needed
peggy charren, president of the cambridge, mass.-based action for children's television, told a house subcommittee thursday that the tv industry cannot be expected to protect the interests of children
since the federal communications commission abandoned its advertising limits, dozens of cartoons starring toymakers' products have appeared, she said
the national association of broadcasters, however, said regulation is unnecessary because commercial broadcasters ``have not and will not desert children.''
the commerce department says foreign countries that export tuna to the united states must reduce the numbers of dolphin deaths that occur during fishing or lose the right to export tuna to america
the department's national marine fisheries service on thursday ordered foreign nations that export tuna to reduce the number of dolphins killed in fishing
the order covers foreign fleets that catch yellowfin tuna in purse seine nets, and requires them to establish dolphin protection rules similar to those that already cover u.s. fishermen
the regulation will take effect in mid-april, and requires that the rate of dolphins killed by the foreign fleets be reduced to the u.s. fishing fleet level by 1991, the fisheries service said
former prime minister pierre trudeau's ex-wife, margaret kemper, has been charged with marijuana possession, her lawyer said
the royal canadian mounted police charged her in provincial court thursday after obtaining a search warrant to seize a package at her home in ottawa last friday
she denies the offense and is anxious to get this matter cleared up in court,'' said the lawyer, michael edelson
canadian press news agency reported that the search warrant said a police informer in british columbia offered the tip that margaret kemper would be receiving one pound of marijuana in the mail. police then watched for the arrival of a package in ottawa, the agency said
ms. kemper is scheduled to appear in court april 11. a final trial date has not been set
the jet-setting former first lady divorced trudeau in 1983 while he was still prime minister, following a stormy marriage and seven-year separation
young and rebellious, she made headlines frequently, including when she spent a few days with the rolling stones rock group in toronto
now 39, she married ottawa real estate developer fried kemper in 1984. after producing an autobiography and a brief career as a tv talk show hostess, she retired into life as a housewife. she had three sons with trudeau and has one son with kemper. attack</head>
better-educated people are more likely to return to work within a year of their first heart attack, says a study that found the severity of the attack and the nature of the victim's job to be less important factors
the study published in today's issue of the journal of the american medical association tracked 151 patients, ages 24 to 70, for one year after they suffered their first heart attack and noted whether they returned to work
it seemed to us that many doctors assumed, `bad heart attack, he doesn't return to work, good heart attack, he does.' that's just not so,'' said dr. g. richard smith, one of the study's two authors
if the patient is well-educated and has a job that is not physically stressful, there's a good chance they'll go back within the first year,'' said co-author diane o'rourke
smith and ms. o'rourke said their study was designed to test the predictive value of factors raised in previous studies of heart-attack patients. the study did not find why the level of education made such a difference, they said
but smith, a psychiatrist and professor at the university of arkansas for medical sciences, said his ``clinical sense is that people who finish high school and beyond are able to persevere ... and are adaptable. all of those areas come into play in health.''
while there may be some truth to the notion that better-educated people have less physically taxing jobs, the study was adjusted to account for those factors, said ms. o'rourke, an assistant professor at the university
the profile developed by smith and ms. o'rourke ranked factors according to their predictive value
educational level was followed by the physical activity demanded by the job, the severity of the heart attack and the patient's perception of his health after the attack
of the 109 patients who returned to work, 78 had at least a high school education and a job that demanded only low levels of physical activity. just 15 patients fitting that description did not return to work within the first year
on the other end of the spectrum, 27 patients who failed to complete high school and had physically taxing jobs did not return to work within the first year. however, 31 patients in the same group returned within the year. drum-beating</head>
thousands of peole prayed, cheered, danced, beat drums and observed other traditions today as a total eclipse of the sun darkened a wide area of indonesia and the southern philippines
the sun was blacked out by the shadow of the moon for up to four minutes along a 108-mile swath that moved from the indian ocean across indonesia and the southern philippine island of mindanao
a partial eclipse was visible across a wide area of asia as far west as india _ including southeast asia, china, japan and new guinea as well as parts of australia and the pacific islands
scientists said the eclipse would end at sunset in the gulf of alaska
clouds obscured the solar spectacular in jakarta, indonesia, hong kong and in the eastern mindanao city of davao, where thousands of tourists and scientists had gathered to observe the eclipse
but it was visible for about 3 minutes in this city about 650 miles southeast of manila despite early scattered clouds. president corazon aquino flew in to witness the event
richard fisher of the high altitude observatory in boulder, colo., said that despite scattered clouds, scientists were confident they had taken useful pictures of the eclipse
in jakarta, wilson sinambela of the national institute of aeronautics said a total eclipse was observed in several parts of the country, including by about 1,000 tourists in the south sumatra capital palembang
he said thousands of indonesians prayed and beat drums to herald the start of the eclipse, which began in southwestern sumatra before heading on to the philippines
in kuala lumpur, where a partial eclipse blocked out about 80 percent of the sun, some malaysian hindus visited temples to pray for protection against harm during the eclipse
in kurukshetra, india, an estimated 1 million pilgrims dipped into the waters of the sacred sannihit and brahmsarover tanks after a public address system announced the start of the eclipse. hymns were chanted and conch shells blown during the ceremony about 90 miles north of new delhi
clouds blocked the first moments of the eclipse in general santos city. but the cloud cover broke, setting off wild cheering among the thousands who watched the phenomenon in a scorching tropical heat
street lights switched on, and members of the naragcas tribe, in the city for a festival, danced in the streets to the beat of drums
in baguio city, 130 miles north of manila, pregnant women of the local ilocano community rinsed their hair during the eclipse with water dripped from burned rice straws in a traditional ritual
according to local superstition, babies conceived during or shortly before an eclipse will be deformed unless their mothers practice the ritual
many other filipinos marked the eclipse by going to church. the philippines is asia's only predominately christian country
this phenomenon is a clear reminder from god for mankind to repent its sins,'' said theresa teopengco, a government employee
officials said about 20,000 tourists and scientists from around the world had come to the southern philippines to watch the eclipse, the last one expected here for at least 50 years
scientists said the area afforded the best opportunity to witness and study the eclipse because skies are usually clear this time of year
but in davao city, 60 miles to the northeast, morning clouds sent hundreds scurrying to the airport for flights to general santos
church bells in davao tolled while police and civilians set off firecrackers and fired weapons in the air to mark the eclipse
in manila, thousands turned out under clear skies to see the partial eclipse that blocked about 75 percent of the sun's surface at its height
police said four people were injured when a passenger bus collided with a jeep during the eclipse
the drivers were probably looking skyward when the accident occurred,'' said policeman ricardo manansala. ``it's impossible to gaze at the sky and drive a vehicle at the same time.''
solar eclipses occur when the moon positions itself between the earth and the sun. the chinese first recorded a total solar eclipse in 2137 b.c., regarding them as signs of a battle to death between the sun and the dragon
