angela patricia schembeck's birth made it a hat trick for the schembeck family. she became the third-generation st. patrick's day baby of the clan that traces its roots to ireland
thursday was her father's 23rd birthday and his father's 47th birthday
it's a miracle. it's absolutely incredible,'' said the baby's father, kevin schembeck. ``this is the best birthday present we could have ever received.''
angela arrived three days late at long island jewish medical center
the schembecks, all of college park, were celebrating in the nursery with a birthday cake baked by the baby's grandmother
my mom baked the cake yesterday so it only has my dad's name and mine on it,'' said schembeck. ``we'll have to add angela's name to it from now on
what makes this so overwhelming is that it was all natural; nothing was used to stimulate the labor,'' he said
the baby's mother, doreen, 22, said that when the birth went past the due date she had a feeling that the baby would be born on the 17th
schembeck said the mutual birthday has been good for him and his father, paul
it's always been the best day of the year for us,'' said schembeck. ``we've always had lots of laughs, lots of parties and lots of good times.''
after 60 years in office, gordon olson would gladly give up his post as cottonwood lake township treasurer-clerk, but instead he has won re-election to yet another term
not that the job entails all that much responsibility _ the township only has nine households
we're about running out of people for these township jobs,'' said olson, 85. ``we have a few younger people here but they are young and single; we don't know how long they will be around
it's just a job, but somebody has do do it.''
township board chairman leon driessen of butte has been in office for 44 or 45 years, olson said
mike nechiporenko, a board supervisor, has quite a few years in, too,'' olson said
when olson was first elected township clerk in 1928, his father, magnus, was treasurer and driessen's father, henry, was acting chairman. the clerk and treasurer jobs were combined later
twenty-six families farmed in cottonwood lake township then. today there are nine families in the township, several of whom no longer farm
people don't turn out for township elections. usually, the only voters are the officers themselves, though they say they follow the correct election procedures anyway
miss america may have been a hit in atlantic city. but unless she's a native of the north, she wouldn't stand a chance in the fort yukon spring carnival queen contest
entrants in the annual competition, which beings march 25, must demonstrate skills that could come in handy in this northeast alaska town _ but might not go over too well on national tv
first, the tea-making contest. each of the young women must build a fire on the snow, melt enough snow to make one cup, boil the water and brew the tea
then there's the snowshoe race. there's not much call for three-inch heels in this secluded yukon river community of less than 700 people
finally, queen candidates must show their prowess at skinning a snowshoe hare, known in some parts of alaska as a ``lowbush moose.'' not surprisingly, the event is not a favorite of most entrants
but in other respects, the contest is similar to the miss america pageant. all contestants must display some special talent, answer impromptu questions and appear in an evening gown
the winner will preside over the carnival, which runs through april 2
government lawyers say that deception by a former fbi agent led to claims by teamsters president jackie presser that the fbi authorized him to start a union payroll-padding scheme
the justice department lawyers said thursday they believe a trial jury should determine whether the fbi gave presser and two other union officials authorization to allegedly embezzle money from his own union local's treasury, as presser's lawyers contend
the government ``has taken the position that fbi agents never authorized any embezzlement,'' the justice department's organized crime strike force said in documents filed thursday in u.s. district court. it also said the so-called authorization defense raises ``factual issues which only a trial jury may resolve.''
presser, 60, is the leader of the 1.6 million-member union and also is secretary-treasurer of teamsters local 507 in cleveland. he was indicted on may 16, 1986, on two charges of labor racketeering, one count of embezzlement, and two counts of filing false reports with the labor department
harold friedman, teamsters vice president and local 507 president, and anthony hughes, the local's recording secretary, are scheduled to stand trial with presser on july 12
the indictment alleged that presser, in his capacity as a local 507 officer, masterminded a $700,000 scheme to pay four people who received union money without doing any work for the union
presser's lawyers say the fbi told presser, who was an fbi informant, to pay certain people who had connections to organized crime so the agency could obtain information from them through presser
in documents filed with the court march 7, presser's lawyers said the government has supplied statements written in 1985 by former cleveland-based fbi agents patrick j. foran and martin p. mccann jr. that say the agency authorized presser to make the payments
but prosecutors william s. lynch, stephen h. jigger and bernard a. smith referred to a finding last week by a federal appeals court in washington that the authorization defense is a ``tangled web of deception'' and is ``the product of a calculated lie.''
the appeals court's finding came in the federal prosecution of robert s. friedrick, a former cleveland-based fbi agent who was fired after an indictment alleged he concocted a scheme to avert the indictment of presser
most of the evidence against friedrick was ruled invalid when a judge found that justice department lawyers misled him by making him believe he was immune from prosecution
a storm dusted the midwest and parts of the south today with snow after snapping power lines and closing schools in arkansas
there were people who planned to lay out in bikinis, and they're packing up their snow suits,'' said donna dickey, a university of arkansas student whose spring break began today
the storm knocked out power to about 3,000 homes and businesses thursday, arkansas power &amp; light co. spokesman charles kelly said
harrison, ark., reported 22 inches of snow on the ground, while most northern parts of the state had 4 to 8 inches
forecasters posted winter storm warnings for nothern arkansas and western kentucky. snow advisories also were posted for southern illinois, western tennessee, southern indiana, ohio, northern west virginia and southwest pennsylvania
early today, snow fell across lower michigan, southwest ohio, indiana, illinois, southern and eastern missouri and northwest kentucky. rain and snow fell across southeast missouri and southwest kentucky. rain fell in western tennessee, arkansas, mississippi, louisiana and eastern texas
snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 a.m. est included an inch at columbia, st. louis and springfield, mo. during the same period, galveston, texas, had nearly 2 inches, lake charles, la., had slightly more than an inch and palacios, texas, had about three-quarters of an inch
the temperature in midland, texas, dropped to 23 degrees, tying the record low for the date set in 1934
in florida, a cold snap that sent temperatures to record lows showed signs of easing today. the cold did little damage to crops, officials said
today's forecast called for snow from southeast missouri and eastern arkansas across much of tennessee and the ohio valley into the central appalachians and new york state; snow scattered over michigan; rain and thunderstorms from the central gulf coast states across east tennessee, georgia and northern and central florida; rain spreading east across the carolinas; and scattered rain along the middle atlantic coast
highs were expected to be in the 40s or 50s in much of the nation; the 30s from north dakota across the upper mississippi valley, the ohio valley and the great lakes into northern new england; the 60s and 70s over the west coast and western portions of the plateau, florida and southern georgia; the 60s along the central gulf coast and along the coast of the carolinas; and the 80s over much of the desert southwest
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 1 degree below zero at laramie, wyo., to 70 at key west, fla
