alderman joe lanahan may no longer have to worry about which side of the bed he sleeps on
lanahan's right to retain his city council seat has sparked heated debate in this st. louis suburb of 3,800 people since just after christmas, when he told the council he had his land surveyed and found that about half his house was in the city and half in madison county
lanahan said he sleeps in the city, however, because the line falls across one corner at the foot of his bed. he also pays city taxes
the troy city council on thursday unanimously approved an ordinance requiring city officials to live entirely within city limits. but all members agreed that if lanahan annexed the rest of his property to the city, he could remain an alderman
lanahan said he was pleased with the decision and will seek to have the section annexed. a crowd of about 50 supporters applauded when the agreement was finally reached
this has been a real hassle for us,'' he said. ``i'm glad to see the support of the people. you really don't know how many friends you have till something like this happens.''
three petitions supporting lanahan containing 380 signatures were presented to the council before the vote
terrorist violence in northern ireland briefly cast a pall over st. patrick's day celebrations in new york, boston and other cities, but for most of the more than 1.5 million parade-goers the usual high spirits flowed freely
new york's traditional parade up fifth avenue began in midtown thursday with somber words from political and religious leaders, but soon the bands, sunshine and some surreptitious sipping produced the usual festive atmosphere among the more than 1 million marchers and watchers
more than 200,000 people crowded the sidewalk in downtown chicago to watch the 40,000 marchers, 50 floats and 45 bands that made up the annual parade. portions of the chicago river were dyed green for the day of revelry
in kansas city, mo., 70,000 irish and would-be irish parade-goers braved a wet snowfall, while 321,000 people thronged the streets of savannah, ga., in the 164th edition of that city's st. patrick's day procession, the second-largest behind new york's
new york's cardinal john j. o'conner, in his homily at a mass preceding the parade, reflected on a terrorist's grenade-and-gunfire attack on an irish republican army funeral in belfast, northern ireland, that left three dead and 68 wounded the day before
i hope everyone marching will remember those killed, catholic or protestant,'' said o'connor, who reviewed the parade from the steps of st. patrick's cathedral. ``the violence is insane.''
o'connor said new york's parade was not canceled because ``that's not the irish way.''
in boston, where the parade is scheduled for sunday, mayor raymond l. flynn said the root of the violence in northern ireland was ``the utter despair that british rule has perpetrated.''
the crowds, in various shades of green and varying stages of sobriety, were generally well-behaved and few arrests were reported. in new york, 15 summonses were issued for drinking in public, and only one person was arrested for disorderly conduct
in washington, president reagan proved his irish wasn't up over past disputes with congress when he toasted ``seamus wright'' _ otherwise known as house speaker jim wright _ during a capitol hill luncheon
standing thursday at a table covered with a green cloth and decorated with green carnations, the president wished wright ``warm words on a cold evening and a full moon on a dark night.''
wright, who wore a green jacket and green tie, declared that ``we've buried all differences that might exist between political parties and branches of government on this day of st. patrick.'' he toasted reagan, 77, for his youthfulness
