the aids virus could spread among american high school and college students because the young tend not to believe health warnings are meant for them, according to surgeon general c. everett koop
my greatest concern is with the group aged 15 to 24,'' koop told a convention of hospital administrators thursday
officials may have a better idea of the extent of the aids virus among college students by the end of the year as more colleges go along with a u.s. centers for disease control request to conduct blind blood testing, koop said
under such procedures, already used by hospitals in about 40 cities, blood drawn for other purposes is tested for aids without the sample being identified by patient
he noted that sexually transmitted diseases in general are rising at the steepest rate in 16 years ``in spite of the tremendous educational campaign in 1987, where for the first time in history we were discussing in the print media and on television very blunt statements about aids and sexually transmitted disease.''
if there is hiv (the aids virus) out there, and we know there is, then there can't help but be some infection going on that we're not going to see until we get down the road about five years,'' he told the federation of american health systems
it can take five years or more for aids to develop after a person contracts the virus
so with teen-agers, who think that they're immortal, who always think the health message is meant for the person next to them, who have sort of a sense that risk-taking is sort of fun, we have our most difficult target group, especially with regard to heterosexual transmission.''
earlier, the federal official who oversees the medicare and medicaid health programs for the elderly and poor told the hospital executives they have been given ``an almost impossible task: controlling physician decision-making.''
there is deep-seated ambivalence in america about intruding on physician decision-making,'' said dr. william l. roper, head of the health care financing administration. ``but we cannot have both physician autonomy and cost constraint.''
a professor pleaded innocent to charges he lied about the dalkon shield's safety when he testified for a.h. robins co. in its attempt to disprove a woman's claim that the contraceptive device made her sterile
dr. louis g. keith remained free on a $10,000 appearance bond after entering his plea here thursday. he said he voluntarily took a leave of absence from northwestern university in chicago, where he teaches obstetrics and gynecology, until the case is resolved
keith testified as an expert witness for a.h. robins, the richmond, va.-based manufacturer of the device, during trial of the lawsuit brought against the company by linda harre of tampa five years ago
the 53-year-old professor told the jury he had conducted experiments that verified the safety of the intrauterine device
but a federal indictment announced march 3 contends that keith ``did not design, direct, conduct or do the scientific experiments about which he testified.''
keith is charged with obstruction of justice and lying eight times on the witness stand. if convicted on all counts, he faces 45 years in prison and $85,000 in fines
the case is being prosecuted by attorneys from the u.s. justice department in washington
mrs. harre, 39, alleged the shield made her sterile, but she lost her $12.5 million lawsuit. she won a new trial in march 1985 when the 11th circuit court of appeals in atlanta issued an opinion that attacked the veracity of keith's testimony
five months later, robins filed for protection from its creditors in federal bankruptcy court in richmond due to the more than 14,300 lawsuits filed against the company by women who claim to have suffered pelvic infections, sterility or spontaneous abortions from using the dalkon shield
the bankruptcy filing barred future action on the pending lawsuits
ann c. tighe, of the chicago law firm representing keith, said: ``my client has proclaimed his innocence. we will expect him to be vindicated.''
after the brief hearing thursday, u.s. magistrate thomas wolfson set the trial for may before judge william castagna
a black man went to the gallows alone today after a judge granted a stay of execution to the ``sharpeville six,'' who were aided in their appeal by an international clemency campaign
the pre-dawn hanging of tsepo letsoara, 24, concluded without fanfare, while world leaders, clergymen and politicians continued to plea with the government to save the ``sharpeville six.''
letsoara was convicted of the murder of a black woman in a port elizabeth township in october 1985, during nationwide racial unrest. the victim, grace mvetye, was killed by the ``necklace'' method, in which a gasoline-soaked tire was placed around her neck and set ablaze
the ``sharpeville six,'' five black men and a woman, would have joined letsoara on the gallows today had pretoria supreme court justice willem human not granted a one-month stay of execution thursday. human made his decision after defense lawyers presented evidence of perjury by one of the prosecution's chief witnesses
human granted the convicts four weeks to apply for a retrial
the case was controversial because the six were convicted under the principle of ``common cause,'' which held them responsible for the september 1984 death of town councilor jacob dlamini because they among a mob of 100 that stoned and burned dlamini to death in sharpeville
dlamini was killed on the first day of riots that lasted nearly three years and claimed more than 2,500 black lives
president p.w. botha had ignored pleas from leaders of most western nations and from countries and organizations around the world to stop the executions. the government said human's decision ``proves the wisdom of the state president and his ministers in deciding not to impede the due process of law
the government also indicated a link between the scheduled hangings and a car bomb that exploded thursday in krugersdorp, killing three black people and injuring 20 people. the explosion occurred in a magistrate's court where the sharpeville six had been held briefly between their arrest and trial
police offered a $25,000 reward for information leading to the arrest of a white man they say is a member of the outlawed african national congress. the man was described as the prime suspect in the bombing
deputy minister of information stoffel van der merwe said neither pressure from overseas nor car bombs would persuade the government to interfere in a court case
the star, an independent johannesburg newspaper, reported today that botha granted clemency three weeks ago to a black policeman who was sentenced to death for murdering a youth two years ago in mamelodi, the black township outside pretoria
a spokesman for the department of justice said botha commuted constable george john sindane's death sentence to eight years in prison. the spokesman said sindane was one of five people whose death sentences were commuted this year
in other developments thursday,
_ attorneys said a $2.25 million wrongful arrest lawsuit was begun against the ministry of law and order after charges of sedition and subversion were dropped against a black roman catholic nun and 13 others who lived in black townships outside krugersdorp
sister bernard ncube, president of the federation of transvaal women, spent 16 months in detention, including 13 in solitary confinement, after being charged. the state alleged that the group established ``kangaroo'' courts, campaigned against the police and initiated a boycott of white-owned shops and buses
the charges were dropped thursday after the prosecution refused to supply a court with details of the alleged acts
_also, the attorney for freed african national congress leader govan mbeki said the government denied his request for a passport, which he sought to visit his three children living in exile. attorney priscilla jana said no reason was given for the denial
mbeki was freed from prison in november after serving 24 years of a life sentence for treason and sabotage in connection with his activities as national chairman of the anc. his oldest son, thabo, is an executive member of the anc in exile in lusaka, zambia
since his release from prison, mbeki has been restricted to the port elizabeth area, and banned from giving public speeches or news interviews
an 84-year-old man distracted two knife-wielding burglars by leading them to a cache of diamonds, then shot one of them with an old gun he had hidden in a drawer
lou marks said it was the first time he'd fired the .32-caliber gun that he had owned for 20 years
when i put my finger on that gun, i said, `dear lord, you have saved my life,' and i shot him point-blank,'' marks said thursday. ``i don't feel a bit of remorse. they weren't going to let me live.''
raymond edward sumther, 39, was in stable condition at bayfront medical center today with bullet wounds in his neck and chest. police said he would be charged with armed burglary
gary glover, a 30-year-old transient marks said he once helped, was charged with burglary and booked into the pinellas county jail on $15,000 bail
marks' daughter, marion macri, 59, who lives in the house, said the incident began wednesday night with a knock on the door. when her father opened it, two men forced their way in, threw marks to the floor and told mrs. macri to get down as well. they held the two at knifepoint, taking $68 in cash from marks and about $20 from mrs. macri's purse
suddenly marks remembered he owned a gun
then i says, `i've got a lot of jewelry you can have. take it and go,''' said marks, who sells jewelry from his home. ``when i said, `follow me, i'll show you my diamonds,' i knew i was halfway home.''
as one would-be robber busied himself with grabbing three quarter-carat diamond rings and loose gems, marks opened a drawer he said held more loot
it really held the gun
after i shot him (twice) he just stood there and looked mortified,'' marks said. both men fled. the wounded man was quickly picked up by police, and the second suspect was found thursday
we kind of blame ourselves for letting them in,'' mrs. macri said
nbc correspondent john hart is leaving the network at the end of the month to pursue other interests
hart, whose thoughtful, poetic style has been featured in his pieces for ``nbc nightly news,'' also served as saturday anchor for the broadcast and anchors nbc's news digests
hart joined nbc in 1975 as a political correspondent and later served as chief european correspondent. before nbc, hart spent about 15 years at cbs, serving as washington anchor and then new york anchor of the ``cbs morning news'' from 1968 to 1973
hart said thursday that the decision to leave ``just kind of grew over several years. the business changed and i changed and i guess we changed differently.''
nbc news president lawrence k. grossman said nbc news would welcome him back if he ever wanted to return. hart said he didn't know what he would do yet, except get his hectic life back to normal
two other prominent network journalists, bill moyers and roger mudd, have left network news for public television in recent years, citing dissatisfaction with the increasing importance of budgets and marketing in news divisions
hart said such issues affected his decision, but he declined to discuss them lest appear he was leaving the network with bad feelings
i'm not going away mad,'' he said. ``it's really a very positive step. i'm really grateful to the business for the life it's given me. i've been able to witness first-hand the major events in my life. i wouldn't do it differently in any way.'' del rio.</note>
roland drew, a movie actor who quit hollywood in the 1940s for a second career in dressmaking, died at home of natural causes, his son said. he was 87
drew's roles included that of prince baron of vulcan in the flash gordon serials of the late 1930s which featured buster crabbe as the adventurous earthman
drew, who died thursday, received a letter requesting his autograph as recently as three months ago, said his son, damon drew
some of roland drew's films, such as ``hitler, beast of berlin,'' have been shown on local television in recent years
the appeal of stardom faded for drew during the 1940s, and he quit acting to enter the garment industry as a representative and maker, his son said. he manufactured women's dresses under the label damon originals
as a romantic leading man, drew co-starred with dolores del rio in the silent film ``ramona.'' the two later were engaged to be married, but the romance fizzled, damon drew said
roland drew married dorothy dearing, a former busby berkeley girl, in 1946. she died in 1965
in addition to his son, drew is survived by two grandsons
a soviet spacecraft bound for phobos will carry a plaque commemorating the martian moon's discovery in 1877 by american astronomer asaph hall
the national aeronautics and space administration said thursday the soviets agreed to the idea ``in the continuing spirit of cooperation in space.''
the phobos mission, scheduled for launch in july, should reach the martian moon in the spring of 1989. there will be two spacecraft, which will enter phobos' orbit and release probes to land on the moon
the two moons of mars, phobos and deimos, were discovered in august 1877 by astronomer asaph hall of the u.s. naval observatory in washington, d.c., using a 26-inch refracting telescope
nasa on thursday presented to representatives of the soviet academy of sciences a photographic transfer on aluminum of hall's telescope logbook page dated aug. 17, 1877. it was turned over at a lunar and planatary science conference at the johnson space center in houston
hall first detected an object moving around mars on aug. 11 and recorded it as a star. the log for the 17th records the position angles and separations of phobos and deimos and notes that phobos is ``faint and difficult to observe.'' three days later, the naval observatory announced the discovery of the martian satellites and said they had been named for the horses of mars, the roman god of war
nasa said the soviets have agreed to place an aluminum plaque on either the main body of one of the spacecraft or on one of the landing vehicles. separate moved as a0564 on drew.</note>
roland drew, a movie actor who quit hollywood in the 1940s for a second career in dressmaking, died at home of natural causes thursday, his son said. he was 87
drew's roles included that of prince baron of vulcan in the flash gordon serials of the late 1930s which featured buster crabbe as the adventurous earthman
the appeal of stardom faded for drew during the 1940s, and he quit acting to enter the garment industry as a representative and maker, said his son, damon drew. he manufactured women's dresses under the label damon originals
john p. ``jack'' sutherland, a former white house correspondent for u.s. news and world report, died wednesday of a heart attack at age 67
sutherland had reported on the u.s. presidency from harry s. truman through gerald ford's administration. he then became associate editor of the u.s. news washington letter, the post he held until he retired in 1985
kathleen noonan, who preserved the manuscript of her irish father's working-class novel, ``the ragged trousered philanthropists,'' died saturday at the age of 95
it was first issued in 1914 after his daughter produced the manuscript and was introduced to publisher grant richards
robert noonan's novel, written under the pseudonym robert tressell, describes life among his fellow house painters and decorators in the english south coast town of hastings, which he called mugsborough
he died of tuberculosis in 1911 in liverpool while waiting to emigrate to the united states. he was buried in a pauper's grave
buffalo bill's buffalo-hide coat, eight guns and a tomahawk go on the auction block today in the largest sale yet of wild west memorabilia collected by the legendary william f. cody
the 300 items offered for sale belong to san franciscan greg martin, who acquired the collection after he had been unable to buy the single item he wanted
it was a double-barrel shotgun that brought martin to a warehouse in billings, mont., last year
i saw it up in storage ... and my pulse skipped a beat,'' said martin, who offered to buy the westley-richards english shotgun inscribed to cody
when the elderly owner refused to sell just one item, martin wrote a check for $300,000 for the entire collection and took it out of storage for the first time in 20 years
he is the living symbol of the west and one of the most famous americans who ever lived,'' said martin, 49, a gun collector and aficionado of american history. ``the way we look at the west is because of how buffalo bill showed it to us.''
the collection, to be auctioned by butterfield &amp; butterfield, includes the buffalo-hide coat worn by cody and the gun he carried as a 14-year-old pony express rider. cody's single-action colt revolver, the type he used as a u.s. army scout, is one of eight guns in the collection
items such as a tomahawk from cody's friend d.f. ``white beaver'' powell, along with dozens of photographs, show bills and theater tickets chronicle cody's life as an indian fighter, buffalo hunter and scout who along with shooting champion w. ``doc'' carver founded the first wild west show
for 11 years, after dime-novel writer ned buntline persuaded cody to appear in the first ``scouts of the prairie'' show, cody traveled between eastern theaters and the plains
the collection consists of items preserved by cody's adoring sister, julia cody goodman, and includes the cody family bible and letters to julia in which cody discussed a troubled marriage, the death of his son and other intimate events
the engraved shotgun, the only item not up for auction, will remain in martin's home, a three-story victorian crammed with western artifacts including a likeness of chief sitting bull and the pearl-handled smith &amp; wesson revolvers owned by annie oakley
martin, a former real estate broker, once paid $1 million for bill harrah's pony express museum in reno, and maintains his collection with the help of his wife, petra, a former federal judge in germany
he flew to billings in search of the collection when he learned julia cody goodman's daughter, josie, sold it for $1 to a woman named stella foote to keep it from going to the cody museum in cody, wyo., martin said
the collection traveled the world under the sponsorship of the department of commerce before it was placed in storage by foote
banana slug backers defeated abalone admirers in an california assembly battle to name the official state mollusk
assemblyman trice harvey tried in vain thursday to add the abalone to a bill that would give the mollusk title to the banana slug. his amendment failed 36-37
i feel there should be a sharing of this,'' harvey said. ``the banana slug could be the inland mollusk. the abalone can be the marine mollusk.''
he said the abalone was deserving because it is ``working hard to try to save the endangered sea otter.''
the banana slug is yucky. abalone is delicious,'' he added
assemblyman byron sher, author of the banana slug bill, opposed the amendment, but said, ``i respect mr. harvey and enjoy abalone, or is it the other way around?''
he said the amendment would be a disservice to the dynamite bluebird troop of redwood city, which did the research and convinced him to carry the slug bill
also, he said, ``the abalone is not an accessible mollusk.'' not only does it live underwater, but it costs $38 a pound
a strong earthquake shook the japanese capital before dawn today, rocking skyscrapers, rattling dishes and injuring at least nine people
japan's central meteorological agency said the tremor registered 6.1 on the richter scale _ meaning a severe quake. it said there was no danger of a tsunami, or seismic tidal waves
the epicenter was 55 miles below ground in the eastern part of tokyo, the agency said
the japan broadcasting corp. said nine people suffered injuries in tokyo and neighboring areas. police had no reports of damage
tremors were felt throughout the area and in parts of the tohoku region to the north. the quake struck at 5:34 a.m., disrupting train service throughout the capital just before the morning rush hour
i could hear dishes rattling in people's kitchens,'' said a woman in kamakura, a southern suburb. ``trees were shaking and there was a rumbling sound.''
tokyo is on a major western pacific fault and is earthquake-prone. most temblors are mild, causing little or no damage
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude, so 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 6.5
an earthquake of 3.5 can cause slight damage, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage and 6 severe damage
the san francisco earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the richter scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3
the poor lose more years of life to diseases, especially those linked to drinking and smoking, according to a study comparing death rates and income
the study by oregon officials tried to pin down the effect of income by focusing solely on one racial group, whites, in one urban county, multnomah, which includes portland, from 1976 to 1984
five income levels were established by the study, published thursday by the u.s. centers for disease control. as income increased, the study found there was a decrease in ``years of potential life lost,'' a statistic that assumes each victim would have lived to age 70
the study found that those in census tracts with a median household income of less than $12,100 per year had a rate of ``years of potential life lost'' that was 50 percent higher than the overall rate and nearly twice as high as the rate for the highest income group, above $19,300 a year
the greatest difference between the groups was found in deaths attributed to alcoholism. the lowest income group's rating for years lost to alcoholism was 3.5 times greater than average and 11.7 times higher than that of the most affluent group
i think to the extent that portland and oregon are like the rest of the country, we can conclude that people in low incomes have higher rates of premature mortality overall, and in particular alcoholism and alcohol-related mortality,'' said dr. gus birkhead, a cdc epidemiologist
they also found that chronic obstructive lung disease, which probably means cigarette smoking, (is more prevalent) in the poorer group.''
birkhead said drinking and smoking may be higher among lower-income people because of a lack of education about the dangers of those activities, ``or it could be as a way to escape the frustrations of life.''
poorer people also have less access to medical care, he said
the oregon study noted that past studies of alcholism and income have prompted theories that doctors are less likely to report alcholism on the death certificates of affluent people
however, the authors said, the oregon center for health statistics questions doctors about any cause of death possibly related to alcohol. the reported death rate for alcoholic liver disease and cirrhosis was twice as high in oregon as the national average in 1984
birkhead said the study suggests that education programs need to be focused on lower income groups, especially programs about the health dangers of cigarettes and alcohol
a fire swept through a restaurant in this balaeric islands resort city today, killing five people and sending smoke into an apartment building above, officials said
twenty-one others were evacuated from the smoke-filled casa sueca during the early morning blaze, officials said
the fire broke out in the bellmar restaurant just after 3 a.m. when a worker dropped a lit cigarette into a paint can causing an explosion, said fire department spokesman guillermo garcia
the man was burned to death, while firemen discovered four other victims, all of them swedish, dead of smoke inhalation on the second floor of the four-story building, garcia said
police identified the four swedes as grace rosemarie birgitta prytz, 46, of eskilstuna, eva lisa tammi, 21, of arboga, elly tammi, no age given, also of arboga, and hokkannen pertti, age and hometown unknown
retired army maj. gen. richard secord, under indictment in the iran-contra affair, today said he ``absolutely'' doesn't expect to serve time for his role in the secret weapons deals
i think the legal system itself is going to see the merit of our case and will dismiss this indictment very quickly,'' he said on abc-tv's ``good morning america.''
asked if he expected to ``do time'' on the charges, secord said: ``absolutely not.''
i don't see any merit whatsoever to the case that's been brought by the special counsel,'' secord continued
he said his lawyers will argue that independent counsel lawrence walsh ``is running amok and without authority'' in prosecuting the case
i think that this is a completely uncontrollable and probably illegal independent counsel ... trying to justify the expenditure of millions and millions and millions of dollars of taxpayer's money and 15 months of effort on a witch hunt,'' secord said
secord said that in return for doing his duty and responding to requests from the white house, he finds himself ``trapped by a set of circumstances which none of us dreamed could ever be criminalized.''
i guess if i were to write a book, i'd proably entitle it, `if the phones rings again, don't answer.'''
county officials have removed an obstacle that kept art students from drawing nude models: bathing suits
the cobb county arts commission voted unanimously thursday to overturn a ban on nude models imposed several weeks ago by community services department chief bob ash. ash had been concerned about how the community would perceive nude modeling, even though it was limited to advanced, adults-only classes
judge mary staley, chairwoman of the arts commission, said members realized the value of the nude as art. ``it's a classical approach to developing your skills as an artist. as long as precautions are taken to avoid exposing people who do not wish to be exposed.''
the commission said nudes could only be used in advanced, adult arts classes and that warning signs must be posted on classroom doors. in addition, the panel also voted to require students between ages 15 and 18 to obtain written parental consent before they can attend classes with nude models
ash has said he would abide by the arts commission's decision
a 4-year-old boy ate food scraps on the floor with his family's german shepherd for about a year and can only howl and whine like a dog because of parental neglect, police said today
the mass-circulation bild newspaper said the female german shepherd had ``raised'' the child, but authorities said that was an exaggeration. bild identified the boy only as horst
the child is unable to speak, because his parents never spoke to him,'' said mettmann police spokesman wolfgang schauer, adding the boy only makes dog-like sounds
the dog had become a bigger part of his (the child's) life than his parents,'' said the police spokesman in mettmann, eight miles from duesseldorf
schauer told the associated press in a telephone interview the boy routinely shared food scraps with the animal on the kitchen floor of the family's apartment and that the boy did not know how to eat at the table
authorities did not release the family's name, but said the parents were being investigated. bild said the father was a 30-year-old unemployed butcher
the couple routinely left the child alone with the dog in the apartment during the day, bild reported
the child's grandfather came for a visit last week and found the youngster on the floor sharing a piece of meat with the dog, the police spokesman said
the grandfather immediately notified authorities, and the child was taken to a children's hospital in nearby wuppertal, said schauer
bild said the child's only word was ``asta,'' the dog's name
a vessel carrying the first shipment of a japanese automaker's u.s.-built cars to japan has resumed its interrupted voyage
the green bay left portland thursday night. it originally set out march 7 from portland with its cargo of 540 honda accord coupes. it turned back sunday with a cracked ballast tank and cracked fuel tank after encountering a storm in the northern pacific ocean
repairs were completed this week at the swan island shipyard
the ship's owner, central gulf lines inc. of new orleans, declined to specify the cost of repairs or the extent of damages
the u.s. coast guard revealed the nature of the damage after inspecting the u.s.-flagged ship
a gala reception next tuesday to welcome the ship at narashino port, east of tokyo, was rescheduled for april 8
tamil rebels armed with pick axes, swords and daggers killed 13 villagers, military and police sources said today
the attack thursday occurred near the historic buddhist temple town of digawapi in ampara district, about 125 miles east of colombo, said the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity
more than 110 people, most of them members of the sinhalese majority, have been killed in the past 18 days in a series of attacks and reprisal attacks. authorities have blamed the violence on the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, the largest tamil militant group
at least six women and two infants were among the victims of the massacre. some reports said the toll could be 15, the sources said
tamil extremists used swords and daggers to kill the villagers because gunshots would have alerted two sri lankan military camps nearby, the sources said
the tigers have been fighting for a separate homeland in the northern and eastern provinces, where most of the tamils live
the attack came hours after a sri lankan minister, gamini dissanayeke, returned from india and announced indian and sri lankan troops will patrol together in the east
the tigers oppose an indian-sponsored peace accord signed last july. the accord was designed to end the 4-year-old tamil guerrilla war against the sinhalese-dominated government and the sinhalese ethnic group
it would grant some autonomy to minority tamils in the north and east. more than 50,000 indian troops are in sri lanka to enforce the india-sri lanka peace pact and disarm the tigers
under the accord, sri lankan security forces were confined to their barracks and only indian troops were dealing with the tamils
both tamil and sinhalese militants oppose the accord. the tamil tigers have refused to surrender their arms, as called for in the pact. many sinhalese say the accord makes too many concessions to tamils
india and sri lanka both have accused tamil militants of killing sinhalese in retaliatory attacks that began march 2 with the killing of 18 sinhalese in morawewa village in eastern trincomalee district
on march 4, tamil rebels used land mines to blow up a crowded truck in the same area. at least 26 sinhalese died in the explosion
a band of men suspected of being sinhalese extremists then killed 22 tamil bus passengers near horawapotana village, also in trincomalee district
the predominantly hindu tamils make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people, 75 percent of whom are sinhalese buddhists. tamils say they are discriminated against by the sinhalese. defects</head>
a cloud of dioxin spread over an area of italy by an industrial accident in 1976 apparently caused no significant increase in birth defects, according to a six-year study
the study reported in today's edition of the journal of the american medical association focused on babies born in and around seveso, italy, from 1977 through 1982. another study in today's journal reported that a blood test developed in sweden might simplify the job of determining how many vietnam veterans have been exposed to the defoliant agent orange
the blood test is less expensive and less invasive than the standard test of fat tissue, which requires surgery, said wayne p. wilson, executive director of the new jersey state commission on agent orange
a team led by dr. peter c. kahn of rutgers university compared both tests in a study involving 27 men and found little difference in the results
although the tests now can be performed only in sweden and at the u.s. centers for disease control, wilson on thursday, urged their increased use
dioxin, a byproduct of pesticide manufacture, causes cancer in laboratory animals, but has not been directly linked to cancers in humans
the july 1976 accident at a chemical factory exposed more than 37,200 residents of seveso and three neighboring towns in northern italy to dioxin _ the largest population ever contaminated by the chemical
the six physicians who performed the six-year study wrote that it confirms previous analyses which concluded that if there is any increased risk related to dioxin, ``the overall risk is unlikely to be large or might be limited to very rare and specific birth defects.''
the italian doctors considered as defects only congenital malformations that were present and obvious at birth. congenital problems that manifest themselves later, such as mental retardation, were not considered
the seveso congenital malformations registry, established shortly after the accident, found that in 15,291 births, 742 infants were born with malformations, a rate of 48.5 per 1,000
the prevalence of malformations over the same period in a nearby, uncontaminated area used as a control was 48.8 per 1,000 births, the study found
the quantity of dioxin released into the environment ``seemed to be enormous'' but was never precisely determined, according to the study
still more important,'' the study concluded, ``is the fact that no infant with a major malformation was identified in the most highly contaminated zone.''
levels of dioxin concentration found on the ground in the area surrounding the factory were nearly 1,000 times higher than the levels termed safe by state and federal officials after a cleanup at times beach, mo
times beach is now deserted, and hundreds of families have filed lawsuits against companies and individuals over exposure to dioxin contained in waste oil sprayed on their streets as a dust-control measure in the 1970s
agent orange, used in vietnam to eliminate ground cover for viet cong and north vietnamese troops, contained the most toxic form of dioxin, 2,3,7,8-tcdd
questions about the effects of agent orange exposure have lingered since the war. some veterans have sought government compensation, contending their exposure resulted in cancers, rashes, headaches, infertility and other side effects, as well as birth defects in their children
the veterans administration has rejected the claims, saying numerous studies have found no link between exposure and reported symptoms
the socialist workers party, the subject of 16 years of illegal fbi surveillance, claimed victory after the justice department decided to withdraw an appeal and pay a damage award to the party
u.s. district judge thomas griesa had awarded the party $264,000 in damages aug. 26, 1986, ruling that an fbi campaign of wiretapping, bugging, burglaries, anonymous letters and harassment was illegal and ``patently unconstitutional.''
the rulings by judge griesa are now final,'' jack barnes, national secretary of the party, said thursday. ``this places a valuable weapon securely in the hands of every fighter for democratic rights and political liberties.''
amy brown, spokeswoman for the justice department's civil division in washington, confirmed that the department notified the u.s. district court in new york on wednesday that it was withdrawing its appeal
she referred a request for comment to assistant u.s. attorney peter salerno in manhattan, who had none
the socialist workers party, the first amendment and the rule of law have won,'' said attorney leonard b. boudin of the political rights defense fund, which represented the party
the case, filed in 1973, challenged an extensive counterintelligence operation by the federal government to infiltrate and neutralize organizations suspected of ``subversive activities.''
according to the court, the fbi planted 1,300 informers in the party and its offshoot, the young socialist alliance, between 1960 and 1976, paying them a total of $1.7 million. the fbi committed 193 burglaries and photographed or removed 9,864 party documents, the judge said
the socialist workers party, a trotskyite offshoot of the communist league, claims about 2,000 members nationwide
gunmen wounded a senior police officer, his chauffeur and two other soldiers in separate attacks today. the military said arrested a provincial deputy commander of the communist new people's army
on thursday, communist rebels killed three people in manila's so-called ``war of the streets.''
police said gunmen in a speeding car opened fire today on a vehicle carrying maj. pepito campos and his driver in suburban quezon city. police said the two were wounded, but out of danger at a local hospital
campos is chief of the special investigations division for the capital's northern police district. police said a philippine constabulary captain was arrested later as a suspect
in a separate incident, gunmen believed to be communist rebels fired on a car carrying three philippine constabulary soldiers in manila's taguig suburb. two of the soldiers were wounded, police said
on thursday, two suspected rebels shot and killed jaime javellana, a neighborhood ward leader, as he was walking along a street in manila's santa mesa district
an hour later, four men armed with .45-caliber pistols opened fire on a jeep near the university of santo tomas. two soldiers, sgt. herman pascua and constable perfecto terte, were mortally wounded. a third soldier suffered wounds in the chest and arms but survived
in san fernando, 40 miles north of here, the philippine constabulary announced the arerest of elizardo lapuz, 42, which it identified as the deputy commander of the new people's army in pampanga province
a military statement said lapuz was arrested late thursday as he left his home in the san fernando area. he offered no resistance. pampanga province, which borders manila to the north, has been a longtime rebel stronghold
in manila, police said a leaflet left near the scene of the first shooting said javellana had been slain by the rebel alex boncayao brigade because of ``crimes against the people.''
the brigade is the manila wing of the communist new people's army, which has been waging a 19-year insurgency to establish a marxist state. it has claimed responsibility for killing scores of police, soldiers and government officials in the capital since president corazon aquino took office in 1986
laugh-in'' creator george schlatter will produce a one-hour comedy series for nbc this summer called ``funny people,'' nbc entertainment president brandon tartikoff told advertising executives
schlatter will bring together a cast of comedians for the weekly show that will premiere wednesday, july 27. schlatter previously produced the landmark comedy hit ``rowan and martin's laugh in'' and ``real people'' for nbc
tartikoff told 250 advertising executives thursday at the nbc studios that the network also would have original episodes of ``sonny spoon'' this summer
if the writers guild of america strike is settled in time, nbc also plans a new situation comedy during the rerun season, he said
tartikoff, describing his no.1-rated network's coming fall season during his annual spring preview, said nbc had six series commitments _ four comedies and two dramas _ with at least 10 other comedy and 14 drama pilots in the wings
the comedy commitments include ``empty nest,'' a show about a miami doctor with two grown daughters starring richard mulligan, kristy mcnichol, dinah manhoff and david leisure. mulligan lives next door to the four women of the ``golden girls'' and will have an occasional romance with rue mcclanahan
other comedy shows include:
_``dear john,'' starring judd hirsch as a man whose wife walks out on him and must start life over
_``baby boom,'' based on the movie starring diane keaton. the show about a career woman who suddenly finds herself with a baby has not been cast
_``channel 99,'' in which marilu henner stars as a woman who takes over a failing uhf station in new york state
|attingers'' is a fa|l drama in which stephen collins stars as a restaurateur and man about town in`a manhattan-based drama that also stars blythe danner and jerry stiller
the disney hour,'' which is moving from abc, will feature a rotating schedule of series specials, including the return of fess parker as ``davy crockett,'' harry anderson as the ``absent-minded professor,'' plus other movies and specials and a third regular series to be created later
robert loggia and lance guest will star as two fbi agents in the mini-series ``favorite son,'' which was described by tartikoff as a back-door pilot, meaning it could be developed into a series featuring the two g-men
aaron spelling, whose long-term exclusive commitment to abc expired last year, is developing a new show for nbc called ``nightingales,'' about six young women who are in a student nursing program
turning to movies planned next year, tartikoff said raymond burr was returning for three more ``perry mason'' films, but he thought one of them probably would be ``perry mason's last case.''
tartikoff said nbc was considering at least 20 shows to counterprogram abc's 30-hour miniseries, ``war and remembrance.''
among the pilots being considered are ``flip side,'' about a rock legend who comes home to face his three alienated children. ex-beatle ringo starr had been cast for the lead role
tartikoff jokingly told the audience starr had been replaced by pete best _ the original drummer for the beatles, who was replaced by starr
another pilot is being prepared for singer morris day, who starred in ``purple rain'' and ``moving'' and will play a flamboyant record producer in a new comedy in development
kate capshaw of ``indiana jones and the temple of doom'' stars in the comedy pilot ``when in rome,'' about a hotshot new york newspaper woman who takes over a local newspaper in rome, n.d
tartikoff said nbc would begin in september with the summer olympics from seoul, south korea, then open its regular season with a special featuring all of its stars at disneyland, to be followed by a new ``davy crockett'' epsiode
nbc also has this year's baseball world series and football super bowl
a senior military official said today that about 100 suspected members of the japanese crime syndicate, the yakuza, slipped into the country and police were trying to place them under surveillance
philippine constabulary chief maj. gen. ramon montano told reporters in this central port city that the military was having trouble distinguishing the gangsters among the thousands of japanese tourists visiting the country
he said local authorities have been coordinating with japanese police investigators who are in manila to track down the gangsters
military intelligence sources say most of the gangsters are in manila to buy locally made guns to be smuggled back to japan. testimony</head>
racing legend mickey thompson and his wife may have been murdered in retaliation for thompson's testimony in a murder trial that led to the conviction of their slain nephew's killer, a prosecutor said
orange county deputy district attorney tom goethals called the coincidence between the thompson murders wednesday and that of scott campbell six years ago ``absolutely incredible.''
first, his nephew is murdered execution-style, then thompson and his wife are hit execution-style. the connection just knocks you right out of your chair,'' goethals said
authorities called the killings of the millionaire couple an assassination and said they had no motive for the crime and no suspects in custody thursday
investigators are seeking a cyclist who abandoned his bicycle and flagged down motorists for a ride shortly after thompson, 59, and his wife, trudy, 41, were fatally shot at dawn wednesday outside their home in bradbury, 20 miles northeast of los angeles
detectives recovered the 12-speed bike and are checking for fingerprints and other clues, sheriff's deputy van mosely said
sheriff's officials refused to say whether the man being sought was one of the cyclists seen fleeing the thompsons' house, a third participant in the slayings, or had some other connection to the case
thompson, the first person to drive a car faster than 400 mph, was a key witness in the murder trial of larry cowell, who was convicted in 1982 of having thompson's nephew pushed from an airplane during a soured drug deal
cowell currently is serving a 25-years-to-life prison sentence for campbell's death. don dimascio, who was hired by cowell to kill campbell, was convicted last summer of first-degree murder and was sentenced to life imprisonment without parole, goethals said
knowing the type of people involved in campbell's murder, retaliation against thompson is very possible,'' goethals said. ``certainly it is an angle that will be explored.''
friends told police that thompson said he had received several death threats, but sheriff's investigators said he never reported them
a racing trade group on thursday put up a $30,000 reward for information leading to the arrest of those responsible for the thompson murders
hollywood agent paul kohner, who represented such diverse talents as charles bronson, ingmar bergman and john huston, has died of heart failure. he was 85
kohner died wednesday at university of california, los angeles, medical center, said john strauss, a longtime associate. his wife, former mexican film star lupita tovar, and family members were at his bedside
until a recent illness, kohner headed the paul kohner agency, which celebrates its 50th anniversary in may
throughout his career, kohner represented hundreds of stars, espcecially europeans, including greta garbo, marlene dietrich, maurice chevalier, liv ullman, max von sydow and klaus maria brandauer
in addition to his native czechoslovakian, kohner spoke italian, german, spanish, french and english. he frequently traveled abroad
over the past 20 years, kohner was instrumental in bringing all of swedish director ingmar bergman's films to the united states, strauss said
during world war ii kohner helped organize the european film fund, later the european relief fund, which provided emigre artists with financial assistance and help in obtaining visas to come to the united states
kohner was born in teplitz schoenau, in what is now czechoslovakia
while working as a reporter for his father's film industry trade newspapers in 1920, kohner interviewed then-head of universal pictures carl laemmle and came away with the promise of a job in new york
he came to the united states the same year and worked in various departments at universal, including publicity, promotion, distribution and production. eventually he produced foreign-language films for the studio, both in the united states and in europe
among the more important english films he produced were ``the hunchback of notre dame,'' starring lon chaney; ``a house divided,'' directed by william wyler; ``the chinese parrot,'' starring conrad veidt; and ``love me and the world is mine,'' starring mary philbin and norman kerry
he is survived by his wife; daughter susan kohner weitz; son paul j. ``pancho'' kohner; four grandchildren and a brother, walter
funeral services will be sunday at hillside memorial park. racial barriers</head> picks up 5th graf, `one of ...' edits thereafter to conform.</note>
police detained a white man and black man participating in a church-sponsored interracial exchange program, an organizer said today
murray hofmeyr, who is white, and sandy lebese, who is black, were picked up thursday night in mamelodi, the main township outside the capital of pretoria, according to rev. kevin cochrane, one of the program organizers
police had no immediate comment
in an unusual attempt to break down racial barriers, more than 200 black and white christians are trading places with each other this week
hofmeyr was among 170 whites who moved in wednesday for four days with black families in mamelodi. in turn, 40 blacks are living with whites in pretoria
hofmeyr, 29, a doctoral candidate in theology, was staying with lebese, 31, a field worker with the pretoria council of churches, in a four-room township house which he shares with nine others
lebese spent seven years in prison, from 1977 to 1983, on a sabotage conviction
cochrane said hofmeyr was released this morning, but that lebese was still being held. he said he had no information on why they were detained
security forces set up a roadblock thursday evening outside a meeting hall where the group participants had gathered. the security forces were checking the identity of all people entering the area
one of the principal organizers of the exchange is the rev. nico smith, a dutch reformed minister who has served in mamelodi since 1982. two years ago, however, he moved into his parish, becoming the first white permitted by the government live in a black township
the only difficulty has been getting everyone to the right place,'' smith said thursday before lebese and hofmeyr were detained. ``but everyone is getting along just fine.''
smith said the goal of the program was to teach both races about life on the other side of the apartheid barricade
apartheid is south africa's legal and traditional system of racial segregation. under it, the minority 5 million whites control the government and the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health systems. the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs
before he was detained, hofmeyr described a night on the town with lebese
we went to several discos last night and at one place they even introduced me over the loud speaker,'' he said. ``i didn't have to pay for a single drink all night.''
lebese said it was important that whites experience a taste of township life
a lot of whites don't even know if it's legal for them to come to mamelodi,'' said lebese. ``they think we're a bunch of dangerous radicals. this week everyone has a chance to talk in a relaxed environment.''
most south african blacks know more about how whites live than vice versa because blacks often work at white homes and in white businesses. whites seldom venture into black townships
the whites said they were concerned about living in the townships, but that their hosts were instantly friendly and open,'' said the rev. ivor jenkins, an aide to smith. ``the blacks said, `it's great to be comfortable.'''
edgar molefe, a 20-year-old from soweto, johannesburg's main township, said he had little trouble adjusting to his new environment
we had a nice long talk and a great dinner,'' he said, recalling his healthy appetite during the meal
henry lederle, a white theology professor, conceded that the participating whites are those already committed to a non-segregated south africa
the whites still need this type of exposure,'' said lederle, 42. ``it's one thing to say you want to end apartheid, it's another to learn about the problems it creates.''
the four-day exchange program includes socializing, bible study and prayer trips throughout the townships. it will culminate sunday evening with a barbecue and church service
this isn't going to solve all south africa's problems,'' said lebese. ``but it will help a few people understand the situation a little better.''
maryland's largest automobile insurer says drivers who use radar detectors are more likely to speed and crash and vows to challenge a state order requiring it to accept applicants who use the devices
associate deputy insurance commissioner thomas p. raimondi ruled thursday that washington-based geico corp. could not refuse auto insurance in maryland ``based solely upon the use or ownership of a radar detection device. (the guideline) constitutes an unfair trade practice.''
geico, formerly government employees insurance co., which is licensed to provide auto insurance in 48 states, instituted the guideline last year. the ruling covers only maryland and does not affect geico's guideline nationwide
geico vice president august alegi called the ruling ``bizarre'' and ``shocking,'' adding the company will seek an injunction against raimondi's order and also will appeal in baltimore circuit court
i can't believe that the state is telling people to go out and kill people and that we can't do anything about it,'' alegi said. geico, which insures about 220,000 drivers in maryland, has received only three complaints in maryland about the guideline, he said
the maryland ruling stemmed from a 1987 complaint by an ohio-based trade association representing makers and sellers of the devices. the ruling was the first in the country on the issue, a lobbyist for the trade association said
the auto insurance industry in recent years has become more concerned about radar detectors, especially since the new 65-mph speed limit became effective in some areas, said john cook, vice president of the insurance institute for highway safety, an industry-financed study organization
geico was believed to be the first large insurer to institute such a guideline, industry groups said. most companies still assess risk based on driving records and convictions, said harvey seymour, vice president of the industry-funded insurance information institute
an estimated 80,000 motorists in maryland and 4 million nationally use radar detectors; the devices are illegal only in washington, d.c., connecticut and virginia
prince charles returned to switzerland today to visit a friend who broke both legs in an avalanche that killed another of the prince's skiing companions and nearly engulfed him
the queen's flight plane, flown by charles, arrived at zurich airport at 12:40 p.m., airport officials said
buckingham palace said the heir to britain's throne was paying a private visit to patricia palmer-tomkinson at the hospital in davos where she is recovering. she underwent further surgery thursday
mrs. palmer-tomkinson and her husband were in the royal party on the slopes of the alpine resort of klosters when the avalanche struck march 10. the palace said charles traveled without any other members of the royal family
meanwhile, the palace refused to comment on a report in the sun, a london tabloid, saying a swiss investigator told it the royal skiing party was responsible for the snowslide
the sun claimed the finding emerged from what it said was a scientific investigation by the local chief of ski police, christian kasper
kasper, however, told a reporter: ``i would not say anything before the investigation was finished.''
a spokesman for the prosecutor's office, albert largiader, said: ``kasper is a private person. he has nothing at all to do with the investigation.''
charles and five companions were skiing off kloster's regular ski runs when the avalanche occurred
british army officer maj. hugh lindsay, 34, was killed, and mrs. palmer-tomkinson was buried with him in the snow. charles and the rest of the party managed to ski clear and were uninjured
they're fitting ``big stan'' with suspenders to keep his outerwear on when the hard wind blows. after all, you can't have someone 1,136 feet tall shedding 275-pound marble slabs
big stan'' is the nickname of the downtown amoco corp. headquarters, formerly the standard oil building. it's the world's fourth-tallest building, and is in danger of losing some of its sheathing, officials say
as a result, amoco will install steel ``suspenders'' to keep the white marble in place, engineering manager shelby pierce said thursday
the sheathing slabs are starting to curl or ``bow'' after 15 years in place, said pierce. the slabs are 1\-inch thick and measure 4 feet 2 inches by 3 feet 9 inches. beginning next week, workers will begin installing bolted-in stainless steel straps, one-sixteenth of an inch thick and 2 inches wide, at the southeast corner of the building at a minimum cost of $1 million
we're looking at an area where the most severe bows occur,'' he said. ``the southeast corner gets most exposure to sun and thermal cycles and heavy wind.''
pierce said company officials first noticed the problem in 1979. by last november, the condition of the marble began to worsen, and officials decided to reinforce the marble
while workers spend six weeks reinforcing the southeast corner, engineers will be checking the rest of the building to see if more drastic measures need to be taken. if the strapping doesn't work, amoco may have to strip the building of its gleaming white facade, he said
a man fell to his death early today after he apparently jumped from the 86th-floor observation deck of the empire state building and landed on a ledge five floors below, officials said
steven murkey, 24, was pronounced dead at 12:25 a.m. today in the emergency room of bellevue hospital center, the hospital's night supervisor robert frazier said
two witnesses at the observatory saw the man jump, but fled before police could question them, said police officer paul pisano
an ambulance crew called to the skyscraper at 11:38 p.m. thursday pulled him inside from a window on the 81st floor, authorities said
emergency medical services capt. don rothschild said the man may have climbed over a fence around the observation deck of the 102-story building, the city's second-talest and a popular tourist attraction
a security guard at the empire state building said no one would be available from there to answer questions until later today
there have been more than 30 suicides at the skyscraper, the world's tallest when it opened in 1931. it since has been surpassed, first by the world trade center in new york, then by the sears tower in chicago
most of those who have leaped to their deaths never made it to the street, landing instead on one of the building's setbacks. gorbachev's departure. no pickup.</note>
the soviet union today praised the practice of socialist self-management pioneered by yugoslavia and said it should prove useful in modernizing the soviet economic system
in a joint declaration issued as soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev ended a five-day visit to yugoslavia, the two nations also signaled other eastern european nations they are free to follow ``any paths to socialism'' without fear of soviet intervention
no one has a monopoly over the truth,'' the document declared, echoing similar pledges gorbachev made in speeches in prague a year ago and in moscow last november. ``the two sides declare that they have no pretensions of imposing their concepts of social development on anyone.''
it said the ``success of any path to socialism'' is tested by practice
this was the first time that view had been outlined in a formal, written statement of policy
under socialist self-management, yugoslavia has begun decentralizing its economy, giving plants and other enterprises local control
the unsigned document was exchanged by gorbachev and yugoslav president lazar mojsov on tuesday but was withheld until today. it supersedes landmark declarations issued in 1955 and 1956 formally acknowledging communist yugoslavia's independence from the soviet bloc
the late josip broz tito's determination to pursue a non-aligned foreign policy led to his break with moscow in 1948 and an economic blockade of yugoslavia until after the death of soviet dictator josef stalin in 1953
gorbachev's visit is the first by a soviet leader here since tito's death in 1980. it gave him a first-hand look at a decentralized economic system that has been developing for more than 35 years along the lines he is seeking to implement in the soviet union
the declaration constitutes his first formal acknowledgement that the system has applications at home. in its formative years, self-management was denounced by the kremlin as heresy and proof that yugoslavia was embarked on a revisionist road
the two sides consider the development of socialist self-management, in keeping with the specificities of each country, to be of the highest importance,'' the document said. ``it ensures the genuine authority of the people and the freedom of the individual.''
earlier in the week, gorbachev expressed some reservations about giving enterprises too much independence from central authority
at a plant that exports robots to the united states and the soviet union, gorbachev told the factory's workers council, which has nominal control of the plant, that ``we have to maintain a regulatory role at the center to safeguard us against mistakes, particularly because the country of the soviet union is so large.''
but in the declaration, the two sides paid particular tribute to self-management without corresponding mention of soviet economic reforms. those reforms are known as ``perestroika,'' or restructuring
yugoslavia's experience,'' it said, ``gained in the development of the political system of socialist self-management, and the orientation to consistently put into practice the principles of socialist self-management by the people of the soviet union, open up new possibilities for benefitting from each other's perceptions on the contemporary forms and methods of functioning of self-management.''
the two sides also called for ``a radical reform of international economic relations.''
without making specific proposals, the declaration cited ``the problem of the enormous foreign debt of most developing countries, discrimination against them in the field of trade and their limited access to technical and technological achievements.''
yugoslavia is engulfed in its worst economic crisis since world war ii, in part due to the $20 billion it owes western creditors
after delaying his departure for an hour to do some sightseeing in dubrovnik, a famed resort city on the adriatic, gorbachev and his wife, raisa, left yugoslavia to return to moscow
earlier, gorbachev toured a 17th century cathedral in what was believed to be his first visit to a roman catholic church, at least since taking over as soviet leader three years ago. as a communist, gorbachev is officially an atheist, although his mother is said to be russian orthodox and reportedly attends church regularly in her home village in southern russia
scientists have found they can create highly accurate animal versions of human diseases by inserting scrambled genes into unborn mice
the new technique should allow researchers in some cases to create animal models on demand
such laboratory animals have long been important tools for studying and curing illnesses. but until now, they have been developed only by breeding animals to bring out naturally occurring defects
in the latest experiments, researchers from the whitehead institute for biomedical research at massachusetts institute of technology produced so-called ``transgenic'' mice, animals with an extra, mutant copy of a normal gene
this bad gene contained the same genetic error that causes a fatal human birth defect called osteogenesis imperfecta type ii. as a result, the mice were born with rubbery and missing bones, just like humans with this disorder
a report on the research, directed by dr. rudolf jaenisch, was published in the march 10 issue of the british journal nature
this study constitutes the first example of the generation of an animal model of a human genetic disease by introducing precisely defined alterations into the normal gene and then transferring the mutant gene into transgenic mice,'' the researchers wrote
at the university of washington, dr. peter byers said the new technique should help researchers understand diseases that cause short stature and a variety of other disorders resulting from defective genes
you now have the potential to do that with almost any other gene in which you can make mutations,'' byers said. ``it's a way of finding out more about other genes and their functions.''
although many diseases are thought to arise from genetic defects, the precise genetic causes are still unknown
researchers say it should be possible to tinker with specific mouse genes, put them into unborn mice and then see if the animals have diseases that resemble human ailments
the mit research was conducted on the gene that produces type 1 collagen, a material essential for healthy bones and tendons
the human collagen molecule is a chain of 1,000 amino acids. of these, 333 are the amino acid glycine. if just one glycine in this chain is replaced by another amino acid, the collagen is defective and the disease osteogenesis imperfecta results
the blueprint that the body uses to assemble these amino acids is contained in one gene. if this code is garbled by a single random mutation, the gene can instruct the body to build collagen incorrectly, putting glycine in the wrong place
the researchers made this kind of mutation in the gene that produces type 1 collagen in mice. they transferred the genes into single-cell mouse embryos
the genes produced defective collagen and the mice were born with the same defects as babies with osteogenesis imperfecta
some of them were dramatic,'' jaenisch said. ``they were missing bones. you poke their heads, and there is just no bone in them.''
having an animal model for osteogenesis imperfecta should help researchers learn more about the disease, but it isn't likely to produce a way to treat it because the defect does its lethal damage before birth
one potential use of the technique, jaenisch said, would be to learn how the body uses other kinds of collagen
there are 20 different collagens, and nobody knows what the functions of these collagens are,'' he said in an interview. ``for any of these collagens, this approach will be perfectly suited.''
a 25-year-old steelworker who had been recommended for medical retirement after a foot injury walked into the company doctor's office with a shotgun and killed him, authorities said
robert jimenez of antioch shot dr. john irion in the head and chest thursday, said contra costa county sheriff's lt. telford terry. ``he set the shotgun down and waited for the arrival of sheriff's deputies,'' said terry
irion, 63, was pronounced dead at his office at the uss-posco steel plant
he had recommended that jimenez be placed on medical retirement after a grinding wheel fell on jimenez's foot at work, crushing it and causing a severe disability that made him miss work frequently, terry said. ``apparently he was going to be retired and he didn't want to be retired.''
jimenez was taken to the county jail in martinez and booked for investigation of murder
we're just in shock,'' said calvin burgess, one of jimenez's foremen. he said plant officials met wednesday to decide whether jimenez should return from disability to take on a ``light job'' of teaching new roll grinders
but it didn't work out, and the company decided against it,'' he said
company spokesman earl macintyre declined additional comment
