the talks recessed for the weekend, and u.n. officials said they would resume monday
an afghan rebel leader said the soviet union was secretly trying to contact the resistance to negotiate an agreement
in moscow, foreign ministry spokesman vadim p. perfiliev said if a settlement proved impossible in geneva, moscow's withdrawal of its troops from afghanistan ``will be performed differently'' from terms agreed to this month
those terms state that the 115,000 red army troops would be out of afghanistan in a nine-month span and that half would leave in the first three months. the troops intervened in december 1979
a source close to the geneva talks, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the statement was expected to add momentum to the u.n.-mediated negotiations
a pakistani source said the soviet statement seemed designed to pressure pakistan into modifying its demand that a settlement be linked to the formation of a new government in afghanistan to oversee a settlement
pakistan represents the guerrillas in the talks
