disagreement over a 1907 border treaty stalled talks friday between laos and thailand to resolve a frontier conflict that has claimed hundreds of lives
thailand's ambassador to laos, niran panupong, said both sides have different interpretations of the treaty between his country and what was then french-ruled laos
in addition, thongsi intapon, a laotian official of the prime minister's office, said laos first wanted to define the role and duties of a joint border committee proposed by the thais before such a body is formed
if we commit ourselves to that committee now, we will find ourselves arguing in the jungles,'' thongsi told reporters accompanying the 15-member thai delegation to the talks
the thais want an agreement defining the location of the border in the disputed wedge of hills between thailand's northern phitsanulok province and laos' sayaboury province
top thai army officials have said 147 thai soldiers and 402 laotian troops died before the two sides began a truce and pledged to enter into peace talks feb. 19
the thais say they will take the dispute to the world court if a bilateral agreement is not reached. but thongsi said such a move would be ``a last resort and not necessary.''
he said the prime ministers of both countries want a speedy agreement but added the talks could take ``quite a while'' if the atmosphere at friday's meeting persisted
the 1,030-mile border is poorly defined, and a similar territorial dispute over three border villages led to battles in 1984
