here is a summary of the latest developments in the sandinista-contra fighting along the honduran-nicaraguan border and repercussions from the united states' deployment of troops in honduras:
the white house denied nicaraguan charges that the united states was behind a honduran bombing raid on the nicaraguan border. reagan administration spokesman marlin fitzwater said: ``we haven't asked them (the hondurans) or instructed them to do anything. we have offered our support and we have sent our forces there in defense of that.''
defense secretary frank carlucci said friday that 3,200 soldiers being sent to honduras were there only for ``moral support'' and that they would be kept away from combat during their 10-day training exercise
the pentagon said 700 paratroopers from the 82nd airborne division of fort bragg, n.c., dropped into honduras on friday from eight aircraft, and the deployment would be completed by tonight
the foreign ministry blamed the united states for a honduran attack on sandinista army targets and formally protested to washington. a spokesman said such cross-border air raids could lead to war between the united states and nicaragua
sandinista officers said two bombs fell in nicaragua and a third landed across the narrow coco river in honduran territory on thursday afternoon. reporters taken to the area by a sandinista official saw at least five bombs fall, but it was impossible to say which side of the border they landed on
newspapers called on nicaraguans to maintain a combat alert in case u.s. troops invaded from honduras, where 3,200 american troops are being deployed
nicaragua requested an emergency meeting of the united nations' security council this afternoon to consider the situation
a military official said honduran troops were moving along the rugged frontier friday and warplanes were on standby to oust nicaraguan soldiers, a day after honduran warplanes fired bombs and rockets at nicaraguan army targets along the border. honduras said its air force fired rockets only inside its own territory
the high-ranking military official said honduran troops had orders to expel the ``invading troops'' from nicaragua. he said an estimated 1,000 sandinistas were reported friday on the honduran side of border at san andres de bocay. the nicaraguan side is the site of sandinista military headquarters in northern nicaragua
scores of people were arrested friday as demonstrators blocked federal buildings in boston and san francisco and slowed rush-hour traffic in chicago's loop in protests against the movement of troops to honduras. more than 100 people were arrested in san francisco, up to 60 in chicago and one in boston on the second day of protests, police said
in miami, contra leaders said cease-fire talks scheduled monday with the government were off unless the sandinistas left honduras
tricycle, unicycle, skateboard, sled and bicycle riders beware: without a driver's license, you could get a ticket, and your vehicle could be seized
the ordinance intended to put the brakes on reckless riders has let loose a storm of protest, and one woman moved so her 13-year-old son could ride his bicycle without fear of arrest
the regulation, passed unanimously by aldermen feb. 15, requires bicyclists to have a driver's license or be supervised by someone who does. it also applies to riders of unicycles, tricycles, all-terrain vehicles, skateboards, minibikes, wagons, sleds, scooters and go-carts
town officials said the law was desperately needed to curtail reckless attitudes among bike riders, especially young ones, some of whom played ``chicken'' with cars
violation of the law is a misdemeanor
the children don't have any freedom,'' said mable lee, who moved two weeks ago to an area northwest of town so her son, tom, could ride his bike again. ``what have they got to do? there's nothing for 'em to do.''
mayor will cathey said something had to be done to protect both drivers and bicyclists. he added that the ordinance was passed after three advertised public hearings, which nobody attended
after the ox got gored, then they (protesters) came down,'' he said. ``i've received a lot of support from my constituents over the town taking action about these bicycles, a tremendous amount of support.''
rosman, population 515, has no police force. the transylvania county sheriff's department confiscated three bikes shortly after the law was passed but later released them, said jim stroup, chief investigator for the department
he said the sheriff's office is waiting to hear from the state attorney general's office about whether the law is constitutional before it actively enforces the ordinance
under the ordinance, youthful violators will be referred to county youth counselor pat roach. ``this is something we will try to settle without going to court,'' she said. ``that's true with any kind of complaint about a child.'' update with testimony resuming today; picks up 10th graf, `during nearly...'</note>
gov. evan mecham, his honesty challenged on the witness stand, shouted he's ``tired of this kind of baloney,'' but acknowledged ordering arizona's top lawman not to cooperate in an investigation of an alleged death threat
the first-term republican governor got into more than one shouting match with prosecutor paul eckstein during his second day of testimony at his impeachment trial thursday, as eckstein sought to damage mecham's credibility
mecham is accused of trying to thwart an investigation of the death threat allegedly made by one of his staffers against a top aide who was scheduled to testify before a grand jury investigating the governor's campaign finances
he returned to the stand today, and was expected to complete his testimony on the accusation, the first of three major charges against him. he also is accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and of misusing $80,000 from a state fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
at least one other witness was expected to be recalled to the stand _ state official peggy griffith, who reported the alleged death threat nov. 13. the last scheduled witness was mecham's own defense attorney, fred craft, who was present at a key meeting in connection with the obstruction claim
mecham, fighting for his political life, insisted thursday he was kept in the dark about the details of the death threat made by a former state official, lee watkins. when he did hear about it, he said he didn't consider it serious
two somewhat excitable people had a verbal exchange and somewhere along the line there were those who determined they would make something out of it,'' he said. ``it's a total manufactured thing.''
mecham acknowledged, however, that he ordered ralph milstead, the state department of public safety director, not to cooperate with an attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat
i said, `tell them we've looked into it and there's nothing to it,''' he said
mecham said today he wishes he had fired milstead, and that if he had, ``we wouldn't be sitting in this body in this action today... i have highly repented of that.''
during nearly three weeks of testimony, witnesses quoted watkins as saying that mecham's former top aide, donna carlson, might ``go on a long boat ride'' if she testified before the grand jury. watkins has denied the charge
it would require a two-thirds vote of the 30-member state senate to remove mecham from office. they could then take another vote on barring him from any future state office
in addition to the impeachment trial, the first of a u.s. governor in six decades, mecham faces a criminal trial april 21 on felony charges that he concealed the $350,000 loan. he also faces a recall election may 17
attorney general bob corbin confirmed thursday his office also is looking into a $150,000 personal loan taken by mecham in december to pay off the unreported campaign loan
in a series of testy exchanges under cross-examination by eckstein thursday, mecham turned combative and at one point declared, ``i am kind of tired of this kind of baloney!''
during six hours on the stand, the governor pleaded a faulty memory for details but said he knew one thing _ he had never been accused of anything worse than a traffic ticket before the current proceedings
eckstein then produced copies of two lawsuits in which mecham was accused of fraud in business deals
the governor bristled, saying that was not the same thing, and attempted a lengthy explanation that became a shouting match as the attorney tried to stop him
this has to be told. you're trying to impugn my honesty!'' mecham said
eckstein interrupted, saying,``i'll ask the questions.''
i'll respond as i see fit,'' snapped mecham. ``i've earned the right to respond!''
at one point mecham said, ``hopefully, i will be back on the ninth floor (the governor's office) in the near future,'' and as he left the senate building he flashed a thumbs-up sign to reporters and well-wishers
tape-recorded police transmissions indicate three officers who stood outside an apartment while a 12-year-old girl was raped didn't heed a supervisor's order to kick in a door
the recording was played thursday during a disciplinary hearing for officer james horka. horka is accused of waiting for the building's landlord to arrive with a key instead of breaking down the door to rescue the girl
the tape indicates horka arrived outside the apartment at 4:39 a.m. on dec. 20 and said over the radio two minutes later, ``we're going to the back door; supposedly it's a home invasion.''
the order to kick down the door came two minutes after horka told his superiors the girl's mother was ``worried for the welfare of her 12-year-old daughter,'' according to the tape
horka's supervisor, sgt. ernest targonski, said, ``...you've got to get in there somehow, so long as she states that the man is in there. we've got to push the door in; push the door in.''
but horka and two other police officers waited almost a half-hour before entering the home, the tape indicates
the girl was rescued when officer peter miller arrived at the scene and entered the apartment through an open back door
hearings for officers kevin beasley and daniel surufka, who arrived with horka and were under his supervision, are to begin march 28
former police chief james shutoski, who retired during the controversy, recommended firing the three officers
horka expressed confusion on the tape. he said of the mother, ``this girl is freaking out.'' when asked by the dispatcher whether the incident was a rape, he replied, ``i don't know; i don't know what this is right now.''
horka's attorney thomas tyrell says the tape proves horka's contention that he decided to wait for a key because he did not know if the intruder had a weapon and would harm the girl or her 10-year-old brother if he heard police breaking in
benjamin valentine, 19, of chicago, has been charged in the assault
the new gene autry western heritage museum in los angeles has purchased an 87-piece western art collection worth an estimated $8.7 million
the collection, which had been on permanent loan to joslyn art museum since 1967, contains works by 37 artists, including frederic remington, charles m. russell, albert bierstadt and george catlin
the autry museum obtained the collection by a sealed bid to the enron art foundation at enron corp. headquarters in houston. an enron spokesman declined to disclose the price or number of bidders. a statement by the autry museum also did not give the price
the collection, assembled from the western art holdings of knoedler galleries in new york city, was purchased for an undisclosed sum in 1967 by the northern natural gas co., an enron corp. predecessor
last may, the enron art foundation offered the collection, along with a collection of 113 works by alfred jacob miller for $10.8 million
joslyn said it would buy the miller collection for $4.4 million, but decided not to buy the western collection. the museum has another western collection, appraised at $14 million, that was donated by the enron foundation in november 1986
under the circumstances that the sale was inevitable, i am pleased that the material is coming to a museum,'' henry flood robert, joslyn's director, said thursday. ``it means the material will still be accessible to the public in the future.''
the autry museum, named after the cowboy movie actor who now owns the california angels baseball team, is being built by a charitable trust set up through the estate of the late ina mae autry, autry's wife
the museum is to open in october with 52,000 square feet of exhibit space on 13 acres in griffith park. it has a collection of 12,000 items, including autry's personal holdings
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis holds a slight edge in kansas democratic presidential caucuses on saturday based on an organization that even his rivals concede is strong
dukakis, jesse jackson and albert gore jr. all campaigned in kansas this week, trying to kindle enthusiasm among registered democrats and spur them to turn out at 117 caucuses. kansas, with only 39 national convention delegates, has been ignored until now
we've been organized in kansas for eight months,'' said state sen. paul feleciano, dukakis' state chairman. ``i feel very good heading into the caucuses. i think we'll get 20 to 24 of the 39 delegates still to be picked.''
state sen. joe norvell, a gore supporter, conceded dukakis' organizational lead in kansas, but said, ``i do believe that, with sen. gore's extensive campaign trip through the state, his efforts could minimize what i would consider an early lead for gov. dukakis.''
gore, lacking a big organization here, campaigned wednesday and thursday throughout the state. the tennessee senator won endorsements from state treasurer joan finney, the highest elected democratic state official, and a qualified endorsement from state chairman jim parrish
were it not for my promise to the democratic state committee early on ... to stay neutral until the 19th of march, i'd be making a public announcement for you,'' parrish told gore. ``i'm leaning very much in your favor.''
jackson has had a better organizational effort in kansas than has gore, but his supporters conceded recently they are not organized in enough counties to garner a majority of the kansas delegates
rep. jim slattery, who supports missouri rep. richard gephardt, said friday his candidate would do well in kansas, and he said michigan ``is a do-or-die state'' for gephardt. michigan's democratic caucuses will be held march 26
i always hate to make predictions that can be proven wrong in 48 hours, so i'll avoid doing that. i think they'll all get delegates. rep. dick gephardt and undecided will do well,'' slattery said
gore supporter norvell also predicted a large uncommitted vote saturday, saying he thinks kansas democrats still are making up their minds
i really do not see a front-runner in kansas,'' he said
democrats will caucus saturday afternoon and vote for delegates to the district conventions april 23 and the state convention may 14
illegal aliens are driving down wages and job conditions for low-income native americans and legal immigrants but also are indirectly enhancing job opportunities for some higher-skilled workers, congressional investigators say in a new report
hurt most by the tide of illegal workers sweeping border, farm and some metropolitan areas are native and legally documented immigrant crop pickers, janitors and food processing workers, the general accounting office says
wage and benefit increases won by largely legal mexican migrants and native black workers under union organizing campaigns in those industries in the 1970s have disappeared as they have been displaced by illegal immigrants working at often below-minimum wages, the gao said in a 70-page report
for example, janitors in downtown los angeles office buildings _ most of them black or legal hispanic immigrants _ had won wage and benefits reaching a peak of $12 an hour by 1983 under union contracts, according to the report
however, a group of aggressive non-union janitorial services hiring predominantly illegal immigrants have since wrested away the best building contracts, driving the union scale back down to $4 an hour and below
of 2,500 black janitors working under high-wage contracts in 1977, only 100 still enjoyed comparative wages by 1985, the gao said. the union still had 600 working members but 500 of them had suffered large pay cuts
citrus and tomato pickers in southern california _ many of them mexicans admitted under guest worker programs _ have seen their wages and benefits drop by 18 percent since 1975 because of the growing use of illegal immigrants by farm labor contractors, the gao said
however, the congressional investigators said it is impossible to measure what it called the ``net effects'' of the growing use of illegal aliens in other businesses, such as full-service restaurants and high-fashion shoe and garment manufacturing
the increased supply of illegal workers undoubtedly depressed wages for some natives or legal immigrants in those industries, too, the gao said
but, at the same time, by stimulating business, (they) also expanded employment opportunities and wages for other legal and native workers in complementary, usually skilled occupations,'' it said
as an example, it cited full-service restaurants that use illegal aliens as dishwashers and busboys. the associated labor savings allow low prices that lead to expanded sales, creating jobs for more higher-skilled and higher-paid chefs and waiters, the gao said
citing case studies in new york city and los angeles, the gao said illegal immigrants working at low wages by u.s. standards have meant the survival of small, specialized companies in the high-fashion women's footwear and garment industries
the studies quoted owners of those companies as saying they are under intense cost pressure from foreign producers and could not find americans or legal immigrants willing to work all day behind sewing machines or with the skills needed to produce high-fashion women's shoes
without a supply of illegal workers, the gao concluded, many of those businesses would close down or move their operations out of the country
the labor department strongly disagreed with the gao's conclusions, saying none of the studies it surveyed offered any concrete evidence of a positive effect from using illegal workers, except the comments from employers
in a formal reply to the report, the department also disputed gao's premise that legal workers won't take many of the low-wage jobs, particuarly in the shoe and garment industries
the fact is that large numbers of native and legal u.s. workers are in the same labor market as illegal workers,'' the labor department said. ``if wages were not depressed by illegal workers, even greater numbers of native and legal workers would be in that labor market.''
the study was requested by congress in 1985, when it was considering immigration reform legislation enacted a year later providing for government fines against employers who use illegal aliens
if successful, the gao said, those employer sanctions will force wages up for legal immigrants and natives, causing ``considerable stress'' financially for growers and some manufacturers
police on friday threatened strict action against organizers of a national strike set for monday, the anniversary of the 1960 sharpeville massacre
anti-apartheid organizations have called for a ``national day of protest'' to mark the anniversary and to protest the recent crackdown on major black opposition groups
the strike also had been intended to protest the scheduled execution friday of six blacks from sharpeville convicted of complicity in the 1984 mob killing of a black town councilor during anti-apartheid riots
on thursday, 15 hours before the hangings were to take place, a judge granted a one-month stay of execution to the ``sharpeville six.'' instead of a mass execution, one black man convicted in a separate murder case was hanged at pretoria central prison at dawn friday without fanfare or an overnight vigil
tsepo letsoara, 24, was convicted of killing a black woman in october 1985. there was no campaign to save him, and neither the government nor its opponents has contended that his crime had political overtones
police commanders announced that reinforcements would be deployed monday in the johannesburg area, where the strike is expected to be most widespread
calls for strikes are illegal under emergency regulations in effect since june 1986. but on other ``days of protests'' since then, hundreds of thousands of black workers and students have stayed home
we are planning all actions humanly possible to prevent persons from intimidating and preventing workers from being able to do a good day's work,'' said lt. pierre louw, a police spokesman
he said labor unions and other ``elements'' organizing the strike were under investigation
march 21 is observed annually by blacks as ``sharpeville day'' to mark the day in 1960 when 69 blacks were shot and killed by police in the township south of johannesburg while demonstrating against the pass laws. the laws restricting blacks' freedom of movement have since been repealed
anti-apartheid riots broke out in sharpeville and nearby townships in september 1984, starting a two-year period of nationwide unrest in which more than 2,000 blacks were killed. the councilor whose murder led to the ``sharpeville six'' trial was killed on the first day of those riots
the five black men and one woman gained their reprieve when pretoria supreme court justice willem human granted a one-month stay of execution after receiving evidence of perjury by a prosecution witness
the government said it ignored a massive international appeal for clemency, leaving the case in the hands of the judge
attorney prakash diar said friday the defense team had already begun preparing an application to reopen the trial and re-examine government witnesses
the six were convicted under the principle of ``common cause,'' which held them responsible for the september 1984 death of town councilor jacob dlamini because they were part of a crowd of 100 who stoned and burned him to death in sharpeville
president p.w. botha had rejected pleas from leaders of most western nations and from countries and organizations around the world to grant clemency. the government said human's decision ``proves the wisdom of the state president and his ministers in deciding not to intervene in the due process of law.''
two johannesburg newspapers reported friday that botha had granted clemency three weeks ago to a black policeman who had been sentenced to death for 1986 murder of a youth in mamelodi, a black township outside pretoria
a spokesman for justice department said botha had commuted constable george john sindane's death sentence to eight years in prison, and he was one of five people whose death sentences were commuted this year
soviet scientists are working around the clock to prepare the first launch of their space shuttle on an unmanned test flight expected by june, officials said friday
alexander i. dunayev, the head of the space agency glavkosmos, also said that the agency plans to use the actual shuttle, not a dummy, in the test flight and that more than one of the craft will be built
dunayev's comments at a news conference were the most detailed to date about the soviet shuttle. the session was called to discuss thursday's launch of an indian satellite by a soviet rocket
the soviets are believed to have been developing their own winged reusable spacecraft since at least 1982, but soviet officials did not confirm the project until december 1984 and have released little information about it
dunayev said the first flight of the shuttle was imminent
we are now working quite energetically on testing on land, on the surface, of the components. we are working literally round the clock,'' he said
he refused to specify when the launch will occur, saying only that it would be ``in the nearest future.''
it is very important that this flight be very thoroughly prepared so i would not get involved in some guesswork,'' dunayev said
however, another soviet space official, speaking privately, said the first flight would occur in the first half of this year. neither he nor dunayev would comment on when the first manned flight would occur
dunayev said soviet scientists were encountering difficulties daily in preparing the shuttle, but he did not provide details
western specialists on the soviet space program have said the flight would be unmanned and computerized. dunayev confirmed the flight would be totally automated because the soviet union believes pilotless tests are prudent
with the development of manned spacecraft, the soviet union prefers at the first stage automats,'' he said. ``and we believe that for the sake of security of human life what is required above all is to ensure that man survives.''
he went on to imply that u.s. space officials were not as concerned about astronauts' safety as the soviets were. seven astronauts were killed when the space shuttle challenger exploded in january 1986
we pursue the fundamental objective: whether man is alive or dead after the flight. on the basis of that we regard the fundamental differences between the soviet direction of development and the u.s. part of development,'' dunayev said
james oberg, an american specialist on the soviet space program, said in a telephone interview from his home in texas that the soviet shuttle may include a separable nose section from which the crew could escape in an emergency
soviet officials have said little about the size or other characteristics of the shuttle. but the soviet press has reported the shuttle will be lifted into orbit by the new energia rocket booster, which can carry up to 100 tons of payload, more than the u.s. shuttle
in its first test may 15, energia successfully carried aloft a payload, but the payload's own engines failed
alexei f. bogomolov, director of the soviet mission control center near moscow called medvezhyi ozero, said in an interview the shuttle will have on-board engines to orient the craft in space and maneuver it through the atmosphere toward a runway landing. the u.s. shuttle glides powerless to landings
the soviet space chief said the soviet union plans a fleet of shuttles
how many, it's difficult to say. it is clear that we will have more than one,'' he said
developer donald trump has a handshake agreement to buy the landmark plaza hotel for $450 million, the wall street journal reported friday
the plaza's owners have agreed on basic terms with trump and are expected to sign a binding contract next week, according to sources quoted in newspaper
a spokeswoman for trump and a spokesman at howard rubenstein associates, which represents trump, did not return telephone calls seeking confirmation friday
another unidentified source quoted by the journal said trump was the preferred bidder because it was believed he was most likely to restore the hotel's luster
the 81-year-old landmark hotel was acquired in january from the allegis corp. when robert m. bass of fort worth, texas, and the tokyo-based aoki corp. bought the westin hotels and resorts chain, an allegis subsidiary, for $1.53 billion. bass owns 71 percent of the plaza; aoki owns the rest. the journal said a bass spokesman declined comment
the hotel, which overlooks central park at fifth avenue, can be seen from trump tower on fifth avenue, which combines restaurants, shops and apartments
the plaza is expected to earn $22 million this year, which industry professionals quoted by the journal said is a meager return for the price trump is offering
i think anything over $350 million is high,'' stephen brenner, a new york hotel consultant, said
in 1907, the plaza opened as a permanent residency hotel and later became a commercial hotel. a few tenants from before world war ii are protected by rent control laws and pay $200 a month in rent
a couple accused of having sex on a transatlantic flight were charged with public indecency, and two men who began throwing food when a flight attendant intervened also have been charged, police said
but the couple, a doctor and his wife, a lawyer and part-time judge, say they were sleeping on american airlines flight 37 from munich, west germany, to san diego, and did nothing wrong
the four were arrested monday when the jet made an intermediate stop in chicago, according to police reports
but phillip matin, who was arrested with his wife, sharyn jo van tassell, denied the charges. ``this was the fantasy of a young girl that is completely uncorroborated,'' he told the sacramento (calif.) bee. ``it's ridiculous.''
police said most passengers apparently were asleep monday during the eight-hour atlantic crossing when a 13-year-old girl told her mother she believed the couple across the aisle was engaged in a sex act. the mother called an attendant, who notified a supervisor, said sgt. jerry thornton
the supervisor, barbara weiderman, told the captain of the problem, and he radioed police to be on standby at o'hare. at that point, two other passengers ``became abusive and belligerent'' and began throwing food and drinks at the flight attendants, according to the police report
when the plane landed, police arrested van tassell, 42, and matin, 52, of loomis, calif. both were charged with public indecency; matin was also charged with possession of a controlled substance after authorities found eight yellow pills in one of his bags
matin said they were valium and he couldn't prove they were prescription drugs because the bottle they came from was in his luggage
roger f. cline, 42, of placerville, calif., and stanley wells, 53, of cameron park, calif., were charged with disorderly conduct in connection with the food fight
all four missed the continuation of their flight to san diego, but paid the bonds set on their misdemeanor charges and were released pending april court appearances, police said
a government commission has declared poland's first sex education book unacceptable and banned it from schools, ending a six-month debate that made the text a best-seller on the black market
preparation for life in the family'' was introduced in high schools last fall to a storm of protest
one normally pro-government lay catholic newspaper called it ``a textbook for masturbation and defloration.'' another called it a ``sex manual for beginners.''
critics said it violated religious teachings and encouraged pre-marital sex
after two months of complaints, minister of national education henryk bednarski in november suspended the book's use in high schools
on friday, official newspapers announced that a special commission appointed by bednarski to evaluate the book now had banned it permanently
the controversy didn't hurt the text's popularity. the first printing of 500,000 copies sold out in state book stores and is available only at inflated prices on the black market, according to newspaper reports
the book was designed for use in a nationwide high school course on family life and sexual matters, which had been taught since 1973 without a text
many parents and clergy lined up against the book, but it was defended by such odd political bedfellows as writers for communist party papers and the underground publications of the banned solidarity trade union federation
the commission reviewing the book, including teachers, psychologists, doctors and other experts, held its final meeting thursday
according to the official pap news agency, the commission chairwoman concluded, ``we appreciate the necessity of giving youth sexual knowledge ... but we think that the book as a mandatory textbook is unacceptable.''
the chairwoman anna przeclawska, dean of warsaw university's pedagogics department, said experts found the book replete with mistakes about biological and psychological topics and filled with overly difficult language and ``inappropriate'' graphics
it presented a ``one-sided biological conception'' of sexual problems, omitting the need for friendship and love, she said
a roman catholic church weekly, niedziela, said explicit illustrations of sexual positions could lead to the ``arousal of children'' and undermine parental authority
the commission recommended that work proceed slowly on a new textbook, stressing that what is ``most important is the teacher who cannot be replaced by anything.''
a commentator on the popular youth-oriented television news broadcast, teleexpress, condemned the book ban and said young people will be ``doomed to barnyard knowledge or often unqualified teachers.''
the book's defenders argued that it presented the roman catholic view of opposing artificial contraception and abortions
they included the polish united workers party weekly polityka, which published letters from readers who complained that poland is sexually backward
one reader said there were cases in which sales clerks deliberately punched holes in condoms ``because this is the kind of `morality' we have in poland.''
daniel passent, a polityka columnist, accused the roman catholic majority of attempting to force its views on the non-catholic minority
several writers in clandestine weeklies published by solidarity also objected to the campaign against the book, which in turn prompted outraged responses from pro-union priests and activists
a commentary in november in the most widely circulated solidarity underground weekly, tygodnik mazowsze, said sexual knowledge among young poles was ``close to medieval.''
the book's backers argued the textbook was needed because many youths lack information about sex and birth control
estimates of the number of abortions per year range as high as 800,000. according to official statistics, every sixth woman who gets married under the age of 20 is already pregnant
a baby with a fatal birth defect who was maintained on a respirator for a week to preserve his organs for transplant clung to life friday without life support, officials said
the boy, born with most of his brain and skull missing, was taken off the respirator thursday at loma linda university medical center after he failed to show signs of brain death the hospital requires before taking organs for transplant
baby d continues to breathe on his own, and is being kept comfortable,'' said spokeswoman anita rockwell
meanwhile, another infant with the same condition being kept alive in the loma linda organ donor program, began to show signs of impending brain death friday
babies with the defect called anencephaly usually die within hours or days of being taken off life-support systems, ms. rockwell said
loma linda developed the first medical guidelines in the united states for using life-support equipment to preserve anencephalics' hearts and other organs for transplant. if the babies are allowed to die naturally, their organs deteriorate to the point of being unsuitable for transplant
the girl is the fifth anencephalic infant delivered into loma linda's donor program. the first was stillborn, and the second met criteria for brain death, but a suitable recipient for his organs couldn't be found before the body parts deteriorated
the other two never met the hospital's criteria
under the guidelines, infants are placed on life-support systems for seven days. if doctors determine an infant is brain dead within that time, the hospital will alert organ procurement agencies nationwide and a search for a suitable recipient will begin
the hospital's criteria for brain death require that an infant be in a coma and unable to breathe on his or her own and show an absence of eye reflexes, ms. rockwell said
the life-support system helps prevent the infant's heart, liver and other vital organs from deteriorating until doctors have determined the baby is brain dead
the hospital's procedure was devised to address ethical questions surrounding the use of doomed anencephalics as organ donors
if an infant is not declared brain dead within seven days, he or she is taken off the respirator and allowed to die naturally without further consideration as a donor
record low precipitation in parts of the west last month has further reduced an already low water supply, the agriculture department said friday
we were hoping that precipitation levels would increase in february and help ease the drought in sections of california, nevada, montana, idaho, oregon, washington and wyoming,'' said wilson scaling, chief of the department's soil conservation service. ``instead, the situation has worsened.''
the western water outlook is based on surveys by scs and the commerce department's national weather service. western states depend on snowmelt for about 75 percent of their water
scaling said some areas are not affected by the dry conditions, including ``very good'' prospects in arizona, new mexico and the lower part of colorado
these areas have had three wet winters in a row,'' he said. ``the soils are wet and there has been excellent carryover from previous years.'' lpga event</head> play; picks up 7th graf, `the petition...'; a version on sports wires.</note>
a golfer who failed to qualify for a tournament after interrupting her play to save a drowning child will be allowed to enter the tournament through an unprecendented exemption, the lpga announced today
commissioner john d. laupheimer called mary bea porter's revival of the stricken child a once-in-a-decade occurence that warrants such an exception to the ladies pro golfing rules
mary bea porter, 38, had returned to the phoenix golf course after the rescue earlier this week but finished three strokes short of qualifying for the standard register turquoise classic tournament next week in phoenix
she had not been told of laupheimer's decision when he made the announcement today during the lpga tucson open that began play thursday, when ms. porter shot a 79 in comparison with the 9-under-par 63 fired by the first-round leader, british rookie laura davies
players had petitioned laupheimer to let ms. porter to play despite having failed to qualify. laupheimer said he took their sentiments into account but had decided to find some way to recognize her ``exemplary heroism.''
laupheimer said he knew of no other instance in which a golfer who failed in a qualifying round had been allowed to play in an lpga tournament. he said he was concerned about setting a precedent in modifying the rules, but added, ``i can't think of anything else in golf that has captured the hearts of not only the golfing community but the public at large.''
the petition originated with bonnie lauer, president of the lpga player council
ms. porter was lining up her shot on the 13th fairway wednesday when she saw 3-year-old jonathon smucker face down in a swimming pool in a yard bordering the moon valley country club golf course in phoenix
she jumped the fence to help the boy's father, who had pulled the boy out, and gave mouth-to-mouth resuscitation. a spokesman for the phoenix fire department said she saved the boy's life
i knew i had to do something ... so i threw him on the ground, reached in and cleaned out his mouth, moved his tongue to the side and blew,'' she said
the boy was crying in her arms when paramedics arrived, ms. porter said
ms. porter has won $50,000 in 15 years on the ladies pro golf tour
very low blood cholesterol increases the risk of one form of stroke, even though it decreases the overall risk of all forms of stroke, researchers said friday
a six-year study of 350,000 men showed that those with cholesterol levels below 160 were three times as likely as others to have a so-called hemorrhagic stroke, in which a blood vessel bursts and the subsequent bleeding damages parts of the brain
the study's principal author, dr. hiroyasu iso of the university of minnesota and the university of tsukuba in tsukuba city, japan, said his findings do not suggest any change in public health efforts to get americans to lower their blood cholesterol levels
public efforts to lower cholesterol should continue, and our efforts to understand the etiology (cause) of stroke should increase,'' iso said in presenting his results at a meeting of the american heart association
hemorrhagic strokes are less common than strokes caused by clots, which account for 70 percent to 80 percent of all strokes
the increased risk of hemorrhagic stroke was observed only in men with high blood pressure, but there might be a smaller increase in risk in people with normal blood pressure, iso said. his study couldn't determine that, he said
the increased risk occurred in men with blood cholesterol levels below 160 milligrams. only 6 percent of the men he studies had cholesterol levels that low, he said. the mean blood cholesterol level in the subjects was 211 milligrams
cholesterol levels below 200 milligrams are associated with a low level of coronary heart disease
levels over 240 milligrams double the risk. twenty percent to 25 percent of americans have cholesterol levels in this range, according to the heart association
in japan, low levels of cholesterol are more common, and hemorrhagic strokes are more common, too, iso said
dr. william kannel of the framingham heart study in massachusetts said that study shows a similar risk associated with low cholesterol, as does the honolulu heart study directed by dr. dwayne reed of the national heart, lung and blood institute
those researchers and others said, however, that the risk associated with very low cholesterol is outweighed by the benefits
nothing confers immortality,'' said kannel. ``you're always dealing with tradeoffs.'' he emphasized that coronary heart disease, with its strong link to elevated cholesterol, is the chief form of heart disease. ``given that, i'd say get your cholesterol as low as you can,'' he said
if you look at total stroke,'' said dr. lewis kuller of the university of pittsburgh, ``there's no question _ the lower the cholesterol, the better.''
the soviet union announced friday it will borrow political and economic reforms from yugoslavia and reiterated that it won't impose its policies on other communist nations
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev pledged as he ended a trip to yugoslavia that eastern european countries are free to follow ``any paths to socialism'' without soviet interference
this echoed speeches gorbachev made twice last year but it marked the first time he put such a pledge into a formal document
the declaration, also signed by yugoslav president lazar mojsov, brings the soviet union one step closer to abandoning, at least on paper, the so-called brezhnev doctrine that tolerates no alternative to moscow's brand of communism
gorbachev returned to moscow on friday after a five-day visit to yugoslavia that gave him a first-hand look at the country's decentralized economy and at its ethnic divisions similar to those the kremlin confronts at home
the trip, one of his longest to a foreign country, included detailed talks with communist leaders, factory visits in belgrade and a stroll friday through the medieval buildings and sun-drenched narrow streets of dubrovnik
proceeding from the conviction that no one has a monopoly over the truth, the two sides declare that they have no pretensions of imposing their concept of social development on anyone,'' the declaration said
for the first time, too, the soviet union embraced the concept of socialist self-management that had been developed by yugoslav leader josip broz tito after he broke with moscow in 1948
the two sides consider the development of socialist self-management, in keeping with the specificities of each country, to be of the highest importance,'' the declaration said
it ensures the genuine authority of the people and the freedom of the individual and is a dependable guarantee against any administrative-bureaucratic distortion of socialism,'' the declaration said
friday's document replaces agreements reached by both countries in 1955 and 1956, when then soviet leader nikita khrushchev signaled that the kremlin might tolerate alternative ways to communism
but in 1956 workers unrests were crushed in poland and soviet tanks quashed revolt in budapest
soviet historians have hinted in past months that moscow may be willing to review its assessment of czechoslovakia's attempt in 1968 to develop an alternative brand of communism
however, the present prague communist leadership took power after the reforms were crushed by a soviet-led warsaw pact invasion
therefore any reassessment of ``prague spring'' would have to be sensitive to those currently in power
friday's declaration indicates moscow wants to borrow some economic and political practices from yugoslavia, whose position between east and west has enhanced its international standing and standard of living over the past four decades
meat, dairy and fresh produce, often in short supply for soviets, are readily available to yugoslavs who also have access to western luxury items, like the sony walkman which are still a coveted prize for most soviets
but triple-digit inflation has cut yugoslavs' standard of living by at least a third since 1980, placing many consumer items out of reach of workers earning an average wage of $180 a month
a $20 billion debt has built up, and many yugoslavs expect times to get even harder after the international monetary fund completes negotiations this spring on how to reschedule debt payments
gorbachev indicated tuesday he also would not favor too much decentralization of his economy, telling workers at the belgrade factory that ``we have to maintain a regulatory role in order not to make mistakes.''
friday's document said the soviets and yugoslavs will work to develop political and personal contacts
the reagan administration is assured that nuclear warheads will not be placed on chinese intermediate-range missiles sold to saudi arabia, but the sale is still a ``disturbing regional trend,'' the state department said friday
the department confirmed that saudi arabia had acquired chinese missiles with a range of 2,200 miles _ capable of hitting all areas of the middle east, including israel
with iran and iraq engaged in a so-called ``war of the cities'' _ the lobbing of missiles against major population centers _ the introduction of more rockets into the region has raised concerns in washington, spokesmen said
it is another part of a disturbing regional trend in surface-to-surface missile proliferation,'' said rudolph boone, a state department press officer. ``the sum total of the proliferation is a degradation of the security of all states in the region.''
the missiles were described as chinese css-2 rockets, similar to those used in china's limited space program in the early 1970s and capable of being outfitted with nuclear warheads
such a system is not in the interests of peace and stability in the region,'' boone said
secretary of state george p. shultz expressed u.s. concern about the sales when he talked last week with chinese foreign minister wu xueqian, spokesman charles e. redman said
wu and other chinese officials since then have told the united states ``categorically that it will not export nuclear weapons to any government. we accept these assurances,'' redman said
saudi arabia as well ``has assured us at the very highest level that saudi arabia does not have nor does it intend to acquire any nuclear capability,'' redman said
he said the united states was in close touch with saudi arabia on the issue, as well as with other governments in the region, presumably israel
the united states and six other major industrialized democracies have agreed not to export ballistic and cruise missiles capable of carrying payloads of 1,100 pounds more than 187 miles
we've been actively engaged in an effort to get other countries to join that regime,'' redman said. ``all nations were invited to join. in the case of the chinese we have approached them specifically on several occasions about discussing it, but we really haven't had any response to that invitation.''
according to other officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, saudi arabia sought the chinese missiles after the u.s. congress blocked the sale of 48 f-15 jet fighters to the saudis. congress agreed late last year to permit the sale of 24 f-15s _ enough to keep saudi air strength at current levels
the administration has said saudi arabia needs sophisticated weapons for defense against a possible widening of the 7-year-old iran-iraq war
nearly 300 people demonstrating against sending u.s. troops to honduras were arrested today after blocking federal buildings in chicago, boston and in san francisco, where baton-wielding police officers waded into the crowd
more than 200 people were arrested in san francisco, up to 60 in chicago and one in boston on the second day of protests, police said. twelve men and 12 women were arrested for blocking traffic in front of the white house
about 50 protesters were arrested in the three cities thursday, the day 3,200 troops were sent to honduras in what the white house called a ``measured response'' to nicaraguan troops crossing the border into honduras
four hundred protesters marched today in chicago, chanting, ``reagan sent the troops today, get them out is what we say.'' five hundred blocked entry to the federal building in san francisco and 80 stopped traffic at a military recruiting office near the john f. kennedy federal building in boston
the chicago arrests, on misdemeanor disorderly conduct charges, came after demonstrators pasted 8{-by-11-inch orange stickers on first-floor windows at the loop federal building and sat in intersections, police said
many of the stickers bore skull and crossbones, and the message ``stop u.s. intervention in central america.''
more than 1,000 people marched thursday night from the honduras consulate to the federal building in san francisco. in minneapolis, protesters burned the u.s. flag. a mock ``central america war memorial'' was erected in philadelphia
at fort ord, calif., home of the 7th light infantry, wives of some of the 1,200 shipped-out soldiers joined protesters at the gates thursday
bring the troops home. no contra aid, no war,'' the boston protesters chanted today as they marched. one person was arrested
we want to non-violently protest president reagan's decision to send combat troops to central america,'' said the rev. michael curry of cliftondale united methodist church in sagus, a protest organizer. curry said the marchers were affiliated with the ecumenical pledge of resistance group
i believe our actions in central america are wrong,'' said lenore azaroff, 22, of somerville. ``i believe sending troops to honduras is the first step to another vietnam.''
more than 200 people were arrested today in san francisco as they blocked traffic and the entrance to the federal building. helmeted police at one point blocked a street, rerouting rush-hour traffic. protesters stalled three cars in streets near the building, forcing police to push them to the side
at least half a dozen violent confrontations erupted when demonstrators tried to grab police equipment, including batons. officers lashed back, jamming the batons in the demonstrators' stomachs and chests
the arrested demonstrators were handcuffed with plastic ties, photographed and booked on the street, then taken in police vans to the hall of justice
police said the demonstrators arrested today would be cited and released by federal authorities, just as 25 protesters were thursday
i'm outraged by the administation's sending troops to honduras. this is to cover-up all of reagan's mistakes. it's also a cover-up to divert our attention from the indictments,'' said businessman peter holbrook
four key figures in the iran-contra scandal were indicted wednesday, the day the white house annouced the troop movements
in washington, d.c., 150 to 200 people demonstrated in front of the white house today, said police officer tom randolph. twelve men and 12 women were arrested after the protest spilled into pennsylvania avenue. they were to have been fined $50 for blocking traffic, but that was cut to $25 for disorderly conduct because they didn't use a vehicle, randolph said
hundreds of sign-carrying demonstrators marched through beverly hills, calif., thursday shouting ``hands off'' and ``no war in central america.'' no one was arrested, although police cited two motorists for excessive honking
authorities in phoenix, ariz., arrested 24 people for trespassing when they blocked the entrance to the downtown federal building with a 30-foot-long homemade sign reading ``u.s. troops out of honduras.''
in minneapolis, 400 people wearing everything from business suits to studded leather jackets dragged newspaper racks and benches into a busy street, bringing traffic to a halt during the afternoon rush hour
the protesters burned a u.s. flag and chanted slogans as they crowded the streets. no injuries were reported
in boston, 200 people marched in a circle and chanted ``u.s. troops out of honduras'' outside the john f. kennedy federal building. police said six people remained inside after closing but were evicted without incident
u.s. rep. peter defazio, d-ore., joined about 200 people who gathered outside the federal courthouse building in eugene to denounce the action by the reagan administration
protesters in philadelphia erected a 30-foot ``central america war memorial'' that mimicked the vietnam memorial in the nation's capital. it bore the names of central americans killed in the region's civil wars. about 200 people marched in front of the federal courthouse
in fargo, n.d., on thursday, 60 people chanted, sang and carried signs outside the post office to protest
at fort ord, a the base 90 miles south of san francisco, the demonstrators included a pregnant renee worthing, 21, wife of soldier james worthing. she carried a sign that said, ``stop the lies.''
i think the whole thing has just been a lie,'' she said. ``every time a presidential election comes up, a crisis comes up and the president runs to the rescue. the community is not going to stand for this.''
once the home of viking chiefs and storyteller hans christian andersen, the city of odense celebrated its 1,000th birthday friday with hopes of recapturing the grandeur of its past
this city in central denmark was once a cultural center and industrial power, but it fell on hard economic times. local officials have planned year-long millenium festivities to help generate new business
queen margrethe ii marked the city's anniversary by attending a day of music and pageantry under clear skies. fireworks and a torchlight procession were scheduled for the evening
cultural and sporting events, such as the junior cycling world championships, ballet, theater and a huge laser-based sound-and-light show, were planned for later in the year
odense is at the geographic center of denmark, on the island of funen. it takes its birth date from the first written reference to the city ever found _ a letter from german emperor otto iii granting the church in odense tax relief. it was dated march 18, 988
the city's symbol is a swan, from andersen's fairy tale of the ugly duckling, because odense developed from a poor, backward farming town to an industrial powerhouse
but odense's shipbuilding, iron and wood industries eventually became outdated, and unemployment climbed
in recent years, much of odense's income has come from tourists visiting the yellow cottage where andersen, the son of a shoemaker and a washerwoman, was born in 1805
about 200,000 people every year visit the home of denmark's most famous author, who wrote ``the princess and the pea,'' ``the emperor's new clothes'' and other tales
parts of odense are the same as in andersen's days, with winding cobblestoned streets lined with 18th-century houses. but today the charm of the inner city is surrounded by high-rise buildings and urban malls
with 173,000 residents, odense is denmark's third largest city. about 100 years ago it was the biggest in the country. today it is dominated by small companies, 97 percent of which employ fewer than 50 people
we have one of the country's highest unemployment rates, almost 11 percent and growing,'' said bjarne christensen, the city manager. the average jobless rate in denmark is 8 percent
christensen said he believed the millenium could mark a turning point
the goal is to market odense nationally and internationally, to support the culture and to create a festive atmosphere,'' he said. ``of course we also aim at attracting people and business.''
an 11-mile tunnel-bridge link between funen and the main island of zealand is to be opened in 1993, giving odense greater chances to bid for conferences
we hope to become denmark's center. with the great belt bridge, you can get here from copenhagen in an hour and 15 minutes,'' mayor verner dahlsgaard said in an interview
denmark's second tv channel, opening later this year, will be based in odense
the name odense is from ``odins vi,'' meaning the shrine of odin who was chief of the nordic gods and patron of culture and language. the city prides itself on its museums, three of them under the roof of a converted 19th-century cloth factory
north of odense at ladby, archaeologists discovered the remains of a 72-foot ship which was put into the 1,000-year-old grave of a viking chief, along with his 11 horses
christianity came to odense in the 9th century. the medevial cathedral built in 1300 contains the tomb of st. knud, a king who was murdered by his subjects for imposing high taxes
rhythm-and-blues musician ike turner, ex-husband of pop star tina turner, was convicted friday on two felony cocaine charges, but was cleared of possessing the drug for sale
turner, 55, of los angeles, was stopped in august by officers who said he was driving erratically. he was arrested when they found 5.6 grams of rock cocaine in his car
jurors deliberated four hours before finding turner guilty of cocaine possession and transportation, but not of possessing the drugs for sale. sentencing was scheduled april 15
in another case, turner was was to appear in pasadena superior court later friday on charges he sold $16,000 worth of cocaine to an undercover officer in hollywood, said the bailiff, deputy robert goldsmith
turner played backup rhythm and blues in the early 1950s before headlining with the ikettes. later that decade, he met and married miss turner. together they formed the ike and tina turner revue. their biggest hit was ``proud mary.''
the couple split in 1976, and miss turner went on to appear in feature films and record the 1985 grammy-winning record of the year, ``what's love got to do with it?'' cyprus</head>
president reagan said friday he sees a chance for significant progress toward settlement of the long-standing dispute over cyprus between greece and turkey
in a bimonthly report to congress as required by law, the president noted that the new special representative of the united nations, oscar camilion, visited cyrpus shortly after the election of george vassilou as president in february and ``expressed his hope that there will be progress in the near future.''
we also have seen the development of a new climate between greece and turkey as a result of the recent meetings between prime ministers (andreas) papandreou and (turgut) ozal,'' the president said
cyprus has been split between turkish and greek cypriots for 14 years. in 1983, the turkish cypriot minority, which makes up 17 percent of the population of 650,000, proclaimed a breakaway state in the turkish-occupied northern third of the mediterranean island nation
vassilou, a leader of the 500,000 greek cypriots, was sworn in as president on feb. 28 and promised to seek direct talks with turkey. the turks have about 30,000 troops and 65,000 settlers in the northern part of cyprus
altough talks between the two sides had been deadlocked for two years, reagan said papandreou and ozal ``have resolved to increase their cooperation and to work toward lasting solutions of the issues dividing greece and turkey. we welcome this development and resultant building of confidence and lessening of tensions in the area.''
these recent developments, he said, ``reinforce my belief that there is an opportunity at this time to make real progress toward a settlement of the dispute.''
reagan made his remarks in a letter to house speaker jim wright, d-texas, and sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., chairman of the senate foreign relations committee
anti-government protesters set fire to a downtown department store friday as demonstrations over the playing of music in a tea shop persisted in the capital
hundreds of students and other protester demonstrated in support of students at the rangoon institute of technology who rioted march 12 after a dispute in a tea shop
one student died in the violence, which began when students argued with villagers over what songs to play on a tape player
police occupied the campus tuesday and detained a number of students suspected of fighting the villagers
larger groups of both students and villagers resumed fighting on sunday and about 200 students set fire to seven buildings, according to the burma broadcasting service
on friday, witnesses said more than 300 students from government high schools gathered at a public park
they shouted anti-government slogans, and joined by outsiders, wrecked government cars in the area. the protesters then set fire to a nearby government department store. traffic was paralyzed
several arrests were made before riot police dispersed the crowd three hours after the protest began
student disturbances are rare in this southeast asian nation, which has been under ne win's one-party rule since 1962
a bipartisan group of senators today proposed a $48 million package of new aid to nicaragua's contra rebels, including renewed authority for the cia to deliver previously stockpiled weapons
supporters said the proposal was designed to trigger negotiations in congress and with the reagan administration aimed at quick passage of an emergency infusion of aid to replace supplies lost or expended during the past week's heavy fighting along the nicaraguan-honduran border
we think it's very important right now to send a signal to the sandinista government'' which allegedly crossed the border into honduras in an effort to destroy rebel camps and supplies, said sen. david boren, d-okla., one of 11 sponsors of the new aid proposal
sen. nancy kassebaum, r-kan., said announcement of the package also would strengthen the contras as they enter direct cease-fire talks with the managua regime on monday
the proposal would use $48 million in unspent pentagon money to buy food, clothing, shelter and medical supplies, and to transport it to troops in the field, over the next year. about $3 million of that amount would go for communications gear
but in what promised to be a controversial provision, the package would allow the cia to airdrop ammunition and weapons previously stockpiled by the rebels to troops in the field. boren said the rebels still have $2 million to $5 million worth of undelivered supplies, about half of them lethal
and it would give president reagan the right to hold a quick, guaranteed vote in congress on any request for further military aid under certain conditions if the peace talks between the sandinistas and contras break down
as a ``carrot,'' the bill also would promise long-term economic aid for the region once political stability is restored
sen. daniel evans, r-wash., who has opposed contra aid in the past, said he was supporting the latest proposal because it ``is the best way to ensure that (the peace talks) have some chance of success.''
action on further aid for the rebels has been stalled since march 3, when the house narrowly rejected a $30 million package of purely humanitarian aid. aid proponents saw the sandinista incursion into honduras as a new opportunity to revive interest in aid
tan siew sin, former finance minister and head of a multinational company based here, died friday of a heart attack at age 72
he served in the cabinet from the time of independence from britain in 1957 until his retirement in 1974
after retirement he continued as economic adviser to the government
the millionaire also was chairman of the sime darby group, which owns rubber, palm oil and cocoa plantations, and trading houses and factories in malaysia, singapore, hong kong, london, australia, indonesia, the philippines and other countries
a hospital is not treating cancer patients older than 70 with radiation because of a shortage of nurses
the head of the radiumhemmet cancer clinic, jerzy einhorn, called the move ``an extremely painful decision,'' but said the hospital lacked resources to treat everyone
associate professor ulrik ringborg, an administrator at the stockholm clinic, told the aftonbladet newspaper that no one had been turned away because of age since the decision was adopted march 7. some patients, however, were offered alternative treatments to radium
the hospital's decision prompted an outcry from prime minister ingvar carlsson and government health officials. ``no one in sweden should be too old to receive the treatment needed,'' carlsson said
health minister gertrud sigurdsen called the age limit ``unacceptable and a violation of the public health care law.''
long waits are common for non-urgent treatments under the socialized medical system, but the clinic's move appeared to mark a new level in the hospital crisis. the employee shorage has been caused by resignations of experienced nurses, who complained of low salaries, overtime, stress and low status
funds for public medicine are distributed by the governments of each county. most health care is free and financed with tax money
the ruling military council on friday announced a government reshuffling that expands the military's role
there were no personnel changes in the six-man council. but one of its members, col. thabe letsie, will take on expanded duties as foreign minister. he replaces lengolo monyake, who has been reassigned as minister of works
col. ramohlanka ntsohi also was named ambassador to nearby mozambique friday. his appointment marks the first time an active military officer has been named to a foreign diplomatic post since lesotho became independent from the british in 1966
in another change, banda machobane, former vice chancellor of the university of lesotho, has become minister of education
the military council, headed by maj. gen. justin lekhanya, has banned all political activity since prime minister leabua jonathan was ousted in a january 1986 coup
the landlocked nation of 1.5 million people was once known as basutoland. it is surrounded by south africa, which heavily bolsters its economy
the european space agency has agreed after two years of contentious negotiations to take part in the u.s. space station project and provide a laboratory module to be permanently attached to the earth-orbiting facility
the agreement, approved by the 13-member esa council, provides for cooperation in the design, development, operation and use of the space station. the european investment in the module to be called ``columbus'' is expected to exceed $2 billion
the united states is currently in the detailed design stage of building the space station, which is expected to be ready for occupancy early in 1998. the estimate of u.s. costs has risen from a projection of $8 billion made in 1984 to more than $30 billion in current dollars
japan also is expected t contribute $2 billion and canada about $800,000
cooperation between the united states and esa seemed doomed to failure late in 1986 when the pentagon announced it wanted to retain its options for military research on the station. the national aeronautics and space administration had to assure its european, as well as canadian and japanese partners, that no major weapons systems would be placed aboard, although the research option remains
nasa said the agreement ``marks the end of more than two years of negotiations on the technical and programmatic framework between the two agencies in the largest cooperative civil space project undertaken.''
in its decision thursday, the esa council authorized director general reimer luest to sign a memorandum of understanding with nasa administrator james c. fletcher in the near future
the memorandum of understanding is being reviewed by the reagan administration, then will be submitted to congress for review before it is signed by the two parties
it also has to be approved by each of the esa member governments: austria, belgium, denmark, france, west germany, ireland, italy, netherlands, norway, spain, sweden, switzerland and the united kingdom
in addition to providing the columbus module to the space station complex, the esa also will furnish an unmanned free-flying polar-orbiting platform for earth observation experiments. the united states is developing a similar platform
as a third element, esa will provide a free-flying spacecraft designed to accommodate long-duration microgravity applications in the fields of fluid physics, life and material sciences, nasa said. that spacecraft will be visited periodically by astronauts
the free-flyer will be launched into an orbit, compatible with that of the space station, by an ariane 5 rocket
presidernt reagan invited european participation in the space station program in 1984 and nasa and esa agreed the following year on what elements would be provided by each agency
roman catholics plan to demonstrate march 25 in the slovakian capital of bratislava to bolster calls for a free and independent church, religious sources said friday
the planned demonstration was intended to back a petition calling for religious freedom and separation of church and state. that petition has been signed by 400,000 czechoslovak catholics, according to slovakian church sources in bratislava and vienna, austria
cardinal frantisek tomasek, czechoslovakia's catholic primate, has urged his flock to sign the petition. it has gained support from religious believers throughout the nation, where bishops and priests are paid with government funds and must receive state approval before taking their posts
demonstrators also will press for quick appointment of 10 new bishops. government officials have been arguing with the vatican over the vacant posts
no breakthrough has been achieved so far, and the talks are scheduled to resume in rome on april 11, a czechoslovak government spokesman said this week
the planned demonstration was announced in a letter to local authorities by franitsek miklosko, a catholic layman, according to the austrian catholic news service kathpress. organizers of the rally reportedly told authorities it will be peaceful with participants lighting candles symbolizing their support
there has been no comment from the government on the planned demonstration
the senate approved by voice vote friday a bill that would boost from $700 million to more than $7 billion the pool of insurance available for swift disbursement to victims of a major nuclear accident
moments earlier, the chamber narrowly rejected an amendment by sen. john glenn, d-ohio, designed to bolster oversight of the 127 nuclear facilities run by the department of energy, including plants involved in the production of nuclear weapons
glenn proposed the establishment of an independent panel to investigate safety problems at the doe's aging reactors. but after winning an early test vote, 47-44, he was defeated on each of four successive roll calls in parliamentary maneuvering that saw both sides scrambling for last-minute converts
on his last chance, glenn lost, 49-42, after coming within a vote or two in the intervening tallies
the senate's action on the overall bill, a 20-year extension of the price-anderson act, sent the measure back to the house, which approved a slightly different version last july
since 1957, the law has provided for a nationwide pool of insurance funds that would be tapped to compensate victims of an accident at a nuclear reactor or related facility
under current provisions, the pool could pay up to $700 million if the accident involved a commercial nuclear power plant, and up to $500 million if it involved a government-owned facility. both the house and senate versions of the renewal legislation would boost the amount in both cases to more than $7 billion
glenn agreed that the monetary boost is necessary when measured against the lessons resulting from the explosion and fire at the chernobyl reactor in the soviet union in 1986. but ``price-anderson insurance is no substitute for steps to prevent a nuclear accident,'' he said
glenn cited a long history of safety and environmental problems at the doe's nuclear plants, including the savannah river production reactors in south carolina
it is a terrible irony,'' he said, that while the nation seeks to deter a nuclear attack by constanting upgrading its own nuclear arsenal, ``large numbers of americans are in danger of being poisoned by radiation in peacetime.''
glenn, whose governmental affairs committee has revealed a number of environmental and safety hazards at doe plants, proposed an independent oversight panel with the authority to appeal directly to the president for safety improvements if the energy department balked at its reports
the amendment was opposed by armed services committee chairman sam nunn, d-ga., and energy committee chairman bennett johnston, d-la. both said they could support glenn's proposal if it is attached to a separate defense authorization bill later in the year, but they argued it did not belong in the price-anderson package
the bill would require nuclear utilities to continue to buy the maximum amount of private liability insurance available, now amounting to about $160 million per plant
if the private insurance proved insufficient to compensate victims of an accident, each of the nation's commercial plants, now totaling 110, would be assessed an equal amount to cover the additional costs, to a maximum of $7.06 billion. under that provision, each plant could have to pay up to $63 million
the government, meanwhile, would self-insure its own plants, up to the same $7 billion total. if a single accident proved even more costly than that, it would be up to congress whether to appropriate additional taxpayer funds
the no-fault system, for both private and government plants, shortcuts the usual legal requirements for damage claims by eliminating the necessity for victims to bring individual lawsuits in court. the nuclear industry has long agreed to that facet of the program in exchange for the cap on total liability. conservatives'</head>
pat robertson said friday he is staying in the republican presidential race despite vice president george bush's overwhelming delegate lead because ``there has to be a rallying point for conservatives.''
otherwise, the former television evangelist told a news conference, conservatives would lose their political leverage to influence bush on specific foreign or domestic policies or influence his selection of a vice presidential running mate
if everybody drops out, then whatever policies are being advocated by george bush will become the policies of the republican party,'' robertson said
but, he conceded, ``if the trend continues, george bush has a pretty close lock on it, absent some unforeseen event.''
certainly i'm a realist and i can count,'' robertson said, referring to bush's accumulation so far of more than 700 of the 1,139 delegates needed to win the gop presidential nomination in august. the associated press delegate count gives robertson just 17 delegates
robertson said he is continuing his campaign to further the conservative principles of president reagan
i'm a supporter of ronald reagan. i'd like to see the reagan policies of 1980 and the republican platform of 1984 carried on to 1988,'' he said
questioned about farm issues, robertson said he wants ``a world that is free of subsidies by the year 2000'' but that he supports ``some writedown of farm debt'' for family farmers. robertson said he would redirect agricultural subsidy funds from agribusiness to family farmers
eighteen members of congress flew to michigan friday trying to help revive the flagging presidential campaign of fellow rep. richard gephardt, who said, ``i'm the underdog today but that doesn't really matter.''
rep. john dingell of trenton, mich., said gephardt's support in the house was significant because ``we in congress don't like weaklings or phonies.''
a new poll published friday showed gephardt well behind democratic rivals michael dukakis and jesse jackson in michigan. but the missouri congressman said, ``i think you will see that the gephardt message about economic revival is going to get through to the michigan voters.''
gephardt, soundly beaten on super tuesday and then again this week in illinois, has pinned much of the future of his campaign on the march 26 michigan caucuses, which will allocate 138 of the state's 150 delegates to the democratic national convention next july in atlanta
eighty house members support his nomination, gephardt has said. among the 18 who joined him friday was michigan's rep. dingell, who said gephardt's support among members of congress reflected their greater experience with him than with jackson and massachusetts gov. dukakis
he ``is obviously a known quantity,'' dingell said. ``we also know how he responds in a crisis. we in congress don't like weaklings or phonies.''
gephardt dismissed a new survey, conducted for the detroit free press and wxyz-tv and published in friday editions of the newspaper, that showed dukakis and jackson each favored by 32 percent of michigan democrats or others leaning toward the party
gephardt was preferred by 10 percent of the 328 voters surveyed earlier this week. sens. albert gore jr. of tennessee and paul simon of illinois each had 6 percent support, and 14 percent was undecided. the poll's margin of error was plus or minus 5 percentage points, the free press said
the candidate said he had overcome poor showings in surveys prior to the iowa democratic caucuses and in other states
we're going to make political history in michigan, just as we did in iowa,'' he said
gephardt had also flown house colleagues in to help him in iowa
that time, 42 congressmen flew on a chartered plane that cost $15,500, an expense partially defrayed by lobbyists who flew along. the plane ride turned into a flying fund-raiser, drawing pointed comments from critics who noted that gephardt was running as the anti-establishment candidate
gephardt spokesman mark johnson said friday there were no lobbyists on the plane this trip. ``you all make much more of this than we do. this is just, send them out to a couple events and come back.''
the congressmen flew into detroit on two planes, he said, one belonging to chrysler and the other a regular charter. ``the campaign paid for it _ first class airfare for everybody,'' he said
illegal immigrants who find amnesty application fees too steep will be able to get interest-free loans from the catholic diocese of el paso, the bishop said friday
i think it's good for our community for these individuals to become citizens,'' bishop raymundo pena said. ``they would have better opportunities to get good-paying jobs and that would help our economy.''
under the program, people who apply for immigration amnesty through the diocese's migrant and refugee services program are eligible for one-year loans if they live below the federal poverty level
under the immigration reform and control act of 1986, people who have lived in the united states illegally since before jan. 1, 1982, are eligible for amnesty. immigrants who qualify for amnesty are granted temporary residency, and are eligible later for permanent residency and then citizenship
the deadline for applying is may 4. the government announced friday it will give people seeking amnesty 60 additional days to submit supporting documents
the immigration and naturalization service charges a filing fee of $185 per person or a maximum of $420 per family, plus a $75 counseling fee and a $10 photo and fingerprint fee
applicants also must go to a doctor for a medical exam. often, they hire lawyers to help them, and the search for documentation can become expensive. the ins justifies the fees by saying they are a way to ensure that applicants won't become public charges
i think the government has a valid argument that they should be self-sufficient,'' pena said at a news conference. ``but illegal immigrants get caught in a catch-22 situation where they can't get a work permit, so they can't get a job that pays enough money.''
ins spokesman art moreno said the agency approves of the program
about 27,000 people in new mexico and west texas have applied for amnesty so far, moreno said. an estimated 10 percent of those qualified for amnesty can't afford the filing fees, the rev. rick matty said
the diocese needs about $60,000 to fund the loan program, and has raised about $12,000 so far from businesses and individuals, pena said
a couple accused by a 13-year-old girl of having sex on a trans-atlantic flight were arrested, and two men who began throwing food when a flight attendant intervened also were charged, police said
the passengers were arrested when american airlines flight 37 from munich, west germany, to san diego, calif., made an intermediate stop in chicago, said sgt. jerry thornton of the police o'hare international airport unit
but phillip matin, 52, of loomis, calif., said he and his wife were sleeping
this was the fantasy of a young girl that is completely uncorroborated,'' matin told the sacramento (calif.) bee on thursday. ``it's ridiculous.''
it was broad daylight, and there were people walking around,'' matin said. ``even at home with our kids, we are careful.''
he and his wife, sharyn jo van tassell, 42, a lawyer and part-time judge, were arrested monday and charged with public indecency
police said most passengers apparently were asleep during the atlantic crossing when the girl motioned to her mother that she believed the couple across the aisle was engaged in a sex act
the girl's mother summoned a flight attendant, who notified a supervisor, barbara weiderman, thornton said
ms. weiderman told the plane's captain, and the captain radioed police to be on standby at o'hare
at that point, two other passengers ``became abusive and belligerent'' and began throwing food and drinks at flight attendants, according to the police report
roger f. cline, 42, of placerville, calif., and stanley wells, 53, of cameron park, calif., were both charged with disorderly conduct
all four missed the continuation of their flight to san diego, but paid the bonds set on their misdemeanor charges and were released pending april court appearances, police said
matin, a doctor, was also charged with possession of a controlled substance after authorities found eight yellow pills in one of his bags. matin said the pills were valium but he couldn't prove they were prescription drugs because the bottle they came from was in his luggage
merv griffin's $225 million offer for resorts international inc. has put him at odds with the hotel and casino operator's flamboyant chairman, donald trump
griffin co., the former talk show host's private company, made its $35 a share offer contingent on winning trump's backing and his agreement to end his five-year management agreement for resorts' atlantic city, n.j., properties
but an attorney for trump spurned griffin's offer thursday as a ``blatant attempt at market manipulation.''
the new york real estate baron controls about 90 percent of resorts' voting power and is offering $22 per share to take the company private. his lawyer claimed griffin's offer was instigated by another major resorts shareholder seeking to force trump to raise his bid
resorts' board decided thursday that griffin's offer was ``moot'' and reiterated its support for trump's bid
in response, a spokesman for griffin, who broke into the hotel business late last year by buying the beverly hilton in beverly hills for $100 million, said he is considering legal action against resorts' outside directors
