the royal canadian mounted police charged her in provincial court thursday after seizing a package at her home
she denies the offense and is anxious to get this matter cleared up in court,'' said lawyer michael edelson
canadian press news agency reported that police seized the package after an informer in british columbia tipped them off that ms. kemper would receive one pound of marijuana in the mail
ms. kemper, 39, is to appear in court april 11
the jet-setting former first lady divorced trudeau in 1983 and married ottawa real estate developer fried kemper the following year, with whom she has one son
former mayor dianne feinstein says she's hoping to learn about big business in her new role as board member of bancal tri-state corp. and its bank of california subsidiary
i'm a private citizen and not looking to make any political decisions this year,'' she said thursday after her election to the board. it was her first professional venture since leaving office two months ago
the new job is ``an opportunity for me to learn more about a major business in the bay area and the state of california,'' feinstein said. ``i'm just a beginner.''
the corporation expanded its board from 15 to 16 members to make room for the ex-mayor, who attended her first meeting after her election and was assigned to the trust committee
audrey hepburn said she was overwhelmed after visiting drought-plagued northern ethiopia, where millions are threatened with starvation
let us hope that the spades we provide them will be used to dig wells, not to dig graves for children,'' she said thursday
miss hepburn, on a three-day visit in her first assignment as a special ambassador for the united nation's children's fund, said she would appeal around the world for long-term development aid to help ethiopia overcome recurrent drought, as well as massive emergency aid to stop this year's disaster reaching famine proportions
western novelist louis l'amour has won a $55,000 out-of-court settlement against la plata county and a power company in a battle over a power line that crosses his ranch
colorado-ute electric association last august completed a 345,000-volt power line supported by three poles and a lattice tower on l'amour's 1,000-acre ranch in southwestern colorado
i can't sit around trying to write looking at these monsters,'' l'amour said earlier. ``that's what these towers look like _ monsters from mars.''
l'amour has shunned 100 acres of his ranch because he fears the power line poses a health hazard, his attorney, russell yates, said friday
the county agreed to pay l'amour $4,000 and colorado-ute will pay $20,000 to settle l'amour's claim that approval for the power line was arbitrary, yates said. the utility also will pay $31,000 in compensation, he added
cheered by about 150 flag-wavers, king carl xvi gustaf and queen silvia of sweden toured this province's legislature friday
the couple received bouquets of flowers from well-wishers as they walked up red-carpeted steps to be welcomed by premier bill vander zalm and other provincial officials
flowers in sweden's colors of blue and yellow adorned the rotunda and the legislative library where the king and queen learned a bit of british columbia history
the royal couple also met 85-year-old britta wickham, who moved to canada in 1923 from sweden. wickham called it a once-in-a-lifetime experience
after two dismal seasons, many maple syrup producers say the sap is running well this season and hope their good luck will last
we've got it coming out of our ears. we've got so much sap we don't know when we're going to get it all boiled in,'' said nancy clark of clark's sugar house in alstead
clark's sugar house, which usually produces about 1,000 gallons a season, only made 620 last year. this year the trees have yielded about 500 gallons
a year ago we were at 411 gallons,'' said roger adams of stuart and john's sugar house in westmoreland. ``this year we're at 1,250.''
last year, stuart and john's produced only 1,400 gallons; in a good year they produce up to 3,000 gallons
about 60 percent of the state's maple syrup is produced in the connecticut river valley, where producers are pressed to keep up with the flow, said agriculture commissioner steve taylor
prices have leveled at about $35 a gallon, taylor said, adding that even with a good season, he does not expect prices to drop dramatically because demand remains high after the last two years
annual maple syrup production in the state averages about 77,000 gallons, taylor said. however, the last two crops yielded about 47,000 gallons, compared to the bumper crop of 102,000 gallons in 1984
the poor crops were directly attributable to a cycle of warm days and warm nights. without cool nights and warm days, sap doesn't run
the weather has everything to do with it,'' adams said
though some producers experienced small sap runs two weeks ago, this week's sunny weather following cool evenings had buckets and pipelines overflowing
this last time it started running it doesn't seem it'll ever stop,'' clark said. adams added that his two wood-fired evaporators are ``going full tilt.''
liz bascom, co-owner of the state's largest syrup producer, bascom's sugar house in acworth, said she was unwilling to predict a banner year because a quick thaw could end the season as quickly as it began
shirley sullivan of broken ridge farm said the sap was running so heavily that it almost guaranteed she would be working until midnight
i like that,'' she said. documents</head>
the federal government on friday tried to bolster its amnesty program by giving illegal aliens who file in the final month of the plan 60 more days to provide documents to support their applications
under the change in the program _ which has attracted a lower-than-anticipated number of applications _ amnesty seekers will be able to file a skeletal application from april 4 to the may 4 deadline without producing back-up documentation and medical data until sometime after july 5
the reagan administration has said it opposes extending the filing deadline, despite sentiment in congress to do so
if any of you have ever filed your income tax on the night of the 14th of april, there's usually one document or one fact you don't get,'' attorney general edwin meese iii told reporters at an immigration office in arlington, va. ``we want to be sure that doesn't stop anybody from this program.''
just over 1 million amnesty applications have been filed, and although a last-minute surge is anticipated, the volume of requests is likely to fall far below the 2 million estimated as recently as january by alan nelson, commission of the u.s. immigration and naturalization service
our goal is not two million,'' meese said. ``our goal is for every eligible person to apply.'' if an eligible alien doesn't apply by may 4, ``that's the person's fault, not ours,'' he added
legislation with 60 co-sponsors would extend the filing deadline for another year, but meese opposed the idea of extending it
there's no reason to,'' he said. ``the more confusion and hesitancy ... in the program, the more the temptation is out there then to postpone and postpone and postpone.''
rep. charles schumer, d-n.y., who introduced the extension legislation, called the change ``virtually meaningless.''
the administration's approach assumes many illegal aliens haven't filed because they lack documentation. but ``many illegal aliens have not stepped forward, because they still fear the ins,'' schumer said. ``to them the ins is the agency that is supposed to throw them out of the country.''
meese said that if an extension were granted, at the end of that time ``people would say they extended it before, they'll probably extend it again.''
it is our hope that on may 4 every single person who is eligible for legalization will have applied,'' the attorney general said
the application can be completed in less than 30 minutes, nelson said
since the amnesty program began last may 4, ins personnel have ``gone the extra mile in all respects and it seems sad at the end not to deal with it in a little more flexible way,'' said jerry tinker, staff director of the senate subcommittee on immigration and refugee policy
short of legislation, there were a number of administrative steps ins could have taken, including deferring the payment of fees _ $420 for families _ to encourage people to apply for amnesty
tinker said there were extensive discussions with ins officials over various administrative moves and ``for them to come forth with this mouse was disappointing.''
under the 1986 immigration reform and control act, illegal aliens who have lived in the united states since jan. 1, 1982, can be granted amnesty if they provide documentation supporting their claim of having lived here for the past six years
meese and nelson also announced another change in the program that would give private groups more time to locate aliens eligible for amnesty
in the past, these private groups assisting the immigration service collected fees only after they had completed filling out forms for an applicant, a process that can take three hours or longer
under the change, the groups will be given a referral fee for each applicant as soon as they have directed an alien to an ins legalization office
the following was filed by otto kreisher of copley news service, steven komarow of the associated press and robert cohen of newsweek, members of a pentagon press pool covering the u.s. troops in honduras
hundreds of american paratroopers filled the morning sky friday in a spectacular show of military muscle
u.s. ambassador everett briggs said the action filled a honduran request for support against what he insisted was an invasion by nicaragua
this readiness exercise is a fine demonstration of our ability to respond very quickly, when requested, and to show support,'' everett briggs told reporters at the scene of the parachute drop of about 800 men from the 82nd airborne division of fort bragg, n.c
briggs said that stories that the united states had pressured honduran president jose azcona into requesting the exercise ``are absolutely false.''
he said azcona first approached him on tuesday
they asked for ways in which we could demonstrate our support,'' briggs said. ``we discussed ways we might respond and settled on this particular method.''
even though the white house said the cable from azcona wasn't received until late wednesday, more than eight hours after troops were put on alert for the mission, briggs said he was sure the letter was written tuesday night
referring to the 1,500 to 2,000 sandinista troops who he said have crossed into honduras, briggs said ``by central american standards, i don't think it's wrong to call it an invasion.'' he said most of those nicaraguan troops were still in honduras
briggs said the honduran ministry had reported that its aircraft ``had made a couple of runs along the border'' in response to the sandinista invasion. he quoted the honduran minister as saying they hit a nicaraguan helicopter
the united states was not suggesting to the hondurans what type of military response to make. ``this is their country and it's their country that has had this fairly large sandinista incursion,'' he said. ``they've been telling us what they plan to do and asking our support.''
gen. fred f. woerner, commander of the u.s. southern command based in panama, came here to review the exercise and said it was ``a reassuring factor to our allies, not only in honduras, but elsewhere.''
woerner said also there were ``some very, very preliminary'' indications that the sandinistas were starting to withdraw, but he said the duration of the u.s. exercise was ``not necessarily'' linked to that
friday's parachute drop went ``absolutely super,'' said brig. gen. daniel schroeder, commander of the joint task force, who said the force of 3,000 men would be complete later in the day after a few more planeloads arrived with troops of the 7th infantry division of fort ord, calif
honduran defense minister wilfredo sanchez valladres greeted the men shortly after they landed in the brush-covered valley about five miles south of the air base
we thank you for coming to work with us,'' he said. ``the morale of the honduran people has been reinforced by this.''
the morale of the troops also was buoyed by the chance to conduct an exercise away from their home base and near a combat scene
schroeder smiled but deferred when asked whether he thought the troops wanted to see action against the sandinistas. obviously, he said, the men were aware of the nearby battles and he said ``the adrenaline is pumping.''
sgt. doug longpre, 22, of the 82nd airborne said, ``everybody is psyched up about being down here.''
hours after the paratroopers arrived, another battalion of the 82nd airborne was flying out of palmerola in helicopters for joint exercises with honduran troops in an area nearer but still 100 miles from the combat zone
the u.s. commanders continued to say their orders were to stay away from actual conflict. troops were ready and had ample ammunition and weapons including light tanks and artillery to respond if called upon, they said
the arrival of the paratroopers was the most dramatic display of the american deployment, but most of the troops and supplies were being delivered by a stream of jet transports that arrived every half hour around the clock. the aerial convoy included a giant c-5 galaxy which brought attack reconnaissance and troop-carrying helicopters
the paratroopers spilled out of eight air force c-141 jets on a calm, clear morning and the airbone commander said it was completed without injury
schroeder said part of the training value of the exercise was the change in climates. they had boarded their planes at fort bragg in freezing cold and then floated down in the tropical heat. nicaraguan request</head>
the security council convened an urgent meeting today at nicaragua's request to discuss the nicaraguan-honduran conflict and the deployment of u.s. troops in honduras
the 15-member council, the highest u.n. body charged with maintaining international peace and security, was to hear three speakers: nicaragua, honduras and the united states
in washington, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said today the united states supports the meeting
asked if the united states would present ``show-and-tell'' evidence of nicaraguan forces invading neighboring honduras, fitzwater said the production of evidence is up to honduras. he stressed that the movement of american forces into honduras was strictly in response to a request of honduran president jose azcona
the united states sent 3,200 troops to honduras after charging that nicaraguan troops entered honduras in pursuit of contra rebels
secretary-general javier perez de cuellar, meanwhile, was studying nicaragua's request to send an observer team to its border with honduras on a fact-finding mission
the meeting was called for information purposes and there were no immediate plans for a resolution. the 159-member world body usually votes with nicaragua and other latin american and developing countries against the united states
on thursday, nicaragua's chief delegate, julio icaza gallard, sent a letter requesting an ``urgent and immediate'' meeting on the u.s. action. nicaragua's speaker was expected to be rita dalia casco, director of international organizations within the foreign ministry
earlier thursday, gallard denounced the united states during a security council debate on british military maneuvers in the disputed falkland islands claimed by argentina
he condemned british ``buccaneers who pillaged our coast in the past.''
nicaragua today is the vicim of the threats and aggression of another american state,'' he said. ``it denounces, once again, this gunboat policy which reflects disdain for our dignity and rights. we must oppose them with the force of right, law, justice and the decisive strength of international solidarity to win respect for our sovereignty.''
the secretary-general has urged all parties to exercise restraint and abide by the guatemala accord, signed by all five central american nations
the council members are the united states, britain, china, france and the soviet union _ the ``big five'' permanent members with veto power _ and yugoslavia, algeria, argentina, brazil, italy, japan, nepal, senegal, west germany and zambia
police on friday announced they recovered nearly all of the $8 million in u.s. cash that vanished from a february air shipment from the united states to argentina
it was the largest brink's robbery in the history of the company, which was protecting the cash
the money was recovered by narcotics agents working for rio de janeiro's specialized police department
four suspects, all brazilian employees of a private cargo firm that operated at rio's international airport, were arrested
it's obvious they planned it together. we are going to interrogate them to find out how they pulled it off,'' said nilo augusto batista, head of the specialized police department
the suspects and the recovered money were shown to reporters at the narcotics squad's headquarters, a dilapidated, turn-of-the-century building in downtown rio
the suspects, all appearing to be in their late 20s, hid their faces from reporters and clicking cameras and refused to answer any questions
the money was part of a $52 million shipment from the federal reserve board in new york to the central bank of argentina, said marven moss, a spokesman for brink's inc., based in darien, conn
the money disappeared feb. 5 when 13 canvas sacks containing $52 million were transferred in rio's international airport from a flight from new york to one to the argentine capital of buenos aires. two of the sacks never made it to argentina
batista said the cargo company which hired the four suspects ``took the money out of the first plane, put it on a cart and took it in for inspection by government officials. afterward the money was placed inside vans and taken to the second plane'' for the trip to argentina. somewhere along the line $8 million vanished
he said the first break in the case came when the narcotics squad of his department came across certain information about the theft apparently from tipsters with connections to rio's drug trafficking world
even though this case was, technically, not in the drug area, our people followed the tip, and the result was nearly total success,'' batista said. he added that the dollars were traced to the states of sao paulo, espirito santo, minas gerais and rio de janeiro, where the thieves tried to exchange them, apparently for other american dollars or for foreign currency
narcotics division detective antonio carlos estevam, who coordinated the three-man team that arrested the four suspects and found the money, said ``it was a combination of solid police work and luck. we have no crystal ball.''
usually, when there is a large theft of money, most of it gravitates to the drug world. this is the theory we operated on after the airport incident. i would say we have achieved what no police force anywhere else has ever achieved. we captured all the suspects, recovered practically all the money and no one was hurt,'' estevam said
estevam said the operation started thursday when two of the suspects were arrested in a car in the ilha do governador district located near the airport. later that day, two more suspects were arrested and the money was recovered
batista said the four suspects were brazilians and that there were no signs of involvement by foreigners. he added that none of the money wound up in the hands of drug dealers
the recovered money belongs to brink's, since its insurance repaid the federal reserve board for the theft, moss said
parents and schools are keeping closer watch on their children as authorities and volunteers look for a man who has tried to lure youngsters into his car in new hampshire-massachusetts border communities
police report that the man has approached children at least a dozen times in the last three weeks in atkinson and plaistow, as well as over the border in merrimac, haverhill and methuen, mass
generally, they say, he drives alongside youngsters walking alone in the late afternoon or early evening, rolls down the window and asks the children their names and where they are going, then offers a ride
the man has driven slowly by children in his town, shouting, ``i'm going to get you,'' atkinson police chief phillip consentino said
so far, police say, he has not been able to lure anyone into his big brown or maroon car, but he gotten out and chased a couple of kids, one of whom escaped to home as the man fell on ice
my concern is that there is going to be one gullible kid out there that is going to get in a car,'' said plaistow police sgt. thomas bourque. ``then who knows what is going to happen.''
he said a plaistow youngster was chased on foot by the man, who got back into his car and left when the youngster ran to a house and pounded on the door
police have distributed a composite drawing of the man, and it is posted in schools and on school buses. schools are scheduling programs to teach children how to deal with strangers and to instruct parents
bus drivers have met to talk about how to better protect their riders, and atkinson police have been following buses
in plaistow, police in unmarked cars, people from the schools or parents have been watching for the stalker
bourque said kids are ``showing some fear,'' but ``seem to know what to do _ they are running. they don't talk to the guy.''
the children are fleeing so quickly, that none has been able to get the license plate number of the man's car
state treasurer ann richards has been loudly urging texans to claim long-forgotten money left in state coffers, but joseph phillips is finding it hard to heed her call
how long does it take?'' phillips, 48, asked thursday, more than seven months after first filing to reclaim $900 from the state
the money belongs to phillips and his sister, patricia crawford, and was part of a trust left by their father, who died in 1985. the money was left erroneously to languish in a bank account and found its way into the treasury under a law stipulating that accounts inactive for at least three years be turned over to the state
the treasurer's office says there is no question that phillips should get the money. it is part of about $60 million owned by 75,000 residents and companies but held by the state
you can be assured that if you have money coming to you, you will get it,'' ms. richards said at a press conference earlier this month to publicize efforts to return the money
but phillips was not assured: ``i thought, if they are that slow in responding to me, how in the world are they going to handle more claims?''
phillips first filed his claim with the treasury last aug. 7 after a trust official told him about the money. in january, he filled out another form. later, he discovered his sister also would have to complete a form, which took him several weeks just to obtain
three weeks later, after reading about ms. richards' news conference, phillips wrote the dallas morning news
a spokesman for ms. richards conceded to the news that the claim had taken too long. he said the claim was complicated and that a series of miscues, including a change of address by the unclaimed property division, caused delays
we are expediting a check,'' he told the news. phillips will get his check within four weeks _ after it's cleared by the attorney general's office, he assured
angry dockworkers moved massive blockades across the entrance to their port near the panama canal on friday to fight off an army takeover by troops loyal to gen. manuel antonio noriega
noriega fired his intelligence chief and four other officers in an apparent purge of his fractured defense forces, which came two days after a failed coup attempt against the military strongman
four american military police officers were arrested in the capital by panamanian authorities and held for several hours, the pentagon said
the panamanian newspaper critica said the americans were carrying handguns, maps of the capital and ``military implements'' when they were detained in an area ``where daily activities disturbing the public order'' had occurred
panamanians, without cash for weeks, lined up at public parks and pay stations to receive partial payment and bags of food being doled out by the government
noriega gave no reason for friday's ousters
col. bernardo barrera had been in charge of intelligence for the 15,000-member defense forces, which includes panama's army, navy, police and air force
a source close to the defense forces said barrera might have been faulted for not knowing in advance of wednesday's coup attempt, which was said to have involved a few junior officers lead by the nation's police chief, col. leonidas macias
the other ousted officers were identified by the military press office as majs. juan oberto, pablo pinto and jose williams and capt. orlando iguez. their units and positions were not disclosed
at the balboa port, about a mile outside the panama canal, about 300 striking dockworkers moved car-sized containers across the port entrance to fight off an army takeover ordered thursday by the government
the port is shut down,'' said one dockworker. ``we won't accept anything less than what they owe us,'' he said, asking not to be identified for fear of reprisal. ``we'll wait here for them (the army).''
four shipping containers were stacked across the port entrance. they formed a barricade nearly 20 feet high and no vehicles or machinery were passing in or out
ports at panama city and colon, used primarily to receive and ship cargo, closed monday when dockworkers angry about not being paid went on strike. the panama canal commission said the shutdowns had no effect on its operations
in addition to the ports, the military was ordered to take over the nation's electrical, water and telephone companies, airports, and the ministries of education, health and finance, all of which had been struck by workers demanding salaries
the four american military police arrested thursday night in panama city were identified by the critica newspaper as danny h. feltro, william jerry, virts richard and tammy markley
the newspaper did not provide their ranks or other information, and the pentagon said friday it could not immediately confirm the identities printed by the paper
a u.s. southern command statement in panama city said the four were members of a military police detachment checking on the ``security of dependent families'' living in the area in which they were detained
the u.s. militry dependents, like everyone else in panama, have been without lights and water for extended periods because of the recent strikes
long lines of public employees, including teachers and electrical workers, gathered at special pay stations around the capital to receive partial payment of their semi-monthly salaries
each employee was receiving only $75, sometimes with $35 paid in old, commemorative panamanian coins kown as balboas
the government also began handing out free bags of food containing beans, rice, processed cheese and other staples of the panamanian diet. it had been selling the bags for between $14 and $15
more than 1,200 people lined up for the bags at a park near the center of the city to receive food
the government, short of cash for months because of its inability to renegotiate a huge foreign debt, began running out of money three weeks ago when depositors began a run on the country's banks
the bank run began on feb. 26, the day after noriega deposed the nation's president, eric arturo delvalle, in a thinly disguised coup. devalle had tried to fire noriega the day before in a move that backfired
the action by delvalle, who still is recognized by the united states, came after noriega was indicted by two grand juries in florida on charges of narcotics trafficking
illinois sen. paul simon said friday he is having trouble raising money but took a jab at better-financed democratic presidential rivals, saying ``if you're talking about buying the nomination, i can't do that.''
simon, in pennsylvania for a series of fund-raising events, said none of the five remaining candidates in the democratic field can win enough delegates to claim the nomination on the first ballot at the atlanta convention this summer
even massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, who has a narrow lead in delegates, would need to pick up 80 percent of the delegates in remaining states to have the 2,082 needed to win the nomination, simon told a news conference
that just isn't going to happen, so we're going to have a wide-open convention,'' he said. ``i think you're going to see a wide-open process and i think it's going to be a very healthy thing for the country.''
he acknowledged he is still having trouble raising money, but said he expects to remain competitive and bring in more money as he wins more delegates. simon won his first primary on tuesday in his homestate
if you're talking about buying the nomination, i can't do that. if you're talking about winning the nomination, i can do that,'' he said. ``i intend to be in the race through atlanta, through november the 8th.''
earlier in the day, simon met briefly with gov. robert p. casey, who has not yet endorsed a candidate for president and might not before the primary
i really have to make a basic decision on whether or not to get involved and that's the process i'm going through now,'' casey said
simon said he would not seriously contest the march 26 michigan caucuses but predicted he would do well in the april 5 wisconsin primary and the april 19 new york primary, which is one week before pennsylvania's vote
commenting on his chances here, simon said, ``i am candid in saying if there were a poll taken today in pennsylvania, i'm sure paul simon would not emerge on the top. but after the headlines and the television coverage for wisconsin and new york, you're going to have a very different situation in pennsylvania.''
a high-ranking east german transport official defected to west germany and led authorities friday to arrest a suspected communist spy, officials and news reports said
the mass-circulation newspaper bild said the woman was arrested following the interrogation of the defector and was suspected of having spied for east germany
west german officials identified her as a secretary in the federal ministry for economic cooperation
earlier friday, security sources said ulrich fuchs, one of the four deputy directors of east germany's state-run deutrans transport company, had defected to west germany
the sources, who requested anonymity, said west german intelligence officials hoped to learn more about how east germany uses its long-haul trucks to spy on the west
bild said the woman had access to secret documents provided to the ministry by west germany's intelligence service. the documents dealt mainly with the situation in third world countries, such as nicaragua and angola, the newspaper said
the national television network ard said the documents did not contain military information
alwin brueck, a former state secretary in the ministry in whose office the woman worked for some time, identified the suspect as elke falk, according to ard
bild said the woman returned several days ago from a vacation in austria, where she may have met with communist colleagues
hans-juergen foerster, spokesman for the federal prosecutor's office, confirmed the woman's arrest but declined to link the two cases
he said the woman, whom he refused to identify, was in investigative custody. she is suspected of having supplied information to a communist secret service since 1975, when she met an agent known to authorities under the false name of gerhard thieme, foerster said. he declined to identify the communist agency
bild said thieme was an east german agent who recruited the woman after seducing her. she is in her 40s and worked in the ministry's european section since 1987, following other positions in the ministry, the newspaper said
west germany's counterespionage agency had placed the woman under surveillance one year ago, bild said
several government secretaries have been unmasked as communist spies in recent years
margret hoeke, a long-time secretary in the west german president's office, was convicted of spying for the soviet kgb and sentenced to eight years in prison last august. during her trial, ms. hoeke described how she began spying after falling in love with an east bloc agent
sonja luenburg, chief secretary to economic minister martin bangemann, vanished in august 1985 and is believed to have fled to east germany
west german sources said fuchs was undergoing interrogation by counterespionage officials at an undisclosed location in west germany
they said fuchs had also unofficially worked for the east german secret service, ``but apparently was no big fish.''
the sources added that further questioning of fuchs could give more insights into his activities for the communist secret service
but bild quoted unidentified security experts as saying fuchs was one of the most important defectors in 10 years
the newspaper said friday fuchs defected in early march during a business trip to the west
bild said fuchs knew ``everything about the secret spying trucks of east germany and the soviet union, he knows secret meeting points for agents and courier methods used by communist spies.''
quoting an unidentified counterespionage expert, bild said the west germans hoped to learn about the electronic equpiment built into soviet bloc trucks, the routes they take while traveling through the west and about ``safe houses'' used by communist agents
west german security officials long have suspected east german truckers of using their drives through west germany to report on military movements and gather other information for the east german secret service
bild said about 3,000 deutrans trucks pass through west germany every month. the trucks are usually equipped with sensitive cameras and electronic listening devices, bild said. study says</head>
a white house comission on friday said the government should turn over to private businesses the operation of prisons, air traffic control facilities, mail delivery and scores of other services
agencies now providing those services ``have become muscle-bound to the point of paralysis,'' the panel's chairman, david f. linowes, told reporters after presenting president reagan with what he called the first ``independent, exhaustive analysis'' of the privatization issue
linowes, however, acknowledged that the bulk of the 78 recommendations in the 278-page report by the president's commission on privatization are unlikely to be enacted before reagan's term ends next janaury
we didn't take on this job with the expectation that it would stay with just one administration,'' he said. ``for the most part we opt for an incremental approach. we know americans don't take kindly to sudden change. they like them to evolve.''
the recommendations include repealing laws that created the u.s. postal service's monopoly, putting the federal aviation administration's flight service facilities and control towers out for private bids and selling the naval petroleum reserves in california and wyoming
the panel also called for the use of vouchers or direct subsidies to individuals for housing, education and elderly care rather than pouring any more money into public housing projects or federal aid for public schools
and the commission would sell to private banks and other financial institutions the government's $250 billion portfolio of housing, business, agriculture and education loans
government should not be in the business of business,'' linowes said. ``the well-developed banking industry can take over those loans ... freeing up billions of dollars for the federal treasury.''
many of the recommendations, such as selling the petroleum reserves and government loans, have been proposed in the past by reagan and rejected soundly in congress each time
and critics were quick friday to predict that initiatives based on the white house commission's report also would fail
luckily, it won't fool anybody except those who want to believe it,'' said robert m. tobias, president of the 59,000-member national treasury employees union. ``it should die with the rest of the administration's foolish ideas at the end of 1988.''
however, linowes, a democrat, said he believes lawmakers gradually will warm to the recommendations as the work of an independent, bipartisan commission
the facts will argue for themselves,'' he said. ``for example, vouchers will provide the same amount of low-income housing for one-third the cost of public housing.''
linowes said all of the commission's recommendations include two caveats:
first, government must never abdicate its responsibilities for setting policy and standards; and second, the rights of current employees cannot be abrograted as a result of these changes.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater, reflecting the scant attention that the administration gave to privatization in its proposed 1989 budget except for pilot studies involving military commissaries and federal prisons, called the report forward-looking
the work ... is close to the president's philosphy of government,'' fitzwater said. reagan ``campaigned ... on a platform of limited government. ... we are continuing those efforts.''
reagan appointed the 13-member commission last september, and linowes estimated the cost of its study at $450,000
he said the panel found that most agencies, often because workers lack incentives for coming up with new ideas, ``are trying to deal with today's problems using yesterday's solutions.''
for example, he said visits to air traffic control towers revealed the use of outdated computers
the checks and balances of government do not lend themselves to managing high technology,'' linowes said. ``government should reach out by opening its operations to the creative talents and drive of entrepreneurs.''
conservatives launched a campaign friday to persuade president reagan to pardon lt. col. oliver l. north, with one saying, ``juries don't convict heroes who stand 10 feet tall.''
indicting a true american hero _ at a tremendous cost _ is completely unacceptable and should be rejected immediately,'' l. francis bouchey, president of the council for inter-american security, said in a statement issued at a news conference
in a related development, pentagon sources said friday that north has asked to retire from the marine corps. north submitted his request thursday, asking that he be allowed to retire effective may 1, when he will have completed 20 years of active military service, the sources said
the conservatives said they have formed an ``ollie north task force'' to lobby for a pardon for north and john m. poindexter, former head of the national security council
sen. steven symms, r-idaho, sent a letter to reagan asking him to pardon north, symms office said
the two former white house aides _ along with arms dealers richard v. secord and albert hakim _ have been charged with conspiring to defraud the government in the iran-contra episode. the case involved diverting money from the sale of weapons to iran to the nicaraguan rebels
bill kling of the foreign policy project said he thought the public supported north. ``juries don't convict heroes who stand 10 feet tall,'' he said
north and poindexter are a ``package deal,'' on pardons, according to andrew messing, head of the national defense council foundation
but he and others refused to commit themselves to seeking pardons for secord and hakim
messing said secord and hakim were in a different category because they were businessmen who stood to gain personally from the iran-contra affair, he said
marlin fitzwater, reagan's spokesman, said there have been no discussions at the white house about possible pardons
leftist guerrillas on friday burned buses, taxis and other vehicles that defied their nationwide ban on transport, and they threatened more sabotage to disrupt weekend elections
the farabundo marti national liberation front, an alliance of five guerrilla groups, claimed its fighters attacked three soldiers guarding a gas station outside this capital
the armed forces press office said it could not confirm or deny the report, made on the guerrilla radio station. the radio said three soldiers were killed or wounded, but it didn't give details
the guerrilla radio venceremos said ``our demolition squads will carry out new actions in repudiation of the elections.'' it also said ``urban commando cells are carrying out actions to ensure the transport ban's success.''
salvadorans on sunday elect all 60 members of the legislative national assembly and mayors and municipal councils nationwide. the guerrillas, who have been fighting the u.s.-backed government since 1979, call the elections a farce. they say free and fair balloting is impossible in wartime
they decreed an indefinite nationwide transport ban beginning friday to protest and disrupt the elections
a poll published friday by san salvador's central american university indicated more than 80 percent of prospective voters intend to cast ballots despite the guerrilla call for a boycott. but the same poll indicated about half the electorate either rejects all the candidates or remains undecided
the poll of 914 people in 11 of the country's 14 provinces gave the rightist national republican alliance, or arena, an edge over the governing christian democrats in the assembly vote
the centrist christian democrats have 33 deputies but are expected to lose that majority. no leftist party is participating in the elections
the privately owned radio station ysu, with correspondents in almost all 14 provinces, said guerrillas burned eight vehicles in the eastern province of usulutan. the radio, citing police and armed forces officials, said the vehicles destroyed were two buses, two tractor-trailers, two pickups, one jeep and one taxi. no injuries were reported in the destruction of the vehicles
there were no other reports of violence from other provinces
intercity bus transport was reduced by about 80 percent nationwide, according to dispatchers. the capital's two main bus terminals were virtually deserted friday morning
one person died and 18 were injured when an overcrowded pickup overturned in the capital
scores of pickups with people packed in the beds and standing on the bumpers circulated in san salvador, partially taking the place of privately owned buses, none of which was seen on the road
the pickup owners were charging 60 cents _ six times the normal bus fare
the government put several dozen blue and white state-owned buses on the street, and they, too, were overcrowded, with people riding on the roof luggage rack, hanging from the doors and standing on the bumpers. army trucks also were used for passenger transport
many people simply walked to work
of 10 people randomly consulted on the city sidewalks, not one supported the transport ban
it hurts everybody,'' said computer programmer jose ortiz. he said he thought election turnout would be high ``because lots of people feel they made a mistake last time they voted and now they want a change.''
he cited what he said were the christian democrats' unkept promises
the (transport) ban is a problem for all of us. it makes a tough situation even tougher,'' said ricardo quintanilla, a laboratory worker consulted during his three-mile walk to work
about the elections, he said: ``they don't offer much hope for solutions to the country's problems. but voting is a habit, so lots of people will vote.''
the following dispatch was filed by frederick kempe of the wall street journal, a member of a pentagon press pool covering the arrival of u.s. troops in honduras
the commander-in-chief of the u.s. southern command said he was skeptical that u.s.-backed efforts to oust panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega would bring any quick results
putting a time line on gen. noriega is probably one of the greatest hazards of our profession,'' said gen. fred woerner, who was on an inspection mission to observe the arrival of about 800 paratroops from the u.s. army's 82nd airborne division
he said this week's failed coup attempt showed that the ``solidarity of the panamanian defense forces has been ruptured.''
woerner ruled out the possibility of using u.s. troops to help bring down noriega, something he said was a matter for the panamanian people
he wouldn't comment on whether the united states military would respond if panamanian president eric arturo delvalle requested its assistance in the future
delvalle has been in hiding since his aborted attempt to fire noriega as military leader last month. noriega responded by forcing the ouster of delvalle, but the united states still regards him as panama's constitutional leader. noriega has been indicted by two federal grand juries in florida on drug-trafficking charges
woerner provided a gloomy description of panama's internal situation in his brief remarks during the second day of maneuvers here
the city is locked up. the economy has come to a standstill. the people are afraid, intimidated. the normal political processes are non-functioning. people are desperately struggling for their basic freedoms,'' he said
bonnie miskanin has been the wife of an 82nd airborne division paratrooper for six years. two days ago, she found out exactly what that means
her husband, sgt. donald miskanin, ``left for work about 4:15 a.m. wednesday,'' she said. ``the day went on and everything was fine when i noticed around 6 o'clock that he wasn't home yet.''
mrs. miskanin, 27, said she called a friend whose husband was in the same unit as her husband at fort bragg
she told me they had been deployed to honduras,'' she said friday
the united states deployed 3,200 u.s. troops, 2,000 of them from the 82nd airborne, after reported incursions into honduras by nicaraguan soldiers pursuing contra rebels. the last of the troops left early friday for what is described as a non-combat show of force
mrs. miskanin said 6-year-old donald jr. has been taking his father's absence ``very rough.''
as for herself, she said she had been drawing on the support of friends, family and other army wives
we just stick together,'' she said. ``we act like our husbands are right here in the field.''
paula arndt, 21, said she also relied on other army wives since the departure of her husband, spec. 4 chester arndt, whom she hasn't seen since wednesday morning
the more the pressure keeps building, you have to let it out,'' she said. ``you take it day by day. i'll be taking care of my baby, doing my household chores, and doing a lot of praying.''
as the last of the troops from the fort prepared to leave thursday, soldiers said they were excited but also nervous
i'm only 18,'' said pfc, james bullard jr. of shallotte, a soldier since july. ``yeah, i get scared. you don't know what's going to happen. all i know is we're going on a readiness exercise. i'm nervous, real nervous
but i signed on the dotted line, so i have to deal with it,'' he said
dewitt bodeen, who wrote or was co-writer on scripts for the films ``cat people'' and ``billy budd,'' has died. he was 79
bodeen, who began his career as an actor and was a former board member of the writers guild of america, died march 12 of bronchial pneumonia at the motion picture and television hospital, said spokeswoman jean ferris
in addition to ``cat people,'' bodeen's scriptwriting during the 1940s included ``the seventh victim,'' ``the curse of the cat people,'' ``the yellow canary,'' ``i remember mama,'' ``mrs. mike,'' ``the girl in the kremlin'' and ``twelve to the moon.''
he also wrote ``the enchanted cottage'' with herman j. mankiewicz, and in 1962 collaborated with peter ustinov on ``billy budd.''
bodeen worked in new york and california, and in the late 1930s became a script reader at rko pictures, which led to a seven-year contract as a staff writer
in the 1950s he returned to new york and wrote for such television shows as ``climax,'' ``lux video theater'' and ``four star playhouse.''
in 1969 the academy of motion picture arts and sciences commissioned him to help edit the book ``who wrote the film.''
he also produced a volume of 12 vignettes of actresses, ``ladies of the footlights.'' his last book was ``the films of cecil b. demille.'' he retired in 1977
