democratic presidential candidate michael dukakis criticized the reagan administration's sending of troops to honduras as he split his campaign day friday between michigan and kansas
he spoke with junior high school students in michigan, then flew to kansas, where democrats hold party caucuses on saturday. he was returning friday night to michigan for appearances at union halls with sen. edward kennedy. michigan's democratic primary is one week from saturday
the whole policy in central america is illegal,'' dukakis said at a news conference after addressing a student assembly at mason junior high school in drayton plains, just outside pontiac
call back the troops and end this,'' he said
the massachusetts governor said the assignment of troops to central america runs against agreements signed by members of the organization of american states. he said if he were president, he would end aid to the contra rebels and back a central american peace plan drafted by costa rican president oscar arias and signed by five central american nations
as long as you have an administration that's obsessed with the overthrow of that government (in nicaragua), the peace process cannot begin,'' dukakis said
on tuesday, dukakis had failed to win any delegates in the illinois primary. but despite gains in illinois by favorite sons paul simon and jesse jackson, dukakis dismissed what some have suggested is a growing possibility of a brokered convention, one in which no candidate enters with a clear majority
i've always felt from the beginning that somebody would emerge ... from the primary process with a good plurality, particularly if the field begins to thin down a little bit,'' he said
on other matters, dukakis:
_urged a reduction in military spending through scaling back the president's star wars space-based missile defense program. ``if you're going to spend $6 billion on star wars, you can't spend $6 billion on housing,'' he said
