the panamanian government declared a national ``state of urgency'' friday that gives it the power to suspend individual freedoms
a decree said the action was taken because of ``a real situaion of undeclared war against the republic of panama'' by the united states and the domestic political opposition
the decree did not specify what measures would be taken and said only that ``the executive branch will adopt the measures adequate for the preservation of public order to repell the domestic and foreign attacks on the national economy and to face the state of urgency throughout the country.''
it said that for the past several weeks, ``panama has been the object of an attack on its economy by the united states of america in coordination with national political sectors desperate to take over the government by force.''
the situation, it said, affects the ``structure of national life.''
the decree was based on article 51 of the panamanian constitution which gives the government the power to suspend ``temporarily, partially or totally individual rights and liberties'' in cases of war or internal disturbances affecting peace and public order. unpaid ...</note>
the panamanian government declared a national ``state of urgency'' today that gives it the power to suspend individual freedoms
a decree said the action was taken because of ``a real situaion of undeclared war against the republic of panama'' by the united states and the domestic political opposition. the decree did not specify what measures would be taken
the nation's military strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega, also dismissed a colonel in charge of military intelligence and four other officers in an apparent purge following a coup attempt
meanwhile, unpaid dockworkers at the balboa port at the mouth of the panama canal in panama city defied an army takeover of the facility, blocking its entrance with large shipping containers
four american military police officers were arrested thursday while they were on duty and released after about eight hours, the pentagon said today
the government-owned newspaper critica said the soldiers were arrested near the university of panama and were carrying handguns, maps of the city and ``other military implements.''
the paper identified them as danny h. feltro, william jerry, virts richard and tammy markley, but did not provide hometowns. the pentagon said it could not immediately confirm the identities
among those forcibly retired by the panama defense forces was col. bernardo barrera, who had been in charge of intelligence for the 15,000-member military organization, which combines panama's army, navy, police and air force. noriega derives his power from the defense forces, which he heads
the others were identified by the military press office as maj. juan oberto, maj. pablo pinto and maj. jose williams and capt. orlando iguez. their units and positions were not disclosed
no reason was given for their dismissal, but the action came only two days after troops loyal to noriega foiled an attempted coup by what was said to be between eight and nine junior officers led by the nation's police chief, col. leonidas macias
macias and four other officers were arrested during an attempted takeover of the defense forces headquarters in panama city early wednesday. they are being held, but no charges have been announced
at the balboa port, about 300 dockworkers said they were awaiting the arrival of soldiers, who were ordered to take over the facility thursday by the nation's civilian head of state, manuel solis palma
by decree, he also ordered the military to take over the nation's state-owned electric, water and telephone companies, airports, and the ministries of education, health and finance, all of which had been struck by workers demanding their salaries
the port is shut down,'' said one dockworker at the union hall at the entrance of the facility, about a mile from the miraflores locks of the panama canal, the first set of three locks for ships entering the canal from the pacific
meanwhile, opposition leaders expressed dismay that widespread protests have been unable to remove noriega, and many now openly say only a u.s. military intervention can do so
it is something we, as panamanians, do not want to see, but the legal conditions for military intervention exist,'' said a leader of an opposition party. like others interviewed, he spoke on condition he not be identified
the civic crusade, a broad anti-government coalition, had planned demonstrations thursday but the sight of hundreds of soldiers carrying automatic rifles and tear gas canisters through the streets of the capital apparently discouraged them
the trans-panama pipeline carrying alaska oil across the isthmus en route to gulf coast markets resumed operations today, a spokesman for the pipeline said. it had stopped because of electrical outages wednesday and thursday
service was restored at 6 a.m. (est) this morning,'' he said. ``we actually never stopped loading and unloading at both ends. we stopped the actual pumping from one end to the other because for that we depend on public energy. but we have our own plant at each end for loading and unloading.''
workers were on strike because the cash-starved government, under economic pressure by the united states, was unable to pay them
some shops opened in downtown panama city thursday but banks, which shut their doors march 4, remained closed
talk of possible u.s. intervention stems from politicians' frustration in a country used to strong military governments that give opposition parties little room to maneuver
i guess right now a large majority of panamanians would welcome a u.s. military intervention,'' said the leader of another large opposition party. ``but three months later everybody would be saying, `yankee, go home
we are just desperate for a change in the situation,'' he added
on feb. 25, a day after noriega was indicted by federal grand juries in florida on drug trafficking and money laundering charges, president eric arturo delvalle tried to fire the general
the next day, noriega had the national legislative assembly, which he controls, vote delvalle out of office. the united states continues to recognize delvalle, who is in hiding, as panama's legitimate president
