the air force adopted a policy friday that decisions by military wives to work outside the home are none of the service's business
if the spouse of a serviceman chooses to work instead of volunteering to help with local air force base activites and charities, that decision ``is a private matter'' and cannot be used in judging the serviceman's qualifications for promotion, the new policy states
the policy change was recommended by a special task force that was created last september, shortly before an internal investigation concluded two wives of senior officers at grissom afb, ind., had been pressured to quit their outside jobs with warnings the careers of their husbands would suffer if they didn't
that investigation also found that while pressure had been brought to bear on the wives, the commanding officers were not guilty of any misconduct because the air force didn't have a written policy on the matter at the time
in its new policy statement friday, the air force said: ``no commander, supervisor or other air force official will directly or indirectly impede or otherwise interfere with this decision (by the spouse)
neither the decision of the spouse in this matter, nor the marital status of the military member, will be a factor used to affect the evaluation, promotion or assignment of the military member.''
the policy statement was signed by air force secretary edward c. aldridge and gen. larry d. welch, the service's chief of staff, who had created the seven-member task force of air force military and civilian officials
that panel, in a 21-page report released friday, described promulgation of the new policy as essential but also warned of widespread skepticism that it would have any effect
the common belief (within the air force) was that the `two-for-one' policy is currently operative, and that spouse participation would continue to be a major factor in promotion and selection for command.''
the ``two-for-one'' policy is shorthand for the expectation that the wife of a serviceman will forgo career aspirations of her own in order to support her husband's career
the task force said the days of unmarried servicemen were long gone _ ``64 percent of the air force's members have family responsibilities'' _ and that ``societal changes'' were having a substantial impact
subtle changes in the nation's family structure have created a dichotomy for the air force spouse _ accommodate the needs and aspirations of the individual family, while meeting the needs of the broader family, the air force community.''
senior commanders schooled in the old ways might not like it, the panel continued, but military spouses increasingly resent the ``institutionalized'' pressure on them to support military careers through volunteer work
and, the panel continued, they particularly resent a dual standard that has now become starkly clear _ ``it is all right for the husband of a military woman to work in the civilian community, but if the wife of a military man works, she is often perceived as shirking her responsibilities to the air force family.''
this conflict between the old and the new results in significant consequences. it reduces participation, erodes morale, impacts retention and limits creative leadership.''
besides recommending a new, enforceable policy statement, the panel urged welch and aldridge to establish a ``professional volunteer management program'' to recruit and recognize military spouses who wish to perform volunteer work, while using air force family support centers to help those spouses who preferred to seek jobs. discussed</head>
a bipartisan group of senators proposed a $48 million package of new aid to nicaragua's contra rebels friday, including renewed authority for the cia to deliver previously stockpiled weapons
as u.s. troops continued to arrive in honduras in a show of force, assistant secretary of state elliott abrams said additional assistance was being discussed with honduran president jose azcona, in response to a reported nicaraguan incursion
white house chief of staff howard baker said president reagan would give ``most careful'' consideration to any request from honduras for troops to help repel nicaraguan forces, although he reiterated that u.s. troops were not expected to be involved in any military operation in the region
one of the senate's leading peace advocates, sen. mark o. hatfield, said the sending of u.s. troops amounted merely to ``matching stupidity with stupidity'' and introduced legislation barring the troops from a combat role without permission from congress
sponsors of the new contra aid proposal said they hoped it would revive negotiations in congress and with the reagan administration on an aid package that could be quickly enacted to replace supplies lost or expended during the past week's heavy fighting along the nicaraguan-honduran border
but the extent of the damage inflicted on the rebels by the sandinista incursion remained unclear. sen. david boren, d-okla., chairman of the senate intelligence committee, said the nicaraguan troops were withdrawing without accomplishing all their objectives
we think it's very important right now to send a signal to the sandinista government'' which allegedly crossed the border into honduras in an effort to destroy rebel camps and supplies, boren said
sen. nancy kassebaum, r-kan., said announcement of the package also would strengthen the contras as they enter direct cease-fire talks with the managua regime, scheduled for monday. ``this is a common-sense, moderate and reasoned approach,'' she said
the proposal would use $48 million in unspent pentagon money to buy food, clothing, shelter and medical supplies, and to transport it to troops in the field, over the next year. about $3 million of that amount would go for communications gear
but in what promised to be a controversial provision, the package would allow the cia to airdrop ammunition and weapons previously stockpiled by the rebels to troops in the field. boren said the rebels still have $2 million to $5 million worth of undelivered supplies, about half of them lethal
and it would give president reagan the right to hold a quick, guaranteed vote in congress on any request for further military aid under certain conditions if the peace talks between the sandinistas and contras break down
as a ``carrot,'' the bill also would promise long-term economic aid for the region once political stability is restored
sen. daniel evans, r-wash., who has opposed contra aid in the past, said he was supporting the latest proposal because it ``is the best way to ensure that (the peace talks) have some chance of success.''
action on further aid for the rebels has been stalled since march 3, when the house narrowly rejected a $30 million package of purely humanitarian aid. aid proponents saw the sandinista incursion into honduras as a new opportunity to revive interest in aid
meanwhile, abrams told reporters that american officials have been discussing with honduran president azcona the possibility of providing additional assistance to that country, in addition to the 3,200 troops already airlifted to palmerola air base near tegucigalpa
there are some other possibilities that we've discussed,'' abrams said, adding that the possibilities did not include additional troops. ``we do not have a formal request from president azcona as of this morning for any other form of assistance. obviously, if we get one we'll take it very seriously.''
baker said that if a request were received from honduras for troops to help repel nicaraguan forces, ``it would be most carefully considered and most deliberately considered. but i cannot tell you what decision the president would make under those circumstances.''
baker, interviewed on the syndicated television program, ``john mclaughlin's one on one,'' was asked at what point u.s. troops would enter action
i don't anticipate that will occur at all. i think that the honduran forces can handle that on their own, and i fully anticipate that either the nicaraguans will retire on their own or honduras will, as they say, encourage them to do that. but i do not expect american troops to be involved in any military operation there,'' he said
hatfield's proposal would permit u.s. military exercises in honduras, like the training mission which began thursday, only if congress has been notified a month in advance. troops could not be sent into combat without a declaration of war or a ``clear and present danger'' of attack on the united states or its citizens. it also would prohibit any increase in the permanent u.s. military presence there
he said the administration's action amounted to ``sinking to the level of those in nicaragua who have no interest in peace.''
under the terms of this legislation we will not allow and will not tolerate sending american military personnel into combat in central america,'' hatfield said. ``it is not an option... we will not permit our young people to be used as pawns in this political game. and we will not push them down the slippery slope of intervention as we pushed their fathers and brothers down that slope into vietnam.''
general motors president robert stempel on friday introduced a new car steering wheel designed to move with the driver on impact and reduce injury in car crashes
stempel told a conference of 1,000 road safety activists that the steering wheel remains ``a primary source of injury in the event of a crash,'' despite the collapsible steering column developed 20 years ago
the new steering wheel has an energy-absorbing hub, the point where the wheel meets the steering column. at this juncture in the new wheel, six metal joints are designed to fold on impact and enable the wheel to move parallel to the driver's chest. this allows the wheel to rest against the body and move with it
that helps spread the force of the impact and reduces chest injuries,'' stempel said
tests showed the new steering wheel also lessened injuries to the abdomen and the face when those were the points of impact, he said
the new wheel will make its debut next year in the chevrolet cavalier and will be phased in on other models not equipped with air bags
stempel used the occasion to encourage the wearing of seatbelts, especially in massachusetts where a seatbelt law was repealed. thirty-two states require motorists to wear seatbelts
he also urged motorists to pay better attention to pedestrians and motorcyclists, who comprise one quarter of the annual road death toll
the three-day national conference, called lifesavers, is the sixth annual meeting of safety experts, state and city officials, car makers and dealers, and representatives from the insurance industry and law enforcement. ``according to;'' adds 4 grafs at end with stastus of request, right to pension after conviction</note>
lt. col. oliver north, the fired national security aide facing trial in the iran-contra affair, announced friday he has asked to retire from the marine corps and said he may subpoena ``the highest-ranking officials in our government'' as part of his defense
north submitted his request on thursday, asking that he be allowed to retire effective may 1 when he will have completed 20 years of active military service, pentagon sources said
that is the minimum amount of service required to retire with a pension. with 20 years of service, north is entitled to a pension totaling 50 percent of his base monthly pay, or slightly over $22,000 a year
in a statement read in the office of his attorney, brendan sullivan, north said the lawyer ``has informed me that the defense against these charges may require him to issue subpoenas for the testimony and records of the highest ranking officials in our government.''
that strikes me as a course of action incompatible with my continued service as a marine officer,'' he continued. ``accordingly, with great sadness, i have tendered my request to retire from the marine corps.''
north, who wopre a civilian busines suit in place of his usual ribbon-bedecked marine uniform, refused an answer questions after reading the statement
according to one official, who agreed to discuss the matter only if not identified, north has available a substantial amount of accumulated leave and probably will stop working as a staff officer at marine corps headquarters pending his retirement
north was reassigned to headquarters in november 1986 after president reagan fired him as an aide to the national security council
the sources said there was nothing to block approval of north's retirement request
they noted that rear adm. john poindexter, north's former boss and reagan's former national security adviser, exercised his right to retire from the navy late last year
north, poindexter and two others were indicted by a federal grand jury wednesday on charges they conspired to divert iranian arms sales profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels
the 23-count indictment, which also named retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord and his business partner, albert hakim, said the defendants organized, directed and concealed ``a program to continue funding of and logistical and other support for military and paramilitary operations in nicaragua by the contras'' at a time u.s. law barred such action
north vowed after the indictment was returned to fight the charges, declaring: ``i did not commit any crime.''
north, a much-decorated combat veteran of vietnam and graduate of the u.s. naval academy, testified last year before congress that he always believed he had the approval of his superiors to take the actions he did
poindexter, during his testimony before congress, said he never informed the president of his decision to divert arms sale profits
the 44-year-old north is currently drawing a base pay of $3,693.60 per month. under military retirement rules, he will be entitled to half that _ or slightly more than $22,000 a year
according to one source, north was technically required to provide the marine corps with four months' advance notice before retiring. the service is unlikely to balk, however, at granting him a waiver of that advance-notice requirement, the source added
one pentagon official said gen. alfred m. gray, the marine corps commandant, had already approved north's request and that it was now awaiting only the approval of the navy secretary's office
and that should come on monday,'' said the source. ``this is all very routine.''
according to the defense department, the pension rights of north and poindexter are unlikely to be affected by the outcome of the legal cases against them since both men served honorably for at least 20 years
generally speaking, a conviction does not affect eligibility for a military pension,'' said col. david shea, a pentagon spokesman
morton thiokol officials said thursday that if five employees killed in fire while loading an mx missile motor with fuel had followed company policy, they would be alive today
they said the crew ignored strict company rules and entered the building during a phase of the operation that should have been handled by remote control from a bunker a quarter of a mile away
we don't know why the people were in the building. by procedure, they should not have been there. we have not been able to come up with a reason ... we just don't know,'' said robert lindstrom, a former nasa executive who directed thiokol's internal investigation of the dec. 29 fire
however, in response to a question, lindstrom said it was possible that the crew had complied with procedures
lindstrom said the company's probe resulted in the same conclusion reached by an air force investigation, namely that the explosive fire which burned 100,000 pounds of solid propellant and destroyed the building was ignited by either a spark of static electricity or heat from friction
the air force conclusions were expected to be released shortly
on wednesday, the utah division of occupational safety and health cited the defense contractor for six safety violations and imposed a $31,700 fine. the victims' presence in the building and failure to use remote-control equipment were among the most serious violations alleged by the agency, which characterized three of them as willful and serious
phillip r. dykstra, vice president of strategic operations for morton thiokol, said the state's contention that management knew that crews occasionally were present during restricted operations was not supported by facts
it's not true,'' dykstra said. ``our investigation shows no one was aware that occasionally (procedures) had been violated..''
lindstrom said that during interviews with numerous employees, one or two said crews had gone into buildings in violation of safety rules. he said investigators did not pursue that issue because their charge was only to find the cause of the fire
dykstra contested uosh's classification of the three violations as willful, although the facts supporting the citations were true. he said the company ``will avail itself of every legal avenue to challenge these citations,'' a procedure which involves appeal to the independent utah uosh review commission
the workers were withdrawing the core from a casting of the first stage of an mx missile when the solid fuel ignited. the blaze caused $6.2 million in damage to the building at the company's wasatch operations plant 25 miles west of brigham city
morton thiokol makes the missile's four stages, and the space shuttle's solid-fuel rocket boosters, one of which failed when the challenger blew up in january 1986
the fire has held up production of the mx missile until the cause and corrective measures could be determined. ed garrison, president of the company's aerospace group, said morton thiokol hopes to reach an agreement on corrective measures with the air force within two weeks
he said those measures include removing the teflon-coated steel core at a slower rate to reduce friction, verification that the motor is properly grounded to prevent buildup of static electricity, and installation of instruments to monitor static electricity
the cores, or forms, are removed after the propellant has been poured into the casing and allowed to harden
the state agency alleged that the missile motor was not properly grounded during the operation, though lindstrom said the previous shift had grounded the missile correctly. because of extensive fire damage, it was impossible to know whether the grounding had remained intact, he said
however, he said static electricity can build up even when there is proper grounding
it takes up to four hours to remove the 60-inch core from the casing. after the initial phase, in which the core is lifted about 30 inches, crews are authorized to enter the building to remove a hydraulic lift and attach the core to a crane that completes the procedure
responding to a question, lindstrom said it was possible the workers had completed the first phase of their task and were in the building to change the equipment. if so, they were following company policy
government radio condemned border air raids by honduras, which it said struck inside nicaragua, and exhorted listeners friday against ``american imperialism and the threat of military intervention.''
a headline in barricada, the sandinista newspaper, said: ``the order of the day: intensify combat.''
honduras said the raids thursday were confined to its own territory, aimed at nicaraguan soldiers it said crossed the frontier the day before in pursuit of contra rebels
the sandinista government continued with plans for cease-fire talks with the contras next monday, but the u.s.-supported rebels were considering a boycott
cease-fires in the region's civil wars, and a ban on the use of one country's territory for attacks on another, are provisions of the peace plan signed aug. 7 by five central american presidents
nicaragua said it had called off its offensive to roust contras from camps along the honduran border wednesday but was maintaining combat positions
although the defense ministry said none of the soldiers entered honduras, a nicaraguan military source indicated privately that they had
honduran officials and the reagan administration say sandinista soldiers crossed the rugged, ill-defined border about 175 miles from managua
on thursday, the united states started flying 3,200 soldiers of the 82nd airborne division and 7th light infantry to honduras in a show of support. defense secretary said they would be on a training exercise there for 10 days but would stay out of combat
president daniel ortega said nicaraguan troops would take on the americans if necessary
he hedged the question of whether nicaraguan soldiers crossed the coco river in the isolated northern region, as he has when previous incursions were reported
here the question is not if army troops penetrated honduran territory or not, but that we have dozens of camps of mercenary forces in honduran territory ... tolerated by the honduran government,'' he said thursday
honduran warplanes bombed the bocay border region, where nicaragua's northern military headquarters is located. the honduran government said a soviet-supplied nicaraguan helicopter was destroyed but the defense ministry denied the claim
journalists taken to the area earlier thursday saw and felt a bomb explode at the confluence of the bocay and coco rivers. lt. col. javier carrion, commander of the offensive against the contras, said two bombs fell in nicaraguan territory and one on the honduran side
carrion told reporters in a jungle clearing at san andres de bocay that 4,500 soldiers were involved in the sweep through an area running from central nicaragua to the frontier. he said they had air support from soviet-supplied helicopter gunships and an-26 propeller-driven planes carrying bombs
he said sandinista troops had killed 92 contras and wounded 300, at the cost of 34 soldiers dead and 68 wounded
the colonel said the purpose was to destroy contra bases in the border area, which is about 40 miles from an important mining region the rebels attacked in december
honduras said about 2,000 nicaraguan soldiers crossed the border, and a high-ranking military officer said about half of them still were there friday. minorities</head>
twenty years after the kerner commission accused the news media of looking at the world ``with white men's eyes,'' newspapers and broadcast stations still are not hiring or promoting enough blacks, a group of black journalists said friday
despite some industry attempts to improve black employment prospects, ``what has resulted in far too many instances can simply be characterized as a lot of motion and little movement,'' the group's report said
the national association of black journalists formed a panel to compare the status of blacks in journalism today with 20 years ago, when race riots prompted president johnson to appoint illinois gov. otto kerner to head the national advisory commission on civil disorders
the kerner commission conclusion that ``the journalistic profession has been shockingly backward in seeking out, hiring, training and promoting'' blacks ``still rings true,'' said dewayne wickham of the gannett news service, president of the nabj
the panel, which wickham said carried out its study over several months, acknowledged ``substantial good will'' among news media executives
but, wickham said: ``we also found there had not been a lot of progress. ... it would be wrong to stand here and say there has been no progress. it would be equally wrong to say it is significant.''
the panel's recommendations:
_newspaper publishers should promise to double the number of black journalists from 3.5 percent of newsroom employees to 7 percent by 1991
_newspaper and broadcast industry foundations should deny grants to college journalism programs ``which do not employ a single full-time black member, or which does not undertake a serious effort to recruit and retain black students.''
_the national association of broadcasters and the radio-television news directors association should join the nabj to form a task force to halt the decline in blacks working in television news. a declining number of black men employed in broadcast news caused the ratio of minority group members in the field to drop from 15 percent in 1979 to 13 percent in 1986, the panel said
believing there is a possible relationship between the deregulation of the broadcast industry and this sharp drop ... the nabj will monitor the compliance of television stations with existing (federal communications commission) regulations,'' the report said
where we are unsuccessful in bringing compliance through negotiations, the nabj will move aggressively to challenge the licenses of broadcast stations,'' it said
ernie schultz, president of the rtnda, said his group supported the report's recommendations ``100 percent.''
wickham said copies of the report also would be sent to the nab, the american society of newspaper editors and the american newspaper publishers association for comment
dwight ellis, nab vice president for minority services, said, ``blacks are losing ground in broadcasting. it's been documented.''
he said that although the reason for the decline was unclear, the nab and the news editors were considering two remedies: an advertising campaign to tell blacks about some of the less obvious jobs available in broadcasting, and creation of an institute to train minority group members for management
lee stinnett, executive director of the asne, said surveys show that the number of minority group members employed in newspaper newsrooms has more than doubled since 1978, rising from 1,700 to 3,600, or from 4 percent of the total to 6.5 percent, he said. slightly more than half the minority newspaper journalists are black, he said
federal regulators on friday pledged to protect all depositors and general creditors of the thrift unit of the troubled california-based financial corp. of america, the nation's second largest thrift holding company
the announcement by the federal home loan bank board came after the company's disclosure, in a report filed with the securities and exchange commission, that its thrift unit _ american savings &amp; loan association of stockton, calif. _ was insolvent under generally accepted accounting principles
the bank board's promise, designed to provide the ailing s&amp;l with stability and stem a drain of deposits, goes beyond its usual mandate of protecting deposit accounts up to $100,000
in the statement, the bank board also reaffirmed its support for the management of fca and american
fca, based in irvine, calif., said american's net worth _ the difference between assets and liabilities _ had fallen to negative $106 million at the end of the year, compared with positive $244.4 million on sept. 30
under less stringent regulatory accounting guidelines, its net worth was plus $69 million at the end of 1987, compared with $357.8 million at the end of the third quarter
fca had previously revealed that its net worth had fallen into the red, but this is the first disclosure that net worth at american, fca's main subsidiary, has fallen below the zero mark. that happened when american concluded that repayment of debts due from its parent company was not assured
fca's annual report, filed with the sec, also disclosed that american had a drain on deposits of $493 million during the first two months of this year. it attributed the drain to publicity about the bank's problems and said the drain eased during the first 10 days of march. deposits had totaled $17.1 billion at the end of the year
the drain was milder than the severe run at american in august and september of 1984, when the bank _ amid heavy operating losses _ lost about $6.8 billion of its $25 billion in deposits
the bank board's sister agency for commercial banks, the federal deposit insurance corp., issued a similar promise on thursday protecting all depositors and general creditors of first republicbank corp. of dallas, a bank holding company of about the same size as fca
however, the fdic went a step further than the bank board by pumping $1 billion into first republicbank
fca on feb. 23 asked the bank board for a $1.5 billion in assistance as soon as possible. karl hoyle, a bank board spokesman, said the request is under review
fca, with $33.7 billion in assets, ranks second among thrift companies only to h.f. ahmanson &amp; co., the los angeles-based parent of home savings of america
the bank board has tried unsuccessfully for nearly a year to find another institution willing to take over all or part of fca on terms that wouldn't be too costly to the federal savings and loan insurance corp., the bank board unit that insures deposits
on-again, off-again talks with the thrift unit of ford motor co. broke down early in january
because of its size, fca is the bank board's largest single problem institution, although the problems collectively of texas s&amp;ls are more severe
on jan. 27, fca reported a loss of $224.6 million in the last three months of last year, bringing its 1987 loss to $468 million
two weeks later, the bank board ordered it to sell off $2.5 billion in mortgage-backed securities to reduce its vulnerablity to interest rate fluctuations
on march 9, the bank board, which regulates about 3,150 s&amp;ls nationally, passed a resolution reassuring nervous wall street firms, which had loaned more than $12 billion to american in the form of reverse repurchase agreements. state of emergency in panama; picks up penultimate graf pvs bgng, `panama was'</note>
four american military police officers were arrested by panamanian authorities on thursday and held in custody for about 8{ hours, during which time they were ``verbally abused and made to stand for long periods of time,'' the pentagon said friday
the defense department said the four mps were on ``official duty'' at the time of their arrest in strife-torn panama city and were arrested without cause and held incognito
they were released late thursday night, but panamanian authorities continued friday to hold their cars, sidearms and flak jackets, the pentagon added
three members of the u.s. army south's military police command and one member of the oklahoma national guard were arrested at approximately 2:30 p.m. thursday while on official business in the vicinity of the hilton park hotel in panama city,'' the defense department said in a statement
the four were detained at panama defense forces facilities for several hours before being released into the custody of u.s. military authorities at approximately 11 p.m. the soldiers were in civilian clothes and were checking on the security of u.s. military families in government-leased quarters in the area who are affected by the lack of electrical, water and telephone service in parts of panama city.''
the government of gen. manuel antonio noriega, meanwhile, declared a national ``state of urgency'' friday that allows it to suspend individual freedoms. a decree said the action was taken because of ``a real situaion of undeclared war against the republic of panama'' by the united states and the domestic political opposition
capt. nancy laluntas, a pentagon spokeswoman, said the one national guardsman was a member of the 745th mp company who was on annual training in panama with the u.s. army south
the spokeswoman added the four were authorized to carry weapons beneath their civilian clothes and were carrying credentials that should have been honored. under the terms of the panama canal treaty, u.s. military authorities also should have been notified of the mps' arrest, she said
u.s. military authorities were not notified of the arrest by panama defense forces,'' laluntas said. ``and during their 8{ hours of being detained, the arrested soldiers asked repeatedly for permission to notify u.s. military authorities of their situation, and their requests were denied
the soldiers were also verbally abused (and) made to stand for long periods of time...,'' she said
the pentagon identified the four as pvt. 1st class tammy markley; pvt. 1st class richard virts; specialist 4 jerry williams, and staff sgt. danny felton, the national guardsman. the ages and hometowns of the four were not available
the pentagon statement was issued following a report in a panamanian newspaper friday. the newspaper critica said the four americans were arrested ``in an area where daily activities disturbing the public order'' had taken place
it said the four were carrying handguns, maps of the city and ``other military implements.''
panama was hit by power outages this week as electric company workers joined continuing protests against the government of military ruler gen. manuel antonio noriega
on wednesday the u.s. southern command placed the 10,000 american troops and their dependents stationed in panama on the highest alert status when panama's police chief, col. leonidas macias, led an unsuccessful coup attempt against noriega
a 19-member u.s. delegation selected by president reagan is heading to el salvador this weekend to monitor legislative and municipal elections that leftist guerrillas have threatened to disrupt with violence, officials said friday
the president strongly supports the people of el salvador and their democratic aspirations and is demonstrating this support by sending this delegation,'' white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said
a delegation member, rep. john g. rowland, r-conn., said, ``our presence there is mainly one to deter any fraud (by the participating political parties) and to objectively and fairly report what we see happening.''
andy fisher, an aide to sen. richard g. lugar, r-ind., said the delegation will visit polling places in san salvador and the countryside despite the pinpointing of the polls as military targets by the leftist forces
the delegation, headed by lugar and rep. john p. murtha, d-pa., was scheduled to leave andrews air force base saturday morning and return late sunday night or early monday morning
the u.s.-backed salvadoran government of president jose napoleon duarte is holding elections sunday for mayors and councils in the country's 262 municipalities and for all 60 seats in the legislative assembly
leftist groups have vowed to obstruct road transportation during the elections to disrupt voting, and said polling places will be ``military objectives.'' the rebels maintain that peace must be achieved before any election is held
the main electoral opposition to the ruling christian democratic party is arena, a rightist group
this particular election is a test for democracy, not only because of the hazards proposed by the rebels, but perhaps because many citizens of el salvador, after five elections, have lost some of their enthusiasm for democracy,'' lugar said in a statement
the delegation will be briefed by state department officials in san salvador before monitoring the elections
additional members of congress in the delegation are sen. christopher bond, r-mo.; rep. mickey edwards, r-okla.; rep. john kasich, r-ohio; rep. beverly byron, d-md.; and rep. alan mollohan, d-w. va
other members of the delegation are howard penniman, an elections expert with the american enterprise institute; mario paredes, executive director of the northwest regional center for hispanics in new york; merom brachman, retired chairman of the ohio ethics commission;
eugenia kemble, executive director of the free trade union institute; susan kaufman-purcell, council on foreign relations, new york; john white, former democratic national chairman; devier pierson of pierson semmes and finley, a washington law firm;
james dyer, deputy assistant to the president; edwin g. corr, u.s. ambassador to el salvador; fritz korth, international foundation for electoral systems, an advisory member; and betsy warren, principal deputy assistant secretary of state for legislation
here is a transcript of the announcement friday by lt. col. oliver north, who is facing trial in the iran-contra case, on his request to retire from the marine corps
there have been many inquiries this afternoon regarding a story, apparently out of the pentagon, about my status in the marine corps
and i would like to clarify the situation at this time
i love the united states marine corps, and the courageous brothers in arms that i have served with over the past 20 years
since graduating from the united states naval academy, my goal has simply been to serve our country as a marine for as long as possible
unfortunately, the indictment delivered two days ago places me in a situation where my continued service would be inconsistent with preparing and presenting a vigorous defense against these unfounded charges
my attorney, brendan sullivan, has informed me that the defense against these charges may require him to issue subpoenas for the testimony and records of the highest-ranking officials of our government
that strikes me as a course of action incompatible with my continued service as a marine officer
accordingly, with great sadness, i have tendered my request to retire from the marine corps
for over 16 months, i have silently endured a torrent of media speculation, as the largest investigation in the history of our country has probed every aspect of my personal and professional life, and that of my family
i have not responded, except when required by law during the course of the congressional hearings last summer
further silence is a disservice to me, my family, and the brave people i have served and worked with on matters of great importance to our country
moreover, while on active duty, i am not fully free to speak out or to take other actions which may be necessary
the months ahead will be difficult, and i recognize that fighting a prosecutor with an unlimited budget, an enormous staff, is a formidable and costly task for me and my counsel
my family and i continue to take heart from the overwhelming expressions of love and concern and encouragement by countless freedom-loving people
we are extremely grateful
your prayers and support have helped us to endure this ordeal in washington
i thank you
god bless you
semper fidelis
thank you
museum curators, history buffs and urban cowboys bought up the biggest collection of william f. ``buffalo bill'' cody memorabilia ever auctioned friday, including a silver-trimmed rifle that brought $22,500
the collection, sold at butterfield &amp; butterfield, consisted of more than 300 items originally preserved by cody's sister, julia cody goodman
a pair of chaps worn by the pony express rider, indian fighter, buffalo hunter, army scout and showman sold for $1,400, and a rope lariat went for $500
a silver-handled plains rifle fetched $22,500. other items included cody's buffalo-hide coat and his silver-handled toothbrush
who better symbolizes the american west than buffalo bill?'' asked r.l. wilson, historical consultant to colt firearms co. of hartford, conn. he came to bid on a single-action colt revolver, one of eight guns in the collection
the collection was sold by greg martin, a san francisco gun collector and history buff who bought the artifacts for $300,000 last year in billings, mont. he had wanted to buy only a shotgun inscribed to cody, but had to buy the whole lot to get the shotgun from the elderly owner
rival bidders eyeing each other across the auction floor included curator paul fees of the buffalo bill museum in cody, wyo., and thomas b. morrison of the buffalo bill ranch historic park in north platte, neb
they vied for a collection of letters to cody's sister discussing his marriage, the death of his son and other intimate events
we are interested in the correspondence because it is so revealing and personal,'' said fees. ``we have a strong biographical interest.''
the collection was unique for its large number of personal items, including a tomahawk from his friend d.f. ``white beaver'' powell and dozens of photographs, show bills and theater tickets chronicling cody's life as the roughrider who along with shooting champion w. ``doc'' carver founded the first wild west show
carl otis, owner of pawnee bill's wild west exposition re-enacted, a northern california traveling show, dressed in white stetson hat and buckskin jacket for the occasion. he bid $3,000 on a smith &amp; wesson ivory-handled revolver used in cody's wild west show but the gun went for $9,000
private collector george kramer, a new jersey real estate developer, hoped to buy cody's silver riding bit for his 80-year-old father, who still rides. but he bid first on cody's winchester rifle, inscribed and hand-carved with buffalo
that's the one item i wanted most,'' said kramer, who successfully bid $11,000 for it. discussed</head> with administration response to aid package. picks up 13th graf pvs bgng: sen. daniel ...</note>
a bipartisan group of senators proposed a $48 million package of new aid to nicaragua's contra rebels friday, including renewed authority for the cia to deliver previously stockpiled weapons
as u.s. troops continued to arrive in honduras in a show of force, assistant secretary of state elliott abrams said additional assistance was being discussed with honduran president jose azcona, in response to a reported nicaraguan incursion
white house chief of staff howard baker said president reagan would give ``most careful'' consideration to any request from honduras for troops to help repel nicaraguan forces, although he reiterated that u.s. troops were not expected to be involved in any military operation in the region
one of the senate's leading peace advocates, sen. mark o. hatfield, said the sending of u.s. troops amounted merely to ``matching stupidity with stupidity'' and introduced legislation barring the troops from a combat role without permission from congress
sponsors of the new contra aid proposal said they hoped it would revive negotiations in congress and with the reagan administration on an aid package that could be quickly enacted to replace supplies lost or expended during the past week's heavy fighting along the nicaraguan-honduran border
but the extent of the damage inflicted on the rebels by the sandinista incursion remained unclear. sen. david boren, d-okla., chairman of the senate intelligence committee, said the nicaraguan troops were withdrawing without accomplishing all their objectives
we think it's very important right now to send a signal to the sandinista government'' which allegedly crossed the border into honduras in an effort to destroy rebel camps and supplies, boren said
sen. nancy kassebaum, r-kan., said announcement of the package also would strengthen the contras as they enter direct cease-fire talks with the managua regime, scheduled for monday. ``this is a common-sense, moderate and reasoned approach,'' she said
the proposal would use $48 million in unspent pentagon money to buy food, clothing, shelter and medical supplies, and to transport it to troops in the field, over the next year. about $3 million of that amount would go for communications gear
but in what promised to be a controversial provision, the package would allow the cia to airdrop ammunition and weapons previously stockpiled by the rebels to troops in the field. boren said the rebels still have $2 million to $5 million worth of undelivered supplies, about half of them lethal
and it would give president reagan the right to hold a quick, guaranteed vote in congress on any request for further military aid under certain conditions if the peace talks between the sandinistas and contras break down
as a ``carrot,'' the bill also would promise long-term economic aid for the region once political stability is restored
an administration official, speaking on condition he not be identified, said of the new aid package, ``we are encouraged from reports we have heard about it, but we will have to wait until we have the actual details.''
sen. daniel evans, r-wash., who has opposed contra aid in the past, said he was supporting the latest proposal because it ``is the best way to ensure that (the peace talks) have some chance of success.''
action on further aid for the rebels has been stalled since march 3, when the house narrowly rejected a $30 million package of purely humanitarian aid. aid proponents saw the sandinista incursion into honduras as a new opportunity to revive interest in aid
meanwhile, abrams told reporters that american officials have been discussing with honduran president azcona the possibility of providing additional assistance to that country, in addition to the 3,200 troops already airlifted to palmerola air base near tegucigalpa
there are some other possibilities that we've discussed,'' abrams said, adding that the possibilities did not include additional troops. ``we do not have a formal request from president azcona as of this morning for any other form of assistance. obviously, if we get one we'll take it very seriously.''
baker said that if a request were received from honduras for troops to help repel nicaraguan forces, ``it would be most carefully considered and most deliberately considered. but i cannot tell you what decision the president would make under those circumstances.''
baker, interviewed on the syndicated television program, ``john mclaughlin's one on one,'' was asked at what point u.s. troops would enter action
i don't anticipate that will occur at all. i think that the honduran forces can handle that on their own, and i fully anticipate that either the nicaraguans will retire on their own or honduras will, as they say, encourage them to do that. but i do not expect american troops to be involved in any military operation there,'' he said
hatfield's proposal would permit u.s. military exercises in honduras, like the training mission which began thursday, only if congress has been notified a month in advance. troops could not be sent into combat without a declaration of war or a ``clear and present danger'' of attack on the united states or its citizens. it also would prohibit any increase in the permanent u.s. military presence there
he said the administration's action amounted to ``sinking to the level of those in nicaragua who have no interest in peace.''
under the terms of this legislation we will not allow and will not tolerate sending american military personnel into combat in central america,'' hatfield said. ``it is not an option... we will not permit our young people to be used as pawns in this political game. and we will not push them down the slippery slope of intervention as we pushed their fathers and brothers down that slope into vietnam.''
partners in a new york banking firm that does business with the state of massachusetts have given money and helped raise more for the presidential bid of gov. michael dukakis, according to a published report friday
a dukakis campaign spokesman denied there was anything improper
michael del giudice, general partner in lazard freres and co., organized eight fund-raisers last june that raised $250,000 for the dukakis campaign, said the boston herald
and jonathan o'herron, a partner in the same firm, was co-host of a fund-raising dinner, also in june, that raised $25,000, the herald said
federal election commission records show del giudice gave the maximum contribution of $1,000 to dukakis, and o'herron and his wife each gave $500, the newspaper said
lazard freres was awarded a three-year contract jan. 7 to advise the state on fiscal management of construction of a third boston harbor tunnel and the depression of the central artery
i think it's ridiculous to suggest that there is any appearance of a conflict of interest,'' said campaign spokesman steve akey. ``there is absolutely no connection between contributions and contracts.''
akey said other members of the banking firm support different candidates. and he said it would be impractical for the campaign to refuse contributions from the thousands of individuals and companies that do business with the state or operate under state regulation
the subject of campaign finance has become a debating point between dukakis and a democratic rival, rep. richard gephardt of missouri
dukakis has faulted gephardt for taking money from political action committees, while noting that his own campaign rejects pac money and contributions from registered massachusetts lobbyists
gephardt has defended his nearly $300,000 in pac donations and persistently raised questions about dukakis' acceptance of contributions from anyone doing business with the state of massachusetts
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir insisted friday that his country remains committed to seeking peace in the middle east despite his rebuff of a u.s. proposal for an international peace conference
israel cannot accept the proposal offered by secretary of state george shultz because such a gathering would give arab countries and the soviet union a chance to impose their will on israel, shamir said
however, israel remains open to direct talks with the arabs, the prime minister said
this approach is enshrined in the camp david accords, to which we remain committed,'' shamir said, referring to the settlement his country made with egypt in 1978 under u.s. auspices. ``they still provide a workable blueprint for resolving issues between us and our arab neighbors, including the palestinian arabs.''
the camp david agreement called for a period of limited self-rule for palestinians in the occupied territories
about 250 palestinians and their supporters demonstrated outside the century plaza hotel as shamir addressed 750 at a luncheon of the world affairs council
the chanting demonstrators carried signs protesting israeli troops' violent suppression of palestinian unrest in the west bank and gaza strip
about 20 members of the militant jewish defense league staged a counter-demonstration outside the hotel, but there were no confrontations, said police sgt. larry mckinley
in the occupied territories friday, israeli troops shot a protester to death and at least 25 others were injured in violence that erupted after moslem noon prayers. the death was the 101st since the unrest began 3{ months ago
shamir's likud bloc, which shares power with the more liberal labor party, rejects shultz' proposal for a conference including the permanent members of the u.n. security council. such a meeting would lead to demands that israel give up territory it has held since 1967 and considers vital to its defense, shamir said
the soviets have been pushing the idea because they know that within this framework they can push a settlement favorable to themselves and their syrian clients,'' he said
shamir, who arrived in los angeles on thursday after talks in washington with shultz, president reagan and congressional leaders, has sought to blunt criticism by some american jews of his country's action in the occupied territories
he reiterated that the picture of the palestinian riots in the occupied west bank and gaza strip has been distorted by the news media, and said americans shouldn't confuse the violence with u.s.-style civil rights activism
it is war. it is an extension of urban terrorism,'' he said, defending his troops' use of rubber bullets, beatings and live ammunition
in answer to a question from the audience, shamir said he believed american jews continue to support israel despite the controversy
i don't see any changes,'' shamir said. ``i think the great majority of the jewish community in america supports the state of israel.'' markets</head>
president reagan on friday named treasury secretary james a. baker iii to head a working group to coordinate recommendations for altering the government's regulation of financial markets
the group was appointed under a presidential order after nicholas f. brady, head of reagan's task force on the oct. 19 stock market crash, told congress on thursday that a repeat of that event could occur unless the government's regulatory authorities are put under one roof
brady's commission earlier had called for making the federal reserve board a ``super regulator'' with authority over both the securities and exchange commission and the commodities futures trading commission in regulating financial markets
but that idea has been rejected by the heads of all three agencies
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan has said he doesn't want the added authority. and a turf fight has erupted between sec chairman david ruder and the cftc's new chairwoman, wendy gramm, over which agency should regulate stock index futures
the sec has blamed trading in stock index futures for worsening the october crash, which saw the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks fall more than 500 points in one day
ruder has suggested that regulation of trading in index futures be transferred from the cftc to his agency, an idea opposed by both gramm and brady
commodity exchanges where the futures are traded and the cftc have maintained that activity on the index futures markets oct. 19 had no affect on the severity of the collapse in stock prices
named with baker to the working group were greenspan, ruder and gramm plus the five other governors now on the federal reserve's board and four other members each from the sec and cftc
reagan gave the group 60 days to report back to him on any progress in ironing out their differences and coming up with recommended legislation
the goals are two-fold,'' said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater. ``first, to ensure the continued integrity, competitiveness and efficiency of our nation's financial markets and, second, to maintain the public's confidence in those markets.''
specifically, the panel was told to look at the desirability of a ``tie-breaking referee'' with emergency powers and more formal inter-maket coordination and cooperation mechanisms among the three agencies
it also was told to examine the adequacy of private sector capital for futures floor traders, market makers and broker-dealers and whether margin requirements need to be strengthened and ``harmonized.''
other issues the panel was told to explore include the desirability of simultaneous trading halts in all markets to clear transactions, imposition of price limits on stocks, index futures and options, emergency measures to restrict large, rapid liquidations and revising equity short-sale rules
none of them is simple,'' fitzwater said of the issues, `and, while deserving high priority, may not be resolved quickly or without considerable reflection.''
snow fell across a wide area of the east on friday and much of the nation's northern half had unseasonably low temperatures just two days before spring
light snow extended from kentucky across west virginia and ohio into pennsylvania and new york
snow advisories were posted in parts of northern kentucky, mountainous areas of pennsylvania, and the northern mountains of north carolina
rain showers extended from there to the gulf coast, scattered in most areas but numerous in alabama, georgia and florida
temperatures were in the 30s and 40s east of the rockies, except for the southeast, where it was warmer, and northern and central minnesota across to upper michigan, where early afternoon readings were in the 20s
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 21 degrees at marquette, mich., to 82 degrees at thermal, calif. the morning low for the nation was 8 degrees below zero at gunnison, colo
the forecast for saturday called for showers and thunderstorms in florida; snow from new england to the great lakes region; rain and snow from indiana to new jersey; rain from maryland and west virginia to eastern south carolina, and scattered showers across washington state and western oregon
temperatures will remain below 40 degrees from eastern montana through the great lakes region and northern ohio valley to new england, including highs in the 20s and upper teens from eastern north dakota through the upper half of michigan. highs above 60 degrees were forecast from the coast of oregon and northern california through the southern plains to northern florida; in the 70s across southern florida; in the 70s to low 80s from southern and central california to southwestern new mexico, and the 40s and 50s across most of the rest of the nation. with north comments on breaking silence, bodyguard's warning to reporters. picks up 7th graf pvs bgng: according to ...</note>
lt. col. oliver north, the fired national security aide facing trial in the iran-contra affair, announced friday he has asked to retire from the marine corps and said he may subpoena ``the highest-ranking officials in our government'' as part of his defense
north submitted his request on thursday, asking that he be allowed to retire effective may 1 when he will have completed 20 years of active military service, pentagon sources said
that is the minimum amount of service required to retire with a pension. with 20 years of service, north is entitled to a pension totaling 50 percent of his base monthly pay, or slightly over $22,000 a year
in a statement read in the office of his attorney, brendan sullivan, north said the lawyer ``has informed me that the defense against these charges may require him to issue subpoenas for the testimony and records of the highest ranking officials in our government.''
that strikes me as a course of action incompatible with my continued service as a marine officer,'' he continued. ``accordingly, with great sadness, i have tendered my request to retire from the marine corps.''
north, who wore a civilian business suit in place of his usual ribbon-bedecked marine uniform, refused to answer questions after reading the statement
north said he has ``silently endured a torrent of media speculation'' during 16 months of iran-contra investigations. he said he had not responded ``except when required by law,'' and that ``further silence is a disservice.''
while on active duty, i am not fully free to speak out or to take other actions which may be necessary,'' north said
a man, apparently a private security guard, controlled the access of reporters and photographers to the room where north read his statement. before north entered, the guard told the press to ``keep your hands out of your pockets'' and to make no ``quick moves.''
according to one official, who agreed to discuss the matter only if not identified, north has available a substantial amount of accumulated leave and probably will stop working as a staff officer at marine corps headquarters pending his retirement
north was reassigned to headquarters in november 1986 after president reagan fired him as an aide to the national security council
the sources said there was nothing to block approval of north's retirement request
they noted that rear adm. john poindexter, north's former boss and reagan's former national security adviser, exercised his right to retire from the navy late last year
north, poindexter and two others were indicted by a federal grand jury wednesday on charges they conspired to divert iranian arms sales profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels
the 23-count indictment, which also named retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord and his business partner, albert hakim, said the defendants organized, directed and concealed ``a program to continue funding of and logistical and other support for military and paramilitary operations in nicaragua by the contras'' at a time u.s. law barred such action
north vowed after the indictment was returned to fight the charges, declaring: ``i did not commit any crime.''
north, a much-decorated combat veteran of vietnam and graduate of the u.s. naval academy, testified last year before congress that he always believed he had the approval of his superiors to take the actions he did
poindexter, during his testimony before congress, said he never informed the president of his decision to divert arms sale profits
the 44-year-old north is currently drawing a base pay of $3,693.60 per month. under military retirement rules, he will be entitled to half that _ or slightly more than $22,000 a year
according to one source, north was technically required to provide the marine corps with four months' advance notice before retiring. the service is unlikely to balk, however, at granting him a waiver of that advance-notice requirement, the source added
one pentagon official said gen. alfred m. gray, the marine corps commandant, had already approved north's request and that it was now awaiting only the approval of the navy secretary's office
and that should come on monday,'' said the source. ``this is all very routine.''
according to the defense department, the pension rights of north and poindexter are unlikely to be affected by the outcome of the legal cases against them since both men served honorably for at least 20 years
generally speaking, a conviction does not affect eligibility for a military pension,'' said col. david shea, a pentagon spokesman
some republican activists said friday they will fight to keep this year's gop presidential campaign platform true to conservative principles
they insisted their fight is not an effort to stop vice president george bush, the front-runner in the gop presidential race
the group seeking to ``save the reagan platform'' is spearheaded by the american conservative union and donald devine, who recently was ousted from a top post in sen. bob dole's lagging presidential campaign
this is not a stop-bush campaign,'' devine told a news conference
but he repeatedly criticized a speech the vice president gave in chicago last week in which bush promised a bush administration would press for a tough new code of ethics for government officials
our purpose is to promote an agenda the republican party can win on,'' said devine, who was president reagan's director of the office of personnel management from 1981 to 1985
to win in november, bush must galvanize the support of republican activists who are overwhelmingly conservative, not shift his policies toward the center, devine and other conservative leaders said
daniel graham, a retired air force lieutenant general who heads high frontier, a group pressing for development of the strategic defense initiative, said the republican party must take a strong stand against cuts in the pentagon budget
l. brent bozell iii, chairman of the conservative victory committee, said the republican platform ``must reaffirm that the party is committed to the elimination of the ruthless marxist regime in nicaragua.''
devine said efforts will be made to raise money for a delegate-tracking system ``to identify the conservatives'' and represent their views at the convention in new orleans in august
bush, in a speech to the governor's club in chicago, had said he was ``personally disturbed at the breaches of ethics i have seen in the past few years in government.'' he said he would appoint an ethics panel in the white house to draft a new code of ethics
devine said bush shouldn't have started ``talking about something unnecessarily critical of ronald reagan.''
i would think that a stronger ethics in government act is one that provided less discretion to independent prosecutors or permanent prosecutors to make up charges,'' said devine. ``we have an ethics in government act that says the appearance of a conflict of interest is a felony. now that's preposterous.''
bozell also criticized the reagan administration's intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty with the soviet union and claimed it has weakened support for anti-communist rebels in afghanistan and angola
we're affirming the 1980 republican platform, which is unfortunately a far cry sometimes from the 1988 adminstration,'' said bozell
asked where conservatives could turn if they don't prevail on the gop platform, devine said: ``stay home.''
some conservatives believe they would be better off if they relinquished the white house this year to a liberal democrat such as massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and reclaimed it in 1992, he said
rescue workers on friday removed remains of the 138 people who died when an avianca jetliner slammed into an andean peak, burst into flames and started a landslide
a bogota newspaper, quoting an avianca executive, reported friday that the boeing 727-100 hit the mountain after it swerved to avoid a collision with with another avianca plane
but another company official said the cause of the crash had not been determined
no americans were reported on the domestic flight
witnesses said the plane clipped trees before slamming into the mountainside thursday near zulia, 50 miles north of cucuta, where it had taken off
a police inspector in nearby campo alicia, augusto bautista, said the impact ``opened a hole that looked like a crater in a volcano.''
col. miguel benedetti, civil defense director for the state of north santander, said thursday night that there were no survivors. the government and avianca said there were 131 passengers and seven crew members aboard. both had given different figures earlier
the government said it had begun an investigation but recovery personnel had not yet located the plane's ``black box,'' which could provide clues to the cause of the crash
this tragedy has saddened many colombian homes,'' president virgilio barco said in a thursday night speech on television
the plane took off from cucuta, 250 miles northeast of bogota, and was to stop at the caribbean ports of barranquilla and cartegena
rain, snow and rough terrain hampered rescue efforts thursday. civil aeronautics agency officials said that work crews, some using helicopters, returned to the crash site friday
bautista said the remains of the victims were scattered and many passengers had been buried by a landslide touched off by the jet
it's not possible to recognize anyone,'' he said
police, civil defense workers, red cross members and local residents placed bodies in plastic bags and loaded them on helicopters headed for cucuta
the bogota daily ``el siglo'' on friday quoted raul garcia, an avianca vice president, as saying that the pilot had swerved ``to avoid a collision'' with another avianca jet flying from bogota to cucuta
garcia was quoted as saying the two pilots communicated by radio before the accident and that the second plane landed safely shortly after the crash
he did not return phone calls to his office friday
airport officials at cucuta would not comment
but jairo mejia, avianca's director of operations, told the newspaper ``we can't give too much credibility to speculation'' and said the cause of the crash had not been determined
local residents said the plane appeared to be flying low before it slammed into 8,000-foot la cuchilla peak
however, the operator of the control tower at cucuta's airport, ivan robayo, said the plane was flying normally and had not reported any trouble
the pilot said he was climbing to 26,000 feet and soon after that i lost radio contact with him,'' robayo said
the agency said the passenger list included monsignor horacio olave velandia, 44, the roman catholic auxiliary bishop of tibu, and at least 31 soccer players from two teams flying to a tournament in cartagena
the soccer teams were affiliated with the state petroleum company ecopetrol
colombia's last major air crash occurred july 27, 1985, when an air force transport plane went down in the amazon jungle, killing 74 people. the military plane was carrying civilian passengers because of an airline strike
an 84-year-old jeweler, threatened at knifepoint by two men, led them to a cache of diamonds then pulled a gun and shot one of them
the wounded man was quickly arrested. the other man was arrested the next day because the jeweler knew him and showed police where he lived, said the jeweler, lou marks
police said they doubt marks would be charged in the shooting, in which one robber was wounded in the chest and neck
marks' daughter, mrs. marion macri, 59, who lives with him, said the incident began wednesday night with a knock on the door. her father opened the door
two men forced their way in, threw marks to the floor and told mrs. macri to get down as well. they took $68 in cash from marks and about $20 from mrs. macri's purse. then marks, who sells jewelry from his home, tricked them
i've got a lot of jewelry you can have. take it and go,'' marks said he told them. ``when i said: `follow me, i'll show you my diamonds,' i knew i was halfway home.''
marks on thursday said he led them into his den. while they looked at the jewels, he grabbed a .32-caliber gun he had owned for 20 years and never fired, he said
i said, `lord, please let the gun be loaded' and it was,'' he said. ``when i put my finger on that gun, i said, `dear lord you have saved my life,' and i shot him point-blank. i let him have it, right in the chest.''
marks shot at the other man but missed. both men fled
i don't feel a bit of remorse,'' he said. ``they weren't going to let me live.''
raymond edward sumther, 39, was under police guard friday at bayfront medical center. he was charged with armed burglary assault, police spokesman george pickney said
gary glover, 30, was arrested thursday on the same charge and was being held on $15,000 bail, pinckney said
marks had led police to glover, whom he said he had once fed. the jeweler went to a motel where glover often stayed, and when marks saw him he called police
you befriend a man and then he comes back six months later and does this,'' marks said. change number of ships reported attacked to five; picks up 2nd graf pvs, ``iran said ...; corrects name of tanker to kyrenicos in 10th graf, ``iranian gunboats ...; inserts one graf after 15th pvs bgng: according to iraqi... with details.</note>
iran and iraq reported firing 41 missiles into each other's cities friday and said their warplanes and gunships attacked five ships in one of the fiercest spasms of fighting in the gulf war in the past year
communiques from both sides said seven jet fighters were shot down and iran claimed thousands of iraqis slain in a northern offensive
iran said its forces had captured two towns in a 5-day-old drive into northeastern iraq, in which it claims 9,200 iraqis have been killed or wounded and 4,000 taken prisoner. it said its forces had recaptured nowsud, an iranian border town
nowsud was overrun by iraqi soldiers soon after the war began in september 1980
dispatches from the official islamic republic news agency claimed five iraqi jets were destroyed in 24 hours, including three french-built f-1 mirage fighter-bombers out to raid iranian tankers in the northern persian gulf. iraq claimed two iranian jets downed
iraq acknowledged losing one plane, but iran did not admit losses
the official iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, said its planes carried out 254 sorties against iranian targets friday including a ``devastating raid'' on the northern city of tabriz
the news agency said air force planes evaded iranian fighter patrols and hit two ``large maritime targets,'' which usually means tankers, off iran between 9 p.m. thursday and 9 a.m. friday
lloyd's shipping intelligence unit in london confirmed one attack, on the iranian-chartered cypriot tanker kyrenicos. it said at least one missile hit the 80,137-ton vessel as it steamed south from iran's kharg island terminal with a full load before dawn friday
chartered and iranian-owned tankers shuttle oil for export from kharg, which has been a frequent target of iraqi bombing raids, to makeshift terminals in the safer waters of the southern gulf
iranian gunboats attacked three neutral ships in the southern gulf friday in apparent retaliation for the kyrenicos raid and two other confirmed iraqi attacks in recent days. there had been a monthlong lull in the ``tanker war,'' in which more than 400 ships have been hit since it began four years ago
shipping officials said a japanese seaman was killed on the panamanian tanker maria 2 in the first iranian raid soon after midnight and the other 20 crewmen, all south koreans, abandoned ship when a fire started. several were reported wounded, but all were rescued by the united arab emirates coast guard
an attack on the 284,494-ton norwegian tanker berge lord started a small fire and the 87,768-ton singapore-flag tanker neptune saburu also was hit. no casualties were reported in either case
irna, the iranian agency, said 24 missiles were fired late thursday and early friday into zubair, an industrial town in southern iraq, and haretha and shubair nearby
six short-range rockets were fired at the southern port of basra, khanaqin in the central border area, mosul in kurdistan and the northern frontier town of banmil, it said
according to iraqi dispatches, seven long-range missiles were launched at tehran. iran reported at least eight civilians killed and many wounded
baghdad radio announced two more iranian missiles struck the northern cities of mosul and kirkuk friday night. but tehran television announced two missiles were fired at each city in the attacks
iraq gave no report on its casualties from missile attacks
hundreds of civilians have been killed on both sides in the latest round of the intermittent ``war of the cities,'' which began feb. 29, and thousands have died since the conflict began
reports of artillery attacks and air raids on a dozen other cities, with heavy casualties, came from both sides
tehran said revolutionary guards pushing into the northern mountains friday overran the ``military towns'' of tawla, three miles north of nowsud, and byara a few miles farther north, killing or wounding 700 iraqis and capturing 200
war communiques claimed iranian forces had seized nearly 400 square miles of territory with a two-pronged offensive
according to irna, the drive was being led by soviet-made t-72 tanks captured from the iraqis when the iranians stormed the faw peninsula in southern iraq two years ago
it claimed iraqi warplanes dropped chemical bombs on dojaila and halabja, two northeastern towns captured thursday, ``killing many defenseless residents.''
a correspondent for the agency reported the two towns were ``in ruins,'' strewn with the bodies of civilians. he said the iraqis also dropped cluster and phosporous bombs that killed ``scores of people.''
the democratic party on friday added another delegate to the number attending this summer's national convention in atlanta, bringing the total to 4,163
mayor joseph riley of charleston, s.c., will attend as a representative of the national conference of democratic mayors
that seat had been held by detroit mayor coleman a. young, who also has claim to a delegate's seat because he is a member of the democratic national committee from michigan
under party rules, young could assign another mayor to take his seat to represent the mayors' conference, according to jim carey, executive director of the party's compliance assistance commission. washburn...</note>
richard gephardt promised friday to defend ``american jobs rather than foreign protectionism,'' and michael dukakis attacked president reagan's policy in central america as the two democratic presidential hopefuls pointed toward next week's michign showdown
vice president george bush, enjoying the status of near-nominee on the republican side, said reagan ``did the right thing'' when he dispatched combat troops to honduras. rival bob dole's campaign was reduced to skeletal remains with only about a dozen paid aides remaining
meanwhile, the man who directed president reagan's investigation into the iran-contra affair said he doubted the episode would damage vice president george bush's bid for the white house. ``i fully expect the opposition to use it on him,'' said former sen. john tower of texas, but he added the voters ``will tend to focus on the problems of the moment'' and not the past
the republican campaign was quiet, appropriately so for a race that has been all but wrapped up by bush
democrats were running full tilt, with caucuses, primaries and conventions in kansas, texas, puerto rico and south dakota this weekend offering 169 delegates, and the big 138-delegate michigan caucus showdown a week away
i'm the underdog today, but that doesn't really matter,'' gephardt said as he and 18 house democratic colleagues moved through michigan. ``i think you will see that the gephardt message about economic revival is going to get through to the michigan voters.''
dukakis, ahead in a new public poll as well as his own, countered with massachusetts sen. edward m. kennedy, who agreed to appear at labor rallies in two michigan cities. looking ahead to other staes, dukakis also picked up an endorsement from rep. sam gejdenson of connecticut. sources said he would receive one from rep. jim florio of new jersey on saturday
the governor divided his time between michigan and kansas during the day, and he hit hard against reagan's decision to airlift 3,200 combat troops to honduras. ``the whole policy in central america is illegal,'' he said. ``call back the troops and end this.''
he also criticized the idea of possible presidential pardons for oliver north and others indicted in the iran-contra affair on wednesday. but he said, ``i don't want to consider the political effects'' of the indictments
bush disagreed strongly with him on central america
we did the proper thing,'' he said in an interview with a puerto rico television station conducted by telephone. ``we are for freedom and democracy. there is no question that nicaragua invaded honduras.''
gephardt was focusing almost exclusively on michigan, which poses a make-or-break test for his faltering candidacy. he and dukakis already have begun airing television commercials in the state, even though the caucuses are a week away
campaigning in regions of the state where factories have closed in recent years, he said, ``it's time we had a president who defended american jobs rather than foreign protectionism. i reject the notion that in order to move some of us ahead, we must leave millions behind.''
jesse jackson won the endorsement of george sallade, who headed former candidate gary hart's michigan campaign in 1984 and again this year. sallade said he thought most of hart's supporters would follow suit. ``i expect the racists, if they exist, to be outnumbered next saturday,'' he said
sen. albert gore jr., of tennessee campaigned in puerto rico looking for support in sunday's primary. he said he would consider a request from the popular democratic party to exempt the commonwealth from federal minimum wage laws and said he favors letting puerto ricans decide whether to become a state
dole's campaign has been severely curtailed since tuesday's illinois primary defeat at the hands of bush. spokeswoman dale tate said only about 10 to 12 aides were left on the payroll, although several other officials were volunteering their services. the campaign once employed about 300 persons, she said
dole has vowed to stay in the race until the wisconsin primary on april 5, but ms. tate said the kansas senator was unlikely to air television commercials in connecticut, which votes on march 29
the other active challenger to bush, former television evangelist pat robertson, campaigned in california, where he proclaimed, ``there has to be a rallying point for conservatives.''
with bush holding an overwhelming lead in nominating delegates over his two rivals, most interest focused on the still murky democratic race
dukakis and jackson both spent time in kansas, which holds caucuses on saturday with 39 delegates at stake
at washburn university in topeka, jackson accused reagan of ``fighting psychological warfare with the congress, manipulating the public mind for more contra aid.''
gephardt also looked to translate his victory in last month's south dakota primary into delegates at a statewide convention on saturday. and dukakis and jackson, the two top finishers in the texas primary on march 8, looked to carve up most of the 64 delegates at the state's caucuses on saturday
the other campaign contest of the weekend is puerto rico's primary, with 51 delegates at stake
gephardt's campaign chartered two jets to ferry house members to michigan to campaign on his behalf. the missouri congressman ``is obviously a known quantity,'' said rep. john dingell, d-mich. ``we also know how he responds in a crisis. we in congress don't like weaklings or phonies.''
the other democrat in the race, sen. paul simon of illinois, is essentially conceding michigan to his rivals. he campaigned in pennsylvania during the day, where he criticized reagan's decision to send combat troops to honduras. ``i think, candidly, it was designed not to meet a military threat to honduras, but to try to line up some votes in the house and the senate for military aid to the contras. and i don't think it's going to work,'' he said
here are some comments friday by candidates for the presidency:

richard gephardt, on the michigan situation: ``i'm the underdog today, but that doesn't really matter. i think you will see that the gephardt message about economic revival is going to get through to the michigan voters.''

paul simon, taking a jab at his better-financed democratic rivals: ``if you're talking about buying the nomination, i can't do that. if you're talking about winning the nomination, i can do that.''

michael dukakis, on the reagan administration's actions in central america: ``the whole policy in central america is illegal. call back the troops and end this.''

pat robertson, saying he will stay in the gop race as a rallying point for conservatives: ``if everybody drops out, then whatever policies are being advocated by george bush will become the policies of the republican party.''

al gore, setting his sights on the presidency in 1988, not beyond: ``anybody who thinks i'm involved in a dress rehearsal will find out otherwise. i'm in this to win.'' paratroopers among last to arrive, not the last; picks up 4th pvs `the honduran and deletes outdated 20th graf `michael o'brien'</note>
the army began moving about 2,000 soldiers into the border jungles friday with orders to drive out a nicaraguan force of half that size
roughly 2,000 nicaraguan soldiers had been reported in the mountainous area thursday, the day after honduras said they crossed the frontier pursuing contra rebels. a ranking honduran officer said 1,000 of them remained on the honduran side friday
about 800 american paratroopers _ among the last to arrive of the 3,200 soldiers sent to honduras _ were dropped onto palmerola air base friday morning. the defense department says the u.s. forces will be in central america for a 10-day training exercise
gen. fred f. woerner, commander of the u.s. southern command based in panama, arrived to review the exercise and said it was ``a reassuring factor to our allies, not only in honduras but elsewhere.''
he said there were ``some very, very preliminary'' indications that sandinista troops were beginning to withdraw, but the duration of the u.s. exercise was ``not necessarily'' linked to that
the honduran officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said two honduran infantry battalions totaling 1,600 to 2,000 soldiers were moving in from a base at juticalpa, about 90 miles west. he said warplanes were on call from the tamara air base 15 miles north of tegucigalpa
orders were given for the soldiers to expel the ``invading troops'' with whatever means necessary, he said, adding that about half the original force had fled to nicaragua. honduran soldiers began sweeping the border region for mines thursday but none had been found, he reported
honduras gave the sandinistas 24 hours to get their soldiers out of the country, but the time of the deadline was not stated
the sandinistas have denied entering honduras but a nicaraguan military source indicated privately that they had
nicaragua's northern military headquarters is near the frontier in bocay and honduran warplanes flew raids in the area thursday, hours after u.s. troops began arriving in honduras
u.s. defense secretary frank carlucci said the american troops from the 82nd airborne and 7th light infantry were sent on a 10-day training exercise to provide ``moral support'' and would be kept away from combat
pentagon officials said privately the four u.s. battalions would spend eight or nine days training with hondurans in different parts of the country
one battalion of the 82nd airborne will be at juticalpa, an official said, ``but anyone who knows the country'' would realize the 90 miles ``might as well be 4,000. there's nothing but mountains and jungle in between.''
the basic order that these troops aren't to get near the fighting still stands,'' he said
president daniel ortega of nicaragua said thursday his soldiers were ready to ``combat and liquidate'' the 82nd airborne if necessary
alejandro bendana, secretary-general of the nicaraguan foreign ministry, said ``one step ... could lead to another'' in the border conflict, indicating war might result
the u.s.-supported contras have secret bases in honduras from which to attack across the border in their 6-year-old battle with the sandinistas
manuel suarez, spokesman for the honduran armed forces, told local reporters president jose azcona hoyo would continue telephone conversations with ortega and other central american leaders, trying ``to avoid a break in the peace process that has been developing in the region.''
among provisions of the peace plan signed by the five central american countries aug. 7 are cease-fires in civil wars and a ban on the use of one country's territory for attacks on another
azcona, 60, has been reported ill with flu for several days and canceled several meetings. the daily newspaper la prensa said he was dealing with the situation from his home
la prensa printed an editorial cartoon in which uncle sam said ``there's an invasion in honduras'' while azcona, a member of the armed forces and a diplomat look around saying, ``where, where, where?''
members of the legislature demanded a meeting with foreign minister carlos lopez to be told why they were not asked to approve azcona's request that american soldiers be sent in
reports on thursday's air raids conflicted
nicaragua's foreign ministry blamed the united states and made a formal protest
reagan administration officials said one of nicaragua's soviet-supplied helicopters was destroyed, but the sandinistas denied it. nicaragua is believed to have more than 40 military helicopters
honduras said its air force attacked only inside its own territory
suarez, the military spokesman, said the honduran air force raided along the border near san andres de bocay, site of the sandinista military headquarters in northern nicaragua
reporters flown to san andres de bocay saw two jet aircraft, unidentified, fly in from honduras just after noon thursday and drop at least five bombs near the border
a wonder both spiritual and touristic will be played out saturday at mission san juan capistrano when thousands of visitors scan the skies for returning cliff swallows
in other urban areas, the small, noisy birds are considered a messy menace. their pilgrimage from argentina to regions as far north as alaska goes unappreciated. their mud nests are destroyed before eggs are laid
but here the annual migration is considered a marvel, thanks to a 1939 song that popularized a legend about a franciscan padre befriending the weary birds when an inn keeper smashed their nests
some 9,000 swallow-seekers are expected to flock to the cobblestone streets around the 212-year-old mission during the annual celebration of the cleft-tailed birds' official return on march 19, st. joseph's day
when you think about it, who really cares if they come back every year? people are cyclical. it assures us that things are not screwed up,'' said alan lieberman, curator of birds for the san diego zoo, some 60 miles south
he added: ``i think it romanticizes love among the animals.''
as legend has it, the swallows have failed the camera- and binocular-toters only once, in 1935, when they were reportedly delayed by a storm
accounts of the swallows were recorded nearly from 1776, the year father junipero serra founded the mission. leon rene's 1939 song ``when the swallows come back to capistrano'' put the town on the map
in recent years, the number of birds sighted on march 19 has dropped from thousands to a handful. mission and tourism officials maintain that the shy birds are scared off by the welcoming hoopla
the insect-eating birds also are a victim of urbanization that has turned the small farming town 60 miles south of los angeles into a community of 22,500. lush orange groves and mudflats have become parking lots and condominiums
instead of nesting in the shade of the renovated mission, many of the white-bellied, brown birds set up house under the eaves of buildings and freeway overpasses in outlying areas
the swallows, they don't come like they used to. there are too many people here now and they scare them away,'' laments paul arbiso, 92, the mission's gardener and bell ringer since 1910
arbiso will ring four antique bells when he first sees a swallow saturday, kicking off an all-day party
the festivities should begin fairly early since the first birds to complete the 6,000-mile journey from goya, argentina, arrived several weeks ago, said brian mcinerney, director of tourism for the mission
we've got about 1,500 swallows at the mission already,'' mcinerney said earlier this week
the mission also has 50 workers answering inquiries from around the world, said mcinerney. last year's event put about $50,000 in the mission's coffers, he said
the local chamber of commerce said it does not keep a tally on the birds' economic impact, but spokeswoman jan hessell said hotels in the area are booked and merchants ready for the onslaught
people will buy anything with a swallow on it, and the mobs have to have somewhere to eat,'' she said
the event has its detractors. some bird experts argue that migrating animals don't make or keep appointments
march 19 is a day people chose and i'm not sure the swallows are aware of it,'' said gerald collier, a san diego state university orinthologist. ``they do come around the beginning of spring.''
he also points out that there are between 50 million and 100 million cliff swallows in the wild. ``so 1,500 come to san juan capistrano,'' he said. ``where are all the rest?''
some swallows will go to a shopping mall in nearby mission viejo, where nests from last year await them under the eaves of a department store
hershey gehris, the mall's general manager, recalls a different attitude towards cliff swallows in campbell, calif
they used to fight them more than here,'' gehris said. ``they do things to your clothes that make you a little upset, and they do marvelous things to the paint job on your car.''
i think they're neat around here,'' he adds. ``but i don't think i'd want them around all the time.''
seven soviet leaders, including the kremlin's no. 2 man, met friday with leading armenians and azerbaijanis to express the ruling politburo's concern about ethnic rioting that killed at least 32 people
the news agency tass said yegor k. ligachev, second to mikhail s. gorbachev in the hierarchy, also met separately with a group of workers from nagorno-karabakh, the predominantly armenian region of azerbaijan that armenians want to annex
armenian protests last month to support the annexation touched off a wave of unrest in the two southern soviet republics. on feb. 28, rioting broke out in sumgait, a city of azerbaijan, and officials say 32 people were killed
tass said that moscow-based science and cultural figures of armenian and azerbaijani descent were at friday's meeting in the communist party central committee
it said that at the session, ``serious concern was expressed in connection with the developments in the nagorno-karabakh autonomous region and the situation in soviet armenia and azerbaijan.''
besides ligachev, officials attending included full politburo members lev zaikov and mikhail solomentsev; candidate members pyotr demichev, vladimir dolgikh and georgy razumovsky, and central committee secretary anatoly lukyanov
among the armenians and azerbaijanis at the meeting were m.p. mchedlov, deputy director of the central committee's institute of marxism-leninism; f.k. salmanov, first deputy geology minister; s.a. sitaryan, first deputy director of the state planning committee; and k.n. brutens, editor of a historical journal, tass reported
it said the meeting was ``at the recommendation of the politburo,'' a sign of official concern about the ethnic unrest
tass said those attending came up with ``constructive suggestions that were taken into account and would help handle in a better way problems of economic, social and intellectual life in the region.'' it did not go into detail
the agency provided no further information on the meeting between ligachev and the workers from nagorno-karabakh
on feb. 26, gorbachev appealed for ``civic maturity and restraint'' in armenia and azerbaijan and pledged that the policy-making central committee would review relations among this vast nation's more than 100 nationalities
armenian activists reported in telephone calls to the associated press on thursday that armenians conducted a general strike in stepanakert, the main city of nagorno-karabakh, to demand annexation to armenia
the armenian republic's official yerevan radio reported friday that 1,661 armenians had arrived in armenia from azerbaijan since the rioting in sumgait. the radio report was monitored by the british broadcasting corp. in london
it said a government commission under first deputy premier vladimir movsisyan was in charge of helping the refugees
armenians are predominantly christians, while azeries, the dominant group in azerbaijan, are mostly shiite moslems
some homes these days go begging for a buyer
but the reason has nothing to do with high prices or rising interest rates
a new sales gimmick allows prospective home buyers to drive up to a house, tune their car radio to an am frequency and hear the low-down on closets, bedrooms and that unseen swimming pool out back without getting out of the car
the device has a range of about 150 feet and a tape that plays for a couple minutes
robin stella, a vice president at robert stone inc. real estate agency, said friday her company began using the talking house device three months ago and sales this year are up 43 percent
ms. stella said the device deserves at least some credit for the boost
the devices are used primarily to sell houses, but its manufacturer, realty electronics in fond du lac, wis., said other applications are being discovered
we certainly envision a time when they are very common _ that you pull up to a bank and hear about their interest rates; that you go to a drive-in restaurant and hear about the specials,'' said scott matthew, vice president
already, some of the 10,000 devices sold have gone to car washes with long lines that use it to peddle their waxes
car dealers closed on sunday employ it to entice buyers who go window shopping. a shopping mall in ohio is using it to advertise mark-downs
the inspiration came from disney amusement parks, where visitors tune their radios to a certain frequency to find out more about the attractions, matthew said
police stood guard at a high school friday after two days of fights between ``jocks'' and ``burnouts'' that began over control of a hallway hangout
louise gates, a spokeswoman at plymouth-canton high school in suburban detroit, said there was one minor scuffle friday that lasted about 10 minutes
fights between student-athletes and burnouts, who students said are distinguished by their leather jackets and rock concert t-shirts, erupted wednesday and thursday
administrators said the fighting began over use of a gathering place known as ``the pit.''
there were no injuries, but at least 12 students were suspended for fighting, and school officials sealed off the pit, officials said
about 20 officers from canton and nearby plymouth township were called in to restore order thursday. police declined to say how many officers were at the school friday
the amount of police that they brought in was outrageous. it gave the kids a reason to keep going,'' said reeder singler, a student at nearby plymouth-salem high school who also takes classes at plymouth-canton
singler, who doesn't align himself with either group, added: ``with the police here, it's just making things worse. things would have died down naturally, but now something might happen sometime in the future.''
he said the battle is ``not really over turf.''
it's over discrimination of one group over another,'' he said. the burnouts feel the jocks receive preferential treatment from some administrators and faculty members, he said
on thursday, the burnouts sent principal thomas tattan a note saying, ``we feel we should be treated with the same courtesy as other peer and social groups. we believe you're taking the jocks' side over the pit issue.''
the two groups met friday to try to resolve the issue, but the meeting broke up when administrators tried to join the discussions, singler said. the groups will continue to talk, he said
gates said administrators talked to both sides, but declined to reveal what was discussed. to conform, subs grafs 11-14 bgng: the army confirmed... with six grafs. pick up 15th graf pvs: in the west bank city...</note>
israeli troops fired on palestinians in the west bank and gaza strip on friday following noontime moslem prayers, killing two arabs, the army said
at least 25 protesters were wounded in the clashes, hospital officials reported
two israeli civilians were detained for allegedly stockpiling an arsenal of weapons intended for anti-arab attacks, according to police
israeli military authorities detained a prominent attorney from gaza and four arab journalists, prompting an outcry from israeli liberals. authorities also ordered foreign journalists out of the gaza strip and many areas of the west bank
chief of staff dan shomron called on israel's leaders to reach an accord with the arabs to end more than 14 weeks of unrest
in an interview with the daily davar newspaper, shomron said the israeli army ``cannot endure this situation forever. the matter has to be solved.''
the latest deaths brought to 102 the number of palestinians killed during the violent uprising, according to u.n. figures. most of the deaths were caused by gunfire or beatings
u.n. officials in nicosia, cyprus said that more than 400 palestinian refugees had been injured in gaza this week, bringing to more than 900 the number of casualties in march
protests erupted at the shati refugee camp in gaza after hundreds of worshipers streamed from the camp's al-gharbi mosque and saw soldiers scuffling with three youths, witnesses said
troops dropped tear gas canisters from helicopters and fired rubber bullets before using live ammunition to restore order, the witnesses and the army said
the army said one palestinian was killed there. officials at shifa hospital identified him as 24-year-old hani abu hamam
at the ein beit ilmah refugee camp near nablus, the largest city in the west bank, a youth was fatally wounded when he attacked a soldier during a protest, an army spokeswoman said
the spokeswoman, not identified in line with military rules, said the victim had assaulted the soldier with ``a dangerous object,'' but did not say what the object was
in saving himself, the soldier shot the boy, and that resulted in death,'' she said
officials at nablus' ittihad hospital said the victim, identified as muhamed mahmud suleiman khaled, 19, was dead on arrival. jehad alawni, a nurse, said khaled was shot in the left thigh and bled to death
the nurse said khaled was shot at a military outpost and not during a protest, but the army spokeswoman denied that account
in the west bank city of ramallah, 10 miles north of jerusalem, troops confronted about 200 arab youths outside ramallah hospital
in an apparently new tactic, troops dumped gravel from helicopters on protesters below before using live ammunition. two palestinian men were shot and wounded. one was in serious condition with a wound to the abdomen, hospital officials said
two 44-year-old israelis, identified by the haaretz newspaper as moshe vinokor of rishon lezion and gershon luxemburg of jerusalem, were detained after police discovered they had stockpiled a large arsenal of weapons, apparently for use in attacks against arabs, police said
investigators determined the two had acted alone and were not part of a larger ring, haaretz said
the army also rounded up scores of suspected palestinian activists this week in a crackdown aimed at curbing riots on land day, a traditional palestinian nationlist day that falls on march 30, israel radio and arab reports said. the arab-owned palestine press service set the number of detainees at about 400
mohammed abu shaban, the vice president of the gaza bar association, was picked up late thursday after participating in a gathering at tel aviv university protesting israeli policies in the territories
abu shaban has represented several gazans in appeals to the israeli supreme court. tel aviv university professors and the left-wing citizens' rights movement sent a telegram to defense minister yitzhak rabin demanding abu shaban's release
israeli army officials alleged abu shaban was involved in subversive activities, but israeli liberals contended he was picked up because of his participation in the tel aviv gathering
it's devastating to believe that people cannot talk freely on our campus,'' university professor moshe shaked said on israel radio
four arab journalists also were detained, according to arab reports
chief of staff shomron said israeli leaders should open peace talks even before calm returns. he said demonstrations could be ended immediately if the army ordered soldiers to open fire on protesters, a move he would oppose
if someone wants to achieve calm at the cost of ordering the army to ... go against the basic norms of the israeli army,'' he said, ``then it will have to be without me.''
the customs service has donated about $20 million in clothing to three african nations through an agreement with the agency for international development, officials said thursday
the agreement, signed by customs commissioner william von raab and aid administrator alan woods, establishes a permanent program allowing the transfer of seized textile merchandise for humanitarian distribution
this is a true case of government triumphing over its own bureaucracy,'' said von raab, noting that ``it benefits more than the egos of government officials. someone will actually benefit from this.''
previously, customs had no recourse but to spend ``hundreds of thousands of taxpayers' dollars to destroy this clothing,'' von raab said
a major shipment of clothing was seized after the people's republic of china alerted customs that counterfeit documents were being used to bring the items into the country
the clothing includes cotton jeans, shirts, dresses, denim jackets and infants' cotton shirts manufactured in china
aid will turn the clothing over to world vision relief organization and the adventist development and relief agency for distribution in mozambique, malawi and zimbabwe, where it is expected to clothe 20,000 children
tan siew sin, former finance minister and head of a multinational company based here, died friday of a heart attack. he was 72
tan siew sin served in the cabinet from the time of independence from britain in 1957 until his retirement in 1974
the millionaire also was chairman of the sime darby group, which owns rubber, palm oil and cocoa plantations, and trading houses and factories in malaysia, singapore, hong kong, london, australia, indonesia, the philippines and other countries
joseph paterno, a reputed mobster who remained out of jail for two years by claiming ill health, died wednesday of lymphatic cancer at age 64
paterno pleaded guilty in dade circuit court after making a plea agreement with the dade state attorney's office in september to charges that he plotted to murder two people in 1985
the terms of his plea agreement with the dade state attorney's office allowed paterno to stay in his miami beach home while seeking medical treatment. the agreement called for paterno to be medically evaluated each year, until such time as he could serve a prison sentence of 12 to 15 years
john r. king, a 114-year-old man believed to be coshocton county's oldest resident and one of the longest-lived people in the united states, died thursday
king worked in the timber industry most of his life, then joined clow corp. in newcomerstown and also worked for the now-defunct heller tool co
lillian anne kirby flynn, the mother of boston mayor raymond l. flynn, died thursday of emphysema at age 74
three powerful senate chairmen and the senate democratic leader agreed friday to seek to amend the arms treaty signed by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev in a way that would limit future presidents' ability to reinterpret the accord
the administration immediately denounced the move
under the amendment, interpretations of the intermediate nuclear forces treaty by president reagan and his sucessors in the white house would be based not just on the treaty text but on the full record of senate ratification hearings
the condition would be attached to prevent the a recurrence of what many senators have charged is reagan's overly broad interpretation of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty
that interpretation has been used to justify testing and development of reagan's strategic defense initiative, often called ``star wars.''
congressional sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the decision to attach the condition _ to prevent future broad interpretations of the inf pact _ was made at a luncheon by the four leading senators
they are majority leader robert byrd of west virginia, foreign relations chairman claiborne pell of rhode island, armed services chairman sam nunn of georgia and intelligence committee co-chairman david boren
the original author of the proposal was sen. joseph biden, d-del
their condition will be presented to the foreign relations panel during consideration of the treaty next week, the sources said
the inf, signed by reagan and gorbachev in december, would eliminate all land-based missiles with ranges between 300 and 3,125 miles and has been hailed by most senators of both parties as an important step forward in arms control
ratification by the required two-thirds of the senate is expected, but the attachments of conditions opposed by the administration would be a complicating factor
in a commentary attached to the proposed amendment the senators have said their purpose was not to resolve the dispute over the abm treaty
rather the provision is intended to reaffirm certain constitutional principles which have been brought into question during the `reinterpretation' debate,'' the commentary said
in that debate, many democrats have argued that the abm treaty, as outlined during the ratification hearings in 1972, prevents much star wars testing and development. the administration has asserted that its interpretation _ based on the text and the record of negotiations with the soviets _ permits star wars development
the white house, meanwhile, in a letter to sen. richard lugar, r-ind., a member of the foreign relations panel, reiterated its opposition to attaching conditions to the inf treaty
the letter, signed by arthur b. culvahouse, counsel to the president, and sent to lugar on thursday, said the resolution is ``seriously flawed.''
he acknowledged that for domestic purposes a president would adhere to an interpretation generally agreed to by the senate, but he said the proposed amendment would go too far, by binding an administration to ``all statements made by official of the executive branch during ratification proceedings.''
these would include ``answers to over 1,000 questions submitted by members of the senate, no matter how trivial or how unimportant the issue addressed may be to the senate's advice and consent deliberations.''
the result might be two inf treaties, one binding domestically against the president and a second one binding internationally between the united states and the soviet union,'' culvahouse said
he said the differences ``will favor the soviet union because the soviet union is not and cannot be bound by our domestic processes.''
the proposal ``only serves the interests of confusion, ambiguity, confrontation and uncertainty,'' he said
backers of former state school superintendent carolyn warner filed petitions friday to put her on the recall election ballot against impeached gov. evan mecham, setting up a possible seven-way race in the may 17 vote
more than 100 people took out petitions to run against the first-term republican governor, but only six came back with signatures as friday's filing deadline passed
backers of mrs. warner, a democrat who lost to mecham in 1986, filed what they said were about 6,500 signatures, well over the total of 3,336 valid signatures required
backers of acting gov. rose mofford, another democrat, and two republican hopefuls _ party national committeeman jack londen and former congressman john rhodes _ submitted signatures thursday
mecham is automatically on the ballot, unless the senate's impeachment trial ends before then with a vote to bar him from public office
two lesser-known candidates, one a real-estate broker with little political experience and the other a member of the socialist workers party, also filed under the deadline
under state law, the highest vote total wins the recall election, even if it is less than a majority. political affiliations are not indicated on the ballot
mecham was elected on his fifth try in a race against mrs. warner and a democrat running as an independent, bill schulz
several candidates have said that a large number of candidates in the may 17 election would boost mecham's chances of retaining office
state law requires that mrs. mofford, who was elected secretary of state in 1986 and became acting governor when mecham was impeached last month, resign both posts if she is to campaign openly for the governor's job
she has declined to say whether she would resign and run actively
warner campaign spokesman dave bolger said mrs. warner would not run if mrs. mofford declared she would campaign actively
on the republican side, londen vowed to drop out if mecham's senate impeachment trial results in acquittal. rhodes said he would stay in the race regardless of the outcome of the trial, which wound up its third week friday
mecham is charged with obstructing justice, concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and loaning $80,000 in state money to his auto dealership
the other two candidates filing petitions were tempe real-estate broker john c. oertle sr. and and socialist workers party candidate bernie senter
the soldiers who left fort ord for honduras are members of the 7th light infantry division, designed for quick airlifts to any part of the world on short notice
some members of the so-called bayonet division have been trained in warfare in saudi arabia, the sinai desert, korea, panama and honduras
in october 1985, the 7th was incorporated into the military's rapid deployment force and became the army's first modern light division. it is one of four light infantry divisions in the army; the others are based in hawaii, alaska and new york
a light infantry division is designed for low- to mid-intensity combat,'' said capt. guy shields, fort ord spokesman
shields said the entire fort ord division of 11,400 soldiers can be moved in less than six days. a description of the 7th light issued by fort ord says ``initial combat elements can be in a potential crisis area in less than 18 hours.''
the description also calls the 7th light ``an offensively oriented, highly responsive combat division deployable three times faster than existing infantry divisions.''
the units at fort ord consist of nine infantry battalions. they have fewer vehicles, less equipment and fewer soldiers than standard infantry divisions, and thus are able to move faster, in 500 airlifts instead of about 1,200
in march 1986, 200 fort ord soldiers were sent to honduras for u.s. and honduran military exercises known as big pine. they were stationed near the nicaraguan border about 100 miles from the site of skirmishes between the nicaraguan army and the contras, and practiced troop deployment
the fort ord troops brought some vehicles and personal weapons such as m-16a1 rifles and sidearms, but were cautioned to avoid any real combat
in march 1987, 750 soldiers from the division were sent to honduras for several weeks of field exercises with honduran troops
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis continued to hold a lead friday as washington state democrats were wrapping up their tally of results from precinct caucuses
with nearly complete results from five congressional districts, dukakis had won support from 3,784, or 44.6 percent, of the delegates elected to county conventions, which will be held in april. jesse jackson was supported by 3,083, or 36.3 percent, of the county delegates and 1,074, or 12.7 percent, were uncommitted
sen. paul simon of illinois won support from 300 county convention delegates, while 166 supported tennessee sen. albert gore jr. and 78 supported missouri rep. richard gephardt
if these figures hold up through the congressional district conventions next month, dukakis will receive 14 delegates to the democratic national convention this summer, jackson will get nine delegates and another five will be uncommitted
washington democrats met in party caucuses on march 8, but results have not been available until now
the state party refused to release partial results from the remaining three congressional districts. those results are expected next week
the precinct caucuses elected delegates to the county conventions, where delegates to the conventions in each of the state's eight congressional districts will be chosen. those conventions will pick a total of 43 national convention delegates, and those delegates will meet later to choose another 22 delegates
in all, washington state will send 73 delegates to the democratic national convention, including 65 chosen through the caucus process. in addition, gov. booth gardner and seven democratic national committee members from the state automatically hold seats as delegates to the convention. discussed</head> troops to front.</note>
honduras asked for u.s. help friday in ferrying honduran troops to the scene of their battle with sandinista forces, administration sources said, adding that the request was likely to be approved
the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the government of honduras asked the united states for helicopter support in moving some additional honduran troops to an area within about 20 miles of the border of nicaragua where the fighting has been going on
the cable came in to the state department today. but no decision has been made as yet,'' said an official who asked not to be identified
but another official said, ``i can't imagine that we would turn it down. we've done it before.''
in december 1986, 40 u.s. helicopters were used to ferry honduran troops and equipment to the nicaraguan border to repel a nicaraguan attack on contra rebel camps on honduran soil. the transported 700 honduran soldiers to the front, after honduran president jose azcona asked for the aid. no americans became involved in comba
the sources said a response to honduras would probably come over the weekend. they said the honduras were not planning to move a large number of troops, but they declined to give a number. they said the united states has sufficient transport helicopters in honduras to do the job
the sources said that they would be following the same type of rules as in l986 when they did this, in that u.s. personnel and equipment would stay well away from the scene of fighting to ensure they were not exposed to hostile fire
the request came as u.s. troops continued to arrive in honduras in a show of force, and a bipartisan group of 11 senators proposed a $48 million package of new aid to nicaragua's contra rebels, including renewed authority for the cia to deliver previously stockpiled weapons
assistant secretary of state elliott abrams said earlier that additional assistance was being discussed with honduran president jose azcona, in response to a reported nicaraguan incursion
white house chief of staff howard baker said president reagan would give ``most careful'' consideration to any request from honduras for troops to help repel nicaraguan forces, although he reiterated that u.s. troops were not expected to be involved in any military operation in the region
one of the senate's leading peace advocates, sen. mark o. hatfield, said the sending of u.s. troops amounted merely to ``matching stupidity with stupidity'' and introduced legislation barring the troops from a combat role without permission from congress
sponsors of the new contra aid proposal said they hoped it would revive negotiations in congress and with the reagan administration on an aid package that could be quickly enacted to replace supplies lost or expended during the past week's heavy fighting along the nicaraguan-honduran border
but the extent of the damage inflicted on the rebels by the sandinista incursion remained unclear. sen. david boren, d-okla., chairman of the senate intelligence committee, said the nicaraguan troops were withdrawing without accomplishing all their objectives
we think it's very important right now to send a signal to the sandinista government'' which allegedly crossed the border into honduras in an effort to destroy rebel camps and supplies, boren said
sen. nancy kassebaum, r-kan., said announcement of the package also would strengthen the contras as they enter direct cease-fire talks with the managua regime, scheduled for monday. ``this is a common-sense, moderate and reasoned approach,'' she said
the proposal would use $48 million in unspent pentagon money to buy food, clothing, shelter and medical supplies, and to transport it to troops in the field, over the next year. about $3 million of that amount would go for communications gear
but in what promised to be a controversial provision, the package would allow the cia to airdrop ammunition and weapons previously stockpiled by the rebels to troops in the field. boren said the rebels still have $2 million to $5 million worth of undelivered supplies, about half of them lethal
and it would give president reagan the right to hold a quick, guaranteed vote in congress on any request for further military aid under certain conditions if the peace talks between the sandinistas and contras break down
as a ``carrot,'' the bill also would promise long-term economic aid for the region once political stability is restored
an administration official, speaking on condition he not be identified, said of the new aid package, ``we are encouraged from reports we have heard about it, but we will have to wait until we have the actual details.''
action on further aid for the rebels has been stalled since march 3, when the house narrowly rejected a $30 million package of purely humanitarian aid. aid proponents saw the sandinista incursion into honduras as a new opportunity to revive interest in aid
meanwhile, abrams told reporters that american officials have been discussing with honduran president azcona the possibility of providing additional assistance to that country, in addition to the 3,200 troops already airlifted to palmerola air base near tegucigalpa
there are some other possibilities that we've discussed,'' abrams said, adding that the possibilities did not include additional troops
baker said that if a request were received from honduras for troops to help repel nicaraguan forces, ``it would be most carefully considered and most deliberately considered. but i cannot tell you what decision the president would make under those circumstances.''
baker, interviewed on the syndicated television program, ``john mclaughlin's one on one,'' was asked at what point u.s. troops would enter action
i don't anticipate that will occur at all. i think that the honduran forces can handle that on their own, and i fully anticipate that either the nicaraguans will retire on their own or honduras will, as they say, encourage them to do that. but i do not expect american troops to be involved in any military operation there,'' he said
hatfield's proposal would permit u.s. military exercises in honduras, like the training mission which began thursday, only if congress has been notified a month in advance. troops could not be sent into combat without a declaration of war or a ``clear and present danger'' of attack on the united states or its citizens. it also would prohibit any increase in the permanent u.s. military presence there
he said the administration's action amounted to ``sinking to the level of those in nicaragua who have no interest in peace.''
under the terms of this legislation we will not allow and will not tolerate sending american military personnel into combat in central america,'' hatfield said. ``it is not an option... we will not permit our young people to be used as pawns in this political game. and we will not push them down the slippery slope of intervention as we pushed their fathers and brothers down that slope into vietnam.''
the senators who proposed the aid package included seven republicans and four democrats. they are boren; lloyd bentsen, d-texas; bob graham, d-fla., sam nunn, d-ga.; richard lugar, r-ind., daniel evans, r-wash., kassebaum, john mccain, r-ariz.; phil gramm, r-texas; mitch mcconnell, r-ky., and frank murkowski, r-alaska

