the plo envoy told an emergency general assembly session friday the united nations should file suit to keep his mission open if the united states tries to close it
some diplomats said the world body should consider fighting the u.s. government in american courts and provide alternative accommodations for the palestine liberation organization on u.n. international territory. the plo has observer status at the united nations
plo observer zehdi labib terzi and other speakers denounced the u.s. justice department decision to close the mission under a new anti-terrorism act, saying the move conflicts with u.s. treaty obligations to the united nations. the u.s. state department has opposed the closure
the justice department says it will take legal action if the mission is not closed by march 21, the effective date of the law. it is not expected to be closed by monday and litigation is expected
terzi said israel also should be denied its place at the united nations if the mission is closed. the united nations regards the plo as the sole legitimate representative of the palestinian people, but israel and the united states consider it a terrorist organization
we deem it proper the general assembly should ask the secretary-general ... to take all steps, including legal steps if necessary, to ensure the plo observer mission be able to discharge its official functions without hindrance,'' terzi said
it was the second emergency session on the plo issue this month and the 159-member assembly is to consider draft resolutions condemning the u.s. action. general assembly resolutions carry the moral weight of world opinion but are not binding on the membership, as are those of the security council
at the same time, deputy assistant secretary of state william walker has gone to panama at noriega's request to discuss possible terms for his departure from panama, the source said
according to the official, walker had instructions to tell noriega that the united states will not seek his extradition on drug trafficking charges if he flees to a third country
the official said that walker went to panama with this offer in the hopes that it would facilitate noriega's departure, thus sparing the country a period of prolonged political upheaval, including widespread suffering
the country has been virtually paralyzed economically for most of the past two weeks
the government of spain has said it would be wiling to admit noriega provided he requests political asylum and the united states agrees not to seek his extradition
people who are moderately physically fit have a lower risk of dying of a heart attack even if they don't exercise, a new study shows
you don't have to be a super athlete. you don't have to have extraordinary levels of fitness or physical activity to get the benefit,'' said one of the study's directors, steven blair of the institute for aerobics research in dallas
blair described the study friday during a meeting of the american heart association
the study is one of the first to show that physical fitness _ as measured by the length of time a subject can walk or run on a treadmill _ protects against fatal heart attacks even in people who don't exercise, blair said
physical fitness is a function of past exercise and genetics, blair said. some people are simply born more fit than others, blair said
it is widely accepted that exercise or other forms of physical activity protect against heart disease, and many studies have shown that the protection extends even to those who engage in only moderate physical activity
this study, of 3,120 women and 10,226 men who came to the cooper clinic in dallas for preventative health exams, extends that observation to physical fitness itself
blair's institute and the cooper clinic are both part of the aerobics center, founded by dr. kenneth cooper to encourage exercise and physical fitness. the institute is the research arm of the aerobics center
blair and his collaborator, harold kohl iii, found that men in the bottom 20 percent when ranked by physical fitness were twice as likely as the others to die of a heart attack
women in the bottom 20 percent had 2.8 times the risk of other women
the conclusions that can be reached by the study are limited by the fact that the subjects were not a representative sample of the american population, blair said
eighty percent were college graduates, they were virtually all white and they were largely well-to-do, he said
in a standard treadmill test, a physically fit 40-year-old man might be able to exercise for 20 or 25 minutes, blair said. a champion athlete could last more than half an hour, and people who are not fit can become exhausted much sooner
here, at a glance, are developments in the nicaragua-honduras crisis thursday:
planeloads of u.s. soldiers began arriving at palmerola air base in honduras to engage in joint exercises with honduran troops. president reagan ordered the troops to honduras in a show of strength to counter what he called an invasion by nicaraguan forces. nicaragua's sandinista army was battling contra rebels in the border region
two battalions from the 82nd airborne division of fort bragg, n.c. and two battalions from the 7th light infantry division of fort ord, calif., were combined into a task force of 3,000 troops deployed about 125 miles west of the reported fighting
nicaragua said warplanes attacked a sandinista military headquarters in northern nicaragua near the honduran border. a reagan administration source in washington confirmed that honduras had launched the raid
a nicaraguan spokesman said the planes fired at least five rockets but there were no injuries or damage. he said sandinista troops fired on the planes, forcing them to turn back
in managua, nicaraguan president daniel ortega called for a meeting of the u.n. security council to deal with what he called ``one more escalation of the war against nicaragua.''
ortega said the sandinistas would continue their offensive against the contra rebels. ``we are ready to combat and liquidate the famous forces of the 82nd airborne division,'' he said
earlier, a foreign ministry spokesman said nicaragua already had begun withdrawing troops from the border region after driving about 2,000 contra rebels back into honduras
col. manuel suarez benavides, spokesman for the honduran armed forces, said the government and the army had given nicaragua ``a peremptory deadline'' of 24 hours to withdraw 2,000 troops from honduras
honduran military intelligence sources said about 4,000 honduran soldiers were still surrounding about 2,000 nicaraguan troops. the armed forces spokesman said the troops were six miles inside honduras
we will not allow the sandinistas to move further into the interior of our territory,'' said one honduras military source. ``we want to avoid a large conflict, but if it isn't possible, we will have to face the invading troops.''
secretary of state george p. shultz said the u.s. troops airlifted to central america are not there in a ``shooting capacity'' but to signal opposition to nicaraguan aggression. he told a senate committee the intent was to ``get people's attention to what is happening in central america'' and to say to the honduran government, ``we are your friends. we stand with you.''
it is important for people to know the united states will fight, but we don't plan to get involved in any military way,'' shultz said
some democrats in congress quickly questioned president reagan's decision to send the troops. senate majority leader robert c. byrd jr., d-w. va., called it an ``overreaction,'' and house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said it was unjustified
senate republican leader bob dole of kansas defended the action, declaring that contra rebels are being overrun and ``slaughtered by the hundreds.'' he called on the president to immediately resubmit a package of military and logistical aid for the contra rebels
in costa rica, president oscar arias said the reported sandinista incursion into honduras jeopardizes truce talks set for monday between the nicaraguan government and contra rebels
being certain that the nicaraguan army invaded honduras, my government condemns it categorically and with firmness,'' arias said
abc news reported friday night that unidentified u.s. and central american sources say noriega has signed off on most parts of a package that will allow some face-saving for him, but will get him out of office and out of panama
the united states has applied economic pressure, including blocking the transfer of currency to panama and withholding panama canal fees, in an attempt to encourage the ouster of noriega. the political opposition has sought to get rid of the de facto leader of panama for months
the united states stepped up its actions against noriega after noriega deposed president eric arturo delvalle on feb. 25. delvalle had tried to fire noriega. the united states still recognizes delvalle, although solis palma was officially installed feb. 26
abc reported that as a condition of noriega's departure, he will never go to jail and will be allowed to retain most of his wealth
according to abc, the deal included that noriega will step down with full honors; several days or weeks later, he will leave panama, going either to spain or france. in addition, abc said, opposition leaders in panama have agreed not to seek criminal charges against noriega there and not to try to get any of his money held in overseas accounts. saying honduras asked for helicopter support; picks up 10th graf pvs, ``the 60-year-old ...</note>
the army on friday began moving 2,000 soldiers to border jungles it says nicaraguan troops have penetrated, and president jose azcona hoyo said he was depending on u.s. support to fend off agression from nicaragua
reagan administration sources said friday that honduras had asked for u.s. help in transporting the troops to the border area. the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the request for helicopter support would probably be approved
honduras said the nicaraguans crossed the border in pursuit of u.s.-backed contra rebels, and a ranking officer said friday that about 1,000 of the soldiers remained on honduran territory
at a news conference friday, azcona said the u.s. deployment of more than 3,000 troops in honduras was a warning and he would ask for more u.s. help if the leftist nicaraguan government didn't withdraw its troops
the u.s. embassy said about 800 american paratroopers, the last of the 3,200 troops sent to honduras, were dropped onto palmerola air base friday. the defense department says the troops will be in central america about 10 days
azcona said his own troops will keep bombing sandinista positions if the nicaraguans do not withdraw
we are preparing an operation to bomb inside honduran territory,'' he said the day after an air raid in the bocay region
azcona said he decided to ask for u.s. troops because their arrival would be ``spectacular.'' he said he expected the ``simple presence and immediate response'' of u.s. troops would scare the sandinista troops into withdrawing
the united states helped honduras move troops to the border in december 1986, after nicaraguan forces attacked contra rebel camps in honduras. forty u.s. helicopters transported 700 honduran soldiers to the front. no americans were involved in combat
the reagan administration sources said that if the request for helicopter support was granted, u.s. personnel would stay away from any fighting
nicaragua has denied its troops entered honduras, but a nicaraguan military source indicated friday that they had
the 60-year-old azcona said honduran infantry was moving into the mountainous bocay region and should be in position by saturday
we're acting with complete calm. the sandinistas only have to leave our territory,'' azcona told a news conference
the honduran officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said two infantry battalions totaling from 1,600 to 2,000 soldiers were moving in from a base at juticalpa, about 90 miles west of bocay. he said warplanes were on call from tamara air base 15 miles north of tegucigalpa
the officer said soldiers had orders to expel ``invading troops'' by whatever means necessary, adding that about half the original force had fled back to nicaragua and about 1,000 remained
he said the remaining sandinista troops were spread over an area about 40 miles square
pentagon officials said privately the four u.s. battalions from the 82nd airborne and 7th light infantry would spend eight or nine days training with hondurans in different parts of the country
one battalion of the 82nd airborne will be at juticalpa, one official said, ``but anyone who knows the country'' would realize the 90 miles ``might as well be 4,000. there's nothing but mountains and jungle in between.''
the basic order that these troops aren't to get near the fighting still stands,'' he said
president daniel ortega of nicaragua said thursday his soldiers were ready to ``combat and liquidate'' the 82nd airborne and would continue the offensive against contra rebels in an area reaching from central nicaragua to the border
alejandro bendana, secretary-general of nicaragua's foreign ministry, said ``one step ... could lead to another'' in the border conflict, indicating war might result
the contras have had secret bases in honduras from which to attack across the border in their 6-year-old battle with the sandinistas
nicaragua's northern military headquarters is in san andres de bocay near the frontier and honduran warplanes flew raids in the area thursday, hours after u.s. troops began arriving
azcona said the planes fired rockets on a dirt airstrip in honduras ``used by nicaraguan helicopters.'' he would not confirm u.s. reports that a soviet-made helicopter was destroyed. the sandinistas denied it
reporters flown from nicaragua to san andres de bocay saw two unidentified jets fly in from honduras thursday and drop at least five bombs near the border. show that baker's remarks about noriega came before officials revealed us envoy in panama. picks up 20th graf pvs bgng: on possible ...</note>
president reagan would give ``most careful'' consideration to any request from honduras for u.s. troops to assist in repelling nicaraguan forces, white house chief of staff howard h. baker jr. said friday
interviewed on the television program, ``john mclaughlin's one on one,'' baker said, however, that he does not expect u.s. troops to be used in any military engagements in the region
the presidential aide defended reagan's decision to send u.s. troops into the area and denied that the united states had put pressure on the honduran government to request them
he said the president made the decision ``in the second floor of the residence portion of the white house a minute after 8:00'' on wednesday evening, after receiving a request from honduran president jose azcona
i do not believe there was any effort, any arm-twisting, to try to contrive a situation where he would make this request,'' baker said. ``i think it was made for the reason stated in this letter: his country was invaded and that he wanted help.''
interviewer john mclaughlin asked baker what the president would do if azcona asked him to have u.s. troops join honduran troops ``in combat, to repel the invaders.''
no such request has been received. i do not believe such a request will be received,'' baker said. ``but were it received, to answer your hypothetical question, were it to be received, it would be most carefully considered and most deliberately considered. but i cannot tell you what decision the president would make under those circumstances.''
when asked at what point u.s. troops would enter action, baker said, ``i don't anticipate that will occur at all. i think that the honduran forces can handle that on their own, and i fully anticipate that either the nicaraguans will retire on their own or honduras will, as they say, encourage them to do that. but i do not expect american troops to be involved in any military operation there.''
baker rejected suggestions that the administration had raised the alarm about the nicaraguan border crossing in order to strengthen its hand in seeking renewed assistance from congress for rebels fighting nicaragua's marxist-led government
it was not our design,'' he said. ``it did not work that way. and we did not want it that way.''
in fact, baker said, he thinks prospects for an agreement on aid to the rebels were better on tuesday, before the crisis arose, than they are now
i think we were on the brink of that until this incursion occurred, and until we received this request from azcona,'' he said. ``after that, there's dust in the air and fur flying, and clearly we are not better off now than we were before.''
he also said, however, that he believes the prospects will improve again after ``the dust settles and people think about it and understand what's happened, and stop imputing bad motives to this administration and this president.''
but if that was our design, it was the dumbest legislative strategy ever devised, because it hasn't worked that way,'' he said
the program was taped for weekend broadcast, and a transcript was distributed for release on friday
on other subjects, baker said:
_that when he went to panama as senate republican leader during the debate on the panama canal treaties, gen. manuel antonio noriega, who was then the panamanian intelligence chief, threatened in a conversation to blow up the canal if the treaties were not ratified. he said omar torrijos, then the panamanian strongman, told him, ``look, noriega's sort of a hot-head, don't pay any attention to him.''
but baker said the administration, which is putting pressure on noriega to step down, has not had direct contact with the panamanian leader. he was asked about reports that noriega wants direct contacts with the united states but that the united states will not agree to those talks until he agrees to leave panama
there have been some contacts that would appear to be from gen. noriega or on his behalf, but that's all i can tell you ... they purport to be ... queries by _ on gen. noriega's part _ but we have not (had) direct contact with gen. noriega,'' baker said
baker made his remarks before other administration officials revealed late friday that a u.s. envoy has gone to panama at noriega's request to discuss terms of his possible departure
_on possible pardons for individuals indicted in the iran-contra affair, ``the president's simply not going to address that question. the president has the constitutional pardoning authority, but he's said over and over, this is not the time and it's not the circumstance in which to consider that.''
_he does not expect vice president george bush, assuming bush is the republican presidential nominee, to ask him to be his running mate. ``i think he needs to go to a governor, perhaps, someone who can bring about a balance to the ticket.'' he said possibilities would include govs. george deukmejian of california, tom kean of new jersey, and former govs. lamar alexander of tennessee and richard thornburgh of pennsylvania
soviets who earn $3,200 or more a month working in a cooperative operating outside state control will have to pay more than half the money back in taxes, and even as much as 90 percent, izvestia said friday
the government newspaper outlined progressive income taxes for members of cooperatives that it said will go into effect april 1
taxes will remain low for the cooperatives themselves, but income taxes for those who earn more than 500 rubles ($800) a month from working in the cooperatives will climb steeply, according to an interview izvestia conducted with finance ministry official y. zemskov
zemskov said taxes will be increased on high salaries because cooperatives in those cases are paying out in salaries what the government would like them to spend improving and expanding their services
under mikhail s. gorbachev's reforms, soviets can get permission to form cooperatives to produce goods and provide services outside the state-run economy. the cooperatives must be approved by local governments, but otherwise operate outside state control
the tax rate now is between 2 percent and 3 percent for cooperatives in their first year and up to 10 percent after their third year
taxes of cooperative members will start going up sharply after an income of 500 rubles a month, zemskov said. the tax on an income of 1,000 rubles, ($1,600) will be 270.20 rubles and on an income of 2,000 rubles ($3,200) will be 53.5 percent
he said the tax eventually reaches 90 percent, but did not say what the income threshold was for that tax
zemskov said local governments will be allowed to keep the money levied in income taxes on cooperatives to provide them with an incentive to help cooperatives develop
crew members of a high-tech, 28-foot rowboat that crossed the treacherous strait between south america and antarctica said friday they encountered squalls that tossed three of them into the turbulent sea
why did we do it?'' said jay morrison, 34. ``because nobody had ever done it before. that's a pretty good reason.''
rowing most of the way, morrison and three colleagues crossed the stormy drake passage between tierra del fuego, the southern tip of south america, and antactica in a 600-mile voyage that ended march 7
you should see what it's like to try to walk on land after being thrown around at sea for 12 days,'' said ned gillette, who organized the voyage and led an similar expedition last year that was scuttled by ice
until we made it, we weren't really sure it could be done,'' said gillette, of stowe, vt. ``i didn't think we'd expire on the trip, but i didn't know where we'd end up.''
the expedition in the $17,000 red boat jokingly dubbed the sea tomato mixed raw adventure with high-technology precision. the expedition was financed by corporate sponsors
while crew members bailed flooded cabins and rowed the boat through 100-foot swells, a massachusetts weather station each day fed the expedition forecasts, and the boat's location was tracked by satellite
after waiting nearly a month for proper weather, the expedition almost ended in disaster off the chilean coast feb. 22, just hours after leaving under sail
a heavy squall erupted and swamped the craft, sending gillette overboard. gillette, an experienced moutaineer, was saved by a line fastened to the boat, as were two other crew members who were washed overboard later in the trip
three days out, the crew took down the sails and began rowing in shifts, sometimes all night. they went about 2.6 mph on average, or about as fast as a person walks
sometimes an albatross would land alongside,'' said gillette. ``it would paddle along and watch us. we would outdistance it _ sometimes.''
the team brought provisions for 25 days. ``we didn't know how long we'd be out,'' said gillette. ``there was a lot of uncertainty.''
the sea tomato, stripped of some expensive equipment, now rests on king george island in antarctica as a gift to the chilean government
i kind of hope they leave it there,'' said gillette. ``it did its job to get us there. it would be fitting it keep it there.''
the mayor and the communist party chief of a city in azerbaijan where at least 32 people died in ethnic rioting were fired thursday, reports from soviet armenia said
those dismissed were said to be the mayor and communist party chief of sumgait, azerbaijan, where riots broke out feb. 28 between azerbaijanis and ethnic armenians
in another development, the editor of glasnost magazine reported a police raid thursday he said was linked to the publication's coverage of ethnic violence in armenia and neighboring azerbaijan
sergei grigoryants, a former political prisoner and editor of glasnost, said six carloads of police descended on the office in kratovo, a town about 15 miles southeast of moscow
he said by telephone that uniformed and plainclothes officers spent more than two hours checking editors' papers and taking photographs
grigoryants said they wanted to search the office but did not have a warrant. the five editors present would not let police into the back half of the office where editorial work is done, he said
the house was completely surrounded by police cars,'' grigoryants said, adding that many police were involved. he said they did not detain anyone or take anything from the office
grigoryants founded glasnost, named for soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's policy of more openness, last june and has unsuccessfully sought official approval for it
gamlet kocharyan, a member of the governing council of the kafar, armenia, said by telephone the dismissals at sumgait were announced in a television broadcast from yerevan, capital of the armenian republic
armenian activists say the victims in sumgait were armenians killed by azeris, the dominant group in neighboring azerbaijan. most azeris are shiite moslems and armenians are predominantly christian
unrest in the southern republics began with armenian demonstrations pressing for nagorno-karabakh, an area of azerbaijan that has an armenian majority, to be annexed by armenia
kocharyan identified the men fired as muslim zade, communist party chief in sumgait, and mayor tavakkula yagub ogly mamedov
the report said they would be replaced by the premier of the nakhichevansky autonomous republic in azerbaijan and a factory manager from sumgait, according to kocharyan
baku radio reported earlier that mamedov was fired for ``serious shortcomings in the work of maintaining appropriate law and order and discipline in the city, and for the lack of political foresight he has shown which has resulted in tragic consequences.''
the television report also said a commission had been formed to search for witnesses to the rioting in sumgait, kocharyan said
grigoryants is armenian and has reported regularly to western correspondents in moscow about the ethnic unrest in armenia and azerbaijan
he traveled to yerevan to witness a memorial procession march 8 for those killed in sumgait. he and fellow editor andrei shelkov, who went to sumgait, held a news conference last friday for foreign journalists who have not been permitted to visit the area
according to grigoryants, the police visit to the glasnost offices was ``undoubtedly'' part of a campaign of reprisals against him
on saturday, shelkov was attacked on a moscow trolley bus by a person who could not be identified, grigoryants said
official soviet media have criticized grigoryants. police made two raids in august on the editorial office, but did not take anything or arrest anyone
in october, police confiscated about 70 copies they said were printed illegally on state-owned equipment
here is a summary of the latest developments friday involving nicaragua, honduras and the united states:
the honduran army began moving about 2,000 soldiers into the border jungles with orders to drive out nicaraguans still on the honduran side. honduran officials said the nicaraguan troops had crossed the border in pursuit of u.s.-backed contra rebels and that about 1,000 remained in honduran territory
honduras gave the sandinistas 24 hours to get their soldiers out of the country, but the ultimatum did not say when the time period began
the u.s. embassy said about 800 american paratroopers were dropped onto palmerola air base friday morning. they are among 3,200 american troops sent to honduras. the defense department says the u.s. troops likely will be in central america for about 10 days
reagan administration sources said honduras asked the united states friday for helicopter support in ferrying honduran troops to the border area. the sources said the request was likely to be approved. white house chief of staff howard baker said president reagan would give ``most careful'' consideration to any request from honduras for troops to help repel nicaraguan forces
nicaragua told the united nations security council that u.s. troops were sent to honduras to create a crisis to justify military action against nicaragua. the united states countered that the troop movement was ``a measured response'' in support of the territorial integrity of honduras
secretary-general javier perez de cuellar was studying nicaragua's request to send an observer team to its border with honduras on a fact-finding mission
a bipartisan group of senators proposed a $48 million package of new aid to the contras, including renewed authority for the cia to deliver previously stockpiled weapons
supporters said the proposal was designed to trigger negotiations in congress and aimed at quick passage of an emergency infusion of aid to replace supplies lost or expended during the past week's heavy fighting
nicaragua said it had called off its offensive to roust contra rebels from camps along the honduran border, but was maintaining combat positions. the defense ministry maintained no nicaraguan troops had crossed the border, but a military source indicated privately they had
the sandinista government continued plans for cease-fire talks with the contras next monday, but the rebels were considering a boycott
more than 300 people were arrested in demonstrations around the united states to protest the deployment of army troops in honduras. the arrests were mostly for blocking traffic or disorderly conduct
