a former wedtech corp. executive testified friday that he was told attorney general edwin meese iii interceded with the pentagon on the defense contractor's behalf over a $24 million navy contract
the allegation came at the racketeering trial of rep. mario biaggi and six others charged in a series of bribery and influence peddling schemes involving wedtech
the government's first witness, ex-wedtech official mario moreno, said he met with a close friend of meese, san francisco lawyer e. robert wallach, in december 1983. meese at the time was presidential counselor
moreno said wedtech had been notified it would be awarded the less lucrative part of a navy contract to build bridge pontoons, and he asked wallach to get meese ``to change the navy's mind.''
moreno said wallach told him, ``mr. meese said he would talk to mr. weinberger,'' referring to then-defense secretary caspar weinberger. moreno testified that he understood weinberger would call then-navy secretary john lehman
moreno said that in january 1984, wedtech received approval making it eligible for the entire pontoon contract, which it signed in april 1984
moreno first described meese's alleged intervention in an affidavit disclosed in october at a senate hearing. at the time, meese and weinberger said through spokesmen they had no recollection of the action described by moreno
moreno previously testified at the wedtech trial that wallach told him that meese had also interceded on wedtech's behalf with the commerce department over a federal financing package
wedtech, a $100 million-a-year defense contractor before declaring bankruptcy in 1986, grew from a small new york machine shop through a series of no-bid defense contracts. prosecutors claim wedtech falsely portrtayed itself as a minority company to get contracts
wallach, meese's former personal lawyer, is under indictment on charges of taking bribes from wedtech officials for trying to influence meese and others
in december, a special prosecutor in washington said there was insufficient evidence to charge meese in the wedtech case
moreno is one of four ex-wedtech officials who have pleaded guilty to bribing public officials and to other crimes. resolution or vote, additional quotes, corrects name of nicaraguan envoy to delia stead dalia and courtesy title to ms. stead mrs. no pickup</note>
the united states and honduras told the security council friday that nicaraguan troops had invaded honduras. nicaragua claimed the sending of u.s. troops to honduras signaled a plot for direct u.s. military action against nicaragua
nicaraguan envoy rita delia casco denied sandinista troops entered honduran territory. ``what they have said is mere lies,'' said ms. casco, the foreign ministry's director of international organizations
we (nicaraguans) can't withdraw from nicaragua,'' she told a news conference after the emergency session ended. ``the military actions we have taken are limited to the defense of our territory and sovereignty.''
the council adjourned without a resolution or a vote and was to decide whether to resume discussions at some future date
nicaragua's sandinista government had asked for the meeting to protest the sending of 3,200 u.s. military personnel to honduras thursday and friday
ms. casco said a u.s. congressional delegation was welcome to visit nicaragua and would be escorted to key border areas to see the situation
after denouncing the united states in an address to the council, ms. casco shook hands and chatted with u.s. ambassador herbert s. okun, who had accused nicaragua of invading honduras and rejecting democracy
okun, deputy chief of the u.s. mission, said sending u.s. troops for military exercises in honduras was a measured response requested by the honduran government
the u.s. force ``does not constitute either a threat or the use of force against nicaragua,'' he said
okun also claimed the santinistas were trying to destroy u.s.-backed rebels, known as contras, and stifle democratic debate. many of the rebels operate from bases in honduras, which borders nicaragua
u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar is considering a nicaraguan request to send a fact-finding mission, coordinated with the organization of american states, to the nicaraguan-honduran border
honduran ambassador jorge ramon hernandez told the council: ``if nicaragua withdraws the troops which even today are in honduras, that would be proof of its commitment to peace
we denounce this invasion as the expansionistic, aggressive attitude of nicaragua, not only to my country but to others. it is trying to disrupt the whole, regional peace process.''
he accused nicaragua of launching a ``broad-ranging offensive in flagrant violation of honduran territorial integrity'' and said honduras had requested u.s. assistance
ms. casco claimed the reagan administration created an artificial crisis and was out to justify direct military action against nicaragua
okun said sending the troops was ``a measured response designed to show our staunch support for the democratic government of honduras at a time when its territorial integrity is being violated by the sandinista army.''
he said the u.s. troops would be involved in exercises away from the area of border hostilities
ms. casco told the council washington wants to sabotage central american cease-fire talks and the peace plan signed in august by the presidents of five central american countries. the plan calls for an end to outside aid to insurgents
this is a crisis artificially created by the u.s. administration in its design to find justification for the continuation and extension of its warlike policy in central america,'' she said
the u.s. administration has considered a series of options, including the possibility of direct military action against nicaragua in order to save its mercenaries (the rebels) who have been strategically defeated _ politically and militarily.''
in asking for the meeting, nicaragua's acting ambassador, julio icaza gallard, said the 15-member council should ``consider the serious situation created by the escalation of threats and aggression against my country and by the u.s. decision to send american troops to honduran territory.''
council members are the united states, britain, china, france and the soviet union, which as permanent members have veto power, and yugoslavia, algeria, argentina, brazil, italy, japan, nepal, senegal, west germany and zambia
a father told police he stuffed his newborn baby into a toilet and later threw him into a lake, but authorities concluded the child had died in the womb and said no murder charges will be filed
however, the case has prompted several tips about pregnant women whose newborns have vanished, and detectives are opening investigations into three cases as a result, said tarrant county sheriff's detective wayne boggus
the so-called benbrook lake case was solved by a tip from an acquaintance of the mother, authorities said. the acquaintance never saw the baby after the mother's pregnancy ended
sheriff's investigators confronted the 22-year-old mother and 24-year-old husband and they gave detailed statements. the couple's names were withheld
the woman gave birth feb. 16 in her bathroom. the frightened husband, apparently unaware the child was stillborn, stuffed the body into the toilet and took a nap next to his bloodied wife, the father told police wednesday
he said when he woke up, he hoped it was all just a nightmare,'' said boggus. the father said he found the baby dead, and he put the body in a bag with heavy rocks and tossed it into lake, boggus said
the man's wife, still weak, did not knew what was in the bag, the man said. it was two weeks before he told her what he did with the baby, authorities said
the only explanation we got from him was that he `freaked out,''' boggus said. ``he said he almost fainted himself. i assume he was pretty scared and confused.''
a fisherman hooked the bag march 7 in a nearby creek. on march 8, the county medical examiner's office ruled that the baby was choked by his umbilical cord in the womb
with the natural-death ruling, murder charges cannot be brought against the couple, robert hester, assistant tarrant county prosecutor, said thursday
hester said authorities may charge the man with abuse of a corpse, a misdemeanor punishable by a maximum of a year in jail and a $2,000 fine
because of a plea through the news media for information on the benbrook lake case, detectives are looking into other cases. police declined to give details of those cases
