defense secrtary frank c. carlucci said thursday he protested to his soviet counterpart nicaragua's alleged intrusion into honduras
carlucci said he and dmitri yazov briefly discussed the nicaragua-honduras dispute and that yazov ``made some attempt to defend the sandinista action.''
i would not characterize it as a vigorous defense,'' he added at a news conference in bern. carlucci arrived back in washington later thursday
u.s. troops arrived in honduras on thursday after the united states and honduras accused nicaraguan troops of entering the country in pursuit of u.s.-backed contra rebels. carlucci said he had endorsed the decision
carlucci described the three days of closed-door talks with yazov as ``cordial and businesslike,'' and said yazov invited him to moscow to continue their discussions at a later date
at a separate news conference, yazov termed the discussions, the first ever business session between u.s. and soviet defense chiefs, as ``quite candid and very useful.''
carlucci said that ``of course, there were a number of areas of disagreement.'' yazov said the kremlin ``does not harbor any illusions'' about a breakthrough in superpower relations
the two sides announced agreement that the chairman of the u.s. joint chiefs of staff, adm. william crowe, and the soviet chief of staff, marshal sergei akhromeyev, will meet soon to work out guidelines to prevent friction between u.s. and soviet forces
carlucci said he had not obtained the apology he sought for the fatal shooting by a soviet soldier of u.s. army maj. arthur nicholson in east germany three years ago
yazov said the incident occurred before he became defense minister last may and was being handled by the foreign ministry, according to carlucci
the two sides also discussed the u.s. proposed space-based defense plan and regional conflicts, including angola, cambodia and korea, carlucci said
yazov said in a statement that both sides agreed to hold further talks on each other's military doctrine and to consider an exchange of data
