two israeli civilians were detained for allegedly stockpiling an arsenal of weapons intended for anti-arab attacks, police said
israeli military authorities detained a prominent attorney from gaza and four arab journalists, prompting an outcry from israeli liberals. authorities also ordered foreign journalists out of the gaza strip and many areas of the west bank
one of the fiercest recent spells in the iran-iraq war was reported friday: 37 missiles fired into cities, four ships attacked, seven warplanes shot down and thousands of soldiers killed or wounded
iran said its forces had captured two towns in a 5-day-old drive into northeastern iraq, in which it claims 9,200 iraqis have been killed or wounded and 4,000 taken prisoner, and recaptured nowsud, an iranian border town. nowsud was overrun by iraqi soldiers soon after the war began in september 1980
dispatches from the official islamic republic news agency claimed five iraqi jets were destroyed in 24 hours, including three french-built f-1 mirage fighter-bombers out to raid iranian tankers friday in the northern persian gulf. iraq claimed two iranian jets downed
leftist guerrillas on friday burned buses, taxis and other vehicles that defied their nationwide ban on transport, and they threatened more sabotage to disrupt weekend elections
the farabundo marti national liberation front, an alliance of five guerrilla groups, claimed its fighters attacked three soldiers guarding a gas station outside this capital
the armed forces press office said it could not confirm or deny the report, made on the guerrilla radio station. the radio said three soldiers were killed or wounded, but it didn't give details
peter simsa is the very model of a modern east bloc businessman
he has his own company, a carpeted office where he serves guests brandy in snifters and a telephone in his car
now he has his own lobbying group, the first of its kind in the east bloc, the national association of hungarian entrepreneurs
the organization, of which simsa is president, is dedicated to promoting small businesses in hungary and representing their interests to the government
under the leadership of communist party chief janos kadar, hungary in the early 1960s adopted economic policies that encouraged some private ownership and enterprise
the so-called ``goulash communism'' gave hungary one of the highest standards of living in the soviet-led east bloc, although mounting foreign debt and big money-losing state enterprises recently have bleakened economic prospects
hungarians were allowed to take second or third jobs, such as providing services or operating small private shops
in the late 1970s, the government began to allow private partnerships and ``small cooperatives'' operating as small private companies
what distinguishes them from state cooperatives is that they spring from private initiative and are established with private capital
simsa's vertikum enterprise was the first such small cooperative to come into being in 1979. today, he said, hungary has 40,000 private businesses, which account for more than 15 percent of the gross national product
some 60,000 of the 10.6 million hungarians are engaged in private business as their main job, and 540,000 others work part time in the private sector
originally, a department specializing in private entrepreneurs was set up in the hungarian chamber of commerce, a governmental agency
but increasing private enterprise and a desire for greater independence led simsa to seek permission for a separate association
our two basic criteria were that ... it should be a nationwide union and ... that it should fulfil the aim of representing our interests,'' he said
the government agreed last year to recognize the association, with the proviso that it be supervised by the chamber of commerce
simsa stressed that the relationship with the chamber ``does not mean a subordination.''
on feb. 20, the association held its first general congress and in less than a week signed up 1,500 members, half its pre-congress goal of 3,000 members this year
it was really difficult to foresee how many people had any sense of community or entrepreneurial identity,'' simsa said
the association has attracted interest from other east bloc countries. izvestia, the soviet government newspaper, and radio prague in czechoslavkia asked for interviews. simsa also had talks with the u.s. chambers of commerce
the chief problem is the economic regulation,'' said simsa. ``regulators do not take into consideration the specific characteristics of our group. while officially they say that they would like to inspire people, to give incentives (but) in reality they are very rigid.''
an example, he said, is the rule that one person can make and sell bread, but a group of people cannot do the same thing
there are plans to change this,'' he added. in addition to fighting regulations, the association will strive to make private business accepted as partners with the government, he said
now, he complained, private enterprises often are at the bottom of the list when it comes to allocating scarce resources
private companies are permitted only 30 employees, and the average size is eight people, simsa said
for a small cooperative, the law mandates 15 to 100 cooperative members, who in turn can hire as many workers as they want. a typical work force is 100 to 200
simsa said when it allowed more business, the original aim of the government was to improve the availability of small service, such as small shoemakers and shopkeepers
however, in reality these private entrepreneurs don't go into this direction where the government wants them to but where there is money,'' he said. ``the best market for them is the state companies and cooperatives.''
so entrepreneurs perform specialized services for the big state factories or provide raw or intermediate materials
simsa's vertikum, for instance, maintains cooling systems and strengthens concrete cooling towers and grain elevators. he started the business with nine workers and $21. today there are 115 co-op members and employees, and the business has $543,000 in property
other entrepreneurs have opened marriage mediation bureaus or factories to make medical protheses
last year, hungary's biggest small cooperative had revenues of $32 million. in 1988, it might exceed $43 million
back in 1985, when stocks were still hot stuff and destined to become hotter, such things as brokerage fees, foreign cars, audio-visual equipment and recreation were among the fast-growing consumer expenditures
it was a year of big hopes, and the stock market was viewed as the way to fulfill those hopes. brokerage fees in that year rose 54 percent, for example, making that category the biggest year-to-year gainer
the economy was full of big notions, many of them generated by the big-spending group of ``baby boomers'' _ those born by the bundles in the 1950s and now in their 30s and sometimes called yuppies. they were a driving force
the spending continued in 1986, when the biggest year-to-year percentage gainer among consumer expenditures was the 97 percent for boats, followed at 50.7 percent by recreational vehicles
those were also years of very low savings rate and strong credit use. in fact, one might safely say that people were too busy spending to bother very much about savings
but something happened early in 1987, and in retrospect it might have given a hint of the crash to come in october. judging from expenditures, hopes weren't as high. mundane, practical items moved to the fore
at 11.5 percent, the big gainer was books and maps, followed by funeral and burial expenses, floor coverings, hand tools and automotive repairs
to edward yardeni, economics director at prudential-bache securities, the figures reveal more _ the ``aging'' of the baby boomers as they move as a demographic wave through the economy
based on their advancing years, he makes a startling forecast: ``we predict that over the next five years the personal savings rate will rise to 10 percent.''
a double-digit savings rate? it has never happened in the united states for any prolonged period of time, barring the world war ii years when there wasn't very much to buy, and lots of money to put away for the bright days to follow
yardeni has a point, though. those low savings and high spending rates of the mid-1980s reflected the economic activities of an age category that traditionally is inclined to big expenditures
now, he observes, the yuppies are turning into couch potatoes. they _ at least some of them _ have made their trips and spent their money and obtained their material possessions, and now they want to rest
instead of running around and looking for things to buy, they are relaxing. they don't go out to eat as often as before, but are home enjoying the products of their own ovens. in a material sense, they've ``got theirs.''
as a direct consequence, yardeni believes, the days of low savings rates is over, at least for a while. last year the savings rate of 3.8 percent was the lowest since 1947, compared with an 8 percent rate in the 1970s
the economic implications are fascinating, including among other things the probability that a lot of folks will start paying off their big bills and that plenty of money will be available for business investment
but if people become such economic dullards as a 10 percent savings rate would suggest, won't the economy almost cease growing?
not so, says economist yardeni
he points out that ``a rising savings rate doesn't imply a reduction in consumption, just a slower growth rate.'' as he sees it, the economy will continue to expand, and the implication is that the growth will be healthier
polly bergen says her two most recent roles, as rhoda in ``war and remembrance'' and as vivian in the abc movie ``addicted to his love,'' represent the extremes of her personality
she reprises her role as rhoda in abc's 30-hour miniseries ``war and remembrance,'' the sequel to ``the winds of war.'' it will be broadcast next season on abc
addicted to his love,'' a movie in which a group of women swindled by a romantic con artist seek revenge, will appear on abc next monday
i loved playing rhoda,'' bergen said. ``i loved her in all her weaknesses and shallowness. i understood her and cared about her
that's why i like vivian so much. she's so strong. she sets up the scam to take care of the jerk who ripped them off. the funny thing is that vivian and rhoda are the two extremes of me. people see me as having all the strength of vivian, but i'm really as frightened as rhoda. but i guess i'm closer to vivian.''
when bergen signed for the movie it was called ``sisterhood.'' at one time it was called ``sweet vengeance.'' she had a few choice, but unprintable, words about the new title
it was a good part but only a moderate script when i signed,'' she said. ``the day i arrived to begin work the script had been drastically improved. as we went along there was more rewriting and it got better and better. that's why i think we got such good people.''
the movie also stars barry bostwick as the con artist, erin gray, linda purl and dee wallace stone as his other victims and colleen camp as a woman who helps them in their plot. arthur allan seidelman directed from a screenplay by ronni simon and richard alfieri
it's not a comedy, but there's a lot of comedy in it,'' said bergen. ``my biggest scene is very moving, heartbreaking, but the rest of my appearances are fun. it becomes a game to get him
i'm the oldest and wealthiest of the women. i play a widow who's lonely and vulnerable, and she fell for this very slick man. when it's over it very nearly destroys my belief in myself as a woman. so i have an enormous anger and have to make a decision. i have to expose myself and my pride to get this done.''
in ``war and remembrance,'' she returned to her role as the wife of pug henry (robert mitchum), the naval officer who observes much of the war effort in the books by herman wouk. rhoda has an affair with the scientist played by peter graves
i had total sympathy for her,'' bergen said. ``she had built her life around her husband. all she ever wanted was a little appreciation and affection. when she no longer got it from him, she turned elsewhere. she was shallow, but she had always been there for her husband and family.''
after four years with the role, playing it, rehearsing it, learning lines, and preparing for it, she was very sad to finally take her leave of rhoda
the last day was very traumatic,'' she said. ``it was like walking away from a part of myself. i had grown very close to her.''
bergen said she is currently considering two theatrical movie scripts and two scripts for tv comedies
the trouble is 90 percent of the scripts for the new season have characters whose oldest age is 22,'' said. ``i'm not 22. i've run companies for more than 20 years. i'm a bright woman. i look at tv's highest-rated shows. they're not about kids. i know the demographics of the country. i don't understand why all the scripts are for kids. it's beyond my comprehension.''
bergen, who is married to business entrepreneur jeffrey endervelt, has three grown children and lives in new york. besides her film and tv work, she also runs companies that manufacture shoes, handbags and belts
elsewhere in television:
anthony the greek _ anthony quinn, who has starred in ``zorba the greek'' and ``the greek tycoon,'' makes a guest appearance as socrates onassis, father of aristotle onassis, in the abc miniseries ``onassis: the richest man in the world.'' quinn's son, lorenzo quinn, plays alexander onassis, aristotle onassis' son who was killed in a plane crash. raul julia stars as aristotle and jane seymour plays opera star maria callas. in ``the greek tycoon,'' quinn played the onassis-like character who married the widow of a u.s. president. ..
russkie business _ harry anderson becomes involved with a beautiful soviet diplomat on nbc's ``night court'' as he tries to help a russian friend, played by comedian yakov smirnoff. johnny carson also makes a cameo appearance as himself. ^eds: note contents, especially 3rd graf, which may offend readers</head>
an alleged racial attack on a black teen-ager in new york's hudson valley has made headlines for months. now, authorities in a rural new jersey town are working to solve a crime with some chilling similarities
hildegard smith doesn't remember the 30-odd years she spent raising her family in this rural county seat. friends say the 50-year-old mother of five knows that the people gathered at her bedside are her children, but only because they've told her so
she believes richard smith when he tells her he is her husband, but cannot conjure memories of their years together or the plans they made to retire soon to florida
yet when she shuts her eyes, those close to her say, mrs. smith sees as vividly as if it were just happening the faces of two white men who accosted her in her apartment building stairwell, chopped off her hair, smeared her with excrement, painted markings on her face and told her, ``we don't want niggers in this town.''
suffering from amnesia since the morning attack feb. 8, mrs. smith is in seclusion, being guarded by her family and supported by a growing coalition of clergy members, citizens and community leaders
meanwhile, the town's tiny detective squad is working overtime trying to find the assailants
the rev. william j. sadler, interim pastor of the first presbyterian church and a leader of the coalition, likened the community's response to the attack to the way a person reacts to the death of a loved one
they go through all the same phases,'' he said. ``first, they say `did this really happen?' ... then, they get angry.''
and underlying the anger here are feelings of impotence and anxiety
we don't know who they are,'' sadler said of the assailants
so, the question remains: was it an evil passing through this town or has something dark within been revealed?
people have been calling, asking, `are we racist?''' newton administrator camille furgiuele said
newton, nestled among hills 60 miles northwest of new york city, is home to 8,000 people, of whom an estimated 150 are black
we're really a lily white community,'' sadler said
but not a racist community, said sadler, mrs. furgiuele and others
there is prejudice no matter where you go,'' mrs. furgiuele said. ``i can't say that there is no prejudice here. but i don't think it exists in newton anymore than anywhere else.''
sylvester fletcher, a 54-year-old black scientist who urged the formation of the coalition, put it this way:
there are undercurrents of racism in every community. in that regard, newton is not an exceptionally good place. it's a decent place
people here either like you or they let you alone,'' he added
john gibson, 37-year-old co-owner of the county seat restaurant, doubted the attackers were locals
i don't think they could be from around here. i've noticed that people here only usually do harm to themselves ... drinking too much, that sort of thing,'' he said
newton is facing transition. a nearby interstate highway completed just over a decade ago has brought traffic to town and made urban new jersey seem closer
the attack on mrs. smith has made the cities seem closer still
people tell me they're locking their doors,'' mrs. furgiuele said
however, more apparent than any sense of fear, is the feeling of a community protecting its own
although dozens knew of the attack shortly after a neighbor found mrs. smith, the story was kept under wraps. mrs. smith, hospitalized for 12 days immediately after the attack, initially was unable to talk about the incident
by the time police had the full story, days had turned into weeks and community leaders were getting anxious, fletcher said
i am a positive person,'' he said. ``i wanted something positive to happen.''
we had to make a statement that this community would not accept this kind of violence,'' sadler added
richard smith finally agreed to let the new coalition publicize his wife's case. a feb. 26 news conference was called at which mrs. smith's identity was revealed and composite sketches of the assailants were handed out
the sketches appear on 10,000 wanted posters that were distributed last week. a reward of $13,000 was offered for information leading to arrests
the ensuing publicity has been rough on police chief larry romyns. he has one full-time detective and one part time. and shortly after the attack on mrs. smith, there was a murder. a man is accused of slaying his wife because she intended to divorce him
romyns said his detectives have received dozens of leads
others are leery of what the publicity might bring to the community
we do not want anyone to escalate this into a wappingers falls situation,'' sadler said, referring to the new york state hometown of a 16-year-old black girl who says she was sexually assaulted by six white men
when the teen-ager, tawana brawley, was found last november, excrement was smeared on her and ``kkk'' and ``nigger'' were written on her body. some of her hair had been chopped off
officials here say they do not know if the attack on mrs. smith was a ``copycat'' reaction to the brawley case. but they are quick to point out the differences between them
mrs. smith was not sexually assaulted; miss brawley was, she told police. also, people here say this is local affair that will be handled without the help of outsiders
if (the rev.) al sharpton showed up, we wouldn't want him here,'' sadler said, referring to the civil rights activist who has taken up miss brawley's case. sharpton and others have encouraged miss brawley not to cooperate with authorities, claiming that for various reasons they cannot be trusted to handle the case properly
the community is not without outside support. the state chapter of the national assocation for the advancement of colored people has intitiated an investigation of the incident. the state assembly has passed a resolution expressing a ``vehement cry of outrage.'' and the newark-north jersey committee of black churchmen says it will ask gov. thomas h. kean to ``intercede in whatever way he would deem necessary to bring this case to justice,'' according to the group's leader, dr. edward verner
one way the state can help, sadler said, is by allocating money from a fund for victims of violent crimes. the smiths have no health insurance and in addition to paying for mrs. smith's hospital stay, the family faces huge bills for psychiatric treatment she'll need
our hope is that through treatment and time her memory will come back,'' sadler said
although there are few signs of a looming recession, the probability of one remains a subject of intense discussion in certain areas of the country, such as new york
why is this so? asks albert sindlinger, who was testing public opinion as long ago as the great depression _ and as recently as this very day _ and who declares again that recession isn't an immediate threat
sindlinger, whose company conducts scores of telephone interviews each day, says he finds a contradiction between what he reads and hears in the media and what ordinary folks around the country are telling him and his staff
the people he and his staff talk to, he states, are confident about their own economic future. he says their household money supply, a measure of existing conditions, is healthy. and so are their expectations, he says
he points out that these opinions can't be taken lightly because the consumer factor _ the ability and willingness to buy _ is the vital ingredient of our total economy, bigger even that business and government
but, he continues, many of the economic reports he reads include phrases such as ``when the recession begins'' rather than ``if there is a recession.''
he was especially indignant about the profiferation of these references following the oct. 19 stock market crash which, he contends, bore no resemblance to 1929, which he vividly recalls. so, he sought the reason why
sindlinger now says the fault lies with the financial press, which he says is headquartered in new york city, close to the financial community
new york, he says, is a special situation that doesn't reflect the country's mood
ever since black monday, he says, ``we have been watching a strong, steady decline in consumer confidence in one _ and only one _ area: eastern new york state.''
he declares that the economy in much of the country has improved in the past year, and is continuing to do so. he couldn't have said that in late 1986, when his readings showed 31 states in recession. now, he says, there are but four in recession: oklahoma, louisiana, west virginia and mississippi
in short, by his estimates the nation's economy has been growing stronger, but the economy of eastern new york has not. he measures that area at barely above recession level
the weakness there is rooted around the new york city financial community,'' he states. ``large numbers have been laid off, and many others say they are extremely concerned about their lack of job security
these layoffs have spilled into the bmw automobile dealerships, fur salons and fern restaurants. mcdonald's also is feeling the pinch on manhattan island, since lower-paid clerks are being laid off, too.''
he concludes:
so, the financial press, stuck on the same island with the financial houses and their current and former employees can't help but get the idea that something's wrong with the economy
they see these people on the streets, and interview them for their stories. being observant people, they immediately sense that people in the big apple are in trouble.''
he asks: ``do these causal observations affect their interviewing and reporting?'' seldom without an answer or an explanation, the crusty sindlinger responds:
are they human? of course they're affected.''
while conditions could improve around the country, he says, they are a lot better than some new yorkers believe they are
in the chaos and intolerance that is lebanon, rmeileh is an oasis of liberty, a haven for people fleeing political and social persecution and assassination
this coastal town, 19 miles south of beirut, is what lebanon used to be before 13 years of civil war, sectarian hatreds and religious fanatacism turned it into a wilderness
leftists and other refugees from beirut and the south have fled to rmeileh following a campaign of assassinations by shiite moslem fundamentalists against communists, pro-iraqi baath socialists and other leftists
one of the things that makes rmeileh different from just about everywhere else in south lebanon is that alcohol is sold openly at the side of the road
alcohol is banned in most areas of the region, dominated by shiite moslem factions, and in beirut's southern slums, the shiite stronghold in the capital
islamic religious laws also ban mixed parties, mixed bathing and the consumption of pork
but in the summer, rmeileh's eight restaurants and three miles of mediterranean beaches and hillside picnic areas are packed with males and females having a good time. pork also is sold
hamza, 35, comes from the staunchly shiite town of nabatiyeh in the south
we can't buy drinks in nabatiyeh any more, so we come to rmeileh,'' he said. ``in summer women have to come here to swim because it's the one of the very few places they can do that.''
because he lives in a shiite area, where such activities are forbidden, hamza declined to disclose his full name
rmeileh was a mainly christian town, with about 5,000 maronite catholics, until 1985, when moslem forces overran the coastal plain. now only about 60 maronite families are left
but rmeileh now is protected by communist party militiamen, most of them christians, who are allied to neighboring druse and sunni moslem forces who help keep the shiites out
the syrian army also has a checkpoint just south of rmeileh on the awali river which also acts as a deterrent for shiite gunmen
abu rim, a leftist official in the town, said 500 refugee families _ moslems, christians and palestinians _ live in rmeileh with the local christians
our aim is to get rid of the sectarian atmosphere and implement co-existence,'' he said
elias tabet, director of the town's government school, said ethnic mix gives rmeileh a non-sectarian nature, where people from different areas and religions ``feel safe and free.''
samih germanos, 57, a christian who fled beirut's shiite-controlled southern slums, said: ``we're very happy and hope things will stay this way.''
acting mayor halim kleib, said the tourist influx last summer was even better than pre-war times
people in the south prefer rmeileh to other places because it's the closest resort to them that provides restaurants and private beaches as well as drinks,'' kleib added
ali hujeiri, 40, a father of nine, who works at a pepsi cola plant in a nearby town, said he sells alcohol on the street to earn extra money and that most of his customers are from the shiite south
i'm the only one to sell pork in this area,'' said abu elie, a 32-year-old shopowner.``i started bringing it from mount lebanon last week and in four days, i sold around 40 kilograms (88 pounds).''
justice minister nabih berri's amal movement and the iranian-backed hezbollah (party of god) have been blamed for many of the assasinations of leftists in south lebanon
but since many of those who have fled to rmeileh _ ``self-deportees,'' amal calls them _ are skilled or professional people, the amal recently asked them to return to their villages
wafiq rihan, a 33-year-old shiite school teacher, didn't sound as though he is ready to return. he said that after he fled nabatiyeh last year the communists and the leftist druse ``helped us find places to stay and in the beginning we relied on red cross supplies.''
i'm teaching at the school now,'' he added. ``i was originally a teacher. but most of the other deportees here are also working in their particular fields, medicine, the law, and so on
one doctor who fled nabatiyeh even has some of his old patients come here to see him for treatment.''
rihan said he wants to go back to his own village but only when it's safe
blunt criticisms of art censors have come to be expected from china's most famous movie director, wu tianming, even more than the evocative and provocative films produced by his studio
it takes no prompting to set him off
those people (censors) were used to making hypocritical propaganda,'' wu grumbled in a recent interview. ``people who have feudal and ultra-left ideas and bureaucrats ... get in the way of our work.''
even the censors, however, have been unable to stop the cascade of domestic and international honors awarded in the past four years to wu's movies and those of young directors who work under him at the xian film studio in china's ancient capital
since wu became its director in 1983, the debt-ridden studio in arid northwestern china has become a prolific producer of hauntingly beautiful, technically innovative movies that have raised china's standing in the international film community. many in one way or another also have been seen as affronts to socialism
for example, wu's own ``old well,'' about a poor village's efforts to dig a well, won top honors last year at the tokyo international film festival and a special prize at the hawaii international film festival and received critical acclaim in new york
but its release to prudish chinese audiences was delayed for months because of the movie's depiction of a love triangle, including several kissing scenes of unusual passion
the black cannon,'' directed by huang jianxing, one of wu's stable of young directors, aroused heated debate because it attacked mindless bureaucracy. it eventually was named best movie of 1985 by china's ministry of broadcast, film and television
another xian studio release, ``the horse thief,'' directed by tian zhuangzhuang, never was shown to general chinese audiences because of its depiction of poverty among tibetan horsemen
from his brick office compound with peeling paint and leaking pipes, the 48-year-old wu said he wants to expand the limits of what is acceptable in chinese filmmaking, largely restricted since 1949 to socialist morality tales
wu said the studio does not seek to create controversy, but it often results because he and his fellow directors are trying to depict the often harsh realities of life in china
this frightens conservative bureaucrats accustomed to propaganda movies, he said: ``they lived illusions. they cannot accept any movie that reflects the dark side of life.''
it's a side of life wu knows well. he was born in the mountains of shaanxi province, north of xian, where perpetual drought keeps many peasants in poverty. during the 1966-76 far-leftist cultural revolution, he was denounced as a rightist and paraded through xian's streets wearing a signboard proclaiming his political sins
afterward, he said, he went home and ``shut my door and studied'' for the rest of the tumultuous decade, during which china made almost no movies
wu is willing to take risks not only for his own movies but those of other directors at the xian studio _ one reason it has attracted talented young directors and cinematographers
on his movie, ``the black cannon,'' huang said: ``the moment we saw the film for the first time we knew it would be controversial
but we had a common idea,'' he said pointing to wu, ``that this film should reflect life. we felt some pressure when the film was not (immediately) approved. but mr. wu said at one meeting if problems occurred he would be held responsible.''
another attraction is wu's readiness to give young directors free rein
asked if he gives advice to the less experienced, 34-year-old huang, wu laughed and said, ``he does fine on his own. if i were to help him ... i might stifle him
there would be great prosperity in china's literature and arts if all artistic leaders followed my example: to let artists do what they like.''
wu is harsh in his criticism of standard chinese movie fare. ``sixty percent of chinese movies are seriously lacking,'' he said. but he is no kinder to foreign movies
he disliked steven spielberg's ``empire of the sun,'' partly filmed in shanghai, about the japanese invasion of china in world war ii. wu also said he does not seek to copy western movies
he says his studio's movies are the best being made in china now, and was confident his own ``old well'' will sweep the chinese critics' and government awards for best movie of 1987
several upcoming xian movies appear ripe to arouse debate: one is about army chief peng dehuai, purged in 1958 for daring to criticize mao tse-tung; another concerns three youths whose lives are failures despite their efforts to get ahead
maybe some people will think it's too gray,'' huang said of the latter movie, which he is directing, to be called ``floating out of the sea.''
his own output is relatively slim. in addition to co-directing two movies, he has directed just three: ``old well,'' ``life'' (1984) and ``river without a buoy'' (1983). all three have received prizes at home or abroad
the demands of running a studio that employs 1,450 and is perpetually in debt will keep him from starting his next movie before next year, he said
will it be controversial?
yes,'' wu said emphatically, using one of his few english words. ``definitely.''
the people's consultative assembly has closed shop for another five years after an 11-day session marked by unprecedented discord
a public outburst by an army general, a dispute over the vice presidency and previously unheard of votes on policy matters upset the script at what is usually a pre-arranged ceremonial occasion
the assembly is supposed to ``elect'' the president and vice president and approve state policy guidelines. it consists of the 500 members of parliament chosen through a general election last april and another 500 people appointed by president suharto
the constitution describes the assembly as the nation's supreme lawmaking body. in fact, suharto rules the world's fifth most populous country with the support of the armed forces and participatory democracy is limited
five factions in the assembly acclaimed suharto as president for a fifth five-year term. the factions include three political parties, the military and appointees from different regions
state secretary sudharmono was sworn in unopposed as vice president only after jailani naro of the moslem-based united development party withdrew at the last minute
i didn't withdraw. i was pulled out by my party,'' naro told a news conference
earlier in the session, naro's party caused the assembly to depart from tradition by voting for the first time ever to break a deadlock
political custom calls for ``musjawarah,'' or negotiating for as long as it takes to reach consensus. some authorities dislike voting as a practice they associate with western-style democracy
the moslem faction was outvoted 280-28 in committee on its request to add a clause to election rules stating that ``general elections should be held in a fair and honest manner.'' opponents maintained this was already embodied in the regulations
the moslem group lost by equally lopsided margins on proposals to reject javanese mysticism as part of religion and subsidize islamic boarding schools
the vice presidency is a largely ceremonial position. but with the 66-year-old suharto starting what is assumed will be his last term, his running mate would be well-placed to stake a claim as heir to the presidency
stepping out as vice president is umar wirahadikusumah, 64, a retired general and suharto's former comrade-in-arms. umar kept a low profile during his one term and was never regarded as having presidential ambitions
constitutional procedures for succession exist, but do not take into account the widespread mystical belief that the national leader must be blessed with a divine ``mandate'' before one has a right to rule
about 90 percent of indonesia's 170 million people are considered at least nominally moslem. but ``dukuns,'' or soothsayers, have a wide following and suharto rules with the help of javanese spiritual advisers, informed sources say
suharto and the late president sukarno are the only presidents indonesia has had since independence from the dutch after world war ii. economic chaos, an attempted coup and bloodshed in the last months of sukarno's rule were supposed to be signs that he had lost the divine mandate. sukarno died in 1970
sudharmono, who is 61, the is leader of golkar, the government political party. as minister in charge of the state secretariat since 1966, he has been boss of the country's 2.6 million civil servants
once known as ``suharto's doorman'' because he wielded power for years by controlling access to the president, sudharmono is a retired army general. his background is in military law not field command, however, and not all in the officer corps welcomed his nomination by golkar
military sources who insisted on anonymity said some generals supported instead the newly appointed armed forces commander, gen. try sutrisno, 52, a popular figure and a former suharto aide
one military figure, gen. ibrahim saleh, startled the assembly session when he took the microphone and said: ``we indonesian soldiers who believe in god and defend honesty and justice have heard rumors that the nomination of the vice president is not being fairly and correctly carried out.''
there are certain things that we feel are against our conscience,'' he added but then was escorted out by other generals of the military faction before he could finish his statement
former armed forces commander gen. l.b. murdani told reporters later that saleh did not reflect the views of the armed forces
the national park service has proposed landmark status for the farm of whittaker chambers, whose allegations about infiltration of the american government fueled the fires of the red scare and whose writings deeply influenced president reagan and other conservatives
forty years ago, in a strange and symbolic incident, chambers, then a time magazine editor, opened a hollowed-out pumpkin on pipe creek farm and retrieved microfilmed documents that connected alger hiss, a longtime state department official, to communist activities a decade earlier
chambers, who had renounced his communist past, accused hiss of having belonged to a secret cell of underground communists that passed documents to the soviets in the 1930s. chambers claimed they had been close associates at one time
hiss sued chambers for libel, but the tables turned as the ``pumpkin papers'' sealed hiss' fate before the house un-american activities committee. criminal indictments followed and after two trials, hiss was sent to prison on march 22, 1951. his libel suit was dismissed in 1951
although he served 44 months in prison after being convicted of perjuring himself before the committee by denying under oath that he ferried the documents to chambers in 1938, he has maintained his innocence
reached at his new york home last week, the 83-year-old hiss said he had no comment on the effort to honor chambers with a landmark
he added: ``i will have something to say about him in the latter part of may,'' when he publishes what he termed a semi-autobiographical book
after turning in his former associates, chambers, who had slept for years with a gun fearing retribution, retreated with his family to the farm's 390 rolling acres, where he tended to the land and wrote about his experiences until his death in 1961
one of the conservatives most influenced by chambers' 1952 autobiographical volume ``witness'' was a young californian. ronald reagan's own book ``where's the rest of me?'' includes references to chambers
he talks about the deep impact that whittaker chambers had on him. he said reading `witness' was one of the most profoundly moving experiences of his life,'' according to white house chief speechwriter tony dolan
dolan said reagan was so stirred by the story of a communist who came to see the evils of totalitarian regimes that he bestowed a posthumous medal of freedom on chambers in 1984
reagan and dolan discussed the president's interest in chambers; a subsequent exchange between dolan and secretary of the interior donald hodel led to the site nomination
hodel is a very devoted conservative, very devoted to the president,'' dolan said
the landmark designation for the chambers farm depends on approval from the national park system advisory board, which is scheduled to meet on april 26, and then from hodel. it would provide the property with a plaque and place it in a league with more than 1,800 other sites, from ships to presidential homes, with national historical value
historians point out that the hiss-chambers case polarized the political world, fueled the paranoia of the cold war, and rocketed then-congressman richard m. nixon to prominence as one of hiss' top interrogators
according to park service historian barry mackintosh, nixon made at least two unpublicized visits to the chambers farm ``and became convinced that chambers was telling the truth about his association with hiss.'' years later, nixon would return to westminster to speak with chambers about his desire to be president, but chambers wrote supporter and national review founder william f. buckley jr. that he found nixon inadequate for the job
asked why the reagan administration chose to honor his father with a landmark nomination, john chambers, a former journalist now serving as deputy staff director of the joint committee on printing in washington, said whittaker chambers ``left behind a literary legacy and a legacy of action, a legacy of conscience, and this is the place where some of this was formulated, and one of the places where it came be focused
it's an honor that we welcome,'' said chambers, who has lived at pipe creek farm off and on since the age of 2
maintaining it as a working farm is, he said, his way of paying tribute to his father's conversion to a simple life of manual labor, expressed in the volume ``cold friday.''
here i determined to root the lives of my children. ... i meant to root them in this way in their nation. for i hold that a nation is first of all the soil on which it lives, for which it is willing to die,'' whittaker chambers wrote
this was all there was to give _ the ground beneath their feet. i meant to give it to them not only against the forces of open revolution but also against that suffocating materialism, which, more than want or hunger, recruits the forces of revolution in the west.''
according to dolan, ``chambers felt there was a death struggle going on in the world between freedom and totalitarianism. and as a matter of fact, he felt (the west) would probably lose that struggle
what he didn't count on was ronald reagan. ... he could not the future
in light of the delaware ruling, henley said it has moved to dismiss a suit challenging santa fe's restructuring and other actions by santa fe's board
earlier this week, henley announced its own restructuring, which would include raising $2.5 billion in new bank financing to fund acquisitions. at the time, henley chairman michael dingman indicated the company was ``on the prowl'' for new takeover prospects
separately, olympia &amp; york announced it has again extended by six days, until next wednesday, the expiration date of its tender offer of $17.50 a share for up to 14 million santa fe shares, which would boost its stake to 19.6 percent. to date, 4.77 million shares have been tender, the company said
the southwest african nation of angola has known only war since independence from portugal in 1975. a marxist government is in place in luanda, the capital, backed by the soviet union and cuba. in the countryside is a u.s.-backed guerrilla force called unita. in between are people often suffering the bullets, mines and bombs of war. an associated press correspondent had a rare look at the war recently during a tour of an angolan war zone
land mines, people with legs blown off, orphans, abandoned farm fields, hunger, the thunder of artillery in the distance, the clatter of helicopter gunships overhead. all this is part of daily life for the people of bie, a highland province in central angola shattered by a dozen years of guerrilla war
for a group of foreign reporters visiting this former farming town and the provincial capital of kuito saw clear evidence of the heavy fighting between government forces and rebel guerrillas
the war has left its mark on everyone, everything
cuemba, set on a rise in undulating grassy countryside, is ringed by trenches and machine-gun emplacements visible from the air, the least hazardous way to reach the town
approaching cuemba from kuito in a casa cn-235 troop transport, a short-takeoff and landing aircraft, the visitors accompanied by government guides saw roads and railways empty of all traffic
the fading outlines of abandoned farmlands farther out from cuemba were also visible from the air, contrasting with orderly rows of lush growth, mainly corn, seen outside kuito, 87 miles to the west, where the fighting of recent months has not been so intense
it is much the same in other parts of angola where the national union for the total independence of angola (unita), supported by the united states and south africa, is fighting a soviet-cuban-backed marxist government in luanda, the capital
an estimated 40,000 cuban troops are in angola, along with more than 1,000 soviet military advisers. the united states sends arms to the rebels and south africa lends air and ground-troop support
unita claims to have full control of about a third of angola _ in the southeast and east, where about 2 million of angola's 8.1 million people live. in the area it calls ``liberated angola,'' unita has established a government and runs schools and hospitals. the guerrillas say they operate in another third of the country while the government maintains full control of the rest
flying is perhaps the only safe way to travel in many parts of the country. thousands of villagers have lost one or both legs to unita land mines, the government says. hundreds of others have been killed, leaving children orphaned and making physical disability a common condition
the international committee of the red cross, which operates several physical rehabilitation centers in the region, last year estimated 15,000 angolan army soldiers and 15,000 civilians have lost limbs in land mine explosions
on the airport road in kuito, the visitors saw three women who had lost legs moving along on crutches or with canes. in the city there were more
there were children too, in tattered, filthy clothes _ some too small, some too large, clearly the only clothing they owned
in cuemba, where unita has been fighting for control of the region since jan. 25, children and older villagers show signs of malnutrition
bullet holes snake across the walls of many houses. the tracks of the strategic benguela railroad, which links landlocked southern african countries to the atlantic ocean, are rusty and caked with thick, dried mud. it was obvious no trains have been through for a long time
hairdressers, cafes, clothing and photography stores, printing presses and transport companies lie abandoned. their windows are broken and paint from before angola gained independence from portugal in 1975 is peeling from the frames. the municipal swimming pools in cuemba and kuito are long out of use
government forces killed 180 unita guerrillas in a recent three-day battle around cuemba, the defense ministry says. the rebels had not shelled the airport's packed-earth runway or taken control of the town as they had claimed
government forces clearly were in control on this day
the first foreign reporters to visit the region since unita launched a major offensive to seize cuemba and munhango, 40 miles to the east, were met by the fit and well-equipped angolan army unit stationed in the town
the commander, maj. jose walter freitas gomes, displayed weapons, including anti-tank missiles, mines and mortars that he said were made in the united states and captured from the rebels
no markings, however, could be seen on the weapons to indicate where they were made
at the end of their 50-minute visit to the town, the reporters were seen off by a small crowd, most of them children, and there was a momentary disturbance
a drum sounded somewhere in the distance and the children suddenly streaked off in fear, mistakenly believing the noise was artillery fire. their lives are full of those sounds
leaving cuemba, the casa cn-235 lifted into the air long before reaching the end of the runway, climbing almost vertically in a spiral, to gain altitude fast and to get away from any unita snipers or artillery
for the same reason, landing had been a reverse of this maneuver, dropping 21,000 feet to cuemba's airport in four minutes. the angolans call this corkscrew drop ``the spiral of death.''
in october, the international red cross suspended operations in bie after its sole cargo plane in angola, a hercules c-130, crashed after takeoff from kuito airport following what appeared to be an engine fire
four people aboard the plane were killed, along with a woman and child on the ground. the red cross began operating in the area again in late february, flying in food and medicine
the red cross resumed the services after rebel leaders at unita's jamba bush headquarters in southern angola said they would permit relief operations
angola's minister of state for inspection and control, kundi payama, said in kuito that unita has supporters and guerrillas among the population of bie. he noted that jonas savimbi, unita's leader, was born in the province
there are people working their family plots in this area who put down their hoes at night, dig up their hidden guns and become unita raiders, planting mines and laying ambushes,'' payama said
these things happen if you can't feed the people and they can't get decent housing, or find a job or work most of the fields
we've got lots of food at the (atlantic) port of lobito, but getting it here is the problem,'' he said. lobito is the starting point of the benguela railroad but rebel attacks have made it impossible for trains to travel as far as cuemba
every time we try to bring a food convoy here by road, it gets attacked and burned,'' payama added. he said the people understood, however, that the government was trying to get food through
cuban soldiers were seen getting off a plane at kuito airport and others were in evidence in huambo, capital of the neighboring province of the same name
soviet-built mig-21 jetfighters, mi-25 helicopter gunships and mi-17 transport helicopters at the airports of both cities were indications of the government's concern about the guerrilla campaign in the area
instead, they expect it will be, at most, part of a growing armamentarium against aids. the fda said there are now more than 100 drugs being tested against aids or against the opportunistic diseases that attack bodies weakened by aids
broder at nci is conducting tests that team azt with other drugs, principally one called ddc, for dideoxycytidine. he is conducting tests in which the drugs are alternated
i believe we eventually be using a combination of several drugs,'' said dr. glen mathisen, chief of infectious diseases at olive view medical center in los angeles
mathisen and others note that drug combinations have been used successfully against major killers such as leukemia and tuberculosis. most cancer chemotherapy includes a combination skillfully administered in cycles
azt's full range of uses are still being explored because the drug now is limited only to patients at a late stage of aids or of aids-related complex, or arc
barry said studies are under way using azt to protect medical workers who have been exposed to the blood or other body fluids of aids patients during treatment. there have been more than 1,000 such reported incidents and its hoped that azt given within hours of the exposure will prevent development of aids
other studies are exploring the use of azt for infants born with the disease, or for people who test positive for the hiv virus, but who do not have the aids sympthoms
but no matter what else is learned about azt, the important thing is that the drug has bought time, said broder
it's not the magic bullet,'' he said. ``but it's keeping people alive. we can now worry about things like longterm toxicity of the drug. before azt, they didn't live long enough for that to be a concern.''
before i. king jordan jr. lost his hearing, he knew nothing about gallaudet university. like many district of columbia residents, he drove by it frequently without so much as a curious thought
now, jordan has taken over the 124-year-old liberal arts university for the hearing impaired. as its first deaf president, he has become an important symbol to the non-hearing, even those who have nothing to do with gallaudet
it's overwhelming,'' jordan said. ``i came here after i accepted the appointment; the students were crying, hugging me. the emotion is still very high. it's a wonderful feeling.''
when i go off campus, i ride in the gallaudet university station wagon and people blow their horns and wave at me. i can see people recognize me
during the last week, the campus has been empty while its 2,200 students, who pushed jordan into power, took spring break
on monday, they'll return, and jordan will hold a celebration assembly to reinforce what has become his motto: ``deaf people can do anything except hear.''
jordan rose to the presidency march 13 on a wave of student protest that followed the decision by gallaudet's trustees to appoint a hearing woman, elisabeth zinser, as president
the outcry led to zinser's resignation and the hiring of jordan, who had been among two deaf people also considered for the job
what you saw was something really unique,'' jordan said of the seven days of protest
it was not dissatisfaction with the university administration at all. what you saw was the deaf community, the entire national and international deaf community finally reach a point where they knew it was time to speak out about their frustrations at not being in the top leadership positions in the field
the conditions were just perfect. the leadership in the student body was tremendous
i can't tell you how proud i am of the students, how well organized they were. how they guaranteed that there would be no violence, no damage and they carried that out. there was never anyone hurt or any damage done.''
virtually all the students were in on the demonstrations. they marched, they rallied, they blocked entrances to the campus and they convinced older deaf people that the time was now to take charge
jordan originally threw his support behind zinser, saying he had hoped to persuade the students to compromise for the good of the university
overnight, literally overnight, it became clear to me that it was getting bigger and bigger by the minute and that i had misread it, that i had made a mistake,'' he said
i don't think anyone realized the support there was on the outside. i've never seen a movement that was universal support before
when the group marched from here to the capitol, people came out of their houses and applauded. people who were tied up in traffic, instead of blowing their horns impatiently and wanting the march to be over, blew their horns in support, got out of their cars and waved
people lining the way between here and the capitol were signing `i love you.' it was probably a once-in-a-lifetime movement.''
jordan's deafness has not impaired his speech, but he uses a sign language interpreter to understand hearing people. though he can read lips, he says a lengthy conversation is exhausting without the help of signing
he lost his hearing in 1965 when he was 21 and stationed in washington with the navy. a motorcycle accident caused multiple skull fractures, severed his auditory nerve and put him in the hospital for a year
when he recovered, someone suggested he enroll at gallaudet. until then, he knew nothing about the school
before i became deaf, i drove by here regularly, a few times a week, and i had no idea what it was,'' he said
though his family was very supportive, deafness had never been a part of their lives. growing up in glen riddle, pa., jordan never even knew a deaf person
his father was a shipping clerk, his mother an office clerk, and his life with two older sisters and one younger brother had been typical small town america
when i first came to gallaudet i was going through a period of adjustment to deafness. one of the things that was easy for me to do was to lose myself in my studies. i found that i was very good at it. while i couldn't hear, i could read and i'd write, and became a very strong student. i made a conscious decision to become as good a student as i could.''
after getting his bachelor's degree in psychology, jordan went on to receive a masters' degree and phd from the university of tennessee. there were no interpreters to translate lectures, so jordan read the professors' lips and got help from his hearing classmates
along the way he married ``a hearing, but very supportive woman'' and now has a 17-year-old son and 15-year-old daughter
he returned to gallaudet in 1973 as a professor of psychology and became dean of the college of arts and sciences in 1986
as it's president, he said he will encourage deaf people to seek teaching positions at gallaudet, but he will not put any quotas on the number of deaf people who should hold either staff or administrative positions
about 30 percent of the professors are deaf. fewer administrators are
academica is becoming a better career program for deaf people, jordan said. in the past the only opportunity for deaf people would have been gallaudet
he said he knows of deaf people in other schools using interpreters to teach hearing students
i really believe that the events of last week show that even when someone needs an interpeter, still there can be clear, meaningful communication,'' he said
the u.s. merchandise trade deficit widened to $12.44 billion in january, but economists say the 1.9 percent increase reported by the government was too small to cause alarm
exports fell by 10 percent to $22.33 billion and imports by 6 percent to $34.77 billion, the commerce department said thursday
analysts said the export drop was expected and happens every january. but the decline in imports was greeted as good news and a further indication that the trade balance is slowly improving
u.s. factories, mines and utilities operated at 82.4 percent of capacity in february, the third consecutive month the operating rate has been at that level, the federal reserve reports
even though the february rate was the same as december and january, those two months were revised up slightly in the newest report published thursday, a change that private economists said was encouraging
before the revision, the operating rate in december and january was reported as 82.2 percent
the federal government moved to calm depositors' fears and protect the nation's banking system by advancing $1 billion to banks owned by an ailing texas bank holding company
the federal deposit insurance corp. said thursday it was lending the money for six months to subsidiaries of first republicbank corp. as an interim step toward restoring the dallas-based company's health
the $1 billion lifeline thrown to first republicbank worked quickly to calm fears of depositors, who in recent days of drained funds from the institution, analysts and bank officials said
firestone tire &amp; rubber co. has agreed to be acquired by japan's bridgestone corp. in an $80 a share all-cash buyout totaling nearly $2.6 billion
firestone also said late thursday that its board recommended shareholders reject the rival, unsolicited $58 a share buyout offer from italian tiremaker pirelli spa that had spurred the bridgestone proposal
in connection with the merger agreement, firestone stated it had granted bridgestone the option effective through the end of this year to buy an 18 percent stake in the company
american standard inc. has accepted a nearly $2.5 billion cash tender offer from an investment banking firm specializing in employee-led leveraged buyouts, spurning black &amp; decker corp.'s hostile advances
industry analysts said thursday that the $78-a-share tender offer from kelso &amp; co. represented a market premium and that the bidding war was unlikely to continue
the offer topped a cash bid of $73 a share, or $2.1 billion, from black &amp; decker, a tool and appliance maker that had tried to gain control of american standard for nearly two months
individuals and businesses voluntarily paid only 83.2 percent of the federal income taxes they owed last year, leaving the government with a tax gap of $84.9 billion, the internal revenue service said
more than half the shortage reported thursday was attributed to individuals who file tax returns but fail to report income from moonlighting, a small business or other legal non-wage sources
irs commissioner lawrence b. gibbs said closing the gap may require a basic change of attitude among taxpayers
r.h. macy &amp; co. inc.'s bid for federated department stores inc. suffered a setback when the securities and exchange commission said it considered a sweetened rival offer by campeau corp. to be an amendment to a previous offer rather than an entirely new bid
a federal judge had sought the sec's opinion on macy's contention that the campeau move constituted a new offer. the sec offered its opinion on thursday
if u.s. district judge leonard sand agrees with the sec, the campeau bid could expire as scheduled before the april 4 expiration of macy's competing offer. the earlier deadline could pressure federated shareholders into tendering their shares to campeau
japan overtook the united states last year in economic output per person, according to a report that highlighted that nation's relentless rise as an economic superpower
the report released thursday by japan's economic planning agency was the latest in a string of reports on that nation's growing wealth
the agency said per-capita gross national product for japan reached the equivalent of $19,642 in 1987, compared with $18,403 in the united states
the canadian dollar, buoyed by higher interest rates north of the border, rose to 80 u.s. cents for the first time in four years
analysts said thursday the possibility that central american instability might drive prices higher for oil and other commodities was one reason for the canadian currency's overnight rise from 79.9 u.s. cents to 80.08 cents
the currency closed at 80.04 u.s. cents in new york foreign-exchange trading
the nation's farm sector is continuing a strong recovery that began in 1987 with record-high net cash income, the agriculture department says
cash income still is expected to decline from last year's $57 billion to between $50 billion and $55 billion in 1988, the department's economic research service said in a new outlook report published thursday
the projected decline will result from lower livestock receipts, rising expenses and lower government payments, the report said. those will more than offset a rise in 1988 crop receipts
sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, has warned cable television operators that congress will consider reregulating the industry if rates continue to rise and programming is withheld from competitors
some of us feel we were had'' by the congressional decision that freed most cable operators of municipal rate control in january 1987 and let them set their own prices, metzenbaum said thursday
metzenbaum said congress is concerned that operators of cable tv, an $11 billion-a-year industry serving 51 percent of u.s. households, enjoy a monopoly that can freeze out competing tv distribution systems and raise prices
stocks surged higher thursday in a rally driven by a better-than-expected trade deficit report and takeover speculation. the dow jones industrial average rose 21.72 points to 2,086.04, its second post-crash peak this month
the dollar rose against most major currencies except the canadian dollar. gold prices fell
bond prices rose on the u.s. trade deficit for january
grain and soybean futures prices posted strong gains, while oil futures prices rose sharply
a better-than-expected january trade deficit helped drive the dow jones average of 30 industrials to a post-crash high, while a report showing sustained factory usage underscored signs of economic strength
the dow jones average of 30 industrials jumped 21.72 points in a late buying spree thursday to close at 2,086.04, the market barometer's best showing since october's stock market crash. analysts credited the better-than-expected trade deficit and takeover-related buying for the strong performance
separately, the federal reserve reported the nation's factories, mines and utilities operated at 82.4 percent of capacity in february, sustaining that rate for the third consecutive month
the commerce department reported a slight widening of the u.s. merchandise trade deficit to $12.44 billion, but economists said the 1.9 percent increase was too small to cause alarm
exports fell in a seasonally-expected trend, this time by 10 percent to $22.33 billion
but economists were more enthusiastic over a 6 percent dip in imports, to $34.77 billion, which they say is a firmer indication the trade balance slowly is improving
january's deficit was up from $12.20 billion in december, but down from the gaps of $13.21 billion in november and $17.63 billion in october
if the january level continued for 12 consecutive months, it would yield an annual trade deficit of about $149 billion. in 1987, the merchandise trade deficit was $171.22 billion
the january report represented a slight setback after two consecutive monthly improvements, but there were some bright spots
the deficit with japan _ still the largest single-country imbalance _ fell by 17.6 percent in january to $3.95 billion, its lowest level since december 1986
the united states showed its first surplus in nearly three years with britain, with exports topping imports by $75 million. for all western europe, the deficit declined 51 percent, to $1.33 billion
the trade news helped support the dollar and pushed interest rates lower in the credit markets, where the yield on the treasury's bellwether 30-year issue fell to 8.53 percent from wednesday's 8.60 percent
the federal reserve's report showing sustained high factory use helped underscore economists' contentions that the industrial sector remained strong
before the year began, some experts had expressed fears that the economy could weaken significantly due to widespread cutbacks in production as businesses tried to work off a huge supply of unsold goods built up in late 1987
while high inventories have led to cuts in auto production, many other industries, such as textiles, chemicals, and paper, have continued to have high operating rates
u.s. and european trade officials are holding a new round of talks in the lengthy dispute over government subsidies to the airbus aircraft manufacturing consortium
but both sides remain far apart on the long-simmering issue of subsidies to airbus, which the united states contends are unfair, and u.s. trade envoys are not optimistic about the outcome of the meeting
the expectations are very low,'' an official close to the negotiations said thursday
the u.s. delegation, led by trade representative clayton yeutter, is expected to use today's meeting to increase pressure on the economic ministers representing the four airbus countries to abolish or at least scale down the payments, sources said
u.s. officials have grown impatient over the slow progress of the talks and are looking for indications that the airbus nations at least are willing to agree to reduce some of their support, sources said
the americans at a minimum want the europeans to give a signal that they are willing to accept some effective discipline in regard to subsidies,'' an informed diplomatic source, who asked not to be identified, said earlier this week
the united states estimates the four countries involved in the airbus industrie consortium _ france, britain, west germany and spain _ have given $10 billion to the consortium since it was created 17 years ago
willy de clercq, the european economic community's external relations commissioner, said last week there was a ``realistic chance'' of settling the dispute. but he also said the eec governments ``cannot entirely renounce'' state aid payments to airbus
de clercq predicted an agreement would require ``further rounds of very difficult negotiations.''
the united states maintains that subsidies to airbus are unfair to u.s. aircraft makers in the wide-body, long-haul passenger jet market
the airbus nations contend the subsidies do not distort trade and are allowed under civil aircraft provisions of the general agreement on tariffs and trade
the eec also argues that u.s. aircraft manufacturers long have enjoyed huge, indirect subsidies through military contracts from the pentagon and millions in government research grants
according to eec figures, the united states exports $5 billion worth of aircraft and aircraft parts to western europe per year, compared to $3 billion of european aircraft exports annually to the united states
the eec says outstanding european orders and options for u.s. aircraft total $23 billion, while u.s. orders and options for airbus stand at $13 billion
the united states contends airbus has 35 percent of the world market, a figure the eec rejects as far too high
the eec claims u.s. manufacturers still dominate the worldwide civilian aircraft market, with boeing controlling 49 percent of the market and mcdonnell douglas corp. 17 percent, while airbus has a 25 percent share
the united states has threatened to retaliate against airbus if the negotiations fail, despite a recent decision by the four airbus ministers to have airbus managers enter into direct negotiations with mcdonnell douglas on a possible joint project
the aim of the talks is to see whether the two sides could collaborate on one or more new airplanes
under the proposal, the new aircraft would not compete with existing models
but diplomatic sources told the associated press that the move was unlikely to reduce tensions over the subsidy issue
it may well be helpful for airbus and mcdonnell douglas to agree on a joint project, but that will not solve the core problem of the current subsidies,'' said another diplomatic source, who also declined to be identified further
campeau corp. has gotten a boost in one aspect of its court fight to gain the upper hand in its attempted take over of federated department stores inc. but still faces major obstacles
the securities and exchange commission on thursday agreed with campeau's contention that its sweetened buyout offer for federated constituted an amendment to a previous proposal rather than an entirely new bid
the sec opinion was sought by a federal judge hearing a lawsuit brought over the issue by rival bidder r.h. macy &amp; co. inc
if u.s. district judge leonard sand agrees with the sec, campeau could let its tender offer expire as scheduled before the april 4 expiration of macy's competing offer, which is supported by federated's management
that could pressure federated shareholders into tendering their shares to campeau, because of the earlier deadline. macy is suing to force campeau to keep its offer open longer
but although campeau got a boost in the dispute over its tender offer, it still must win a victory in its challenge to federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense
both campeau and macy have bid more than $6 billion for federated, one of the nation's biggest department store operators
in a ``friend of the court'' brief, the sec told sand the revised bid campeau announced on march 2 was not a new offer, and as such did not have to remain open for 20 business days past its publication
earlier this week, sand ordered both companies' offers to remain open for three business days after he rules on campeau's lawsuit seeking to invalidate federated's poison pill
campeau has told sand its offer could not proceed while the poison pill remained in effect. the pill would allow current federated shareholders to buy more of the company's stock at a steep discount unless the board of directors withdrew the provision, making a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive
it was not known when sand would make his ruling
macy had no comment on the sec's opinion, said maureen milano, a spokeswoman for the retailer
macy is offering $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million federated shares, for a total of $5.4 billion. macy would exchange shares in the merged company, macy's-federated inc., and issue convertible debt securities for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares, which analysts have estimated would produce a total value of $6.3 billion
campeau's bid is a two-step, all-cash package that would be worth $68 a share, or $6.18 billion. it is offering $75 each for 70.5 million federated shares, and would acquire the remaining stock for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger
federated stock fell 62{ cents to $62.50 a share thursday on the new york stock exchange
in a related matter, the head of the federal trade commission refused thursday to appear before a house panel reviewing the proposed federated takeover
rep. thomas luken, d-ohio, said ftc chairman daniel oliver and ftc commissioner terry calvani told the house energy and commerce transportation subcommittee they would neither testify nor turn over documents on the agency's review of any possible anticompetitive effects of a merger between federated and campeau
luken said he was considering subpoenaing the officials if they did not testify voluntarily
robert paul, general counsel for the ftc, said the commissioners decided not to give the documents to the subcommittee because several weeks ago the panel released to the press an ftc staff memo on the campeau bid the agency considered confidential
federated owns 650 stores including the bloomingdale's, burdine's, filene's, foley's, lazarus and rich's department store chains; ralphs supermarkets; gold circle discount stores; and main street and children's place specialty stores
macy owns nearly 100 department and specialty stores, while campeau owns allied stores corp
the head of the federal trade commission has been asked to justify his refusal to give congress documents on the agency's review of campeau corp.'s proposed takeover of federated department stores inc
the request was made thursday by rep. thomas luken, d-ohio, after ftc chairman daniel oliver and ftc commissioner terry calvani refused to appear before the house energy and commerce transportation subcommittee
i'm a little outraged at this conduct,'' luken said following the hearing. ``they're setting up roadblocks.''
luken, chairman of the subcommittee, said if the officials continue to refuse to comply, ``i will obviously be thinking about proceeding with subpoenas'' and possibly contempt citations
campeau and r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. are locked in a takeover battle for cincinnati-based federated. the congressman has accused the ftc of failing to thoroughly investigate the hostile takeover bid by campeau, which preceded the friendly takeover agreement between federated by macy's
robert paul, the ftc general counsel, said the commissioners decided not to give the documents to the subcommittee because several weeks ago the panel released to the press an ftc staff memo on the campeau bid the agency considered confidential
there's tremendous concern on their part that this was very, very bad precedent,'' said paul. ``chairman oliver and commissioner calvani are not going to be party to producing documents further...until there is assurance by the subcommittee that this type of thing will not happen again.''
paul said that if there was an ftc investigation of the macy's bid and the commissioners rendered a decision, they might be subject to allegations by private parties that the agency acted because of congressional pressure
the more the congress acts on this, puts pressure on us, the greater the possibility of arguing that we have been influenced by congress, that we've been tainted,'' said paul
luken said 80 percent to 90 percent of the information marked confidential in the ftc memo released by the subcommittee was contained in public filings and that the rest is just ``chit-chat.'' he said federated and campeau were told the memo was being given to the subcommittee and neither objected
luken asked that oliver and calvani submit a legal memo giving their reason for not providing the documents and for not appearing before the panel
ftc commissioners mary azcuenaga and andrew strenio, who appeared before the subcommittee thursday, said they had voted to turn over the requested documents but had failed to obtain the necessary majority vote to do so
federated operates about 650 stores in 36 states and had sales exceeding $11 billion in 1987
campeau is a retailing and real estate development company based in toronto
a $1 billion federal cash infusion to first republicbank corp. has helped stanch a run on deposits, but federal officials say the advance is only an interim step to steady the troubled bank holding company
the federal deposit insurance corp.'s cash advance on thursday helped calm jittery depositors and slow runoff of deposits that has drained an undisclosed amount of reserves from the ailing company, bank spokesman joseph c. bowles said
as soon as the fdic action was made available to the public, the deposit outflow stopped,'' bowles said
in washington, fdic chairman william seidman said his agency was talking to private investors about participating in a restructuring of the company, as a long-term solution to first republicbank's problems
in a move intended to stem any ripple effect on the banking system as a whole, seidman also pledged his agency to fully protect all depositors of the banks as well as general creditors
that goes beyond the minimum the agency normally would be expected to insure, which is deposits of $100,000 and less
the promise covers money borrowed overnight from other banks by first republicbank to meet the cash rules of the federal reserve board. however, it does not apply to the holding company and its bond and note holders
the action today confirms that all depositors and other general creditors of first republicbank's banks will be fully protected,'' said gerald fronterhouse, first republicbank's chairman and chief executive
bowles and other bank officials refused thursday to say how much of the company's deposits had been withdrwan since tuesday when it announced its decision to seek federal help
last month, the bank lost $600 million in deposits over a five-day period amid rumors that it was in danger because of billions of dollars in bad loans, particularly in real estate
but several customers at the company's lead bank in downtown dallas indicated they were not worried about losing their deposits
i have confidence in the people running the bank. it'll survive,'' said alex cochrane
gail scott said: ``it's pretty scary. i hope they can work it out.''
a woman who declined to identify herself said she wasn't worried because the fdic insures accounts up to $100,000, and ``before they go under i will have spent my money.''
an associated press reporter was escorted out of the bank under guard thursday as he tried to interview customers and bank officials
george reagan, investment manager of the texas teachers retirement system, a major institutional investor that holds 498,000 shares of first republicbank stock, said the fdic money would provide a cushion for the bank until the economy recovers
this will allow first republic to get through the hard times. no one, especially first republic, realized that we would go through such a hard time with the texas real estate market for so long,'' he said
h.r. ``bum'' bright, owner of the dallas cowboys and bright banc savings association, is the company's largest individual investor with more than 1 million shares
nine months ago, those shares were worth $24 million; now they're worth approximately $1.5 million. bright did not return repeated telephone calls on thursday
state treasurer ann richards said the federal action ``assures that all depositors, including the state treasury, are safe.''
first republicbank is one of four state treasury clearing banks, and as of wednesday held $152 million in state deposits. ms. richards said the deposits are fully collateralized and therefore protected
life has gotten sweeter for chocolate lovers, thanks to a drop in cocoa prices that has translated into bigger candy bars and could mean future price-cutting promotions
the price of raw cocoa _ which typically constitutes up to 20 percent of a typical chocolate bar _ has fallen to five-year lows
while that hasn't meant direct reductions in the cost of a snickers or hershey bar at the corner newsstand or vending machine, it has helped candy makers offer a bigger bar at the same price
the near-month cocoa future traded on the coffee, sugar and cocoa exchange in new york traded at $1,552 per ton on thursday, down from the mid-july price of $2,175. analysts say abundant supplies and rising production have depressed prices
but cheaper cocoa doesn't directly translate into cheaper bars because cocoa and chocolate don't have the direct price relationship of, for example, oil and gasoline or beans and coffee, industry analysts say
while cocoa and its by-products constitute up to 20 percent of a chocolate bar, about 50 percent of the candy is sugar and the rest milk, nuts, vanilla or other ingredients, said susan smith, a spokeswoman for the chocolate manufacturers association
hackettstown-based m&amp;m-mars, a privately-held company considered to be the nation's argest candy bar maker, has increased the size of two popular products by about 8 percent in recent years
last fall, m&amp;m-mars enlarged its milky way bar as it had done with its snickers bar _ the nation's biggest seller, according to industry estimates _ the previous year
hans fiuczynski, a spokesman for m&amp;m-mars, said the lower cocoa price ``augmented and abetted'' the decision to increase the bar size, although he said similar moves by other candy makers also played a major role
we did what other people did, not necessarily because of the price of raw materials,'' fiuczynski said
a spokesman for hershey chocolate u.s.a., in hershey, pa., said a drop in cocoa prices and stabilization in the cost of other ingredients contributed to its decision to boost the size of its various chocolate bars by 10 percent to 14 percent in july 1986
but the price of cocoa ``doesn't have that direct an effect on us'' in terms of the cost of its products, said spokesman carl anderson
kim badenhop, an analyst with merrill lynch capital markets inc., said recent cocoa prices could be considered the lowest in decades if inflation was taken into account
badenhop predicted the increased cash flow resulting from cheaper commodity costs could show up in still-bigger bars and more promotions such as coupons or discounted brands
retailers probably won't pass on their savings to consumers by cutting the price of an individual chocolate bar, but are likely to do it by offering a bigger product for the same price, discount coupons or through other promotions, badenhop said
we've been told through the grapevine that has happened with some of the companies,'' said ms. smith
consumers may see direct savings in products such as packages of candy bars sold in supermarkets or bags of small chocolates, said ms. smith
television producer burt sugarman has launched a two-pronged attack against media general inc., filing a countersuit against the company and launching a proxy fight to win three seats on the board of directors
sugarman filed suit thursday in u.s. district court against media general and each of its directors, asking a judge to order that his $61.50 per share buyout offer, worth about $1.6 billion be considered solely by the three directors elected by holders of the company's publicly-held stock
the suit also sought a ruling that shareholders, voting as a single class, could approve sugarman's offer by simple majority vote
separately, sugarman disclosed in a filing with the securities and exchange commission that he was undertaking a proxy battle to place himself and two others in the three seats on media general's board for holders of the class a publicly traded shares
the disclosures mark the latest skirmish in the weeks-long struggle between sugarman and the family of media general's chairman, d. tennant bryan, which controls a majority of the company's voting power
the family _ which has rejected sugarman's overtures repeatedly _ owns 71 percent of the company's class b common stock, which is not publicly traded. the 559,168 class b shares have the voting power to elect seven of the company's 10 directors
media general has 28 million publicly-traded class a shares, which have one vote each and elect three directors
sugarman, who controls 10 percent of the company's class a stock and none of the class b, has argued that the disproportionate voting rule doesn't apply if a holder of more than 10 percent of the company's stock proposes a merger. media general says its counsel disagrees
sugarman's suit said the bryans are thwarting a vote by stockholders, even though their class b shares constitute only 1.4 percent of the company's total equity
david l. jordan, a media general vice president, said the company's lawyers had reviewed the suit and ``think it is without merit.''
media general sued sugarman and his companies in federal court monday, asking the court to block the takeover attempt and force sugarman to sell his 10 percent holding
the suit alleges sugarman submitted incomplete and inaccurate information to federal regulators about his proposed takeover
sugarman's group includes barris industries inc. of beverly hills, calif., which produces game shows, and giant group ltd. of harleyville, s.c., which makes cement products
media general owns several communications interests, including richmond newspapers inc., which publishes the richmond news leader and the richmond times-dispatch
the dollar rose in europe early today on the back of better-than-expected u.s. trade performance in january. gold bullion fell
the u.s. currency was holding steady at mostly higher levels at midmorning, and traders said a rally triggered by thursday's trade report appeared to be running out of steam
the commerce department reported thursday that the u.s. merchandise trade deficit widened slightly to $12.4 billion in january from $12.2 billion in december. the market had expected a shortfall of $12.8 billion
a trader in frankfurt, west germany, said the dollar was boosted both by the trade figures and the deployment of u.s. troops to honduras. but he said market sentiment was not changed fundamentally
another jump in the british pound, however, could push the dollar lower, the trader said. ``the pound is seen as a real alternative for financial investments,'' he said
the pound fell to $1.8265 from $1.8385. sterling, which has surged this month, was knocked back thursday after major british banks cut interest rates
other dollar rates in europe at midmorning, compared with late thursday's rates, included: 1.6940 west german marks, up from 1.6775; 1.4020 swiss francs, up from 1.3940; 5.7490 french francs, up from 5.7175; 1.8985 dutch guilders, up from 1.8885; 1,253.25 italian lire, up from 1,244.37; 1.2490 canadian dollars, down from 1.2493
