firestone tire &amp; rubber jumped 15| to 78[. the company agreed thursday to be acquired by bridgestone of japan for $80 a share, in a deal that topped a previous $58-a-share bid by pirelli group of italy
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose .47 to 153.15. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up .43 at 299.42
the great u.s. airline giveaway seems to be grinding to a halt
worried about the potential financial impact of burgeoning frequent-flier programs and triple-mileage travel awards, many major air carriers have imposed restrictions on the plans or are thinking of doing so
the frequent-flier plans, which reward passengers with free tickets or upgrades to first class after they have flown a set number of miles, were launched in 1981 to stimulate ``brand loyalty'' to airlines in a fiercely competitive climate
the giveaway escalated to fever pitch at the beginning of this year, when delta air lines introduced a new program to automatically triple the mileage accumulated by frequent fliers. most big airlines quickly followed suit
but the u.s. airline industry is facing a staggering revenue loss if the estimated 8 million people enrolled in those programs start redeeming their bonuses and bumping paying passengers. the accumulated value of those bonuses is around $1.24 billion, reckons julius maldutis, senior airline analyst for the investment firm salomon brothers inc
that compares with total industry revenue of around $46.7 billion in 1985, $50.5 billion in 1986 and just over $60 billion last year
the frequent-flier programs have really gotten out of control,'' said dan sheehy, a spokesman for united airlines. ``we're concerned with the direction that the programs are taking.''
john zeeman, united's executive vice president for marketing and planning, said in a speech early this month that the airline is considering imposing restrictions on its frequent-flier programs. he said the options under review include requiring that travel awards be redeemed by a certain deadline, and even eliminating free trips and providing only first-class upgrades instead
if united decides to limit its program, the changes would be announced in early may, zeeman said
many other airlines have recently slapped restrictions on their programs _ most notably by limiting the number of free tickets for any one flight. but the limits being mulled by united, a subsidiary of allegis corp. and the nation's largest airline, are more far-reaching and could be matched by the other carriers
the last thing these airlines need is more damage on their balance sheets,'' said peter tanous, an editor of frequent, a monthly newsletter on frequent-flier programs published in colorado springs, colo. ``the airlines are scared stiff that they may be forced to take a hit against their earnings.''
observers warn that the internal revenue service could decide to tax the programs, sparking a ``mad rush'' by passengers to redeem their travel bonuses. the irs indicated recently that it considers travel awards a form of reportable income when transportation costs for a frequent business flier are paid by an employer
and the financial accounting standards board is expected to require airlines to provide for the liability of unredeemed awards in their 1988 financial statements
the looming crisis has taken hold during an already turbulent period for the nation's airline industry. the business is coming off one of its worst safety performances in 1987, struggling with unions and threatened strikes against some big carriers, and worrying about the possibility of a recession later in the year
for now, though, many airlines are enjoying robust passenger traffic and earnings _ prompting them to raise fares recently and to eliminate some discount fares
analysts say nearly all the major airlines except delta have started to limit their frequent-flier largesse by instituting ``capacity control,'' or reducing the number of freebies on a flight
everyone else is doing it; you have to control and manage your inventory,'' said bob gibbons, a spokesman for northwest airlines _ which will start capacity control on april 1 for bonuses issued after feb. 15
even holdout delta has ``blackout'' dates, or certain peak travel periods when free tickets cannot be used. delta, the third largest airline, also has the unique requirement that frequent fliers must charge their tickets on an american express card
we want to remain competitive with the industry,'' delta spokesman jim lundy said when asked what might happen if united instituted major restrictions
some airlines also are looking at other approaches, such as replacing free travel with merchandise awards or hotel and car rental premiums
while they could significantly restrict their frequent-flier programs, the airlines are not about to eliminate them or triple-mileage awards altogether, observers say. when the triple-mileage plans were launched at the start of the year, the carriers assured passengers that the popular gimmicks would be retained through 1988
we recognize that there certainly is an economic impact associated with the triple-mileage program,'' said frank dinuzzo, managing director of sales promotion for american airlines. but, he added, american has no intention of canceling its program
indeed, some observers suggest the airlines may be caught in a sort of ``catch-22'' by their frequent-flier programs, forced to keep them because there is no way to end them
i suspect that if the airlines had their druthers, they would throw frequent-flier programs into a bonfire because they've just become so expensive,'' said michael j. friedman, a vice president of sh&amp;e inc., an aviation consulting firm
however, he noted, it would be extremely difficult for a carrier to end its frequent-flier program without all its competitors doing the same
while the major u.s. airlines may be losing millions of dollars with their frequent-flier programs and triple-mileage travel awards, a new study contends that companies are wasting as much as $12 billion a year on business travel
the survey of 57 large and medium-sized companies by travelmation corp., a travel agency based in stamford, conn., found that u.s. businesses are squandering 10 percent to 15 percent of their annual travel budgets
travel agents' use of ``antiquated'' airline reservation systems that can't keep pace with fast-changing fares is the main cause of the waste, according to the study
airline analysts estimate that u.s. carriers currently make around 40,000 fare changes a day
millions of dollars could be saved by companies each year without reducing quality, by combining the use of advanced computer technology with a carefully worked out corporate travel plan,'' said travelmation president louis van leeuwen, who directed the survey
conventional travel agencies _ whose methods worked well before deregulation of the u.s. airline industry in 1978 _ are now unable to offer companies the best travel values, van leeuwen said
among the study's other findings:
_conventional travel agencies, even those equipped with computers, can't keep track of constant fare changes
_many travel agents can't guarantee they will find flights at the lowest fares available
_many agents don't automatically process the daily-changing rules governing which fares can be used on which flights
_corporate travel policies are largely ignored by travel agents
wheat futures moved a little higher early today on the chicago board of trade, but soybeans and most corn contracts were on the decline
a large speculator who triggered a sharp rally in soybeans on thursday was not in the market early today, said victor lespinasse, a trader with the investment firm dean witter reynolds inc
as a result, he said, a lot of traders who rode thursday's momentum with buy orders, were selling off ahead of the weekend
