on thursday, cattle futures were lower while pork advanced
the trans-panama pipeline that carries alaska oil across the isthmus en route to markets on the u.s. gulf coast resumed operations friday, the pipeline said
pumping had stopped because a strike by electrical workers cut off power wednesday and thursday, prompting the panamanian government to announce it was taking over all public utilities
service was restored at 6 a.m. (est) this morning,'' a spokesman for the pipeline operator said. ``we actually never stopped loading and unloading at both ends. we stopped the actual pumping from one end to the other because for that we depend on public energy. but we have our own plant at each end for loading and unloading.''
the pipeline carries 650,000 barrels a day of alaska oil, roughly 10 percent of u.s. domestic production. a barrel is equivalent to 42 gallons
bp america inc. owns two-thirds to three-quarters of the oil flowing through the pipeline. the rest is owned by exxon co. usa
the flow was first halted at 2 p.m. est wednesday when electrical workers joined a widespread strike against gen. manuel antonio noriega, said tim reynolds, a bp america spokesman in washington, d.c. the strike cut off power to a pump station at the foot of a mountain, he said
the company was taking steps to set up a ship-to-ship transfer operation in order to put at least some of its oil through the canal, but service was restored, making thaat action unnecessary
alaska officials were worried about a panama pipeline shutdown because it could slow sales of alaska crude, which account for the bulk of state revenues
west coast oil markets are glutted with alaska oil, and the federal export ban prevents its sale overseas
chuck logsdon, chief oil revenue analyst for the state, said the gulf coast markets have been handling more than 600,000 barrels of the total daily alaska production of 1.8 million to 1.9 million barrels
stock prices churned ahead today, extending the advance that has carried the market to its highest levels since black monday last fall
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.13 to 2,093.17 by noontime on wall street
gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 5 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 770 up, 563 down and 485 unchanged
activity was swollen by the quarterly ``triple witching hour'' involving a group of expiring options and futures on stock indexes that are used in large-scale computer program trading
settlement of one key futures contract was done based on stock prices as of the opening today. reports from the nyse of preopening order imbalances were on the buy side
the rest of the settlement process was slated to be conducted at the close
beyond that, analysts said the market was still benefiting from thursday's news of a smaller-than-expected trade deficit in january, with imports exceeding exports by $12.44 billion
