a squabble among british unions over single-union representation at factories led ford motor co. to cancel plans friday for an electronics plant in scotland
ford said the proposed $73 million plant could not compete if its workers were represented by more than one union
conservative party politicians reacted quickly, accusing the unions of causing job losses in an economically depressed area
the dundee fiasco is a tragic return to the socialist anarchy of the 1970s,'' said michael heseltine, a conservative lawmaker in parliament
malcolm rifkind, the government's scottish secretary, criticized the unions for holding ``neanderthal attitudes.''
ford said that it had reached agreement with the amalgamated engineering union to represent the initial work force of 450 employees, but that the 11 other unions also representing workers at ford's current british plants balked. plans called for the scottish factory to employ about 1,000 workers at peak production
britain's unions are deeply divided about whether to accept single-union deals and no-strike agreements, which have become more common in this country, particularly at japanese-owned plants
union leaders have also been struggling to find a way to regain the power they lost under the legislation enacted by prime minister margaret thatcher's conservative government
years of relative labor calm have been disrupted by recent strikes at ford and other auto plants, as well as walkouts by miners and nurses
ford said there was ``no prospect'' of reaching an agreement for a single union to represent the plant's hourly workers
after very careful consideration, we have decided not to proceed with development of a new electronics plant in scotland,'' frank macher, general manager of ford's electrical and electronics division in detroit, said in a statement
a single trade union agreement was necessary to make the plant ``competitive in its industry in cost and quality,'' macher said. ``we had not expected that this requirement ... would prove so difficult to achieve.''
norman willis, general secretary of the trades union congress, said he was calling two urgent meetings on monday to discuss the ford decision and to try to reverse it
the 12 ford unions would meet the same day, he said
gavin laird, leader of the amalgamated engineering union which represents about two-thirds of ford's more than 32,000 hourly workers, said he was pressing ford's senior management for a top-level meeting at its detroit headquarters early next week to try to save the plant
however, a ford spokesman in detroit, john emmert, said later in a telephone interview with independent television news: ``there is no chance that the decision will be changed.''
the deal's opponents feared workers at the dundee plant would earn lower wages than workers at ford's 21 other british plants
state officials moved friday to recover $40 million they say american telephone &amp; telegraph co. has added unfairly to the telephone bills of connecticut customers during the last two years
in a complaint filed with the federal communications commission, the officials challenged the telephone company's right to add a 7.3 percent surcharge on long-distance charges to recoup the gross-receipts tax it pays in connecticut
they argued that the surcharge imposed in connecticut and nine other states violates the longstanding practice of having uniform telephone rates across the country
the other states where the surcharge is imposed are: florida, maine, maryland, new york, rhode island, vermont, virginia, west virginia and wisconsin, according to the complaint filed with the fcc
since the early days of the telephone company, this country was built upon having an average rate throughout the country,'' consumer counsel james f. meehan said in announcing the action
the thought was that people in montana should be able to call people in hartford at the same rate that people in hartford ... call people in montana,'' he said
meehan and attorney general joseph i. lieberman have formed an alliance with the state department of public utility control in challenging federal regulators for allowing at&amp;t to impose the surcharge
the complaint seeks to recover the $40 million collected by at&amp;t so far and to eliminate the surcharge
the fcc allowed at&amp;t to add the surcharge in states with a gross-receipts tax on long-distance companies starting in april 1986. the surcharge in connectict was initially 3.6 percent, but rose to 7.3 percent in january
at&amp;t is the only long-distance carrier regulated by the fcc, although other long-distance companies such as sprint and mci also add the surcharge to their bills, meehan said
at&amp;t officials responded that figuring the gross receipts tax into its national rates would be unfair to customers elsewhere in the country
only connecticut residents benefit from the state gross receipts tax on telecommunications companies, and therefore connecticut customers should pay those extra costs of doing business,'' said paul karoff, an at&amp;t spokesman in connecticut
meehan said at&amp;t came up with the idea of imposing the surcharge in the 10 states with a gross receipts tax in order to generate millions of dollars that would allow it to reduce rates
connecticut officials contend it is unfair given that the actual cost providing telephone service is lower in here than in many other parts of the country because of the high volume of business. connecticut is the 10th-largest telecommunications market in the united states and generates about $550 million in annual revenues for at&amp;t, meehan said
also, at&amp;t doesn't add surcharges to recover other types of taxes it pays, they said
the officials acknowledged it may be difficult to convince the fcc to hold a hearing on the complaint, particularly since the fcc previously approved the surcharge. they vowed to take the case to court if the fcc refuses to hear it
there are fundamental issues of how rates are set in the country,'' meehan said. ``if we are successful, i think create some new case law that will have major impact on rate setting practices throughout the federal system.''
domino's pizza inc. advertises ``domino's delivers,'' and the company delivered its annual report this year in an unmistakably shaped 12\-inch-by-12\-inch flip-open box
that would be a small medium,'' said ron hingst, one of those involved in what has become a tradition of non-traditional annual reports
the 1986 version was in the form of a spiral school-style notebook with tabbed dividers for different subjects. an earlier report came with a set of dominos
it's a chance for the financial guys to play marketing,'' hingst said
this year's pizza-style box contained a cardboard jigsaw puzzle of the domino's pizza name and trademark, and the report, with a quotation from thomas s. monaghan, chairman and founder, on the cover: ``1987 was the year we worked hard to pull all the pieces together.''
along with sections on areas such as development and service, the report gave financial results reported earlier: net income of $7.7 million on total revenue of $883.7 million for 1987, up from $7.1 million on revenue of $721.6 million for 1986
because domino's is privately-held, its annual report goes to suppliers, media contacts, and other people and companies it deals with, hingst said
