nestle s.a., the giant swiss multinational food group, friday said it agreed to acquire the commercial and industrial holdings of italy's buitoni food group for 1.6 trillion lire, or $1.2 billion
nestle said it was buying buitoni's operations from cie. industriali riunite spa (cir), a key holding of italian financier carlo de benedetti
under the specifics of the transaction, cir will sell all the operating units of buitoni spa, its chocolate and confectionary company perugina spa, and buitoni s.a., the french holding which controls buitoni's foreign operations
the acquisition represents the end of de benedetti's dream of creating a major european food conglomerate, which was frustrated by his failure to gain control of societe meridionale finanzaria spa (sme), italy's major state-run food group
the sale also raises a considerable sum of cash to help de benedetti in his fight to gain control of societe generale de belgique, belgium's biggest company
cir acquired control of buitoni in 1985 with an initial investment of 25 billion lire, $20 million at today's exchange rates, which was subsequently increased to 160 billion lire
given the size of the initial investment, analysts said de benedetti had achieved a remarkable return on his original investment
it looks as if the engineer (de benedetti) has pulled out of the food industry in style. the problem was that buitoni didn't reach sufficient critical mass,'' said giovanni raimondi, an analyst with milan brokerage studio aletti
in 1987, the buitoni group earned consolidated net income before payments to minority interests of $40.8 million, up from a loss of $37.6 million in 1984
buitoni produces pasta, crackers and sauces in italy, france and britain. the perugia-based buitoni group also includes perugina, one of italy's leading chocolate producers as well as davigel s.a. of france, which produces frozen food and food services, olio sasso spa, an edible oils group and vismara spa, a meat producer
the buitoni group, which employs some 8,000 people, earned 39 percent of its revenue in italy in 1987, 36 percent in france, 16 percent in britain, 4 percent in the rest of europe and 5 percent in the rest of the world
nestle said it was particularly interested in the acquisiton of buitoni because it would give it a niche in the market for typically italian foods, such as pasta. it also will mesh perugina with its own chocolate sector. final decision on dropping its bid, today's stock action. picks up 10th graf: yeiri said ...</note>
japan's bridgestone corp. agreed to buy firestone tire &amp; rubber co. for nearly $2.6 billion in cash, an offer that leaped far beyond a rival bid for firestone from the italian tiremaker pirelli spa
pirelli, which offered $1.93 billion for firestone, said today from its headquarters in milan, italy, that it would not increase its offer. later, in a statement issued in new york, the company said it would wait before making a final decision on dropping its current offer
firestone directors announced the agreement to bridgestone's $80-a-share offer late thursday, and recommended that shareholders reject the pirelli bid
firestone stock, which had closed at $62.50 a share on thursday, shot up to $78 by midafternoon on the new york stock exchange
bridgestone and firestone had announced an agreement in mid-february that called for the japanese company to buy 75 percent of firestone's worldwide tire manufacturing business for $1.5 billion
but after pirelli launched its bid last week, bridgestone, faced with losing the world's fourth largest tire manufacturer, decided to bid for the entire company
we never considered backing away from our agreement with firestone to become its partner in operating its worldwide tire businesses,'' bridgestone president akira yeiri said. ``the merger agreement merely represents an expansion and extension of our original agreement.''
in its statement in milan, pirelli said it would not raise its bid
pirelli has always said that its offer would be limited by its evaluation of industrial logic,'' the statement said. ``the figure offered by bridgestone does not fit into such logic.''
but pirelli added in the later statement that it would wait until bridgestone formally began its tender offer for firestone before deciding whether to terminate its own offer
yeiri said his company planned to keep firestone's worldwide tire operations headquarters in akron, ohio, under existing management. all of firestone's north american plants will stay in operation
firestone chairman john j. nevin said a bridgestone subsidiary would begin a cash tender offer within the next few days for all of firestone's 32 million outstanding shares. the offer is subject to at least two-thirds of the shares being tendered and approval of the deal by firestone shareholders
bridgestone also has an option to acquire up to 5.8 million shares held by firestone's treasury, a ``lock-up'' option typically granted to discourage hostile suitors
firestone ranks fourth in tire sales worldwide, behind industry leader goodyear, michelin and bridgestone, according to industry estimates
in the fiscal year ending october 1987, firestone had net income of $1.45 million, or $3.96 a share, on sales of $3.87 billion
firestone's agreement with bridgestone was a major blow to pirelli, which wants a foothold in the u.s. tire market, the world's largest. pirelli has a nominal 1.5 percent share of the u.s. market
sources close to pirelli said pirelli will continue to seek new markets
there are always new opportunities in the u.s.,'' said one source, speaking on condition of anonymity
with the failure of its bid, pirelli is canceling an agreement with france's michelin group. pirelli had agreed to sell firestone's retails stores division, its brazilian operations and some other assets to michelin for as much as $800 million if its bid succeeded
that agreement (with michelin) was contingent on us acquiring firestone, so that goes up in the air,'' a pirelli spokesman said
there's nothing roger kropf likes less than a bruised apple
for years the lowell fruit grower has looked for a way to package the perfect fruit _ and to keep it that way during the long haul to the supermarket and, eventually, the consumer's kitchen
but no matter how we handle the product here, it can be damaged any time, starting at the point the trucks are unloaded at the store up until the consumer puts it in the refrigerator,'' said kropf, president of kropf fruit co
kropf's company grows and markets its own apples, peaches and plums and markets fruit for about 100 other growers across michigan
kropf wrestled with a variety of ideas on how to protect produce from damage in shipment, but it took a trip to an egg-carton company to get the answer
i was standing in the production area of a company which makes polyfoam products and watching them make egg cartons,'' kropf said. ``i thought, `good lord, if they can protect eggs, they ought to be able to protect apples.'''
kropf began exploring the idea last year with dolco of decatur, ill. after a lengthy testing period, the two companies produced a deep-blue, polyfoam container with wings to distribute the weight of stacked packages without damaging the fruit
kropf's company began marketing fruit in the new containers in january
much like the egg carton, kropf's new container is a 12-pack. the container and contents are covered with a clear, plastic film providing a view of the fruit
the fruit is shipped in the specially designed packages and kept in them while on retailers' shelves. a 3-pound package of apples averages about 25 cents more than the 3-pound, plastic bag of apples now found in supermarket produce departments
this is really geared for only about 10 percent of the market, for the clientele willing to pay a bit more for quality fruit,'' said steve krampe, sales manager for the company
kropf ships his fruit throughout the united states east of the rockies and exports to foreign countries
but the company isn't stopping at shipping the perfect apple. it also plans to develop the special packaging for shipping peaches
we're very excited about the possibilities with peaches,'' said krampe. ``they bruise even more easily than apples.''
the public may be able to buy shares this spring in sotheby's holdings inc., the world's richest art auction house said friday
a statement from the u.s.-owned private company said the share flotation will be in london and new york
the flotation was originally planned for last fall but was postponed when stock markets crashed in october
since the stock market downturn ... the international art market has remained strong, with record prices continuing to be set in many collecting areas,'' the statement said
the announcement followed swiftly on a report in london's evening standard newspaper that the flotation is planned for late april and values the firm at ``slightly less than 300 million pounds,'' or $546 million
that was 100 million pounds, or $182 million, less than the pre-crash valuation, the report added
alfred taubman, the michigan shopping mall tycoon, gained control of sotheby's in september 1983 at a cost of 83 million pounds, or $124.5 million at the time
sotheby's said a spring flotation would depend on ``favorable stock market conditions'' and no definite sale date was set
the evening standard said a complex share-voting structure is planned which would leave control with taubman
sotheby's is being advised on the flotation by the wall street house of salomon brothers and british merchant bank lazard brothers and co. ltd
the founder and ex-president of an irradiation company and a leading spokesman for the food preservation process was indicted friday on charges he ordered workers to bypass safety precautions and lied about it to federal regulators
the company, radiation technology inc. of morris plains, wednesday pleaded guilty to related charges involving violations at its rockaway plant. rti irradiates medical products and spices
company founder martin welt had planned to plead guilty to unspecified charges in the case the same day but withdrew from a plea agreement at the last moment, said prosecutors in the u.s. attorney's newark office
welt, 55, of denville, withdrew as rti's president in mid-1986 after the federal nuclear regulatory commission temporarily suspended the company's license for the safety violations
he has been one of the process's most vocal supporters, touting it in the media and making a promotional trip to china last year. welt also was a physicist with the nrc's predecessor, the atomic energy commission
also named in the 11-count indictment was william jouris, 48, of littleton, mass. in 1985, jouris was a resident nuclear engineer and operations manager at the rockaway plant, the indictment said
welt and jouris were charged with conspiracy to defraud the nrc, making false statements and violating the atomic energy act. welt also was charged with obstruction of justice
welt's attorney, theodore h. wells, said he had not seen the indictment and could not comment. he also refused to comment on the apparent breakdown in plea negotiations. welt did not return a message left on his answering machine
jouris could not be reached for comment. he did not return a message left on his home answering machine. attorney robert fettweis, who prosecutors said has represented jouris, did not return a message left at his office
the indictment said the defendants bypassed or told others to bypass ``conveyor door safety interlocks'' at the rockaway plant. the devices automatically lower the radiation source, in this case cobalt 60, into a protective pool when a human or an object other than the product to be irradiated enters the area
welt ordered the locks routinely bypassed starting in april 1984, the indictment said, and sought to impede an nrc investigation into the matter
the criminal investigation grew out of the nrc probe, which led to a pair of temporary license suspensions in 1986
welt called a meeting and threatened rti workers with dismissal if they didn't lie to investigators, the indictment said
jouris was accused of removing a radiation safety monitor that prevented workers from being inadvertently exposed to radiation
the company has said no worker or member of the public was harmed because of the violations
assistant u.s. attorney jacqueline c. wolff said authorities know of at least one worker who entered the cell area while products were being irradiated, but said the worker suffered no immediate injury
she said it was difficult to measure the health affects of the safety violations because the results of low-level dosages don't appear until years later
she said the safety interlocks frequently malfunctioned, preventing the irradiation process from going on, so company officials bypassed them to keep operating
the indictment said jouris and welt lied to the nrc about the installation of a new conveyor door safety system at the rockaway plant, telling regulators during a routine inspection that it had tested a new system in tandem with the old system for two weeks before dismantling the old one
instead, the indictment charged, the old system was taken apart and the new one installed without testing
welt faces up to 37 years in prison if convicted and jouris faces 22 years
rti also has operations in salem, n.j., west memphis, ark., and haw river, n.c
stock prices turned downward today, running into some resistance at their highest levels since black monday last fall
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 10 points in early trading, was down 5.64 at 2,080.40 by 3 p.m. on wall street
gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 661 up, 806 down and 479 unchanged
activity was swollen by the quarterly ``triple witching hour'' involving a group of expiring options and futures on stock indexes that are used in large-scale computer program trading
settlement of one key futures contract was done based on stock prices as of the opening today. reports from the nyse of preopening order imbalances were on the buy side
the rest of the settlement process was slated to be conducted at the close
beyond that, analysts said the market drew some added benefit from thursday's news of a smaller-than-expected trade deficit in january, with imports exceeding exports by $12.44 billion
but as the session passed prices fell back as traders moved to cash in on the market's recent gains
firestone tire &amp; rubber led the active list and jumped 15[ to 77|. the company agreed thursday to be acquired by bridgestone of japan for $80 a share, in a deal that topped a previous $58-a-share bid by pirelli group of italy
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell .35 to 152.33. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up .50 at 299.49
volume on the big board came to 205.94 million shares with an hour to go
wheat futures prices advanced while soybeans and corn skidded lower friday on the chicago board of trade
wheat was about the only market that showed any strength,'' said victor lespinasse, a trader with dean witter reynolds inc
soybeans dropped about a nickel a bushel despite heavy buying again friday by a large speculator who triggered a strong rally on thursday
friday's buying by the c &amp; d commodities was accompanied by heavy selling of soybean options, negating any strong response by other traders, said lespinasse
he said beans were under pressure from selling by south american interests and by traders unloading contracts before the weekend
increased farmer selling overnight weakened the corn market
a rumor that the agriculture department was about to make an announcement of a large offer of subsidized wheat helped that grain, said lespinasse
on the close, wheat was 1 cent to 3{ cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $2.99{ a bushel; corn was { cent to 1\ cents lower with march at $1.97} a bushel; oats were \ cent lower to 3} cents higher with march at $1.96 a bushel; and soybeans were 1} cents to 6 cents lower with march at $6.20 a bushel
a top officer at lotus development corp. has resigned from the computer software company over management disagreements with the firm's chairman and other senior executives, the company said friday
charles j. digate, 34, a senior vice president in charge of the company's analytic software group, resigned thursday ``under mutual agreement,'' a company statement said
but company sources quoted in several published reports said digate's resignation was urged by lotus chairman jim p. manzi, 36, because his brusk style upset other top executives
digate, who joined lotus in 1983 from the european products division at texas instruments, played a key role in development of new software products, including the best-selling lotus 1-2-3 programs. he also helped expand the company's growth in european and japanese markets
he was assigned nine months ago to the the analytical software group, which includes the 1-2-3 programs
digate's abrupt resignation raised questions that problems may exist with the scheduled june introduction of lotus 1-2-3 release 3, an upgraded version of the company's spreadsheet package, but a company statement said there are no changes in the schedule for the program
lotus is expected to replace digate with someone from outside the company
bridgestone corp. of japan plans to create the most-technologically advanced tire company in the world when it purchases firestone tire &amp; rubber co., bridgestone president akira yeiri said friday
firestone's board of directors recommended thursday that shareholders accept bridgestone's offer to purchase firestone's 32 million outstanding shares for $80 a share. bridgestone was spurred to make the $2.6 billion offer thursday because of an unsolicited offer from italian tiremaker pirelli spa
pirelli did not make a counter offer friday. the italian firm said in a news release that it will await the merger of bridgestone and firestone before making a final decision on terminating its $58-a-share offer
firestone shareholders meet in akron on tuesday
yeiri said bridgestone, which employs 32,500 people worldwide, wants to become a global tiremaker with the most efficient production facilities and the most effective marketing organization in the world
the bridgestone-firestone alliance brings together many complimentary strengths,'' yeiri told a news conference at firestone's north american tire headquarters in akron. ``together we have the design and manufacturing capability necessary to build high-quality tires and to improve our global competitive position.''
bridgestone plans to keep firestone's corporate offices in chicago and its north american tire headquarters in akron, he said. all of firestone's north american plants will remain in operation, he said
in the meantime, bridgestone still plans to move its north american sales operation from los angeles to nashville, tenn. bridgestone purchased a plant outside nashville from firestone in 1983
firestone employs 55,000 people worldwide, including 1,650 in the akron area. the company has streamlined itself to the number of employees needed to operate effectively, yeiri said. no changes are planned in firestone management, he said
the two operations complement one another, yeiri said. firestone has production plants in the united states, canada, europe and latin america, he said, while bridgestone has a strong sales network in asia and australia
yeiri also noted that firestone provides original equipment to ford and general motors and has made considerable progress in the international market with porche, volvo, audi and volkswagon. original equipment is bridgestone's weakest area, he said
although financing for the purchase hasn't been worked out, yeiri said he thinks 50 percent of the purchase price will come from bridgestone assets, and bridgestone will borrow the rest. the japanese tire maker decided $80 a share would be a fair offer after consulting with investment bankers, he said
in mid-february, firestone announced an agreement to sell 75 percent of its worldwide tire manufacturing business to bridgestone for $1.5 billion. but that agreement was in jeopardy after pirelli launched its tender offer for the entire company last week
akron officials were pleased about bridgestone's plans to keep firestone's akron operations intact
the commitment to say we're going to do everything we can to keep the operations in place with everyone working where they are _ it's good news for akron,'' said mayor don plusquellic
stock prices declined slightly today in an erratic session
five minutes before the close, the dow jones average of 30 industrials was down 1.16 at 2,084.88
stock prices turned in an inconclusive showing today, meeting with some resistance from sellers at their highest levels since black monday last fall
activity was swollen by the quarterly ``triple witching hour'' involving a group of expiring options and futures on stock indexes that are used in large-scale computer program trading
settlement of one key futures contract was done based on stock prices as of the opening today. reports from the nyse of preopening order imbalances were on the buy side
the rest of the settlement process was conducted at the close, with a few preclosing order imbalances leaning to the sell side
beyond that, analysts said the market drew some added benefit from thursday's news of a smaller-than-expected trade deficit in january, with imports exceeding exports by $12.44 billion
but prices fell back from their midsession peaks as traders moved to cash in on the market's recent gains
steel imports rose from december to january and were sharply higher than in january 1987, the american iron and steel institute said thursday
the additional tonnage came almost entirely from developing nations not covered by the reagan administration's voluntary import quotas, the washington-based producers' group said
the january imports, as reported to aisi by the commerce department, were 1.81 million tons, up 7 percent from 1.69 million tons in december and up 24 percent from 1.46 million tons in january 1987
preliminary figures suggest foreign metal captured 22 percent of the domestic market, up from 20 percent in january and higher than the 20 percent target set for the quota plan. stock price</note>
pillsbury co.'s report of a larger-than-expected quarterly loss ended a two-day run-up in its stock price that was spurred by takeover speculation, but analysts said friday that the company remained vulnerable
i don't think anything has really changed,'' said craig carver of dain bosworth inc. in minneapolis. ``i think this company is still a very strong takeover possibility even though the stock has traded down somewhat today.''
in active trading on the new york stock exchange, pillsbury closed down $2.50 to $42.87{
speculation that the minneapolis food and restaurant giant was a takeover target had pushed the company's stock up more than $7 a share from wednesday to thursday
but that trend reversed friday. pillsbury announced thursday it lost $107.8 million during its third fiscal quarter, $50 million more than anticipated and a sharp downturn from the $48.5 million, or 56-cents-a-share profit posted in the year-ago period
sales during the quarter fell to $1.5 billion from $1.53 billion a year earlier
william spoor, pillsbury chairman and chief executive, said the quarterly loss stemmed from $140.9 million in restructuring charges to close businesses, restaurant properties and plants. he said he expected earnings to decline in fiscal 1988, which ends may 31
pillsbury said it would continue streamlining its troubled restaurant and food groups and was negotiating to sell its godfather's pizza chain. the company said it would rally around its core businesses, such as burger king and haagen-dazs ice cream
the moves, however, failed to impress analysts
godfather's is a drop in the bucket in this whole company,'' carver said. ``i would think regardless of what they do short of going out and making a major acquisition in an attempt to make themselves unattractive is not going to deter a possible raider or for that matter a friendly buyout attempt.''
the sale of godfather's is unlikely to generate cash proceeds exceeding $50 million. to me, investors want more,'' added john m. mcmillin of prudential-bache securities in new york. ``i think people want more restructuring.''
the 580-unit godfather's chain, acquired by pillsbury in 1985, is being sold because it does not have ``near-term'' potential to be a ``major strategic component of pillsbury's portfolio,'' spoor said
pillsbury, which employs about 104,000 worldwide with 97,200 workers in the united states, had no comment friday on whether it had received any takeover offers
analysts have speculated that potential buyers for pillsbury included swiss-based nestle s.a., beatrice co. of chicago and new york investor saul steinberg
in a letter to shareholders thursday, spoor said he was committed to keeping pillsbury independent
the dow jones average of 30 industrials edged up 1.33 to 2,087.37, stretching its gain for the week to 52.39 points
but declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 6 on the new york stock exchange, with 699 up, 824 down and 440 unchanged
big board volume totaled 245.75 million shares, against 211.92 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index slipped .07 to 152.61
the dollar turned mixed in domestic dealings friday after rising overseas, as uneasiness set in over the upcoming close of japan's fiscal year and the long-term prospects for the u.s. economy
gold prices were mostly higher. republic national bank of new york said gold was bid at $444 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, up from $443.40 an ounce late thursday
analysts said the dollar had a slightly firmer tone and continued to draw support from better-than-expected trade figures released thursday
but there's fear that we'll see trade numbers in the future that are not that good,'' said earl i. johnson, a vice president at harris trust and savings bank in chicago
there's still a lot of uncertainty about the economy,'' he said
analysts said there also is concern about what effect the end of japan's fiscal year will have on the u.s. currency
some speculate that japanese dealers will keep the dollar steady through the year's march 31 close so they will not have to write down losses on their portfolios. ``but there's a fear they might dump dollars'' after that, johnson said
in addition, ``there is a growing fear that because the japanese economy is so strong, the bank of japan might tighten monetary policy,'' thereby hiking interest rates, said james o'neill, vice president and financial markets economist at marine midland bank
under that scenario, the dollar would fall as japanese-u.s. interest rate differentials narrowed, he said
in tokyo, the dollar closed at 128.35 japanese yen, up from 127.43 yen thursday. in later london trading, the dollar was holding steady at 128.35 yen. in new york, the dollar fell to 128.00 yen from 128.75 yen on thursday
in london, the british pound fell to $1.8235 from $1.8385 late thursday. in new york trading, it cost $1.8240 to buy one pound, less expensive than thursday's $1.8330
other late dollar rates in new york, compared with late thursday, included: 1.69575 west german marks, up from 1.69165; 1.4040 swiss francs, down from 1.4045; 5.7590 french francs, up from 5.7455; 1,255.50 italian lire, up from 1.252.50, and 1.24885 canadian dollars, down from 1.24925
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late thursday, included: 1.6950 west german marks, up from 1.6775; 1.4010 swiss francs, up from 1.3940; 5.7480 french francs, up from 5.7175; 1.9010 dutch guilders, up from 1.8885; 1,252.50 italian lire, up from 1,244.37, and 1.2495 canadian dollars, up from 1.2493
gold bullion closed at $445.20 a troy ounce on the new york commodity exchange, up from $444.90 on thursday
in london, gold was quoted at a late bid price of $443.25 a troy ounce, up from $443 late thursday. gold was bid at $445 in zurich, unchanged from late thursday. earlier, the metal closed in hong kong at a bid $446.39, down from $448.75
silver closed at $6.365 a troy ounce on new york's comex, up from $6.305 on thursday. earlier in london, silver bullion traded at a bid $6.31 a troy ounce, down from $6.34. up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, firestone shareholders ...</note>
