as measured by wilshire associates' index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks, the market increased $0.29 billion, or 0.01 percent, in value
nationwide turnover in nyse-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 274.91 million shares
standard &amp; poor's index of 400 industrials dropped .14 to 314.64, and s&amp;p's 500-stock composite index was down .10 at 271.12
the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market rose .88 to 381.58. at the american stock exchange, the market value index closed at 299.11, up .12
less than a week before insider trader ivan f. boesky was to start serving a federal prison term, officials declined to discuss his whereabouts friday and there were indications he might already be in custody
the mystery of the ex-financier's location came against a background of death threats made against him, raising the possibility that he might have sought federal protection prior to his scheduled surrender date of march 24
boesky, the central figure in wall street's biggest insider trading scandal, was sentenced to a three-year prison term for securities fraud last dec. 18 by u.s. district judge morris e. lasker
the judge recommended that the ex-financier spend the time at a minimum security facility in lompoc, calif. he permitted boesky to remain free pending the surrender date
but according to the bureau of prison's computerized prison locator service in washington, boesky was listed as ``in transit,'' meaning he was no longer free on bail and was in custody
locator service dispatchers, who declined to be identified by name, said boesky had been assigned a prisoner identification number, 139-87-054. the last three digits indicated he was in the jurisdiction of the federal marshal's office in manhattan, they said
flip lorenzoni, an official of the marshal's office, said he could not comment on boesky's whereabouts and referred inquiries to a regional office in philadelphia
that office referred questions to bureau of prisons spokeswoman kathryn morse, who said a prison was chosen for boesky a few weeks ago but she declined to identify it until after his arrival, in accordance with government policy. she would not comment on whether boesky already had been placed in custody
john carroll, an assistant u.s. attorney handling the boesky case, declined to discuss boesky's whereabouts, saying, ``that's not a question i'm inclined to answer.''
boesky's attorney, theodore levine, did not return repeated telephone calls to his washington office
officials familiar with the federal prisoner assignment system said it was likely that boesky would go to lompoc, a former army barracks near the pacific coast about 150 miles northwest of los angeles
in a telephone interview, lompoc warden richard rison declined to confirm or deny boesky's impending arrival but said highly publicized prisoners tended to check in unannounced before their surrender deadline, in order to avoid press photographers at the gate
if i was speculating, i would say he won't be here on the 24th,'' rison said. ``i just wouldn't believe he'd plan to come with a lot of fanfare.''
rison emphasized his remarks did not necessarily mean boesky had been assigned to lompoc
formerly one of wall street's best-known speculators, boesky was fined a record $100 million in november 1986 to settle charges of insider trading, which is the illicit use of confidential corporate information to profit in securities trading
under a plea-bargain arrangement, boesky promised to cooperate in implicating others in exchange for pleading guilty to a single felony count _ conspiracy to lie to the sec, which carried a maximum punishment of five years imprisonment and $250,000 fine
boesky's cooperation has raised expectatations of major indictments for securities fraud on wall street
last month john mulheren, a former boesky friend and fellow stock speculator, was arrested on charges he plotted to kill boesky and a boesky aide because he thought they had implicated him
livestock futures prices advanced friday on the chicago mercantile exchange as traders jockeyed their positions before the government released its cattle-on-feed report
on other markets, oil futures moved higher for the fourth consecutive day, wheat was higher while corn and soybeans declined, and treasury bonds retreated sharply
the cattle-on-feed report, released by the agriculture department after the close of trading, was not far off from what was expected
the data probably will be only slightly bearish for the nearby april and june contracts, said chuck levitt, an analyst in chicago with shearson lehman hutton inc
the survey of seven leading cattle states indicated that there were 6 percent more cattle on feed as of march 1 than a year earlier. the number of animals placed on feed during february was 5 percent fewer than 12 months ago, while the marketings was put at 3 percent above the year-ago figure
because the distant contract months are at a substantial discount to the nearby deliveries, traders will be inclined to sell april and june deliveries and buy the back months, levitt said
live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .22 cent higher with the contract for delivery in april at 73.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .32 cent higher with march at 82.12 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent lower to .40 cent higher with april at 46.20 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .25 cent lower to 1.65 cents higher with march at 55.80 cents a pound
oil futures prices advanced for the fourth consecutive day on the new york mercantile exchange
friday's advances were a continuation of a rally begun near the close of the previous session after opec president rilwanu lukman announced he'd have something to say next tuesday about stabilizing prices, said nauman barakat, a analyst in new york with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
my feeling, though, is that they won't do anything but continue to talk up the market for a couple weeks,'' he said. ``after that, the seasonal demand for gasoline will pick up and so opec won't have to do anything to shore up prices.''
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 13 cents to 30 cents higher with the april contract at $16.58 a barrel; heating oil was .52 cent to .83 cent higher with april at 45.05 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .16 cent to .39 cent higher with april at 45.99 cents a gallon
treasury bond futures plunged sharply on the chicago board of trade, responding to what analysts said were renewed fears of inflation
thursday's balance of trade figures helped the dollar and the bond market initially, but further examination of the data gave the markets a different view, said jack barbanel, an analyst in new york with gruntal &amp; co
inflation fears came not only from the trade data, he said, but also from the rising crb index, which was partially influenced by the $1-a-barrel gain by oil over the last four sessions
treasury bonds lost 1 9-32 points, with the june contract settling at 91 1-32 points
wheat futures prices advanced while soybeans and corn skidded lower on the chicago board of trade
wheat was about the only market that showed any strength,'' said victor lespinasse, a trader with dean witter reynolds inc
soybeans dropped about a nickel a bushel despite heavy buying again friday by a large speculator who triggered a strong rally on thursday
friday's buying by the c &amp; d commodities was accompanied by heavy selling of soybean options, negating any strong response by other traders, said lespinasse
he said beans were under pressure from selling by south american interests and by traders unloading contracts before the weekend
increased farmer selling overnight weakened the corn market
a rumor that the agriculture department was about to make an announcement of a large offer of subsidized wheat helped that grain, said lespinasse
after the close, the usda said it offered the soviet union 1 million tons of wheat
wheat settled 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher with the march contract at $2.99 a bushel; corn was { cent to 1 cent lower with march at $1.98 a bushel; oats were unchanged to 3} cents higher with march at $1.96 a bushel; and soybeans were 3\ cents to 6 cents lower with march at $6.20 a bushel
precious metals futures posted gains on the commodity exchange in new york
gold was 30 cents higher with the april contract at $445.20 a troy ounce; and silver was 6 cents to 6.1 cents higher with march at $6.365 a troy ounce
young families trying to purchase their first home and low-income families struggling to meet escalating rental payments are two groups which have suffered the most from flawed housing policies in the 1980s, according to a new study released thursday
america is increasingly becoming a nation of housing haves and have-nots,'' said h. james brown, one of the authors of the report and the director of the joint center for housing studies at harvard university. ``while a majority of americans are well-housed, too many americans have not been able to share in this prosperity.''
the report, titled ``the state of the nation's housing,'' contended that the number of americans unable to secure decent and affordable housing was growing at an alarming rate. among its findings:
_since 1981, rental costs including utilities, have risen 14 percent faster than prices generally. after adjusting for inflation, rental costs are now at their highest level in two decades
_the steep increase in rental costs means that single-parent households must devote 58.4 percent of their incomes to rent, compared to 34.9 percent in 1974
_homeownership rates have fallen steadily during this decade, particularly among young people. in 1980, 43.3 percent of households in the 24-29 age group owned their own home, a figure that has now declined to 35.9 percent
_the after-tax cost of buying a typical first home in 1987 was $7,449, or 32.4 percent of the average annual income of potential first-time buyers, about 50 percent higher than the share of income required in the early 1970s
the study, which was financed by a grant from the ford foundation and several housing trade groups, did not make any recommendations for needed changes in government policy
the reagan administration has been criticized in the past for its efforts to scale back federal housing assistance programs, but brown said it was important to realize that the country's housing problems were a result of a number of forces which have been at work well before the current administration took office
in reacting to the report, carl d. covitz, undersecretary of the department of housing and urban development, said that the administration was proud of its efforts in the past seven years to boost housing subsidies to low-income families but realized ``much more needs to be done.''
it's never been easy for the typical family to buy their first home or for very low-income people to afford decent housing and the harvard study performs a valuable service by pointing up some of the very real problems still faced by many american families,'' covitz said in a statement
william apgar, another author of the report, said that one particular problem was that even minimal federal housing assistance was reaching only one in four families in need
only one in four rentor households with incomes at or below the poverty level live in public housing or receive some other form of federal housing assistance,'' apgar said
the nation's farm sector is continuing a strong recovery that began in 1987 with record-high net cash income, the agriculture department said thursday
cash income is still expected to recede from last year's $57 billion to between $50 billion and $55 billion in 1988, the department's economic research service said in a new outlook report
the projected decline will result from lower livestock receipts, rising expenses and lower government payments, the report said. those will more than offset a rise in 1988 crop receipts
net cash income is the difference between gross cash income and cash expenses in the calendar year
the income and debt-service problems that plagued agriculture during the 1980s have largely been weathered, although financial problems persist for some producers who acquired long-term debt at high interest rates,'' the report said
a major contributor to increased cash flow is a marked reduction in interest expenses since the difficult 1980-83 years.''
economists said receipts from crop sales are improving as a result of increased domestic and export demand for major commodities, including wheat and corn
receipts from livestock sales should be off slightly, as red meat and poultry production expands almost 2 percent and prices falter,'' the report said. ``fruit prices this spring will be below a year ago as larger supplies come to market.''
speculation that pillsbury co. had been targeted for a takeover bid sent the food and restaurant company's stock soaring for a second straight day thursday
pillsbury jumped $3.50 a share to close at $45.50 a share in heavy new york stock exchange composite trading. about 3.48 million shares changed hands compared with average trading volume in the stock of 1.1 million shares a day
analysts speculated that potential buyers included swiss-based nestle s.a., beatrice co. of chicago and new york investor saul steinberg
pillsbury spokesman johnny thompson declined to comment thursday on whether the company has received any offers. the company's rumored suitors earlier had also declined to comment
anything could be true here,'' said robert cummins, food industry analyst at wertheim schroder &amp; co. in new york. ``the main story is that nestle wants to acquire them for $55 per share.''
piper jaffray &amp; hopwood analyst stephen carnes said he suspects the rumors have pillbury's executives ``scrambling for an acquisition'' to increase their company's debt and make it a less desirable takeover target
the management at beatrice, which went private in 1986, has nearly finished retiring the debt incurred in its leveraged buyout of the company. under chairman donald kelly, beatrice has profited from divesting itself of some units and is said to be looking to acquire a whole food company
carnes said wednesday he doubts that kelly is interested in pillsbury for its ``breakup'' value. instead, carnes, a former pillsbury executive, said rumblings of a $55-a-share offer by nestle ``make more sense.''
analysts have been expecting pillsbury to announce a restructuring _ including the sale of its steak &amp; ale, bennigan's and godfather's restaurant operations _ since chairman john stafford resigned last month. interim chairman william spoor has insisted pillsbury's largest restaurant operation, the burger king fast-food chain, is not for sale
pillsbury's announcement in february of lower-than-expected earnings for the fiscal year ended in may preceded stafford's feb. 29 departure
roper corp. said friday it accepted a sweetened $470 million buyout offer from whirlpool corp., which filed suit charging that general electric corp. tried to ``sabotage'' the deal with a competing bid
roper said its board reviewed both offers before recommending whirlpool's $50-a-share cash tender offer to shareholders
on the new york stock exchange friday, roper's stock jumped $5.75 a share to close at $53
the bid tops the $37.50-a-share whirlpool offer made last month, which prompted a bidding war for the augusta, ga.-based maker of garden equipment and cooking ranges. on march 6, ge said it would pay $45 a share, or about $423 million, for roper's outstanding shares
whirlpool chairman david r. whitwam said the higher bid ``underscores whirlpool's determination to complete our agreed-upon merger with roper, despite the deliberate and heavy-handed interference of general electric.''
in a suit filed friday in u.s. district court in grand rapids, whirlpool charged that ge knew whirlpool and roper had signed an acquisition agreement and intentionally sought to block that merger
the suit seeks a court order barring ge from acquiring any interest in roper or interfering in a whirlpool-roper merger
whirlpool alleged that the head of ge's appliance business personally tried to persuade roper to break its contract with whirlpool. the suit said ge ``intentionally, maliciously and unjustifiedly engaged in a continuing course of conduct to sabotage'' the deal
bruce bunch, a spokesman at ge headquarters in fairfield, conn., said the lawsuit ``grossly misstates the facts and is utterly without merit.''
we clearly have not'' interfered, he said. ``our offer is directly to the roper shareowners.''
analysts say the merger will move whirlpool ahead of ge as the nation's leading appliance maker. whirlpool has said it would expand roper from a maker of ranges into a producer and marketer of a full line of appliances
roper has a strong desire to see this combination successfully completed,'' said roper chief executive officer robert cook. whirlpool's whitwam also noted that the merger is of strategic importance
on thursday, whirlpool and ge disclosed that the federal trade commission was investigating the outstanding tender offers for roper. both companies indicated they would respond promptly
whirlpool said in a statement that a thorough ftc review would ``conclude that a ge takeover would have serious anti-competitive effects.''
whirlpool extended its offer through midnight est march 31
bond prices dropped friday in active trading, pressured by resurgent anxiety about inflation
the losses were steepest in longer-maturing issues
the treasury's closely watched 30-year bond tumbled about 1{ point, or $15 for every $1,000 in face amount. its yield, which moves inversely to its price, soared to 8.67 percent from 8.53 percent late thursday
the retreat reversed a brisk increase on thursday, inspired by a government report on the u.s. merchandise trade deficit for january, which pushed the 30-year bond up about $7.50 per $1,000
analysts said bond prices were weakened by unconfirmed reports that the federal reserve is concerned about a possible reigniting of inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income securities such as bonds. also, oil prices continued to rise friday, signaling a possible recurrence of inflation
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude oil, jumped 30 cents to $16.58 per 42-gallon barrel
the bond market got hit pretty hard,'' said jay goldinger, a principal of capital insight inc., an investment firm in beverly hills, calif. ``the market's scared of its shadow right now, and so it's running.''
in the secondary market for treasury bonds, prices of short-term government issues declined 3-16 point to 9-32 point, intermediate maturities fell ] point to 13-16 point, and 20-year issues dropped about 1 5-16 point, according to figures provided by telerate inc., a financial information service
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the price of a bond with a $1,000 face value
the merrill lynch daily treasury index, which measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities of a year or longer, was down 0.59 at 112.34. the shearson lehman treasury bond index, which makes a similar measurement, dropped 7.17 to 1,175.03
moody's investment grade corporate bond index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, fell 1.19 to 283.08
in the municipal bond market, the bond buyer index of 40 actively traded general obligation and revenue bonds fell ] point to 88 15-32 as of 3 p.m. est. the average yield rose to 8.11 percent from 8.07 percent late thursday
yields on three-month treasury bills, meanwhile, jumped 13 basis points to 5.69 percent. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. six-month bills advanced 12 basis points to 5.84 percent and one-year bills rose 8 basis points to 6.26 percent
the federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted late in the day at 6] percent, down from 6 7-16 percent late thursday. of union. picks up 3rd graf ``the meeting ...''</note>
international paper co. said friday it planned to begin discussions with union representatives aimed at resolving bitter labor disputes at several plants around the country
officials for the company and the united paperworkers international union said they had agreed to meet with intermediaries within the next several weeks
the meetings are intended to defuse the hostility between management and labor and set up a framework for pursuing the company's labor problems on a local level, the company said
the company and the union have been at odds for more than a year over contracts that have come up for renewal. at the heart of the disagreements is the issue of whether local contracts should restore premium pay for sundays and holidays
premium pay had been eliminated with labor's approval from past contracts, but since the industry's fortunes have improved in the last year, the union has campaigned to revive the benefit
the parties recognize that continuation of the adversarial relationship is not in the best interests of either party and have committed themselves not only to resolution of the current disputes but to building a proper relationship for the future,'' said a statement released from the company's headquarters in purchase, n.y
bob frase, assistant to the president of the union, which is based in nashville, tenn., said the union was encouraged by the prospect of the talks
anytime we can sit down and talk, that's positive,'' said frase
but he cautioned, as did the company, that the talks would not involve formal contract negotiations. a final resolution of the disputes, affecting at least seven plants, might be hammered out later at the local level, the company suggested
about 3,500 workers in four locations are embroiled in contract fights. in mobile, ala., 1,200 workers have been locked out of their jobs by the company; while an additional 2,300 have struck plants in jay, maine; lock haven, pa.; and depere, wis., frase said
contracts also are open pine bluff and camden, ark., and natchez, miss., said holly kinser, a spokeswoman for the company
analysts who follow international paper said the talks were a step in the right direction
it can be significant, if out of it comes a settlement,'' said lawrence ross of the investment firm painewebber group inc
although the company's plants have continued to operate through the disturbances, the analysts said the bitter struggle with the union has hindered the company's performance at a time when the industry has turned profitable
the mills are all running (with replacement workers), but efficiency has been affected,'' said mark rogers of prudential-bache securities inc
the company said it earned $305 million in 1986 and expects to post earnings of $407 million for 1987 when final figures are released next week. however, the company said its profitability was below the industry average in both 1986 and 1987, when measured in terms of its net worth
the announcement said the company and the union had asked malcolm r. lovell jr., a professor of government and business at george washington university, and gayle wineriter, special assistant to the director of the federal mediation and conciliation service, to assist in the talks
the stock market greeted the news indifferently, sending international paper shares down 25 cents to $44.37{ per share in new york stock exchange trading
a federal judge friday set a january court date in polaroid corp.'s $5.7 billion patent infringement claim against eastman kodak co
judge rya zobel set a jan. 9, 1989, trial date in the 12-year-old case and ordered pre-trial evidence be presented to the court on july 27
in 1985, zobel ruled that kodak had infringed on seven of about 150 polaroid patents on instant cameras and film
in january 1986, zobel barred the rochester, n.y.-based kodak from the instant photography business, pioneered by polaroid
the damage award amount, filed last month in federal court in boston, has increased polaroid stock value and also triggered speculation that a corporate raider may seek control of the cambridge-based company in anticipation of a big settlement
kodak, however, has labeled the claim as ``ludicrous'' and excessively high. several analysts predict a settlement between $1 billion to $2 billion
a $1 billion award would translate to about $10 per share for polaroid
polaroid, which was trading in the low $20 a share before the damage claim was announced, closed friday down { at $34\ on the new york stock exchange. kodak closed down } at $42
polaroid claims $3.2 billion in lost camera and film sales and seeks an additional $2.5 billion for lost opportunities to develop and market new products
polaroid, which introduced instant photography in 1948, held a monopoly in the field until kodak entered the market in the late 1970s
polaroid camera sales peaked at 7.5 million in 1978 before sinking to 3.4 million in 1984. sales rebounded to 4.4 million in 1986 after the introduction of the spectra camera, which offered better quality prints, but fell 16 percent last year
polaroid next month plans to introduce two new cameras, the spectra 600 and image
black &amp; decker corp. friday sweetened its bid again for american standard inc. to $77 per share, or about $2.4 billion cash, one day after the plumbing conglomerate's board approved a $78-per-share leveraged buyout
we believe that our offer of $77 in the light of timing and probability of payment (from the leveraged buyout) represents a better choice for american standard stockholders,'' black &amp; decker chairman nolan b. archibald said in a statement
american standard, which has fought black &amp; decker's bid for nearly two months, said after a marathon board meeting thursday that it would recommend its stockholders accept a $2.45 billion cash offer led by kelso &amp; co., a new york investment banking firm specializing in employee-led leveraged buyouts
the kelso buyout plan _ under which an employee stock ownership plan, or esop, would acquire 20 percent of the company _ topped black &amp; decker's previous bid of $73 a share, or $2.3 billion
stephen f. page, black &amp; decker's treasurer and vice president for finance, said officials of the towson, md.-based tool and appliance maker were confident they could acquire american standard. but he indicated they were reaching their limit
it's always tough to say never,'' page said. ``but i don't see what would be there to make us go higher. i just have a hard time seeing anything there.''
american standard spokeswoman lois stewart said the company would have no comment
black &amp; decker initially proposed a buyout at $65 a share, later sweetening its bid to $68 and finally to $73, before making its latest bid
american standard fell 50 cents to close at $75.87{ a share on the new york stock exchange friday. black &amp; decker closed at $20.62{, up $1.12{ a share
american standard has about 31.5 million common shares outstanding
black &amp; decker's bid came despite analysts' speculation thursday that the bidding war for american standard was over, citing the size of the premium kelso was offering over the market price
but black &amp; decker said it hiked the bid again ``after reviewing the information supplied by american standard (and) after a due diligence session with american standard management.''
black &amp; decker also cited a delaware court ruling on tuesday ``invalidating the golden parachute and pension fund lock-up put into place by american standard after black &amp; decker commenced its offer.''
archibald said the action of the court ``would have justified an additional increase, but we have to take into account the break-up fees and other costs that american standard has incurred since the date of that decision.''
black &amp; decker set midnight march 31 as an expiration date for its tender offer
american standard, a maker of plumbing and air conditioning equipment, said its definitive agreement with kelso is subject to kelso obtaining necessary financing
american standard said kelso planned to finance the deal through a $1.8 billion loan to be syndicated by bankers trust co.; a $900 million short-term ``bridge'' loan from first boston securities corp., an affiliate of the investment bank; and $250 million of common equity from kelso and certain institutional investors
kelso specializes in leveraged buyouts involving employee stock ownership plans, or esops, a concept it pioneered about 30 years ago
the company added it expected a newly formed esop would acquire about 20 percent of american standard's common shares
in a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired largely through borrowed money repaid from the target company's profits or sale of assets. esops also are financed mostly with borrowed funds, but equity is divided among all of the company's workers rather than just a few investors
ms. stewart said american standard, which repeatedly rejected black &amp; decker's earlier overtures, had received several offers but she refused to identify the bidders
page said black &amp; decker plans to sell american standard's transportation division
under the kelso offer, american standard's management likely would remain largely intact but the company might be forced to sell its transportation division and new york headquarters to help reduce debt incurred in the buyout
thirteen people were charged friday in a worldwide, $400,000-a-week money-laundering operation run by israelis in the united states on behalf of two men in colombia
the network laundered $25 million since at least late 1986, mainly through nearly 40 banks in the new york metropolitan area, seattle, and los angeles for ultimate deposit in panama, prosecutors said
at least ten suspects were arrested friday in washington, new jersey and california. they included a rabbi and two former flight attendants nearly nine months pregnant
according to documents filed in federal court here, adi tal, a 27-year-old israeli and former el al airlines employee, supervised the u.s. operations, coordinating operations in the three states
he reported the activities to his superiors in cali, colombia, identified as enrique korc and kimaro, last name unknown, according to u.s. attorney samuel a. alito jr. in newark
the defendants were charged with conspiring to violate federal laws requiring that transactions of more than $10,000 be reported. the charge carries a five-year prison term
the defendants allegedly deposited smaller amounts of cash in banks in the united states and transferred the funds in the form of checks, money orders and cashier's checks shipped in parcels for deposit mainly in the banco cafetero in panama city, panama, alito said
authorities refused to say what the source of the money was, or where it went after reaching the panamanian bank. the case was investigated by the internal revenue service, u.s. customs service and drug enforcement administration
attorney clifford n. kuhn jr., representing tal, his 26-year-old wife jacqueline and another married couple at their initial appearance friday, said he could not comment on the case because he had not discussed it with his clients in detail
asked if the cash resulted from drug sales, he commented: ``i think that's what they're alleging, but i'm not quite sure.''
prosecutors also charged that some defendants illegally transported hundreds of thousands of dollars in cash by plane to england and west germany
tal, who authorities said moved to edison this month from woodland hills, calif., allegedly supervised nir goldeshstein, 27, of edison and the two men's wives in operations in the new york area
each family had access to hundreds of thousands of dollars, had ties to israel and had established ``nest eggs'' there in case they had to flee, assistant u.s. attorney stuart rabner said in court arguments
tal and goldeshstein were ordered held without bail until a hearing monday by u.s. magistrate stanley r. chesler
hedges set bail at $50,000 for mrs. tal and goldeshtein's wife, zoe lawton, 23, both pregnant and close to term
arrested in seattle were baruch zeltzer, 32; sergio dias, 26; avi hazan, 24; and rabbi shalom levitan, said u.s. attorney gene s. anderson
charged in california were moshe begim, 25; guy marom, 26, both of west hollywood; and alon redko, 32, from the los angeles area, said alito. all were arrested by friday afternoon except redko, rabner said
tal, goldeshtein, zeltzer, hazan, begim, marom and redko are israeli citizens, rabner said
levitan holds a ``supervisory position'' at chabad house, a community center for the lubavitch hasidic community, anderson said
the suspects referred to quantities of money as diamond karats in intercepted telephone calls, according to a custom service agent's affidavit filed with the court
ms. lawton was a flight attendant for trans world airlines, and mrs. tal was an attendant for northwest airlines, said the 55-page document
both have family members in seattle and mrs. tal grew up in panama, rabner told the judge
tal and goldeshtein were not employed but were planning to open a private mail drop business in edison where customers could ship packages, rent beepers and purchase money orders, among other things, the affidavit said. $6.5 billion</head>
texaco inc. suggested late friday that back taxes owed to the federal government likely would total less than $1 billion, not the $6.5 billion originally suggested two months ago
the oil giant made the suggestion in an announcement that it had reached a framework agreement to review all tax claims with the internal revenue service. the agreement removed one of the last remaining impediments to texaco's efforts to extricate itself from federal bankruptcy protection
the nation's third-largest oil company sought bankruptcy court refuge nearly a year ago because of a protracted court struggle with the much smaller pennzoil co., which held a $10.3 billion damage claim against texaco
pennzoil won the mammoth judgment from a texas jury that decided texaco had wrecked pennzoil's agreement to buy part of getty oil co. in 1984 by acquiring getty itself
last december pennzoil agreed to drop the claim in exchange for $3 billion cash, setting in motion a complex process under which texaco would emerge from bankruptcy as a smaller restructured company
but under the bankruptcy laws, texaco's other creditors had to state their estimated claims against the company before it emerged from bankruptcy. in january the irs, as a priority creditor, indicated texaco might owe $6.5 billion in back taxes based on an audit of the company for 1965 through 1986
if the irs were correct, industry analysts said, the back taxes would likely have crippled the company
the irs claim stemmed from a theory the agency had developed that would have raised the market value of saudi oil handled by texaco during some of the years in question. theoretically, the irs might have demanded texaco pay taxes on what the company would have earned had it sold the oil for a higher price
although analysts were certain the final tax bill would total much less, the agreement announced friday marked the first time a figure in the $1 billion range was suggested
under the agreement, texaco will make cash deposits against tax claims totaling $1 billion over a four-year period, with the first installment of $200 million on the date its bankruptcy reorganization is approved and $200 million thereafter on each of the next four anniversary dates
texaco's announcement implied the final bill might even be less than $1 billion because of a provision that any leftover money will be returned to the company. the company also downplayed the significance of the irs claim compared with the taxes texaco pays during the course of one year
the amount of the deposits provided for in the agreement, which cover outstanding tax claims spanning a period of 13 years, should be viewed in the context of the $3.8 billion in direct taxes the company incurred in 1987 alone on its $35.8 billion in business revenue worldwide,'' texaco said
texaco officials declined to comment further because of what they called an arrangement with the irs not to elaborate on the agreement
ellen murphy, public affairs director for the irs in washington, said the $1 billion figure represented only money to be deposited for claims and ``obviously it's too soon to say what size liability we're talking about.''
nevertheless, accountants familiar with irs policies on large back-tax claimssuggested that if the agency felt texaco might owe more than $1 billion, it would have demanded a bigger deposit
